{"title_page": "Paul Wentworth (spy)", "text_new": "'''Paul Wentworth'''  (c. 1736\u20131793) was a British intelligence agent and politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] briefly in 1780.\n\n==Early life==\nWentworth  may have been  born in Barbados. He moved to [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]] in the 1750s, and won the patronage of the governor [[Benning Wentworth]]. He settled in [[Suriname|Surinam]] in about 1760 where he married a widow, and on her death inherited a sugar plantation. In 1764 he hired [[Edward Bancroft]] to survey and improve the Surinam plantation and in 1766 left for London. He established himself as a stockbroker or speculator in London and Paris. [[Sir John Wentworth, 1st Baronet|John Wentworth]] the next governor of New Hampshire appointed him as a member of the New Hampshire council and also as the province's agent to the Parliament of Great Britain despite the two offices needing to be on opposite sides of the Atlantic.<ref name= EAR>[http://www.encyclopedia.com \"Wentworth, Paul.\" Encyclopedia of the American Revolution: Library of Military History. . Encyclopedia.com. 12 Nov. 2017 ]</ref>\n\n==Intelligence activities==\nWentworth decided  that the British crown offered better opportunities than the Americans.  He started supplying information to the British secret service in 1772. When the American war began, [[William Eden, 1st Baron Auckland|Sir William Eden]], head of the British secret service, granted Wentworth a pension of five hundred pounds a year for his services. Wentworth was to spy on the American delegation to the French court  when  [[Silas Deane]] was sent to Paris in 1776. Deane and [[Benjamin Franklin]] were both old friends of Wentworth and he could easily make the necessary contacts. Wentworth's friend Edward Bancroft  joined the American mission in Paris in 1776 and. Wentworth  recruited him to spy for the British government in December 1776.<ref name= EAR/>  In 1777 [[Pierre Beaumarchais]] wrote to [[Charles Gravier, comte de Vergennes|Vergennes]]  that Wentworth spoke  French \"like you and better than I do: he is one of the cleverest men in England\".<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/wentworth-paul-1793| title= WENTWORTH, Paul (d. 1793), of Hammersmith, Mdx.| publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 12 November 2017}}</ref> In 1778 Wentworth was in discussions with Franklin on peace terms but the effect of this was to help drive the French into alliance with the Americans.<ref name=EAR/>\n\nWentworth was seeking a baronetcy, a place at the Treasury Board, and a seat in Parliament<ref name=HOP/> and wanted a British victory to save his New Hampshire estates. He built up and controlled a spy network and provided military intelligence to the British government on the basis of the reports he gathered.  He often went in disguise to mainland Europe but in time the French police recognized him and he had to stay in London.<ref name= EAR/> Lord North considered him \"the most important and truest informer\"<ref name=HOP/> although George III had little confidence in his reports and disliked his speculative activities.<ref name= EAR/>\n\n==Political career==\nWentworth was returned as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Saltash (UK Parliament constituency)|Saltash]] with administration support, at a by-election on 12 July 1780. However the dissolution of Parliament was announced before he could take his seat. At the [[1780 British general election|1780 general election]] he stood at [[Penryn (UK Parliament constituency)|Penryn]] as Government candidate, but came last in the poll.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==Later life and legacy==\nWentworth retired to Surinam and died there in December 1793.<ref name= EAR/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==Further reading==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n* Bemis, Samuel Flagg. \"British secret service and the French-American Alliance.\" ''American Historical Review'' 29.3 (1924): 474-495. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/pdf/1836521.pdf online]\n* Otoole, George JA. \"Benjamin Franklin: American spymaster or British mole?.\" ''International Journal of Intelligence and Counter Intelligence'' 3.1 (1989): 45-53.\n* Wecter, Dixon. \"Burke, Franklin, and Samuel Petrie.\" ''Huntington Library Quarterly'' (1940): 315-338. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/3816049 online]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Grey Cooper]]\n | before2 = [[Sir Henry Strachey, 1st Baronet|Henry Strachey]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Saltash (UK Parliament constituency)|Saltash]]\n | years = 1780\u2013[[1780 British general election|1780]]\n | with  =  [[Grey Cooper]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Grey Cooper]]\n\n | after2 = [[Charles Jenkinson, 1st Earl of Liverpool|Charles Jenkinson]]\n}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wentworth, Paul (spy)}}\n[[Category:British spies during the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1774\u20131780]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for Saltash]]\n[[Category:1730s births]]\n[[Category:1793 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''Paul Wentworth'''  (c. 1736\u20131793) was a British intelligence agent and politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] briefly in 1780.\n\n==Early life==\nWentworth  may have been  born in Barbados. He moved to [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]] in the 1750s, and won the patronage of the governor [[Benning Wentworth]]. He settled in [[Suriname|Surinam]] in about 1760 where he married a widow, and on her death inherited a sugar plantation. In 1764 he hired [[Edward Bancroft]] to survey and improve the Surinam plantation and in 1766 left for London. He established himself as a stockbroker or speculator in London and Paris. [[Sir John Wentworth, 1st Baronet|John Wentworth]] the next governor of New Hampshire appointed him as a member of the New Hampshire council and also as the province's agent to the Parliament of Great Britain despite the two offices needing to be on opposite sides of the Atlantic.<ref name= EAR>[http://www.encyclopedia.com \"Wentworth, Paul.\" Encyclopedia of the American Revolution: Library of Military History. . Encyclopedia.com. 12 Nov. 2017 ]</ref>\n\n==Intelligence activities==\nWentworth decided  that the British crown offered better opportunities than the Americans.  He started supplying information to the British secret service in 1772. When the American war began, [[William Eden, 1st Baron Auckland|Sir William Eden]], head of the British secret service, granted Wentworth a pension of five hundred pounds a year for his services. Wentworth was to spy on the American delegation to the French court  when  [[Silas Deane]] was sent to Paris in 1776. Deane and [[Benjamin Franklin]] were both old friends of Wentworth and he could easily make the necessary contacts. Wentworth's friend Edward Bancroft  joined the American mission in Paris in 1776 and. Wentworth  recruited him to spy for the British government in December 1776.<ref name= EAR/>  In 1777 [[Pierre Beaumarchais]] wrote to [[Charles Gravier, comte de Vergennes|Vergennes]]  that Wentworth spoke  French \"like you and better than I do: he is one of the cleverest men in England\".<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/wentworth-paul-1793| title= WENTWORTH, Paul (d. 1793), of Hammersmith, Mdx.| publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 12 November 2017}}</ref> In 1778 Wentworth was in discussions with Franklin on peace terms but the effect of this was to help drive the French into alliance with the Americans.<ref name=EAR/>\n\nWentworth was seeking a baronetcy, a place at the Treasury Board, and a seat in Parliament<ref name=HOP/> and wanted a British victory to save his New Hampshire estates. He built up and controlled a spy network and provided military intelligence to the British government on the basis of the reports he gathered.  He often went in disguise to mainland Europe but in time the French police recognized him and he had to stay in London.<ref name= EAR/> Lord North considered him \"the most important and truest informer\"<ref name=HOP/> although George III had little confidence in his reports and disliked his speculative activities.<ref name= EAR/>\n\n==Political career==\nWentworth was returned as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Saltash (UK Parliament constituency)|Saltash]] with administration support, at a by-election on 12 July 1780. However the dissolution of Parliament was announced before he could take his seat. At the [[1780 British general election|1780 general election]] he stood at [[Penryn (UK Parliament constituency)|Penryn]] as Government candidate, but came last in the poll.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==Later life and legacy==\nWentworth retired to Surinam and died there in December 1793.<ref name= EAR/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==Further reading==\n* Bemis, Samuel Flagg. \"British secret service and the French-American Alliance.\" ''American Historical Review'' 29.3 (1924): 474-495. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/pdf/1836521.pdf online]\n* Otoole, George JA. \"Benjamin Franklin: American spymaster or British mole?.\" ''International Journal of Intelligence and Counter Intelligence'' 3.1 (1989): 45-53.\n* Wecter, Dixon. \"Burke, Franklin, and Samuel Petrie.\" ''Huntington Library Quarterly'' (1940): 315-338. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/3816049 online]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Grey Cooper]]\n | before2 = [[Sir Henry Strachey, 1st Baronet|Henry Strachey]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Saltash (UK Parliament constituency)|Saltash]]\n | years = 1780\u2013[[1780 British general election|1780]]\n | with  =  [[Grey Cooper]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Grey Cooper]]\n\n | after2 = [[Charles Jenkinson, 1st Earl of Liverpool|Charles Jenkinson]]\n}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wentworth, Paul (spy)}}\n[[Category:British spies during the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1774\u20131780]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for Saltash]]\n[[Category:1730s births]]\n[[Category:1793 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Wentworth_(spy)"}
{"title_page": "Compassion", "text_new": "{{short description|Moved or motivated to help others}}\n{{other uses|Compassion (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:There's no crying in baseball! (4549295140) 2.jpg|alt=|thumb|One child showing compassion for another child.]]\n'''Compassion''' motivates people to go out of their way to help the physical, mental, or emotional pains of another and themselves. Compassion is often regarded as having sensitivity, an emotional aspect to suffering, though when based on cerebral notions such as fairness, justice, and interdependence, it may be considered rational in nature and its application understood as an activity also based on sound judgment. There is also an aspect of equal dimension, such that an individual's compassion is often given a property of \"depth\", \"vigor\", or \"[[passion (emotion)|passion]]\". The etymology of \"compassion\" is Latin, meaning \"co-suffering.\" Compassion involves \"feeling for another\" and is a precursor to [[empathy]], the \"feeling as another\" capacity for better person-centered acts of active compassion; in common parlance active compassion is the [[desire (emotion)|desire]] to alleviate another's suffering.<ref name=\"sjsl\">Sherlyn Jimenez, see article on ''Compassion'', The Encyclopedia of Positive Psychology, Volume I, Editor: Shane Lopez, Wiley-Blackwell, {{ISBN|978-1-4051-6125-1}}</ref>\n\nCompassion involves allowing ourselves to be moved by suffering and experiencing the motivation to help alleviate and prevent it. An act of compassion is defined by its [[helpfulness]]. Qualities of compassion are patience and wisdom; kindness and perseverance; warmth and resolve. It is often, though not inevitably, the key component in what manifests in the social context as [[altruism]]. Expression of compassion is prone to be hierarchical, paternalistic and controlling in responses.<ref name=\"Gilbert2010\"/> Difference between sympathy and compassion is that the former responds to suffering from sorrow and concern while the latter responds with warmth and care.<ref name=\"CompInteg\"/>\n\nThe English [[noun]] ''compassion'', meaning ''to suffer together with'', comes from [[Latin]]. Its [[prefix]] ''com-'' comes directly from ''com'', an archaic version of the Latin [[preposition]] and affix [[wikt:cum|cum]] (= with); the ''-passion'' segment is derived from ''passus'', [[past participle]] of the [[deponent verb]] [[wikt:patior|patior, pat\u012b, passus sum]]. Compassion is thus related in origin, form and meaning to the English noun [[patient]] (= one who suffers), from ''patiens'', [[present participle]] of the same [[wikt:patior|patior]], and is akin to the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] verb \u03c0\u03ac\u03c3\u03c7\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd (= ''paskhein'', to suffer) and to its [[cognate]] noun [[wikt:\u03c0\u03ac\u03b8\u03bf\u03c2|\u03c0\u03ac\u03b8\u03bf\u03c2]] (= [[pathos]]).<ref name=\"newSOED\">{{cite book |author=Brown, Lesley |title=The New shorter Oxford English dictionary on historical principles |publisher=Clarendon |location=Oxford [Eng.] |year=2002 |pages= |isbn=978-0-19-861271-1 |oclc= |doi= |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/newshorteroxford00lesl }}</ref><ref name=\"Partridge\">{{cite book |author=Partridge, Eric |title=Origins: a short etymological dictionary of modern English |publisher=Macmillan |location=New York |year=1966 |pages= |isbn=978-0-02-594840-2 |oclc= |doi=}}</ref> Ranked a great virtue in numerous [[philosophy|philosophies]], compassion is considered in almost all the major [[religion|religious traditions]] as among the greatest of [[virtue]]s.\n\n== Theories ==\nTheoretical perspectives of compassion have been developed through the years, the following three proposed perspectives show contrasts in their evolution and approaches to compassion.\n:* Compassion is simply a variation of love or sadness, not a distinct emotion.<ref name=\"Shaver et. al: Emotion Knowledge\">{{cite journal|last=Shaver|first=P|author2=J Schwartz |author3=D Kirson |author4=C O'Connor |title=Emotion knowledge: further exploration of a prototype approach|journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|date=June 1987|volume=52|issue=6|pages=1061\u20131086|doi=10.1037/0022-3514.52.6.1061 |pmid=3598857}}</ref>\n:* From the perspective of evolutionary psychology, compassion can be viewed as a distinct emotional state, which can be differentiated from distress, [[sadness]], and [[love]].<ref name=\"Bowlby: Attach and loss vol. 1\">{{cite book|last=Bowlby|first=John|title=Attachment: Attachment and Loss Volume One|year=1983|publisher=Basic Books|location=New York, NY}}</ref><ref name=\"The Moral Emotions: Haidt\">{{cite book|last=Haidt|first=Jonathan|title=The Moral Emotions|year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|pages=852\u2013870}}</ref><ref name=\"Social Functionalism and the Evolution of Emotions: Keltner et al\">{{cite book|last=Keltner|first=Dacher|title=Social Functionalism and the Evolution of Emotions|year=2006|publisher=Psychology Press|location=New York|pages=115\u2013142|author2=Jonathan Haidt |author3=Michelle Shiota}}</ref>\n:* Compassion as a synonym of empathic distress, which is characterized by the feeling of distress in connection with another person's suffering.<ref name=\"Compassion: An Evolutionary Analysis and Empirical Review\">{{cite journal|last=Goetz|first=Jennifer|author2=Dacher Kelter |author3=Emiliana Simon-Thomas |title=Compassion: An Evolutionary Analysis and Empirical Review|journal=Psychological Bulletin|year=2010|volume=136|issue=3|pages=351\u2013374|doi=10.1037/a0018807|pmid=20438142|pmc=2864937}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ekman|first=Paul|title=Emotions Revealed: Recognizing Faces and Feelings to improve communication and emotional life|year=2003|publisher=Henry Holt & Company|location=New York, NY}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Hoffman|first=Martin|title=Is altruism part of human nature?|journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|year=1981|volume=40|issue=1|pages=121\u2013137|doi=10.1037/0022-3514.40.1.121}}</ref> This perspective of compassion is based on the finding that people sometimes emulate and feel the emotions of people around them.<ref name=\"Hatfield, 1993: Emotional Contagion\">{{cite journal|last=Hatfield|first=Elaine|author2=John Cacioppo|title=Emotional Contagion|journal=Current Directions in Psychological Science|year=1993|volume=2|issue=3|pages=96\u201399|doi=10.1111/1467-8721.ep10770953|last3=Rapson|first3=Richard L.}}</ref>\n\nThe more one person knows about the human condition and the associated experiences, the more vivid the route to identification with suffering becomes.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\">{{cite book|last=Cassell|first=Eric|title=Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology|year=2009|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York, New York|isbn=978-0-19-518724-3|pages=393\u2013403|edition=2}}</ref> Identifying with another person is an essential process for human beings, it is commonly seen throughout the world as people adapt and change with new styles of clothing, language, behavior, etc., which is even illustrated by infants who begin to mirror the facial expressions and body movements of their mother as early as the first days of their lives.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Meltzoff|first=Andrew|title=The Roots of Social and Cognitive Development: Models of Man's Original Nature|journal=Social Perception in Infants|year=1985|pages=1\u201330}}</ref> [[Personality psychology]] agrees that people are inherently different and distinct from one another, which leads to the conclusion that human suffering is always individual and unique. Suffering can result from psychological, social, and physical trauma<ref name=\"cassell1995\">{{cite book|last=Cassell|first=Eric|title=The Healer's Art|year=1995|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-53062-0}}</ref> and it happens in acute forms as often as chronically.<ref name=\"cassell1995\"/> Due to the inherent differences in people's personalities some may define their early stages of suffering to their external circumstances and those life events being quiet or not discussed. The later stages may involve the person expressing their [[victimization]] and searching for help.<ref name=\"Models of Point Suffering\">{{cite book|last=Reich|first=Warren|title=Models of Point Suffering: Foundations for an Ethic Compassion |year=1987|volume=38|pages=117\u2013122|doi=10.1007/978-3-7091-6975-9_20|series=Acta Neurochirurgica Supplementum|isbn=978-3-7091-7457-9}}</ref> [[Suffering]] has been defined as the perception of a person's impending destruction or loss of integrity, which continues until the threat is vanished or the person's integrity can be restored.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> The importance of identifying with others for compassion is contrasted by the negative physical and psychological effects of [[Abandonment (emotional)|abandonment]]. Compassion is often a characteristic element of democratic societies.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> Compassion is recognized through identifying with other people, the knowledge of human behavior, the perception of suffering, transfer of feelings, knowledge of goal and purpose changes in sufferers, and leads to the absence of the suffering from the group.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" />\n\nThe compassion process is highly related to identifying with the other person because sympathizing with others is possible among people from other countries, cultures, locations, etc. A possible source of this process of identifying with others comes from a universal category called \"Spirit.\" Toward the late 1970s, very different cultures and nations around the world took a turn to [[religious fundamentalism]], which has occasionally been attributed to \"Spirit\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Hegal|first=Georg|title=Phenomenology of Spirit|year=1952|publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-824597-1}}</ref> The role of compassion as a factor contributing to individual or societal behavior has been the topic of continuous debate.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brown|first=Lee |title=Compassion and Societal Well-Being|journal=Pacific Philosophical Quarterly|date=1 January 1996}}</ref> In contrast to the process of identifying with other people, a complete absence of compassion may require ignoring or disapproving identification with other people or groups.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> Earlier studies established the links between interpersonal violence and cruelty which leads to indifference.<ref>Frank R. Ascione, Phil Arkow Child abuse, domestic violence, and animal abuse: linking the circles of compassion for prevention and intervention {{ISBN|1-55753-142-0}}</ref><ref>Randall Lockwood, Frank R. Ascione. Cruelty to Animals and Interpersonal Violence. Purdue University Press, 1998</ref> This concept has been illustrated throughout history: [[The Holocaust]], [[Genocide]], [[European colonization of the Americas]], etc. The seemingly essential step in these atrocities could be the definition of the victims as \"not human\" or \"not us.\" The atrocities committed throughout human history have only been relieved, minimized, or overcome it's damaging effects through the presence of compassion.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=MacIntyre|first=Alisdair|title=A Short History of Ethics|year=1966|publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul|isbn=978-0-203-13112-1}}</ref>\n\nCompassion may have the ability to induce feelings of kindness and [[forgiveness]], which could give people the ability to stop situations that have the potential to be distressing and occasionally lead to violence.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Goetz|first=J|author2=D Keltner |author3=E Simon-Thomas  |title=Compassion: An evolutionary analysis and empirical review|journal=Psychological Bulletin|year=2010 |volume=136|issue=3|pages=351\u2013374|doi=10.1037/a0018807|pmid=20438142 |pmc=2864937}}</ref>\n\n=== Psychology ===\nCompassion has become associated with and researched in the fields of [[positive psychology]] and social psychology.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jazaieri|first=Hooria|last2=Jinpa|first2=Geshe Thupten|last3=McGonigal|first3=Kelly|last4=Rosenberg|first4=Erika L.|last5=Finkelstein|first5=Joel|last6=Simon-Thomas|first6=Emiliana|last7=Cullen|first7=Margaret|last8=Doty|first8=James R.|last9=Gross|first9=James J.|date=2012-07-25|title=Enhancing Compassion: A Randomized Controlled Trial of a Compassion Cultivation Training Program|journal=Journal of Happiness Studies|language=en|volume=14|issue=4|pages=1113\u20131126|doi=10.1007/s10902-012-9373-z|issn=1389-4978|citeseerx=10.1.1.362.5161}}</ref> The [[Dalai Lama]] once said that \"compassion is a necessity, not a luxury\"<ref name=\"CompInteg\">{{cite book|author1=Reddy, Nanda Kishore|author2=Ajmera, Santosh|title=Ethics, Integrity and Aptitude|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YLlyCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA146|publisher=McGraw-Hill Education|isbn=978-93-5134-236-6|page=146}}</ref> and that \"it is a question of human survival\".<ref name=\"Lama1990\">{{cite book|author=H.H. the Fourteenth Dalai Lama|title=Policy of Kindness: An Anthology of Writings by and about the Dalai Lama|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_GZ4LRsqEegC&pg=PA112|year=1990|publisher=Shambhala|isbn=978-1-55939-769-8|page=112}}</ref> Compassion is a process of connecting by identifying with another person. This identification with others through compassion can lead to increased motivation to do something in an effort to relieve the suffering of others.\n\nCompassion is an evolved function from the harmony of a three grid internal system: contentment-and-peace system, goals-and-drives system and threat-and-safety system. Paul Gilbert defines these collectively as necessary regulated systems for compassion.<ref name=\"Gilbert2010\">{{cite book|author=Paul Gilbert|title=The Compassionate Mind: A New Approach to Life's Challenges|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=krNPL6xCVL0C|year=2010|publisher=New Harbinger Publications|isbn=978-1-57224-840-3}}</ref> In examination of the motivated regulation of compassion in the context of large-scale crises, such as natural disasters and genocides, much research has established that people tend to feel more compassion for single identifiable victims than large masses of victims (the [[Identifiable victim effect]]). It is found that people only show less compassion for many victims than for single victims of disasters when they expect to incur a financial cost upon helping. This [[collapse of compassion]] depends on having the motivation and ability to regulate emotions.<ref>Cameron & Payne, 2011, JPSP</ref> In laboratory research, psychologists are exploring how concerns about becoming emotionally exhausted may motivate people to curb their compassion for\u2014and dehumanize\u2014members of stigmatized social groups, such as homeless individuals and drug addicts.<ref>Cameron, Harris, & Payne, in prep</ref>\n\nCompassion consists of three major requirements: People must feel that troubles that evoke their feelings are serious, the understanding that sufferers' troubles are not self-inflicted, and ability to picture oneself with the same problems in a non-blaming and non-shaming manner.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" />\n\n===Neurobiology===\n{{Globalize|section|date=October 2019}}\nJorge Moll and Jordan Grafman, [[neuroscientists]] at the [[National Institutes of Health]] and LABS-D'Or Hospital Network (J.M.) provided the first evidence for the neural bases of altruistic giving in normal healthy volunteers, using [[functional magnetic resonance imaging]]. In their research, published in the [[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences]] USA in October 2006,<ref>Human fronto\u2013mesolimbic networks guide decisions about charitable donation, PNAS 2006:103(42);15623\u201315628</ref> they showed that both pure monetary rewards and charitable donations activated the [[Mesolimbic pathway|mesolimbic]] reward pathway, a primitive part of the brain that usually responds to food and sex. However, when volunteers generously placed the interests of others before their own by making charitable donations, another brain circuit was selectively activated: the subgenual cortex/[[septal region]]. These structures are intimately related to social attachment and bonding in other species. Altruism, the experiment suggested, was not a superior moral faculty that suppresses basic selfish urges but rather was basic to the brain, hard-wired and pleasurable.<ref name=\"brain\">{{cite news\n|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/27/AR2007052701056.html\n|title=If It Feels Good to Be Good, It Might Be Only Natural\n|publisher=Washington Post\n|date=May 2007\n|first=Shankar\n|last=Vedantam\n|accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref> One brain region, the subgenual [[anterior cingulate]] cortex/[[basal forebrain]], contributes to learning altruistic behavior, especially in those with trait empathy.<ref name=PMID_27528669>{{ cite journal |last1 = Lockwood |first1 = Patricia L |last2 = Apps |first2 = Matthew A J |last3 = Valton |first3 = Vincent |last4 = Viding |first4 = Essi |last5 = Roiser |first5 = Jonathan P |year = 2016 |title = Neurocomputational mechanisms of prosocial learning and links to empathy. |journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America |quote = . fMRI revealed that activity in a posterior portion of the subgenual anterior cingulate cortex/basal forebrain (sgACC) drives learning only when we are acting in a prosocial context |lay-url = http://neurosciencenews.com/generosity-empathy-neuroscience-4850/ |pmid = 27528669 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1603198113 |volume=113 |issue = 35 |pages=9763\u20138|pmc = 5024617 }}</ref> The same study has shown a connection between giving to charity and the promotion of social bonding.<ref name=\"neurons\">{{cite news\n|url=https://generosityresearch.nd.edu/news/hard-wired-for-giving/\n|title=Scientists Are Finding That We Are Hard-Wired for Giving\n|publisher=University of Notre Dame\n|date=September 5, 2013\n|first=Elizabeth\n|last=Svoboda\n|accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn fact, in an experiment published in March 2007 at the [[University of Southern California]] neuroscientist [[Antonio R. Damasio]] and his colleagues showed that subjects with damage to the [[ventromedial prefrontal cortex]] lack the ability to feel their way empathically to moral answers, and that when confronted with moral dilemmas, these brain-damaged patients coldly came up with \"end-justifies-the-means\" answers, leading Damasio to conclude that the point was not that they reached immoral conclusions, but that when they were confronted by a difficult issue \u2014 in this case as whether to shoot down a passenger plane hijacked by terrorists before it hits a major city \u2014 these patients appear to reach decisions without the anguish that afflicts those with normally functioning brains. According to [[Adrian Raine]], a clinical neuroscientist also at the University of Southern California, one of this study's implications is that society may have to rethink how it judges immoral people: \"Psychopaths often feel no empathy or remorse. Without that awareness, people relying exclusively on reasoning seem to find it harder to sort their way through moral thickets. Does that mean they should be held to different standards of accountability?\"<ref name=\"brain\"/>\n\nIn another study, in the 1990s, Dr. Bill Harbaugh, a [[University of Oregon]] economist, concluded people are motivated to give for reasons of personal prestige and in a similar fMRI scanner test in 2007 with his psychologist colleague Dr. Ulrich Mayr, reached the same conclusions of Jorge Moll and Jordan Grafman about giving to charity, although they were able to divide the study group into two groups: \"egoists\" and \"altruists\". One of their discoveries was that, though rarely, even some of the considered \"egoists\" sometimes gave more than expected because that would help others, leading to the conclusion that there are other factors in cause in charity, such as a person's environment and values.<ref name=\"neurons\"/>\n\n=== Medicine ===\nCompassion is one of the most important attributes for physicians practicing medical services.<ref>{{cite book|title=Principles of Medical Ethics|year=1981|publisher=American Medical Association|location=Chicago}}</ref> It has been suggested that felt compassion brings about the desire to do something to help the sufferer.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> That desire to be helpful is not compassion, but it does suggest that compassion is similar to other emotions by motivating behaviors to reduce the tension brought on by the emotion.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> Physicians generally identify their central duties as the responsibility to put the patient's interests first, including the duty not to harm, deliver proper care, and maintain confidentiality.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> Compassion is seen in each of those duties because of its direct relation to the recognition and treatment of suffering.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> Physicians who use compassion understand the effects of sickness and suffering on human behavior.<ref>{{cite book|last=Cassell|first=Eric|title=The Nature of Suffering|year=1985|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York}}</ref> Compassion may be closely related to love and the emotions evoked in both. This is illustrated by the relationship between patients and physicians in medical institutions.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> The relationship between suffering patients and their caregivers provides evidence that compassion is a social emotion, which is highly related to the closeness between individuals.\n\n=== Compassion fatigue ===\n{{Further|Compassion fatigue}}\nAccording to Figley, individuals with a higher capacity or responsibility to empathize with others may be at risk for \"compassion fatigue\" or stress, which is related to professionals and individuals who spend a significant amount of time responding to information related to suffering.<ref name=\"Compassion Fatigue: Figley\">{{cite book |last=Figley |first=Charles|title=Compassion Fatigue: Coping With Secondary Traumatic Stress Disorder In Those Who Treat The Traumatized|year=1995|publisher=Brunner-Routledge|location=London|isbn=978-0876307595}}</ref> However, newer research by [[Tania Singer|Singer]] and [[Matthieu Ricard|Ricard]] suggests that it is lack of suitable [[distress tolerance]] which gets people fatigued in compassion activities.<ref name=\"Altruism: Ricard\">{{cite book |last=Ricard |first=Matthieu|title=Altruism: The Power of Compassion to Change Yourself and the World|chapter=IV|chapter-url=http://info-buddhism.com/Empathy-Compassion-Neuroscience-Ricard-Altruism.html|pages=56\u201364|year=2015|publisher=Brown and Company|isbn=978-0316208246}}</ref> Research suggests that practice of nonjudgmental compassion can prevent fatigue and [[Occupational burnout|burnout]].<ref>[http://www.matthieuricard.org/system/resources/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMDYvMDQvMTBfMjNfNDNfNjIxX0tsaW1lY2tpX0xlaWJlcmdfUmljYXJkX1Npbmdlcl8yMDEzX1NDQU4ucGRmIl1d/Klimecki_Leiberg_Ricard_Singer_2013_SCAN.pdf Differential pattern of functional brain plasticity after compassion and empathy training], Olga M. Klimecki, Susanne Leiberg, Matthieu Ricard, and Tania Singer, Department of Social Neuroscience, Max Planck Institute for Human Cognitive and Brain Sciences</ref>\n\n=== Self-compassion ===\n{{Further|Self-compassion}}\nSelf-compassion is a process of self kindness and accepting suffering as a quality of being human. It has positive effects on subjective [[happiness]], [[optimism]], [[wisdom]], [[curiosity]], [[agreeableness]], and [[extroversion]].<ref name=\"Emotional effects of compassion - NeV\">{{cite journal|last=NeV|first=Kristen|author2=Stephanie Rude |author3=Kristin Kirpatrick |title=An examination of self-compassion in relation to positive psychological functioning and personality traits|journal=Journal of Research in Psychology|year=2007|volume=41|issue=4|pages=908\u2013916|doi=10.1016/j.jrp.2006.08.002}}</ref> [[Kristin Neff]] and Christopher Germer have identified that there are three levels of activities that thwart self-compassion and they are self-criticism, self-isolation and self-absorption, they equate this to fight, flight and freeze responses.<ref>http://self-compassion.org/wp-content/uploads/publications/germer.neff.pdf</ref><ref>https://chrisgermer.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Transforming-Trauma.pdf</ref> It is identified that people who lack of life skill equanimity that is akin with distress tolerance are prone to such spontaneous responses. Certain activities may increase feelings of and readiness to practice self-compassion; some of these activities include creating a loving-kindness rituals, practicing empathy, practice random acts of warmth and goodwill like [[tonglen]], etc.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nFor increasing compassion in the workplace to self and others, ''authentic leadership'' centered on humanism and nourishing quality interconnectedness are considered as the key.<ref name=\"Compassion in the workplace\">{{cite journal|last=Peus|first=Claudia|title=Money over man versus caring and compassion? Challenges for today's organizations and their leaders|journal=Journal of Organizational Behavior|date=15 April 2011|volume=32|issue=7|pages=955\u2013960|doi=10.1002/job.751}}</ref> [[Judith V. Jordan|Judith Jordan]]'s concept of ''self-empathy'' is similar to self-compassion, it implies the capacity to notice, care and respond towards the ones own felt needs. The strategies of self-care involve valuing oneself, thinking about one's ideations of needs compassionately, and connecting with others in order to conversely experience renewal, support, and validation. Research indicates that self-compassionate individuals experience greater [[psychological health]] than those who lack self-compassion.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1037/0022-3514.92.5.887|pmid = 17484611|title = Self-compassion and reactions to unpleasant self-relevant events: The implications of treating oneself kindly|journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume = 92|issue = 5|pages = 887\u2013904|year = 2007|last1 = Leary|first1 = Mark R.|last2 = Tate|first2 = Eleanor B.|last3 = Adams|first3 = Claire E.|last4 = Batts Allen|first4 = Ashley|last5 = Hancock|first5 = Jessica}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.jrp.2006.08.002 | last1 = Neff | first1 = K. D. | last2 = Rude | first2 = S. S. | last3 = Kirkpatrick | first3 = K. | year = 2007 | title = An examination of self-compassion in relation to positive psychological functioning and personality traits | url = | journal = Journal of Research in Personality | volume = 41 | issue = 4| pages = 908\u2013916 }}</ref>\n\n== Historical and spiritual-religious views ==\n===Abrahamic religions===\n\n====Christianity====\n[[File:G. Conti La parabola del Buon Samaritano Messina Chiesa della Medaglia Miracolosa Casa di Ospitalit\u00e0 Collereale.jpg|thumb|Compassion in action: an 18th-century Italian depiction of the Parable of the [[Good Samaritan]]]]\n\nThe Christian [[Bible]]'s [[Second Epistle to the Corinthians]] is but one place where God is spoken of as the \"Father of compassion\" and the \"God of all comfort.\" It reads as follows: 2 Corinthians 1:3\u20137 \"Praise be to the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, the Father of compassion and the God of all comfort, who comforts us in all our troubles, so that we can comfort those in any trouble with the comfort we ourselves received from God. For just as the sufferings of Christ flow over into our lives, so also through Christ our comfort overflows. If we are distressed, it is for your comfort and salvation; if we are comforted, it is for your comfort, which produces in you patient endurance of the same sufferings we suffer. And our hope for you is firm, because we know that just as you share in our sufferings, so also you share in our comfort.\" [[Jesus]] embodies for [[Christians]], the very essence of compassion and relational care. Christ challenges Christians to forsake their own desires and to act compassionately towards others, particularly those in need or distress.<ref>Lampert Khen (2006), Ch. 1</ref>{{Full citation needed|date=October 2019}} Most significantly, he demonstrated compassion to those his society had condemned \u2013 tax collectors, prostitutes and criminals, by saying \"just because you received a loaf of bread, does not mean you were more conscientious about it, or more caring about your fellow man.\"<ref name=\"Drake-Brockman 2012\">{{cite book|last=Drake-Brockman|first=Tom|title=Christian Humanism: the compassionate theology of a Jew called Jesus|year=2012|publisher=Denis Jones and associates|location=Sydney|isbn=9780646530390}}</ref>\n\nConversely, a 2012 study of the [[historical Jesus]] has claimed that the founder of Christianity sought to elevate Judaic compassion as the supreme human virtue, capable of reducing suffering and fulfilling our God-ordained purpose of transforming the world into something more worthy of its creator.<ref name=\"Drake-Brockman 2012\"/>\n\n====Islam====\n[[File:Nomad prayer.jpg|thumb|A 1930s photograph of a [[desert]] traveler seeking the assistance of [[Allah]] the Merciful, the Compassionate]]\n\nIn the Muslim tradition, foremost among [[Allah|God's]] [[99 Names of Allah#List of Names|attributes]] are mercy and compassion or, in the canonical language of Arabic, ''Rahman'' and ''Rahim''. Each of the 114 chapters of the [[Quran]], with one exception, begins with the verse, \"In the name of Allah the Compassionate, the Merciful.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/dept/MSA/fundamentals/tawheed/conceptofgod.html |title=University of Southern California |publisher=Usc.edu |date= |accessdate=2014-06-02}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Certainly a Messenger has come to you from among yourselves; grievous to him is your falling into distress, excessively solicitous respecting you; to the believers (he is) compassionate.|[[Qur'an]]|{{quran-usc|9|128}}||}}\n\nThe Arabic word for compassion is ''rahmah''. As a cultural influence, its roots abound in the Quran. A good Muslim is to commence each day, each prayer and each significant action by invoking Allah the Merciful and Compassionate, i.e., by reciting ''Bism-i-llah a-Rahman-i-Rahim''. The [http://vimeo.com/11262742 womb and family ties] are characterized by compassion and named after the exalted attribute of Allah \"Al-Rahim\" (The Compassionate).{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n====Judaism====\nIn the [[Judaism|Jewish tradition]], [[God]] is the Compassionate and is invoked as the Father of Compassion:<ref>Lampert K., ''Traditions of Compassion: From Religious Duty to Social Activism'', Palgrave-Macmillan, 2006; {{ISBN|978-1-4039-8527-9}}</ref> hence ''Ra\u1e25mana'' or Compassionate becomes the usual designation for His revealed word. (Compare, below, the frequent use of ''ra\u1e25man'' in the [[Quran]]).<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=699&letter=C&search=compassion |title=The Jewish Encyclopedia |publisher=The Jewish Encyclopedia |date= |accessdate=2014-06-02}}</ref> Sorrow and pity for one in distress, creating a desire to relieve it, is a feeling ascribed alike to man and God: in [[Biblical Hebrew]], (\"ri\u1e25am,\" from \"re\u1e25em,\" the mother, womb), \"to pity\" or \"to show mercy\" in view of the sufferer's helplessness, hence also \"to forgive\" (Hab. iii. 2), \"to forbear\" (Ex. ii. 6; I Sam. xv. 3; Jer. xv. 15, xxi. 7). The [[Rabbi]]s speak of the \"thirteen attributes of compassion.\" The [[Hebrew Bible|Biblical]] conception of compassion is the feeling of the parent for the child. Hence the prophet's appeal in confirmation of his trust in God invokes the feeling of a mother for her offspring (Isa. xlix. 15).<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nA classic articulation of the Golden Rule (see above) came from the first century [[Hillel the Elder|Rabbi Hillel the Elder]]. Renowned in the Jewish tradition as a sage and a scholar, he is associated with the development of the [[Mishnah]] and the [[Talmud]] and, as such, one of the most important figures in [[Jewish history]]. Asked for a summary of the Jewish religion in the \"while standing on one leg\" meaning in the most concise terms, Hillel stated: \"That which is hateful to you, do not do to your fellow. That is the whole Torah. The rest is the explanation; go and learn.\"<ref>[[Talmud|Babylonian Talmud]], tractate Shabbat 31a. See also the [[ethic of reciprocity]] or \"The [[Ethic of reciprocity|Golden rule]].\"</ref> Post [[9/11]], the words of Rabbi Hillel are frequently quoted in public lectures and interviews around the world by the prominent writer on comparative religion [[Karen Armstrong]].\n\nMany Jewish sources speak of the importance of compassion for animals. Significant rabbis who have done so include Rabbi Samson Raphael Hirsch,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jewishveg.com/schwartz/rabbinic.htm |title=Judaism and Vegetarianism: RABBINIC TEACHINGS ON VEGETARIANISM |publisher=Jewishveg.com |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref> Rabbi Simhah Zissel Ziv,<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/413321|title=Jewish Virtue Ethics and Compassion for Animals: A Model from the Musar Movement|last=Claussen|first=Geoffrey|date=2011|accessdate=2013-09-28|journal=Crosscurrents}}</ref> and Rabbi Moshe Cordovero.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jewishveg.com/DScordovero.html |title=Rav Moshe Cordoero on Compassion for Animals |publisher=JewishVeg |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref>\n\n===Ancient Greek and Roman religion===\nThe ancient Greek and Roman philosophers typically distrusted (feeling) compassion. In the view of many, reason alone was the proper guide to conduct. To some, compassion was an effect, neither admirable nor contemptible. Compassion historically is considered as a passion; [[Justitia]] is blindfolded because her virtue is dispassion and not compassion.<ref>{{cite book|author=[[Thomas Szasz]]|title=Cruel Compassion: Psychiatric Control of Society's Unwanted|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2pduB22E43oC&pg=PA4|year=1998|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=978-0-8156-0510-2}}</ref> In Roman society, in fact, compassion was often seen as a vice when it was inclined toward pity, as opposed to mercy. In other words, showing empathy toward someone who was seen as deserving was considered virtuous, whereas showing empathy to someone deemed unworthy was considered immoral (weak).<ref>{{cite book | title=Gladiators: Violence and Spectacle in Ancient Rome | author=Dunkle, Roger | publisher=Routledge | year=2008 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NdvbAAAAQBAJ | page=18| isbn=9781317905219 }}</ref>\n\n===Confucianism===\n[[Mencius]] maintained that everyone possesses the germ or root of compassion, illustrating his case with the famous example of the child at an open well:\n\n\u201cSuppose a man were, all of a sudden, to see a young child on the verge of falling into a well. He would certainly be moved to compassion, not because he wanted to get into the good graces of the parents, nor because he wished to win the praise of his fellow-villagers or friends, nor yet because he disliked the cry of the child\u201d.<ref>D. C. Lau trans., ''Mencius'' (Penguin 1970)  p. 18 and p. 82</ref>\n\nMencius saw the task of moral cultivation as that of developing the initial impulse of compassion into an enduring quality of [[Ren (Confucianism)|benevolence]].<ref>D. C. Lau trans., ''Mencius'' (Penguin 1970)  p. 22-7</ref>\n\n===Indian religions===\n\n====Buddhism====\n{{Main|Karu\u1e47\u0101|l1=Karu\u1e47\u0101|Brahmavihara|l2=The Four Immeassurables|Metta|l3=Metta|Kayagatasati Sutta|l4=Kayagatasati Sutta|Anapanasati Sutta|l5=Anapanasati Sutta|Satipatthana|l6=Satipatthanas, the four main methods for compassion and release in Buddhism|Parashiva|l7=Parashiva, the soul's destiny in Shaivism}}\n[[File:Liao Dynasty Avalokitesvara Statue Clear.jpeg|thumb|[[Avalokite\u015bvara]] looking out over the sea of suffering. [[China]], [[Liao Dynasty]].]]\n\nThe first of what in English are called the [[Four Noble Truths]] is the truth of [[suffering]] or [[dukkha]] (unsatisfactoriness or stress). [[Dukkha]] is identified as one of the [[Three marks of existence|three distinguishing characteristics]] of all conditioned existence. It arises as a consequence of the failure to adapt to change  or [[anicca]] (the second characteristic) and the insubstantiality, lack of fixed identity, the horrendous lack of certainty of [[anatta]] (the third characteristic) to which all this constant change in turn gives rise. Compassion made possible by observation and accurate perception is the appropriate practical response. The ultimate and earnest wish, manifest in the Buddha, both as archetype and as historical entity, is to relieve the suffering of all living beings everywhere.<ref>HarperCollins  Dictionary of Religion, 1995.</ref>\n\nThe [[Dalai Lama]] has said, \"If you want others to be happy, practice compassion. If you want to be happy, practice compassion.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Twitter \u2013 Dalai Lama|url=https://twitter.com/dalailama/status/576314276228390912|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=24 January 2016}}</ref> The American [[Buddhist monk|monk]] [[Bhikkhu Bodhi]] states that compassion \"supplies the complement to [[metta|loving-kindness]]: whereas loving-kindness has the characteristic of wishing for the [[happiness]] and welfare of others, compassion has the characteristic of wishing that others be free from suffering, a wish to be extended without limits to all living beings. Like [[metta]], compassion arises by entering into the [[subjectivity]] of others, by sharing their interiority in a deep and total way. It springs up by considering that all beings, like ourselves, wish to be free from suffering, yet despite their wishes continue to be harassed by [[Pain and nociception|pain]], [[fear]], [[sorrow (emotion)|sorrow]], and other forms of dukkha.\"<ref>Bhikkhu Bodhi, ''The Noble Eightfold Path: Way to the End of Suffering''. Buddhist Publication Society, 1994, page 39.</ref>\n\n====Hinduism====\n{{Main|Daya (Hinduism)|Karu\u1e47\u0101|Samatva (Equanimity)|The Five Yamas of Yoga|\u0100tman (Hinduism)|Chakra#The seven chakra system|Ahimsa#Hinduism|Mett\u0101|Samadhana}} \n{{See also|Enlightenment (spiritual)#Hinduism|Hospitality|Kama|Samyama}}\n\n[[File:1 Sannyasi in yoga meditation on the Ganges, Rishikesh.jpg|thumb|left|[[Yoga]] aims at physical, mental and spiritual purification, with a compassionate mind and spirit being one of its most important goals.<ref>[[Klaus K. Klostermaier]] (1989), A Survey of Hinduism: First Edition, State University of New York Press, {{ISBN|978-0887068072}}, pp 362\u2013367</ref> Various ''asanas'' and ''mudras'' are combined with meditation and self-reflection exercises to cultivate compassion.<ref>Timothy McCall [http://www.yogajournal.com/for_teachers/2490 Yoga to Cultivate Compassion, Gratitude, and Joy \u2013 Part I] Yoga Journal (2010); see also: Timothy McCall, Yoga as Medicine: The Yogic Prescription for Health and Healing, (Bantam Dell, August 2007)</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Jeste | first1 = D. V. | last2 = Vahia | first2 = I. V. | year = 2008 | title = Comparison of the conceptualization of wisdom in ancient Indian literature with modern views: focus on the Bhagavad Gita | url = | journal = Psychiatry | volume = 71 | issue = 3| pages = 197\u2013202 | doi=10.1521/psyc.2008.71.3.197| pmid = 18834271 | pmc = 2603047 }}</ref>]]\n\nIn classical literature of [[Hinduism]], compassion<ref name=nmgc>Nancy Martin, Brill's Encyclopedia of Hinduism, Editor: Knut Jacobsen (2010), Volume II, Brill, {{ISBN|978-90-04-17893-9}}, see Article on ''Grace and Compassion'', pp 752\u2013757</ref> is a virtue with many shades, each shade explained by different terms. Three most common terms are ''[[Daya (Hinduism)|daya]]'' (\u0926\u092f\u093e),<ref>[http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?tinput=dayA&direction=SE&script=HK&link=yes&beginning= dayA] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112023437/http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?tinput=dayA&direction=SE&script=HK&link=yes&beginning= |date=2016-11-12 }} Sanskrit English Dictionary, Spoken Sanskrit, Germany (2011)</ref> ''[[karu\u1e47\u0101]]'' (\u0915\u0930\u0941\u0923\u093e),<ref>[http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?tinput=karuNA&direction=SE&script=HK&link=yes&beginning= karuNA] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112015253/http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?tinput=karuNA&direction=SE&script=HK&link=yes&beginning= |date=2016-11-12 }} Sanskrit English Dictionary, Spoken Sanskrit, Germany (2011)</ref> and ''[[anukamp\u0101]]'' (\u0905\u0928\u0941\u0915\u092e\u094d\u092a\u093e).<ref>[http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?tinput=anukampA&direction=SE&script=HK&link=yes&beginning= AnukampA] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116090230/http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?tinput=anukampA&direction=SE&script=HK&link=yes&beginning= |date=2017-01-16 }} Sanskrit English Dictionary, Spoken Sanskrit, Germany (2011)</ref> Other words related to compassion in Hinduism include ''karunya'', ''kripa'', and ''anukrosha''.<ref name=abde/><ref>[http://www.sanskrit-lexicon.uni-koeln.de/aequery/index.html Compassion] Apte English Sanskrit Dictionary, University of Koeln, Germany</ref> Some of these words are used interchangeably among the schools of Hinduism to explain the concept of compassion, its sources, its consequences, and its nature. The virtue of compassion to all living beings, claim [[Mahatma Gandhi|Gandhi]] and others,<ref>M.K. Gandhi, Hindu Dharma, {{ISBN|978-8122201086}}, Orient Paperbacks</ref><ref>Tripathi, A., & Mullet, E. (2010), Conceptualizations of forgiveness and forgivingness among Hindus, The International Journal for the Psychology of Religion, 20(4), pp 255\u2013266</ref> is a central concept in Hindu philosophy.<ref name=nmgc/>\n\n''Daya'' is defined by [[Padma Purana]] as the virtuous desire to mitigate the sorrow and difficulties of others by putting forth whatever effort necessary.<ref name=abde/><ref>S. Parmeshwaranand, Encyclopaedic Dictionary of The Dharmasastra, {{ISBN|978-8176253659}}, pp 369\u2013370</ref> Matsya Purana describes ''daya'' as the value that treats all living beings (including human beings) as one's own self, wanting the welfare and good of the other living being.<ref name=abde/><ref>Matsya Purana, 52.8 and 143.31 through 332</ref> Such compassion, claims [[Matsya Purana]], is one of necessary paths to being happy. Ekadashi Tattvam<ref>Ekadashi Tattvam, [[Raghunandana Bhattacharya]], Smriti, Calcutta/London (1816)</ref> explains ''daya'' is treating a stranger, a relative, a friend and a foe as one's own self; it argues that compassion is that state when one sees all living beings as part of one's own self, and when everyone's suffering is seen as one's own suffering. Compassion to all living beings, including to those who are strangers and those who are foes, is seen as a noble virtue.<ref name=abde>Anandita Balslev and Dirk Evers (Editors), Compassion in the World's Religions: Envisioning Human Solidarity (Religionswissenschaft: Forschung und Wissenschaft), {{ISBN|978-3643104762}}, LIT Verlag (2009), see Chapter 4, Compassion: Etymology, Rituals, Anecdotes from the Hindu Tradition</ref> ''Karuna'', another word for compassion in Hindu philosophy, means placing one's mind in other's favor, thereby seeking to understand the other from their perspective. ''Anukampa'', yet another word for compassion, refers to one's state after one has observed and understood the pain and suffering in others.<ref>Mohapatra & Mohapatra (1993), Hinduism: Analytical Study, South Asia Books, {{ISBN|978-8170993889}}</ref><ref>Rye, M. S., Pargament, K. I., Ali, M. A., Beck, G. L., Dorff, E. N., Hallisey, C., ... & Williams, J. G. (2000). Religious perspectives on forgiveness. Forgiveness: Theory, research, and practice, pp 17\u201340</ref> In [[Mahabharata]], Indra praises [[Yudhishthira]] for his ''anukrosha'' \u2014 compassion, sympathy \u2014 for all creatures.<ref>W. Doniger, The Hindus: An Alternative History, Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|978-0199593347}}, page 270</ref> [[Tulsidas]] contrasts ''daya'' (compassion) with ''abhiman'' (arrogance, contempt of others), claiming compassion is a source of ''[[Dharma#Definition and meaning|dharmic]]'' life, while arrogance a source of sin. ''Daya'' (compassion) is not ''kripa'' (pity) in Hinduism, or feeling sorry for the sufferer, because that is marred with condescension; compassion is feeling one with the sufferer.<ref>Pujya Paramtattva Swami, [http://www.cbcew.org.uk/CBCEW-Home/Departments/Dialogue-and-Unity/Other-Religions/Cardinal-Tauran-s-UK-Visit-2013/Hindu-Temple-Visit/Pujya-Paramtattva-Swami Catholics and Hindus: The Practice of Compassion as a Contribution to Peace] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314130215/http://www.cbcew.org.uk/CBCEW-Home/Departments/Dialogue-and-Unity/Other-Religions/Cardinal-Tauran-s-UK-Visit-2013/Hindu-Temple-Visit/Pujya-Paramtattva-Swami |date=2016-03-14 }} The Catholic Church in England and Wales, United Kingdom (June 2013), pp 1\u20133</ref> Compassion is the basis for [[ahimsa]], a core virtue in Hindu philosophy.<ref>Aloysius Michael (1979), Radhakrishnan on Hindu Moral Life and Action, South Asia Books, {{ISBN|978-0836403343}}, pp 67\u201368</ref><ref>Lisa Kemmerer and Anthony Nocella (2011), Call to Compassion, Lantern Books New York, {{ISBN|978-1-59056-182-9}}, pp 31\u201332</ref>\n\nCompassion in Hinduism is discussed as an absolute and relative concept. There are two forms of compassion: one for those who suffer even though they have done nothing wrong and one for those who suffer because they did something wrong. Absolute compassion applies to both, while relative compassion addresses the difference between the former and the latter. An example of the latter include those who plead guilty or are convicted of a crime such as murder; in these cases, the virtue of compassion must be balanced with the virtue of justice.<ref name=abde/>\n\nThe classical literature of Hinduism exists in many Indian languages. For example, ''[[Tirukku\u1e5ba\u1e37]],'' written between 200 BC and AD 400, and sometimes called the Tamil [[Veda]], is a cherished classic on Hinduism written in a South Indian language. It dedicates Chapter 25 of Book 1 to compassion,<ref>[http://ebooks.gutenberg.us/HimalayanAcademy/SacredHinduLiterature/weaver/content.htm Tirukku\u1e5ba\u1e37] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216064046/http://ebooks.gutenberg.us/HimalayanAcademy/SacredHinduLiterature/weaver/content.htm |date=December 16, 2014 }} verses 241\u2013250</ref> further dedicating separate chapters each for the resulting values of compassion, chiefly, [[vegetarianism]] or [[veganism]] (Chapter 26), [[non-violence|doing no harm]] (Chapter 32), [[non-killing]] (Chapter 33), possession of [[kindness]] (Chapter 8), dreading evil deeds (Chapter 21), [[benignity]] (Chapter 58), the right [[scepter]] (Chapter 55), and absence of [[terrorism]] (Chapter 57), to name a few.<ref>{{cite book | last = Pope | first = George Uglow | author-link = | title = The Sacred Kurral of Tiruvalluva Nayanar | publisher = Asian Educational Services | series = | volume = | edition = First | date = 1886 | location = New Delhi | pages = | language = | url = http://www.projectmadurai.org/pm_etexts/pdf/pm0153.pdf | doi = | id = | isbn = 8120600223 | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref>\n\n====Jainism====\n{{further|Ahimsa in Jainism}}\nCompassion for all life, human and non-human, is central to the [[Jainism|Jain]] tradition. Though all life is considered sacred, human life is deemed the highest form of earthly existence. To kill any person, no matter their crime, is considered unimaginably abhorrent. It is the only substantial religious tradition that requires both monks and laity to be vegetarian. It is suggested that certain strains of the [[Hinduism|Hindu tradition]] became vegetarian due to strong Jain influences.<ref>South India Handbook: The Travel Guide By Robert Bradnock, 2000 Footprint Travel Guides, p. 543, Vegetarianism: A History By Colin Spencer, 2002 Thunder's Mouth Press, p. 342</ref> The Jain tradition's stance on [[ahimsa|nonviolence]], however, goes far beyond [[vegetarianism]]. Jains refuse food obtained with unnecessary cruelty. Many practice [[veganism]].  Jains run animal shelters all over India. The [[Lal Mandir]], a prominent Jain temple in Delhi, is known for the Jain Birds Hospital in a second building behind the main temple.<ref>{{cite web|author=Powell Ettinger |url=http://www.wildlifeextra.com/go/world/bird-hospital.html#cr |title=Jainism and the legendary Delhi bird hospital |publisher=Wildlifeextra.com |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ja7iTij7Bc0C&pg=PT81&dq=birds+hospital+in+delhi#v=onepage&q=birds%20hospital%20in%20delhi&f=false |title=Top 10 Delhi \u2013 Dorling Kindersley \u2013 Google Books |accessdate=2013-09-28|isbn=9780756695637 |date=2012-11-01 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=18em|\n* [[Agape]], [[Philia]], [[Philautia]], [[Storge (familial love)|Storge]], [[Eros (concept)|Eros]]: Greek terms for [[Greek words for love|love]]\n* [[Brahmavihara]]\n* [[Brotherly love (philosophy)|Brotherly love]]\n* [[Charter for Compassion]]\n* [[Christian humanism]]\n* [[Compassion fatigue]]\n* [[Charity (virtue)]]\n* [[Caregiving]]\n* [[Daya Mata]]\n* [[Empathic concern]]\n* [[Fake compassion]]\n* [[Humanism]]\n* [[Karu\u1e47\u0101|Karuna]]\n* [[Moral emotions]]\n* [[Moral psychology]]\n* [[Pity]]\n* [[Radical compassion]]\n* [[Role-taking theory]]\n* [[Self-compassion]]\n* [[Shabad (hymn)]]\n* [[Social emotions]]\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n{{Commons category|Compassion}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.ted.com/index.php/talks/karen_armstrong_makes_her_ted_prize_wish_the_charter_for_compassion.html TED Prize winner Karen Armstrong's video lecture on compassion]\n* [http://magazine.uchicago.edu/0604/features/emotion.shtml ''Mirrored emotion''] [[Jean Decety]], [[University of Chicago]]\n*''[http://bigthink.com/philip-perry/compassion-is-weaved-throughout-our-nervous-system-researchers-have-found Compassion Is Weaved Throughout Our Nervous System, Researchers Have Found]'' (December 2016). Discusses some of the work of [[Dacher Keltner]] as well as other researchers\n* [http://www.ted.com/talks/view/id/200 Daniel Goleman, psychologist & author of ''Emotional Intelligence'', video lecture on compassion]\n* [http://webcast.rice.edu/index.php?action=details&event=966 Dalai Lama on compassion, Rice University, May 2007.]\n* [http://www.ted.com/index.php/talks/bob_thurman_says_we_can_be_buddhas.html Professor Robert Thurman: ''Compassion is feeling the feelings of others'']\n\n{{emotion-footer}}\n\n[[Category:Emotions]]\n[[Category:Kindness]]\n[[Category:Giving]]\n[[Category:Suffering]]\n[[Category:Virtue]]\n[[Category:Religious ethics]]\n[[Category:Relational ethics]]\n[[Category:Hindu ethics]]\n[[Category:Buddhist ethics]]\n[[Category:Moral psychology]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Moved or motivated to help others}}\n{{other uses|Compassion (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:There's no crying in baseball! (4549295140) 2.jpg|alt=|thumb|One child showing compassion for another child.]]\n'''Compassion''' motivates people to go out of their way to help the physical, mental, or emotional pains of another and themselves. Compassion is often regarded as having sensitivity, an emotional aspect to suffering, though when based on cerebral notions such as fairness, justice, and interdependence, it may be considered rational in nature and its application understood as an activity also based on sound judgment. There is also an aspect of equal dimension, such that an individual's compassion is often given a property of \"depth\", \"vigor\", or \"[[passion (emotion)|passion]]\". The etymology of \"compassion\" is Latin, meaning \"co-suffering.\" Compassion involves \"feeling for another\" and is a precursor to [[empathy]], the \"feeling as another\" capacity for better person-centered acts of active compassion; in common parlance active compassion is the [[desire (emotion)|desire]] to alleviate another's suffering.<ref name=\"sjsl\">Sherlyn Jimenez, see article on ''Compassion'', The Encyclopedia of Positive Psychology, Volume I, Editor: Shane Lopez, Wiley-Blackwell, {{ISBN|978-1-4051-6125-1}}</ref>\n\nCompassion involves allowing ourselves to be moved by suffering and experiencing the motivation to help alleviate and prevent it. An act of compassion is defined by its [[helpfulness]]. Qualities of compassion are patience and wisdom; kindness and perseverance; warmth and resolve. It is often, though not inevitably, the key component in what manifests in the social context as [[altruism]]. Expression of compassion is prone to be hierarchical, paternalistic and controlling in responses.<ref name=\"Gilbert2010\"/> Difference between sympathy and compassion is that the former responds to suffering from sorrow and concern while the latter responds with warmth and care.<ref name=\"CompInteg\"/>\n\nThe English [[noun]] ''compassion'', meaning ''to suffer together with'', comes from [[Latin]]. Its [[prefix]] ''com-'' comes directly from ''com'', an archaic version of the Latin [[preposition]] and affix [[wikt:cum|cum]] (= with); the ''-passion'' segment is derived from ''passus'', [[past participle]] of the [[deponent verb]] [[wikt:patior|patior, pat\u012b, passus sum]]. Compassion is thus related in origin, form and meaning to the English noun [[patient]] (= one who suffers), from ''patiens'', [[present participle]] of the same [[wikt:patior|patior]], and is akin to the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] verb \u03c0\u03ac\u03c3\u03c7\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd (= ''paskhein'', to suffer) and to its [[cognate]] noun [[wikt:\u03c0\u03ac\u03b8\u03bf\u03c2|\u03c0\u03ac\u03b8\u03bf\u03c2]] (= [[pathos]]).<ref name=\"newSOED\">{{cite book |author=Brown, Lesley |title=The New shorter Oxford English dictionary on historical principles |publisher=Clarendon |location=Oxford [Eng.] |year=2002 |pages= |isbn=978-0-19-861271-1 |oclc= |doi= |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/newshorteroxford00lesl }}</ref><ref name=\"Partridge\">{{cite book |author=Partridge, Eric |title=Origins: a short etymological dictionary of modern English |publisher=Macmillan |location=New York |year=1966 |pages= |isbn=978-0-02-594840-2 |oclc= |doi=}}</ref> Ranked a great virtue in numerous [[philosophy|philosophies]], compassion is considered in almost all the major [[religion|religious traditions]] as among the greatest of [[virtue]]s.\n\n== Theories ==\nTheoretical perspectives of compassion have been developed through the years, the following three proposed perspectives show contrasts in their evolution and approaches to compassion.\n:* Compassion is simply a variation of love or sadness, not a distinct emotion.<ref name=\"Shaver et. al: Emotion Knowledge\">{{cite journal|last=Shaver|first=P|author2=J Schwartz |author3=D Kirson |author4=C O'Connor |title=Emotion knowledge: further exploration of a prototype approach|journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|date=June 1987|volume=52|issue=6|pages=1061\u20131086|doi=10.1037/0022-3514.52.6.1061 |pmid=3598857}}</ref>\n:* From the perspective of evolutionary psychology, compassion can be viewed as a distinct emotional state, which can be differentiated from distress, [[sadness]], and [[love]].<ref name=\"Bowlby: Attach and loss vol. 1\">{{cite book|last=Bowlby|first=John|title=Attachment: Attachment and Loss Volume One|year=1983|publisher=Basic Books|location=New York, NY}}</ref><ref name=\"The Moral Emotions: Haidt\">{{cite book|last=Haidt|first=Jonathan|title=The Moral Emotions|year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|pages=852\u2013870}}</ref><ref name=\"Social Functionalism and the Evolution of Emotions: Keltner et al\">{{cite book|last=Keltner|first=Dacher|title=Social Functionalism and the Evolution of Emotions|year=2006|publisher=Psychology Press|location=New York|pages=115\u2013142|author2=Jonathan Haidt |author3=Michelle Shiota}}</ref>\n:* Compassion as a synonym of empathic distress, which is characterized by the feeling of distress in connection with another person's suffering.<ref name=\"Compassion: An Evolutionary Analysis and Empirical Review\">{{cite journal|last=Goetz|first=Jennifer|author2=Dacher Kelter |author3=Emiliana Simon-Thomas |title=Compassion: An Evolutionary Analysis and Empirical Review|journal=Psychological Bulletin|year=2010|volume=136|issue=3|pages=351\u2013374|doi=10.1037/a0018807|pmid=20438142|pmc=2864937}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ekman|first=Paul|title=Emotions Revealed: Recognizing Faces and Feelings to improve communication and emotional life|year=2003|publisher=Henry Holt & Company|location=New York, NY}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Hoffman|first=Martin|title=Is altruism part of human nature?|journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|year=1981|volume=40|issue=1|pages=121\u2013137|doi=10.1037/0022-3514.40.1.121}}</ref> This perspective of compassion is based on the finding that people sometimes emulate and feel the emotions of people around them.<ref name=\"Hatfield, 1993: Emotional Contagion\">{{cite journal|last=Hatfield|first=Elaine|author2=John Cacioppo|title=Emotional Contagion|journal=Current Directions in Psychological Science|year=1993|volume=2|issue=3|pages=96\u201399|doi=10.1111/1467-8721.ep10770953|last3=Rapson|first3=Richard L.}}</ref>\n\nThe more one person knows about the human condition and the associated experiences, the more vivid the route to identification with suffering becomes.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\">{{cite book|last=Cassell|first=Eric|title=Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology|year=2009|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York, New York|isbn=978-0-19-518724-3|pages=393\u2013403|edition=2}}</ref> Identifying with another person is an essential process for human beings, it is commonly seen throughout the world as people adapt and change with new styles of clothing, language, behavior, etc., which is even illustrated by infants who begin to mirror the facial expressions and body movements of their mother as early as the first days of their lives.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Meltzoff|first=Andrew|title=The Roots of Social and Cognitive Development: Models of Man's Original Nature|journal=Social Perception in Infants|year=1985|pages=1\u201330}}</ref> [[Personality psychology]] agrees that people are inherently different and distinct from one another, which leads to the conclusion that human suffering is always individual and unique. Suffering can result from psychological, social, and physical trauma<ref name=\"cassell1995\">{{cite book|last=Cassell|first=Eric|title=The Healer's Art|year=1995|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-53062-0}}</ref> and it happens in acute forms as often as chronically.<ref name=\"cassell1995\"/> Due to the inherent differences in people's personalities some may define their early stages of suffering to their external circumstances and those life events being quiet or not discussed. The later stages may involve the person expressing their [[victimization]] and searching for help.<ref name=\"Models of Point Suffering\">{{cite book|last=Reich|first=Warren|title=Models of Point Suffering: Foundations for an Ethic Compassion |year=1987|volume=38|pages=117\u2013122|doi=10.1007/978-3-7091-6975-9_20|series=Acta Neurochirurgica Supplementum|isbn=978-3-7091-7457-9}}</ref> [[Suffering]] has been defined as the perception of a person's impending destruction or loss of integrity, which continues until the threat is vanished or the person's integrity can be restored.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> The importance of identifying with others for compassion is contrasted by the negative physical and psychological effects of [[Abandonment (emotional)|abandonment]]. Compassion is often a characteristic element of democratic societies.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> Compassion is recognized through identifying with other people, the knowledge of human behavior, the perception of suffering, transfer of feelings, knowledge of goal and purpose changes in sufferers, and leads to the absence of the suffering from the group.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" />\n\nThe compassion process is highly related to identifying with the other person because sympathizing with others is possible among people from other countries, cultures, locations, etc. A possible source of this process of identifying with others comes from a universal category called \"Spirit.\" Toward the late 1970s, very different cultures and nations around the world took a turn to [[religious fundamentalism]], which has occasionally been attributed to \"Spirit\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Hegal|first=Georg|title=Phenomenology of Spirit|year=1952|publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-824597-1}}</ref> The role of compassion as a factor contributing to individual or societal behavior has been the topic of continuous debate.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brown|first=Lee |title=Compassion and Societal Well-Being|journal=Pacific Philosophical Quarterly|date=1 January 1996}}</ref> In contrast to the process of identifying with other people, a complete absence of compassion may require ignoring or disapproving identification with other people or groups.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> Earlier studies established the links between interpersonal violence and cruelty which leads to indifference.<ref>Frank R. Ascione, Phil Arkow Child abuse, domestic violence, and animal abuse: linking the circles of compassion for prevention and intervention {{ISBN|1-55753-142-0}}</ref><ref>Randall Lockwood, Frank R. Ascione. Cruelty to Animals and Interpersonal Violence. Purdue University Press, 1998</ref> This concept has been illustrated throughout history: [[The Holocaust]], [[Genocide]], [[European colonization of the Americas]], etc. The seemingly essential step in these atrocities could be the definition of the victims as \"not human\" or \"not us.\" The atrocities committed throughout human history have only been relieved, minimized, or overcome it's damaging effects through the presence of compassion.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=MacIntyre|first=Alisdair|title=A Short History of Ethics|year=1966|publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul|isbn=978-0-203-13112-1}}</ref>\n\nCompassion may have the ability to induce feelings of kindness and [[forgiveness]], which could give people the ability to stop situations that have the potential to be distressing and occasionally lead to violence.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Goetz|first=J|author2=D Keltner |author3=E Simon-Thomas  |title=Compassion: An evolutionary analysis and empirical review|journal=Psychological Bulletin|year=2010 |volume=136|issue=3|pages=351\u2013374|doi=10.1037/a0018807|pmid=20438142 |pmc=2864937}}</ref>\n\n=== Psychology ===\nCompassion has become associated with and researched in the fields of [[positive psychology]] and social psychology.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jazaieri|first=Hooria|last2=Jinpa|first2=Geshe Thupten|last3=McGonigal|first3=Kelly|last4=Rosenberg|first4=Erika L.|last5=Finkelstein|first5=Joel|last6=Simon-Thomas|first6=Emiliana|last7=Cullen|first7=Margaret|last8=Doty|first8=James R.|last9=Gross|first9=James J.|date=2012-07-25|title=Enhancing Compassion: A Randomized Controlled Trial of a Compassion Cultivation Training Program|journal=Journal of Happiness Studies|language=en|volume=14|issue=4|pages=1113\u20131126|doi=10.1007/s10902-012-9373-z|issn=1389-4978|citeseerx=10.1.1.362.5161}}</ref> The [[Dalai Lama]] once said that \"compassion is a necessity, not a luxury\"<ref name=\"CompInteg\">{{cite book|author1=Reddy, Nanda Kishore|author2=Ajmera, Santosh|title=Ethics, Integrity and Aptitude|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YLlyCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA146|publisher=McGraw-Hill Education|isbn=978-93-5134-236-6|page=146}}</ref> and that \"it is a question of human survival\".<ref name=\"Lama1990\">{{cite book|author=H.H. the Fourteenth Dalai Lama|title=Policy of Kindness: An Anthology of Writings by and about the Dalai Lama|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_GZ4LRsqEegC&pg=PA112|year=1990|publisher=Shambhala|isbn=978-1-55939-769-8|page=112}}</ref> Compassion is a process of connecting by identifying with another person. This identification with others through compassion can lead to increased motivation to do something in an effort to relieve the suffering of others.\n\nCompassion is an evolved function from the harmony of a three grid internal system: contentment-and-peace system, goals-and-drives system and threat-and-safety system. Paul Gilbert defines these collectively as necessary regulated systems for compassion.<ref name=\"Gilbert2010\">{{cite book|author=Paul Gilbert|title=The Compassionate Mind: A New Approach to Life's Challenges|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=krNPL6xCVL0C|year=2010|publisher=New Harbinger Publications|isbn=978-1-57224-840-3}}</ref> In examination of the motivated regulation of compassion in the context of large-scale crises, such as natural disasters and genocides, much research has established that people tend to feel more compassion for single identifiable victims than large masses of victims (the [[Identifiable victim effect]]). It is found that people only show less compassion for many victims than for single victims of disasters when they expect to incur a financial cost upon helping. This [[collapse of compassion]] depends on having the motivation and ability to regulate emotions.<ref>Cameron & Payne, 2011, JPSP</ref> In laboratory research, psychologists are exploring how concerns about becoming emotionally exhausted may motivate people to curb their compassion for\u2014and dehumanize\u2014members of stigmatized social groups, such as homeless individuals and drug addicts.<ref>Cameron, Harris, & Payne, in prep</ref>\n\nCompassion consists of three major requirements: People must feel that troubles that evoke their feelings are serious, the understanding that sufferers' troubles are not self-inflicted, and ability to picture oneself with the same problems in a non-blaming and non-shaming manner.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" />\n\n===Neurobiology===\n{{Globalize|section|date=October 2019}}\nJorge Moll and Jordan Grafman, [[neuroscientists]] at the [[National Institutes of Health]] and LABS-D'Or Hospital Network (J.M.) provided the first evidence for the neural bases of altruistic giving in normal healthy volunteers, using [[functional magnetic resonance imaging]]. In their research, published in the [[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences]] USA in October 2006,<ref>Human fronto\u2013mesolimbic networks guide decisions about charitable donation, PNAS 2006:103(42);15623\u201315628</ref> they showed that both pure monetary rewards and charitable donations activated the [[Mesolimbic pathway|mesolimbic]] reward pathway, a primitive part of the brain that usually responds to food and sex. However, when volunteers generously placed the interests of others before their own by making charitable donations, another brain circuit was selectively activated: the subgenual cortex/[[septal region]]. These structures are intimately related to social attachment and bonding in other species. Altruism, the experiment suggested, was not a superior moral faculty that suppresses basic selfish urges but rather was basic to the brain, hard-wired and pleasurable.<ref name=\"brain\">{{cite news\n|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/27/AR2007052701056.html\n|title=If It Feels Good to Be Good, It Might Be Only Natural\n|publisher=Washington Post\n|date=May 2007\n|first=Shankar\n|last=Vedantam\n|accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref> One brain region, the subgenual [[anterior cingulate]] cortex/[[basal forebrain]], contributes to learning altruistic behavior, especially in those with trait empathy.<ref name=PMID_27528669>{{ cite journal |last1 = Lockwood |first1 = Patricia L |last2 = Apps |first2 = Matthew A J |last3 = Valton |first3 = Vincent |last4 = Viding |first4 = Essi |last5 = Roiser |first5 = Jonathan P |year = 2016 |title = Neurocomputational mechanisms of prosocial learning and links to empathy. |journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America |quote = . fMRI revealed that activity in a posterior portion of the subgenual anterior cingulate cortex/basal forebrain (sgACC) drives learning only when we are acting in a prosocial context |lay-url = http://neurosciencenews.com/generosity-empathy-neuroscience-4850/ |pmid = 27528669 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1603198113 |volume=113 |issue = 35 |pages=9763\u20138|pmc = 5024617 }}</ref> The same study has shown a connection between giving to charity and the promotion of social bonding.<ref name=\"neurons\">{{cite news\n|url=https://generosityresearch.nd.edu/news/hard-wired-for-giving/\n|title=Scientists Are Finding That We Are Hard-Wired for Giving\n|publisher=University of Notre Dame\n|date=September 5, 2013\n|first=Elizabeth\n|last=Svoboda\n|accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn fact, in an experiment published in March 2007 at the [[University of Southern California]] neuroscientist [[Antonio R. Damasio]] and his colleagues showed that subjects with damage to the [[ventromedial prefrontal cortex]] lack the ability to feel their way empathically to moral answers, and that when confronted with moral dilemmas, these brain-damaged patients coldly came up with \"end-justifies-the-means\" answers, leading Damasio to conclude that the point was not that they reached immoral conclusions, but that when they were confronted by a difficult issue \u2014 in this case as whether to shoot down a passenger plane hijacked by terrorists before it hits a major city \u2014 these patients appear to reach decisions without the anguish that afflicts those with normally functioning brains. According to [[Adrian Raine]], a clinical neuroscientist also at the University of Southern California, one of this study's implications is that society may have to rethink how it judges immoral people: \"Psychopaths often feel no empathy or remorse. Without that awareness, people relying exclusively on reasoning seem to find it harder to sort their way through moral thickets. Does that mean they should be held to different standards of accountability?\"<ref name=\"brain\"/>\n\nIn another study, in the 1990s, Dr. Bill Harbaugh, a [[University of Oregon]] economist, concluded people are motivated to give for reasons of personal prestige and in a similar fMRI scanner test in 2007 with his psychologist colleague Dr. Ulrich Mayr, reached the same conclusions of Jorge Moll and Jordan Grafman about giving to charity, although they were able to divide the study group into two groups: \"egoists\" and \"altruists\". One of their discoveries was that, though rarely, even some of the considered \"egoists\" sometimes gave more than expected because that would help others, leading to the conclusion that there are other factors in cause in charity, such as a person's environment and values.<ref name=\"neurons\"/>\n\n=== Medicine ===\nCompassion is one of the most important attributes for physicians practicing medical services.<ref>{{cite book|title=Principles of Medical Ethics|year=1981|publisher=American Medical Association|location=Chicago}}</ref> It has been suggested that felt compassion brings about the desire to do something to help the sufferer.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> That desire to be helpful is not compassion, but it does suggest that compassion is similar to other emotions by motivating behaviors to reduce the tension brought on by the emotion.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> Physicians generally identify their central duties as the responsibility to put the patient's interests first, including the duty not to harm, deliver proper care, and maintain confidentiality.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> Compassion is seen in each of those duties because of its direct relation to the recognition and treatment of suffering.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> Physicians who use compassion understand the effects of sickness and suffering on human behavior.<ref>{{cite book|last=Cassell|first=Eric|title=The Nature of Suffering|year=1985|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York}}</ref> Compassion may be closely related to love and the emotions evoked in both. This is illustrated by the relationship between patients and physicians in medical institutions.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook of Positive Psychology\" /> The relationship between suffering patients and their caregivers provides evidence that compassion is a social emotion, which is highly related to the closeness between individuals.\n\n=== Compassion fatigue ===\n{{Further|Compassion fatigue}}\nAccording to Figley, individuals with a higher capacity or responsibility to empathize with others may be at risk for \"compassion fatigue\" or stress, which is related to professionals and individuals who spend a significant amount of time responding to information related to suffering.<ref name=\"Compassion Fatigue: Figley\">{{cite book |last=Figley |first=Charles|title=Compassion Fatigue: Coping With Secondary Traumatic Stress Disorder In Those Who Treat The Traumatized|year=1995|publisher=Brunner-Routledge|location=London|isbn=978-0876307595}}</ref> However, newer research by [[Tania Singer|Singer]] and [[Matthieu Ricard|Ricard]] suggests that it is lack of suitable [[distress tolerance]] which gets people fatigued in compassion activities.<ref name=\"Altruism: Ricard\">{{cite book |last=Ricard |first=Matthieu|title=Altruism: The Power of Compassion to Change Yourself and the World|chapter=IV|chapter-url=http://info-buddhism.com/Empathy-Compassion-Neuroscience-Ricard-Altruism.html|pages=56\u201364|year=2015|publisher=Brown and Company|isbn=978-0316208246}}</ref> Research suggests that practice of nonjudgmental compassion can prevent fatigue and [[Occupational burnout|burnout]].<ref>[http://www.matthieuricard.org/system/resources/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMDYvMDQvMTBfMjNfNDNfNjIxX0tsaW1lY2tpX0xlaWJlcmdfUmljYXJkX1Npbmdlcl8yMDEzX1NDQU4ucGRmIl1d/Klimecki_Leiberg_Ricard_Singer_2013_SCAN.pdf Differential pattern of functional brain plasticity after compassion and empathy training], Olga M. Klimecki, Susanne Leiberg, Matthieu Ricard, and Tania Singer, Department of Social Neuroscience, Max Planck Institute for Human Cognitive and Brain Sciences</ref>\n\n=== Self-compassion ===\n{{Further|Self-compassion}}\nSelf-compassion is a process of self kindness and accepting suffering as a quality of being human. It has positive effects on subjective [[happiness]], [[optimism]], [[wisdom]], [[curiosity]], [[agreeableness]], and [[extroversion]].<ref name=\"Emotional effects of compassion - NeV\">{{cite journal|last=NeV|first=Kristen|author2=Stephanie Rude |author3=Kristin Kirpatrick |title=An examination of self-compassion in relation to positive psychological functioning and personality traits|journal=Journal of Research in Psychology|year=2007|volume=41|issue=4|pages=908\u2013916|doi=10.1016/j.jrp.2006.08.002}}</ref> [[Kristin Neff]] and Christopher Germer have identified that there are three levels of activities that thwart self-compassion and they are self-criticism, self-isolation and self-absorption, they equate this to fight, flight and freeze responses.<ref>http://self-compassion.org/wp-content/uploads/publications/germer.neff.pdf</ref><ref>https://chrisgermer.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Transforming-Trauma.pdf</ref> It is identified that people who lack of life skill equanimity that is akin with distress tolerance are prone to such spontaneous responses. Certain activities may increase feelings of and readiness to practice self-compassion; some of these activities include creating a loving-kindness rituals, practicing empathy, practice random acts of warmth and goodwill like [[tonglen]], etc.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nFor increasing compassion in the workplace to self and others, ''authentic leadership'' centered on humanism and nourishing quality interconnectedness are considered as the key.<ref name=\"Compassion in the workplace\">{{cite journal|last=Peus|first=Claudia|title=Money over man versus caring and compassion? Challenges for today's organizations and their leaders|journal=Journal of Organizational Behavior|date=15 April 2011|volume=32|issue=7|pages=955\u2013960|doi=10.1002/job.751}}</ref> [[Judith V. Jordan|Judith Jordan]]'s concept of ''self-empathy'' is similar to self-compassion, it implies the capacity to notice, care and respond towards the ones own felt needs. The strategies of self-care involve valuing oneself, thinking about one's ideations of needs compassionately, and connecting with others in order to conversely experience renewal, support, and validation. Research indicates that self-compassionate individuals experience greater [[psychological health]] than those who lack self-compassion.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1037/0022-3514.92.5.887|pmid = 17484611|title = Self-compassion and reactions to unpleasant self-relevant events: The implications of treating oneself kindly|journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume = 92|issue = 5|pages = 887\u2013904|year = 2007|last1 = Leary|first1 = Mark R.|last2 = Tate|first2 = Eleanor B.|last3 = Adams|first3 = Claire E.|last4 = Batts Allen|first4 = Ashley|last5 = Hancock|first5 = Jessica}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.jrp.2006.08.002 | last1 = Neff | first1 = K. D. | last2 = Rude | first2 = S. S. | last3 = Kirkpatrick | first3 = K. | year = 2007 | title = An examination of self-compassion in relation to positive psychological functioning and personality traits | url = | journal = Journal of Research in Personality | volume = 41 | issue = 4| pages = 908\u2013916 }}</ref>\n\n== Historical and spiritual-religious views ==\n===Abrahamic religions===\n\n====Christianity====\n[[File:G. Conti La parabola del Buon Samaritano Messina Chiesa della Medaglia Miracolosa Casa di Ospitalit\u00e0 Collereale.jpg|thumb|Compassion in action: an 18th-century Italian depiction of the Parable of the [[Good Samaritan]]]]\n\nThe Christian [[Bible]]'s [[Second Epistle to the Corinthians]] is but one place where God is spoken of as the \"Father of compassion\" and the \"God of all comfort.\" It reads as follows: 2 Corinthians 1:3\u20137 \"Praise be to the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, the Father of compassion and the God of all comfort, who comforts us in all our troubles, so that we can comfort those in any trouble with the comfort we ourselves received from God. For just as the sufferings of Christ flow over into our lives, so also through Christ our comfort overflows. If we are distressed, it is for your comfort and salvation; if we are comforted, it is for your comfort, which produces in you patient endurance of the same sufferings we suffer. And our hope for you is firm, because we know that just as you share in our sufferings, so also you share in our comfort.\" [[Jesus]] embodies for [[Christians]], the very essence of compassion and relational care. Christ challenges Christians to forsake their own desires and to act compassionately towards others, particularly those in need or distress.<ref>Lampert Khen (2006), Ch. 1</ref>{{Full citation needed|date=October 2019}} Most significantly, he demonstrated compassion to those his society had condemned \u2013 tax collectors, prostitutes and criminals, by saying \"just because you received a loaf of bread, does not mean you were more conscientious about it, or more caring about your fellow man.\"<ref name=\"Drake-Brockman 2012\">{{cite book|last=Drake-Brockman|first=Tom|title=Christian Humanism: the compassionate theology of a Jew called Jesus|year=2012|publisher=Denis Jones and associates|location=Sydney|isbn=9780646530390}}</ref>\n\nConversely, a 2012 study of the [[historical Jesus]] has claimed that the founder of Christianity sought to elevate Judaic compassion as the supreme human virtue, capable of reducing suffering and fulfilling our God-ordained purpose of transforming the world into something more worthy of its creator.<ref name=\"Drake-Brockman 2012\"/>\n\n====Islam====\n[[File:Nomad prayer.jpg|thumb|A 1930s photograph of a [[desert]] traveler seeking the assistance of [[Allah]] the Merciful, the Compassionate]]\n\nIn the Muslim tradition, foremost among [[Allah|God's]] [[99 Names of Allah#List of Names|attributes]] are mercy and compassion or, in the canonical language of Arabic, ''Rahman'' and ''Rahim''. Each of the 114 chapters of the [[Quran]], with one exception, begins with the verse, \"In the name of Allah the Compassionate, the Merciful.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/dept/MSA/fundamentals/tawheed/conceptofgod.html |title=University of Southern California |publisher=Usc.edu |date= |accessdate=2014-06-02}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Certainly a Messenger has come to you from among yourselves; grievous to him is your falling into distress, excessively solicitous respecting you; to the believers (he is) compassionate.|[[Qur'an]]|{{quran-usc|9|128}}||}}\n\nThe Arabic word for compassion is ''rahmah''. As a cultural influence, its roots abound in the Quran. A good Muslim is to commence each day, each prayer and each significant action by invoking Allah the Merciful and Compassionate, i.e., by reciting ''Bism-i-llah a-Rahman-i-Rahim''. The [http://vimeo.com/11262742 womb and family ties] are characterized by compassion and named after the exalted attribute of Allah \"Al-Rahim\" (The Compassionate).{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n====Judaism====\nIn the [[Judaism|Jewish tradition]], [[God]] is the Compassionate and is invoked as the Father of Compassion:<ref>Lampert K., ''Traditions of Compassion: From Religious Duty to Social Activism'', Palgrave-Macmillan, 2006; {{ISBN|978-1-4039-8527-9}}</ref> hence ''Ra\u1e25mana'' or Compassionate becomes the usual designation for His revealed word. (Compare, below, the frequent use of ''ra\u1e25man'' in the [[Quran]]).<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=699&letter=C&search=compassion |title=The Jewish Encyclopedia |publisher=The Jewish Encyclopedia |date= |accessdate=2014-06-02}}</ref> Sorrow and pity for one in distress, creating a desire to relieve it, is a feeling ascribed alike to man and God: in [[Biblical Hebrew]], (\"ri\u1e25am,\" from \"re\u1e25em,\" the mother, womb), \"to pity\" or \"to show mercy\" in view of the sufferer's helplessness, hence also \"to forgive\" (Hab. iii. 2), \"to forbear\" (Ex. ii. 6; I Sam. xv. 3; Jer. xv. 15, xxi. 7). The [[Rabbi]]s speak of the \"thirteen attributes of compassion.\" The [[Hebrew Bible|Biblical]] conception of compassion is the feeling of the parent for the child. Hence the prophet's appeal in confirmation of his trust in God invokes the feeling of a mother for her offspring (Isa. xlix. 15).<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nA classic articulation of the Golden Rule (see above) came from the first century [[Hillel the Elder|Rabbi Hillel the Elder]]. Renowned in the Jewish tradition as a sage and a scholar, he is associated with the development of the [[Mishnah]] and the [[Talmud]] and, as such, one of the most important figures in [[Jewish history]]. Asked for a summary of the Jewish religion in the \"while standing on one leg\" meaning in the most concise terms, Hillel stated: \"That which is hateful to you, do not do to your fellow. That is the whole Torah. The rest is the explanation; go and learn.\"<ref>[[Talmud|Babylonian Talmud]], tractate Shabbat 31a. See also the [[ethic of reciprocity]] or \"The [[Ethic of reciprocity|Golden rule]].\"</ref> Post [[9/11]], the words of Rabbi Hillel are frequently quoted in public lectures and interviews around the world by the prominent writer on comparative religion [[Karen Armstrong]].\n\nMany Jewish sources speak of the importance of compassion for animals. Significant rabbis who have done so include Rabbi Samson Raphael Hirsch,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jewishveg.com/schwartz/rabbinic.htm |title=Judaism and Vegetarianism: RABBINIC TEACHINGS ON VEGETARIANISM |publisher=Jewishveg.com |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref> Rabbi Simhah Zissel Ziv,<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/413321|title=Jewish Virtue Ethics and Compassion for Animals: A Model from the Musar Movement|last=Claussen|first=Geoffrey|date=2011|accessdate=2013-09-28|journal=Crosscurrents}}</ref> and Rabbi Moshe Cordovero.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jewishveg.com/DScordovero.html |title=Rav Moshe Cordoero on Compassion for Animals |publisher=JewishVeg |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref>\n\n===Ancient Greek and Roman religion===\nThe ancient Greek and Roman philosophers typically distrusted (feeling) compassion. In the view of many, reason alone was the proper guide to conduct. To some, compassion was an effect, neither admirable nor contemptible. Compassion historically is considered as a passion; [[Justitia]] is blindfolded because her virtue is dispassion and not compassion.<ref>{{cite book|author=[[Thomas Szasz]]|title=Cruel Compassion: Psychiatric Control of Society's Unwanted|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2pduB22E43oC&pg=PA4|year=1998|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=978-0-8156-0510-2}}</ref> In Roman society, in fact, compassion was often seen as a vice when it was inclined toward pity, as opposed to mercy. In other words, showing empathy toward someone who was seen as deserving was considered virtuous, whereas showing empathy to someone deemed unworthy was considered immoral (weak).<ref>{{cite book | title=Gladiators: Violence and Spectacle in Ancient Rome | author=Dunkle, Roger | publisher=Routledge | year=2008 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NdvbAAAAQBAJ | page=18| isbn=9781317905219 }}</ref>\n\n===Confucianism===\n[[Mencius]] maintained that everyone possesses the germ or root of compassion, illustrating his case with the famous example of the child at an open well:\n\n\u201cSuppose a man were, all of a sudden, to see a young child on the verge of falling into a well. He would certainly be moved to compassion, not because he wanted to get into the good graces of the parents, nor because he wished to win the praise of his fellow-villagers or friends, nor yet because he disliked the cry of the child\u201d.<ref>D. C. Lau trans., ''Mencius'' (Penguin 1970)  p. 18 and p. 82</ref>\n\nMencius saw the task of moral cultivation as that of developing the initial impulse of compassion into an enduring quality of [[Ren (Confucianism)|benevolence]].<ref>D. C. Lau trans., ''Mencius'' (Penguin 1970)  p. 22-7</ref>\n\n===Indian religions===\n\n====Buddhism====\n{{Main|Karu\u1e47\u0101|l1=Karu\u1e47\u0101|Brahmavihara|l2=The Four Immeassurables|Metta|l3=Metta|Kayagatasati Sutta|l4=Kayagatasati Sutta|Anapanasati Sutta|l5=Anapanasati Sutta|Satipatthana|l6=Satipatthanas, the four main methods for compassion and release in Buddhism|Parashiva|l7=Parashiva, the soul's destiny in Shaivism}}\n[[File:Liao Dynasty Avalokitesvara Statue Clear.jpeg|thumb|[[Avalokite\u015bvara]] looking out over the sea of suffering. [[China]], [[Liao Dynasty]].]]\n\nThe first of what in English are called the [[Four Noble Truths]] is the truth of [[suffering]] or [[dukkha]] (unsatisfactoriness or stress). [[Dukkha]] is identified as one of the [[Three marks of existence|three distinguishing characteristics]] of all conditioned existence. It arises as a consequence of the failure to adapt to change  or [[anicca]] (the second characteristic) and the insubstantiality, lack of fixed identity, the horrendous lack of certainty of [[anatta]] (the third characteristic) to which all this constant change in turn gives rise. Compassion made possible by observation and accurate perception is the appropriate practical response. The ultimate and earnest wish, manifest in the Buddha, both as archetype and as historical entity, is to relieve the suffering of all living beings everywhere.<ref>HarperCollins  Dictionary of Religion, 1995.</ref>\n\nThe [[Dalai Lama]] has said, \"If you want others to be happy, practice compassion. If you want to be happy, practice compassion.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Twitter \u2013 Dalai Lama|url=https://twitter.com/dalailama/status/576314276228390912|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=24 January 2016}}</ref> The American [[Buddhist monk|monk]] [[Bhikkhu Bodhi]] states that compassion \"supplies the complement to [[metta|loving-kindness]]: whereas loving-kindness has the characteristic of wishing for the [[happiness]] and welfare of others, compassion has the characteristic of wishing that others be free from suffering, a wish to be extended without limits to all living beings. Like [[metta]], compassion arises by entering into the [[subjectivity]] of others, by sharing their interiority in a deep and total way. It springs up by considering that all beings, like ourselves, wish to be free from suffering, yet despite their wishes continue to be harassed by [[Pain and nociception|pain]], [[fear]], [[sorrow (emotion)|sorrow]], and other forms of dukkha.\"<ref>Bhikkhu Bodhi, ''The Noble Eightfold Path: Way to the End of Suffering''. Buddhist Publication Society, 1994, page 39.</ref>\n\n====Hinduism====\n{{Main|Daya (Hinduism)|Karu\u1e47\u0101|Samatva (Equanimity)|The Five Yamas of Yoga|\u0100tman (Hinduism)|Chakra#The seven chakra system|Ahimsa#Hinduism|Mett\u0101|Samadhana}} \n{{See also|Enlightenment (spiritual)#Hinduism|Hospitality|Kama|Samyama}}\n\n[[File:1 Sannyasi in yoga meditation on the Ganges, Rishikesh.jpg|thumb|left|[[Yoga]] aims at physical, mental and spiritual purification, with a compassionate mind and spirit being one of its most important goals.<ref>[[Klaus K. Klostermaier]] (1989), A Survey of Hinduism: First Edition, State University of New York Press, {{ISBN|978-0887068072}}, pp 362\u2013367</ref> Various ''asanas'' and ''mudras'' are combined with meditation and self-reflection exercises to cultivate compassion.<ref>Timothy McCall [http://www.yogajournal.com/for_teachers/2490 Yoga to Cultivate Compassion, Gratitude, and Joy \u2013 Part I] Yoga Journal (2010); see also: Timothy McCall, Yoga as Medicine: The Yogic Prescription for Health and Healing, (Bantam Dell, August 2007)</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Jeste | first1 = D. V. | last2 = Vahia | first2 = I. V. | year = 2008 | title = Comparison of the conceptualization of wisdom in ancient Indian literature with modern views: focus on the Bhagavad Gita | url = | journal = Psychiatry | volume = 71 | issue = 3| pages = 197\u2013202 | doi=10.1521/psyc.2008.71.3.197| pmid = 18834271 | pmc = 2603047 }}</ref>]]\n\nIn classical literature of [[Hinduism]], compassion<ref name=nmgc>Nancy Martin, Brill's Encyclopedia of Hinduism, Editor: Knut Jacobsen (2010), Volume II, Brill, {{ISBN|978-90-04-17893-9}}, see Article on ''Grace and Compassion'', pp 752\u2013757</ref> is a virtue with many shades, each shade explained by different terms. Three most common terms are ''[[Daya (Hinduism)|daya]]'' (\u0926\u092f\u093e),<ref>[http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?tinput=dayA&direction=SE&script=HK&link=yes&beginning= dayA] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112023437/http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?tinput=dayA&direction=SE&script=HK&link=yes&beginning= |date=2016-11-12 }} Sanskrit English Dictionary, Spoken Sanskrit, Germany (2011)</ref> ''[[karu\u1e47\u0101]]'' (\u0915\u0930\u0941\u0923\u093e),<ref>[http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?tinput=karuNA&direction=SE&script=HK&link=yes&beginning= karuNA] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112015253/http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?tinput=karuNA&direction=SE&script=HK&link=yes&beginning= |date=2016-11-12 }} Sanskrit English Dictionary, Spoken Sanskrit, Germany (2011)</ref> and ''[[anukamp\u0101]]'' (\u0905\u0928\u0941\u0915\u092e\u094d\u092a\u093e).<ref>[http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?tinput=anukampA&direction=SE&script=HK&link=yes&beginning= AnukampA] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116090230/http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?tinput=anukampA&direction=SE&script=HK&link=yes&beginning= |date=2017-01-16 }} Sanskrit English Dictionary, Spoken Sanskrit, Germany (2011)</ref> Other words related to compassion in Hinduism include ''karunya'', ''kripa'', and ''anukrosha''.<ref name=abde/><ref>[http://www.sanskrit-lexicon.uni-koeln.de/aequery/index.html Compassion] Apte English Sanskrit Dictionary, University of Koeln, Germany</ref> Some of these words are used interchangeably among the schools of Hinduism to explain the concept of compassion, its sources, its consequences, and its nature. The virtue of compassion to all living beings, claim [[Mahatma Gandhi|Gandhi]] and others,<ref>M.K. Gandhi, Hindu Dharma, {{ISBN|978-8122201086}}, Orient Paperbacks</ref><ref>Tripathi, A., & Mullet, E. (2010), Conceptualizations of forgiveness and forgivingness among Hindus, The International Journal for the Psychology of Religion, 20(4), pp 255\u2013266</ref> is a central concept in Hindu philosophy.<ref name=nmgc/>\n\n''Daya'' is defined by [[Padma Purana]] as the virtuous desire to mitigate the sorrow and difficulties of others by putting forth whatever effort necessary.<ref name=abde/><ref>S. Parmeshwaranand, Encyclopaedic Dictionary of The Dharmasastra, {{ISBN|978-8176253659}}, pp 369\u2013370</ref> Matsya Purana describes ''daya'' as the value that treats all living beings (including human beings) as one's own self, wanting the welfare and good of the other living being.<ref name=abde/><ref>Matsya Purana, 52.8 and 143.31 through 332</ref> Such compassion, claims [[Matsya Purana]], is one of necessary paths to being happy. Ekadashi Tattvam<ref>Ekadashi Tattvam, [[Raghunandana Bhattacharya]], Smriti, Calcutta/London (1816)</ref> explains ''daya'' is treating a stranger, a relative, a friend and a foe as one's own self; it argues that compassion is that state when one sees all living beings as part of one's own self, and when everyone's suffering is seen as one's own suffering. Compassion to all living beings, including to those who are strangers and those who are foes, is seen as a noble virtue.<ref name=abde>Anandita Balslev and Dirk Evers (Editors), Compassion in the World's Religions: Envisioning Human Solidarity (Religionswissenschaft: Forschung und Wissenschaft), {{ISBN|978-3643104762}}, LIT Verlag (2009), see Chapter 4, Compassion: Etymology, Rituals, Anecdotes from the Hindu Tradition</ref> ''Karuna'', another word for compassion in Hindu philosophy, means placing one's mind in other's favor, thereby seeking to understand the other from their perspective. ''Anukampa'', yet another word for compassion, refers to one's state after one has observed and understood the pain and suffering in others.<ref>Mohapatra & Mohapatra (1993), Hinduism: Analytical Study, South Asia Books, {{ISBN|978-8170993889}}</ref><ref>Rye, M. S., Pargament, K. I., Ali, M. A., Beck, G. L., Dorff, E. N., Hallisey, C., ... & Williams, J. G. (2000). Religious perspectives on forgiveness. Forgiveness: Theory, research, and practice, pp 17\u201340</ref> In [[Mahabharata]], Indra praises [[Yudhishthira]] for his ''anukrosha'' \u2014 compassion, sympathy \u2014 for all creatures.<ref>W. Doniger, The Hindus: An Alternative History, Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|978-0199593347}}, page 270</ref> [[Tulsidas]] contrasts ''daya'' (compassion) with ''abhiman'' (arrogance, contempt of others), claiming compassion is a source of ''[[Dharma#Definition and meaning|dharmic]]'' life, while arrogance a source of sin. ''Daya'' (compassion) is not ''kripa'' (pity) in Hinduism, or feeling sorry for the sufferer, because that is marred with condescension; compassion is feeling one with the sufferer.<ref>Pujya Paramtattva Swami, [http://www.cbcew.org.uk/CBCEW-Home/Departments/Dialogue-and-Unity/Other-Religions/Cardinal-Tauran-s-UK-Visit-2013/Hindu-Temple-Visit/Pujya-Paramtattva-Swami Catholics and Hindus: The Practice of Compassion as a Contribution to Peace] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314130215/http://www.cbcew.org.uk/CBCEW-Home/Departments/Dialogue-and-Unity/Other-Religions/Cardinal-Tauran-s-UK-Visit-2013/Hindu-Temple-Visit/Pujya-Paramtattva-Swami |date=2016-03-14 }} The Catholic Church in England and Wales, United Kingdom (June 2013), pp 1\u20133</ref> Compassion is the basis for [[ahimsa]], a core virtue in Hindu philosophy.<ref>Aloysius Michael (1979), Radhakrishnan on Hindu Moral Life and Action, South Asia Books, {{ISBN|978-0836403343}}, pp 67\u201368</ref><ref>Lisa Kemmerer and Anthony Nocella (2011), Call to Compassion, Lantern Books New York, {{ISBN|978-1-59056-182-9}}, pp 31\u201332</ref>\n\nCompassion in Hinduism is discussed as an absolute and relative concept. There are two forms of compassion: one for those who suffer even though they have done nothing wrong and one for those who suffer because they did something wrong. Absolute compassion applies to both, while relative compassion addresses the difference between the former and the latter. An example of the latter include those who plead guilty or are convicted of a crime such as murder; in these cases, the virtue of compassion must be balanced with the virtue of justice.<ref name=abde/>\n\nThe classical literature of Hinduism exists in many Indian languages. For example, ''[[Tirukku\u1e5ba\u1e37]],'' written between 200 BC and AD 400, and sometimes called the Tamil [[Veda]], is a cherished classic on Hinduism written in a South Indian language. It dedicates Chapter 25 of Book 1 to compassion,<ref>[http://ebooks.gutenberg.us/HimalayanAcademy/SacredHinduLiterature/weaver/content.htm Tirukku\u1e5ba\u1e37] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216064046/http://ebooks.gutenberg.us/HimalayanAcademy/SacredHinduLiterature/weaver/content.htm |date=December 16, 2014 }} verses 241\u2013250</ref> further dedicating separate chapters each for the resulting values of compassion, chiefly, [[vegetarianism]] or [[veganism]] (Chapter 26), [[non-violence|doing no harm]] (Chapter 32), [[non-killing]] (Chapter 33), possession of [[kindness]] (Chapter 8), dreading evil deeds (Chapter 21), [[benignity]] (Chapter 58), the right [[scepter]] (Chapter 55), and absence of [[terrorism]] (Chapter 57), to name a few.<ref>{{cite book | last = Pope | first = George Uglow | author-link = | title = The Sacred Kurral of Tiruvalluva Nayanar | publisher = Asian Educational Services | series = | volume = | edition = First | date = 1886 | location = New Delhi | pages = | language = | url = http://www.projectmadurai.org/pm_etexts/pdf/pm0153.pdf | doi = | id = | isbn = 8120600223 | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref>\n\n====Jainism====\n{{further|Ahimsa in Jainism}}\nCompassion for all life, human and non-human, is central to the [[Jainism|Jain]] tradition. Though all life is considered sacred, human life is deemed the highest form of earthly existence. To kill any person, no matter their crime, is considered unimaginably abhorrent. It is the only substantial religious tradition that requires both monks and laity to be vegetarian. It is suggested that certain strains of the [[Hinduism|Hindu tradition]] became vegetarian due to strong Jain influences.<ref>South India Handbook: The Travel Guide By Robert Bradnock, 2000 Footprint Travel Guides, p. 543, Vegetarianism: A History By Colin Spencer, 2002 Thunder's Mouth Press, p. 342</ref> The Jain tradition's stance on [[ahimsa|nonviolence]], however, goes far beyond [[vegetarianism]]. Jains refuse food obtained with unnecessary cruelty. Many practice [[veganism]].  Jains run animal shelters all over India. The [[Lal Mandir]], a prominent Jain temple in Delhi, is known for the Jain Birds Hospital in a second building behind the main temple.<ref>{{cite web|author=Powell Ettinger |url=http://www.wildlifeextra.com/go/world/bird-hospital.html#cr |title=Jainism and the legendary Delhi bird hospital |publisher=Wildlifeextra.com |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ja7iTij7Bc0C&pg=PT81&dq=birds+hospital+in+delhi#v=onepage&q=birds%20hospital%20in%20delhi&f=false |title=Top 10 Delhi \u2013 Dorling Kindersley \u2013 Google Books |accessdate=2013-09-28|isbn=9780756695637 |date=2012-11-01 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=18em|\n* [[Agape]], [[Philia]], [[Philautia]], [[Storge (familial love)|Storge]], [[Eros (concept)|Eros]]: Greek terms for [[Greek words for love|love]]\n* [[Brahmavihara]]\n* [[Brotherly love (philosophy)|Brotherly love]]\n* [[Charter for Compassion]]\n* [[Christian humanism]]\n* [[Compassion fatigue]]\n* [[Charity (virtue)]]\n* [[Caregiving]]\n* [[Daya Mata]]\n* [[Empathic concern]]\n* [[Fake compassion]]\n* [[Humanism]]\n* [[Karu\u1e47\u0101|Karuna]]\n* [[Moral emotions]]\n* [[Pity]]\n* [[Radical compassion]]\n* [[Role-taking theory]]\n* [[Self-compassion]]\n* [[Shabad (hymn)]]\n* [[Social emotions]]\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n{{Commons category|Compassion}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.ted.com/index.php/talks/karen_armstrong_makes_her_ted_prize_wish_the_charter_for_compassion.html TED Prize winner Karen Armstrong's video lecture on compassion]\n* [http://magazine.uchicago.edu/0604/features/emotion.shtml ''Mirrored emotion''] [[Jean Decety]], [[University of Chicago]]\n*''[http://bigthink.com/philip-perry/compassion-is-weaved-throughout-our-nervous-system-researchers-have-found Compassion Is Weaved Throughout Our Nervous System, Researchers Have Found]'' (December 2016). Discusses some of the work of [[Dacher Keltner]] as well as other researchers\n* [http://www.ted.com/talks/view/id/200 Daniel Goleman, psychologist & author of ''Emotional Intelligence'', video lecture on compassion]\n* [http://webcast.rice.edu/index.php?action=details&event=966 Dalai Lama on compassion, Rice University, May 2007.]\n* [http://www.ted.com/index.php/talks/bob_thurman_says_we_can_be_buddhas.html Professor Robert Thurman: ''Compassion is feeling the feelings of others'']\n\n{{emotion-footer}}\n\n[[Category:Emotions]]\n[[Category:Kindness]]\n[[Category:Giving]]\n[[Category:Suffering]]\n[[Category:Virtue]]\n[[Category:Religious ethics]]\n[[Category:Relational ethics]]\n[[Category:Hindu ethics]]\n[[Category:Buddhist ethics]]\n[[Category:Moral psychology]]\n", "name_user": "Lcscnc", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compassion"}
{"title_page": "Tottenham Hotspur Stadium", "text_new": "{{short description|Football stadium in London}}\n{{Infobox stadium\n| stadium_name      = Tottenham Hotspur Stadium\n| location           = [[Tottenham]] <br />[[London]], [[N postcode area|N17]]\n| image             = Tottenham Hotspur Stadium June 2019, view from East.jpg\n| image_size        = 280\n| caption           = View of the stadium from the east\n| coordinates       = {{coord|51|36|16|N|0|03|59|W|region:GB|display=it}}\n|publictransit      = {{rail-interchange|london|overground}} {{rws|White Hart Lane}}<br>{{rail-interchange|gb|rail}} {{rws|Northumberland Park}}<br>{{rail-interchange|london|underground}} {{rws|Seven Sisters}}\n| fullname          = Tottenham Hotspur Stadium\n| nickname          =\n| owner             = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n| operator          = Tottenham Hotspur\n| construction_cost = \u00a31 billion (entire project)<ref name=\"gilmour\"/>\n| built             = 2016\u20132019\n| opened            = 3 April 2019\n| dimensions        = {{convert|105|x|68|m|yd|1}}\n| surface           = [[Desso GrassMaster]] (football)<br>Turf Nation (NFL)<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Turf Nation |magazine=Stadia |url=http://www.stadia-magazine.com/directory.php?CompanyID=1033}}</ref>\n| status            = \n| architect         = [[Populous (company)|Populous]]\n| general_contractor = [[Mace (construction company)|Mace]] \n| structural engineer = [[BuroHappold Engineering|BuroHappold]]<ref name=\"architects\">{{cite web |url=https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/buildings/populouss-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-awe-inspiring/10041690.article |title=Populous\u2019s Tottenham Hotspur Stadium \u2013 awe inspiring |date=4 April 2019 |first=Rupert|last= Bickersteth |work=Architects Journal |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref><br /> [[Schlaich Bergermann Partner|Schlaich Bergermann]] (roof)<ref name=\"architects\" /><br />SCX (retractable pitch)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/behind-the-scenes-look-at-tottenhams-retractable-pitch/10041699.article |title= Behind the scenes look at Tottenham\u2019s retractable pitch |date=4 April 2019 |first= Connor |last= Ibbetson|work=New Civil Engineer |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n| seating_capacity  = 62,303<ref name=capacity>{{cite news|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/the-stadium/local/|title=Local: Information for local residents and businesses|publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n| record_attendance  = 61,104 (vs. [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], 22 December 2019)<ref name=\"record attendance\">{{cite news |url=https://www.premierleague.com/match/46782 |title=Spurs v Chelsea  |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=22 December 2019 }}</ref><br />60,463 (NFL)<ref name=\"nflfirrst\"/>\n}}\n\nThe '''Tottenham Hotspur Stadium''' is a load of utter shite. Memorable features include that overrated disabled English striker (Tesco) and big black Tanganga, as well as many other diabolical football players. The trophy cabinet is completely butt naked empty, and the manager and staff are currently working on a documentary about the club about their champions league run of 2019, in which they lost, making the documentary utterly worthless. Joke Club. London is red.\n\nThe construction of the stadium was initiated as the centrepiece of the [[Northumberland Development Project]], intended to be the catalyst for a 20-year regeneration plan for [[Tottenham]]. The project covers the site of the now demolished ground of White Hart Lane and areas adjacent to it. The project was first conceived in 2007 and announced in 2008, but the plan was revised several times, and the construction of the stadium, beset by disputes and delays, did not commence until 2015. The stadium subsequently opened on 3 April 2019 with a ceremony before the first Premier League game held at the stadium.\n\nThe name \"Tottenham Hotspur Stadium\" is temporary, the intention being to sell the [[naming rights]], so that it will be named after a sponsor.<ref name=\"name\"/><ref name=\"thenational_726821\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thenational.ae/sport/comment/the-penny-finally-drops-as-tottenham-deal-with-spiralling-costs-of-move-back-to-white-hart-lane-1.726821 |title=The penny finally drops as Tottenham deal with spiralling costs of move back to White Hart Lane |first=Steve |last=Luckings|date=3 May 2018|work=The National|accessdate=14 July 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph_2018-08-30\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/08/30/tottenham-hotspurstruggle-200m-naming-deal-new-stadium/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur struggle for \u00a3200m naming deal for new stadium |first=Tom |last=Morgan |date=30 August 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph }}</ref> The stadium is occasionally referred to as '''New White Hart Lane''' by fans and some in the media.<ref name=\"independent_a8398106\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/tottenham-premier-league-fixtures-wembley-stadium-vs-fulham-first-game-white-hart-lane-liverpool-a8398106.html|title= Tottenham announce stay at Wembley Stadium and reveal first game at new White Hart Lane against Liverpool |first=Jack |last=de Menezes|date=14 June 2018|work=The Independent |accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Flavius |first1=Kevin |title=Tottenham Confirm New White Hart Lane Will Not Be Ready to Host Matches Until Next Year |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6206967-tottenham-confirm-new-white-hart-lane-will-not-be-ready-to-host-matches-until-next-year |website=90MIN |accessdate=30 October 2018 |date=26 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mannion |first1=Damian |title=PITCH PERFECT Tottenham stadium news: Pitch being laid at new White Hart Lane ground and fans can watch it live |url=https://talksport.com/football/428677/tottenham-stadium-news-pitch-being-laid-new-white-hart-lane/ |website=talkSPORT |accessdate=30 October 2018 |date=2 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wallace |first1=Sam |title=Workers on Spurs' new White Hart Lane stadium 'off their heads on cocaine' during construction |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/09/20/spurs-stadium-workers-heads-cocaine-alcohol-construction/ |accessdate=30 October 2018 |work=The Telegraph |date=20 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{See|White Hart Lane|Northumberland Development Project}}\n===Early grounds===\n[[File:Aerial view Tottenham Hotspur Football Club -trimmed.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|Aerial view of [[White Hart Lane]], demolished in 2017. Great part of the area in view was redeveloped in the new stadium project.]]\n\nTottenham Hotspur was formed in 1882, and early matches of the club were played on public land at [[Tottenham Marshes]].<ref name=Goodwin>{{cite book |first=Bob |last=Goodwin |title=Tottenham Hotspur: The Complete Record |publisher=Derby Books |edition=2 |year=2007 |isbn=978-1-85983-846-4}}</ref> As their matches became more popular with the public and the number of spectators increased, the club decided to move to an enclosed ground allowing it to charge an entrance fee and control the crowd. In 1888, the club rented a pitch at Asplins Farm, next to the railway line at [[Northumberland Park, London|Northumberland Park]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S07SDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT24&lpg=PT24#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=People's History of Tottenham Hotspur: How Spurs Fans Shaped the Identity of One of the World's Most Famous Clubs|authors= Martin Cloake, Alan Fisher |publisher=Pitch Publishing |date=15 August 2016 |chapter=Chapter 2: Enclosure Changed the Game Forever}}</ref> However, the ground soon became overcrowded, and in 1899 the club moved to a piece of land owned by the brewery company [[Charringtons]] to the east of [[Tottenham High Road]] behind the White Hart pub.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/tottenham-hotspur-spurs-white-hart-lane-farewell-goodbye-diego-maradon-johan-cruyff-a7733846.html|title=White Hart Lane has seen Diego Maradona and Johan Cruyff, but after 118 years Tottenham have outgrown it|first=Martin |last=Cloake |date=13 May 2017|work=The Independent}}</ref> This became the [[White Hart Lane]] ground.\n\nThe club acquired the freehold of the ground, as well as additional land at the northern (Paxton Road) end, in 1905.<ref name=\"haringey\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/AttachmentShowServlet?ImageName=236039 |title=Northumberland Development Project, Tottenham|date=October 2009 |publisher=Haringey Council}}</ref><ref name=\"stadium history\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/the-stadium/history/ |title= History of White Hart Lane |work=Tottenham Hotspur}}</ref> Starting in 1909, a new stadium with stands designed by [[Archibald Leitch]] was built over a period of two and a half decades. The stadium had a capacity of nearly 80,000 by 1934. Over the years, the stadium underwent a number of changes and seating replaced the standing areas, which reduced the capacity to about 50,000 in 1979. Significant standing areas, however, still existed, including the long stretch of raised standing terrace favoured by fans on the East Stand known as The Shelf.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/the-shelf-at-tottenham-once-made-white-hart-lane-londons-most-hostile-stadium-a3537971.html |title=The Shelf at Tottenham once made White Hart Lane London's most hostile stadium |first=Tony |last=Evans | date= 13 May 2017 |work=Evening Standard}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in the early 1980s, the White Hart Lane ground was redeveloped, and in order to comply with the recommendation of the [[Taylor Report]] of 1989, it was then turned into an all-seater stadium. The capacity of the stadium was reduced to around 36,000 by the time the refurbishment was completed in 1998. The capacity was, by then, lower than the grounds of other major English clubs, with many of these clubs also planning to expand further. As revenues from gate receipts in that period formed a substantial part of the club's income (before it became dominated by TV broadcast rights deals),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-36412394 |title=Premier League finances enter new era, says Deloitte |first= Bill|last= Wilson|work=BBC }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jun/06/premier-league-finances-club-guide-2016-17 |title=Premier League finances: the full club-by-club breakdown and verdict |first=David |last=Conn|date=6 June 2018 |work=The Guardian|accessdate= 9 December 2018 }}</ref> Tottenham began to explore ways of increasing the stadium capacity to allow it to more effectively compete financially with rival clubs.<ref name=\"east stand\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spurs1882.org/misc/WHL_EastStand2001_PlanningStatement.pdf |title=Proposed New East Stand Redevelopment for Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |date=June 2001 |work=Spurs Since 1882}}</ref>\n\nOver the years, a number of schemes were considered; these included rebuilding the East Stand as a three-tier structure, and moving to different stadiums and locations such as [[Picketts Lock]] and the [[Olympic Stadium (London)|Olympic Stadium]] at [[Stratford, London]].<ref name=\"east stand\"/> These plans however failed to come to fruition,<ref>{{cite news |title =Spurs plan down the Tube |first=Raoul |last=Simons |work=Evening Standard |date=30 July 2003 |url= https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/spurs-plan-down-the-tube-6985469.html }}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-12424549 West Ham chosen as preferred Olympic Stadium tenant BBC Sport online] Retrieved 12 February 2011</ref> except for a proposal to redevelop the existing site that became the [[Northumberland Development Project]].<ref name=\"Collett\">{{cite web |url= https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-england-tottenham/spurs-commit-to-new-stadium-in-tottenham-idUKTRE80U12620120131 |title=Spurs commit to new stadium in Tottenham|first=Mike|last= Collett|date=31 January 2012 |work=Reuters }}</ref>\n\n===Planning===\nThe club first announced in 2007 that redevelopment of the current site was one of the options under consideration.<ref name=young>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/new-tottenham-stadium-guide-pictures-video-capacity-cost-opening-date-and-what-we-know-so-far-a4047846.html |title=New Tottenham stadium guide: Opening date, pictures, video, capacity, cost and more |first=Alex |last= Young |date=24 January 2019 |work=Evening Standard |accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/articles/stadiumupdate060508.html|title=Stadium Update|publisher=Tottenhamhotspur.com|date=6 May 2008|accessdate=25 May 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509062202/http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/articles/stadiumupdate060508.html |archivedate=9 May 2008 }}</ref> In April 2008, the club revealed that it was considering the acquisition of the Wingate Trading Estate immediately adjacent to the north of White Hart Lane for building the stadium.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/0,,2271881,00.html |title=Spurs consider White Hart Lane exit for 55,000-seat stadium|work=The Guardian|date= 9 April 2008 |first=David|last= Hytner}}</ref> In October 2008, the Northumberland Development Project, that included the construction of a stadium, as well as a club museum, homes, shops and other facilities, was announced.<ref name=\"confirmed\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/tottenham-hotspur-confirms-northumberland-development-project-301008/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur Confirms Northumberland Development Project|date= 30 October 2008 |work=Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref><ref name=\"image released\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/t/tottenham_hotspur/7784290.stm|title=Spurs reveal images of new ground|publisher=BBC Sport|date=15 December 2008|accessdate=16 December 2008}}</ref> The early plan was for Tottenham to move into the new stadium, while it was partially built, at the beginning of the 2012\u201313 season, with the stadium  completed by the end of the following season. However, the project was delayed, with the plan undergoing a number of revisions and the completion date pushed back several times.<ref name=stadiumplans2013>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamjournal.co.uk/news/tottenham_hotspur_stadium_plan_drops_hotel_for_college_and_more_flats_1_1187677 |title=Tottenham Hotspur stadium plan drops hotel for college and more flats |work=Tottenahm and Wood Green Journal |date=25 January 2012 |accessdate= 29 May 2013|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221012501/http://www.tottenhamjournal.co.uk/news/tottenham_hotspur_stadium_plan_drops_hotel_for_college_and_more_flats_1_1187677 |archivedate= 21 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29144491 |title=Tottenham stadium delay means club face season away from home BBC Sport website 10 December 2014|accessdate= 20 February 2015|work=BBC}}</ref> The club also did not fully commit itself to building the stadium in Tottenham until January 2012, after it had lost its bid for the [[Olympic Stadium (London)|Olympic Stadium]] to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref name=\"Collett\"/>\n\nThe first plan of the project, with a 58,000-capacity stadium, was released in April 2009 for public consultation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/5084823/Tottenhams-new-stadium-could-have-an-ice-rink.html |title=Tottenham's new stadium could have an ice rink |first= Richard|last= Bright|date=1 April 2009 |work=The Telegraph }}</ref> In October 2009, the planning application for a 56,000-seat stadium, designed by [[KSS Design Group]], and other buildings was then submitted.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/t/tottenham_hotspur/8326735.stm |title=Spurs aim for new stadium by 2012 |work=BBC |first=Sam |last=Sheringham|date=26 October 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/make-and-kss-to-design-spurs-stadium/3127797.article |title=Make and KSS to design Spurs stadium |first= Sarah |last=Richardson|date=18 November 2008|work=Building }}</ref> The proposal, which included the demolition of eight locally listed buildings and two nationally listed buildings, was criticised by conservation groups including [[English Heritage]], as well as the Government's advisory body on architecture, the [[Commission for Architecture and the Built Environment]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/spurs-try-again-as-400m-stadium-plan-is-ruled-offside-6471651.html |title=Spurs try again as \u00a3400m stadium plan is ruled offside |first=Felix |last=Allen |date= 20 May 2010 |work= Evening Standard}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/tottenham/article7131149.ece |title= Tottenham's plans to redevelop White Hart Lane shown red card |work=Times online|accessdate= 22 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528094547/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/tottenham/article7131149.ece |archivedate=28 May 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.savebritainsheritage.org/campaigns/item/50/15-historic-buildings-set-for-demolition-under-Spurs-stadium-plans |title=15 historic buildings set for demolition under Spurs stadium plans |work=SAVE Britain Heritage }}</ref> In response to the objections, a revised plan, that retained some of the listed buildings, was resubmitted in May 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/9498772/premier-league-tottenham-press-ahead-with-stadium-plans |title=Premier League: Tottenham press ahead with stadium plans |first= Lyall |last=Thomas|date= 2 October 2014 |work=Sky Sports }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/7744297/Tottenham-redesign-new-stadium-to-preserve-listed-buildings.html |title=Tottenham redesign new stadium to preserve listed buildings |first=John |last=Ley |date= 20 May 2010 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=15 June 2018 }}</ref> This plan was accepted by Haringey Council on 30 September 2010, and later by the [[Mayor of London]], [[Boris Johnson]], as well as the government.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/8160140/Tottenham-given-go-ahead-to-redevelop-White-Hart-lane-by-Mayor-of-London-Boris-Johnson.html |title=Tottenham given go ahead to redevelop White Hart Lane by Mayor of London Boris Johnson |date=25 November 2010|work=The Telegraph}}</ref><ref name=NDPPressrelease>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/futureplans/news/stadium-plans-011010.html |title=Stadium Plans |work=THFC Official website|accessdate= 15 June 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101003104828/http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/futureplans/news/stadium-plans-011010.html |archivedate= 3 October 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/new-stadium-plans-update1-091210/|title=New Stadium Plans Update|date= 9 December 2010 |work=Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref> However, only part of this plan, the construction of Lilywhite House, was implemented.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club-announcement-160215/ |title=Club Announcement|date= 16 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Northumnerland Development Project.svg|thumb|upright=0.8|The layout for the [[Northumberland Development Project]]]]\nIn August 2011, a [[2011 England riots|major riot]] erupted in a deprived area of Tottenham. [[Haringey Council]], keen to keep the economically-important club within the community, issued planning permission for the project on 20 September 2011,<ref name=\"kilpatrick\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/articles/northumberland-development-project-update-200911.html |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124142051/http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/articles/northumberland-development-project-update-200911.html |archivedate=24 November 2011 | title=Northumberland Development Project Update |work= Tottenhamhotspur.com|accessdate= 20 September 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/14996725 |title=Tottenham sign planning agreement to build new stadium |date = 20 September 2011 |work=BBC}}</ref> and a week later removed the demand for community infrastructure payments usually required for such a project.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-15095674|title=Club reveal next stage plans for Northumberland Development Tottenham stadium: Club offered White Hart Lane deal|publisher=BBC |date=28 September 2011|accessdate=18 November 2011}}</ref> In a joint statement with Haringey Council in January 2012, Tottenham announced that it would stay in North Tottenham and work with the council to rejuvenate the area.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.enfieldindependent.co.uk/news/tottenhamhotspurstadiumplans/9502824.Spurs_confirm_intention_to_stay_in_Tottenham_and_help_rejuvenate_the_area/ |title= Spurs confirm intention to stay in Tottenham and help rejuvenate the area|first=Bruce |last=Thain|work=Enfield Independent |date=31 January 2012 }}</ref> In this scheme, the Northumberland Development Project would serve as the catalyst for a 20-year regeneration program planned by the Haringey Council.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.haringey.gov.uk/sites/haringeygovuk/files/a_plan_for_tottenham.pdf |title=A Plan Tottenham |work=Haringey Council |date=2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"projectupdateJuly2015\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/tottenham-in-1-billion-turnaround-9214361.html |title=Tottenham in \u00a31 billion turnaround |work= London Evening Standard |date=25 March 2014 |first=Robert |last=Bevan }}</ref> In March 2012, Haringey Council approved of plans to hand over council-owned land in the redevelopment area, including part of Wingate Trading Estate, as well as Paxton Road and Bill Nicholson Way, to Spurs. It also agreed on a Compulsory Purchase Order (CPO) to buy the remaining properties on Paxton Road that had yet to sell.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.tottenhamjournal.co.uk/news/spurs_granted_right_to_remove_final_business_in_the_way_of_new_ground_1_1334278|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20130215060058/http://www.tottenhamjournal.co.uk/news/spurs_granted_right_to_remove_final_business_in_the_way_of_new_ground_1_1334278|title=Spurs granted right to remove final business in the way of new ground|first= Tim |last=Lamden|date= March 29, 2012 |archivedate=15 February 2013 |work=Tottenham and Wood Green Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://cartilagefreecaptain.sbnation.com/2012/3/29/2911018/another-obstacle-between-tottenham-hotspur-and-their-new-stadium-falls |title=Another Obstacle Between Tottenham Hotspur and Their New Stadium Falls |author=Bryan A.|date= 29 March 2012 |work=Cartilage Free Captain}}</ref> After a long delay, the Secretary of State for the [[Department for Communities and Local Government]], [[Eric Pickles]], confirmed the CPO on 11 July 2014.<ref name=\"DCMS\">{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-scheme-gets-the-green-light|title=New Tottenham Hotspur stadium scheme gets the green light|date=11 July 2014|publisher=Department for Communities and Local Government|accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/northumberland-development-project-cpo-confirmed-110714/|title=Northumberland Development Project - CPO Confirmed|date=11 July 2014|publisher=Tottenham Hotspur|accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref> The owner of the remaining business with two plots on the development site, Archway Sheet Metal Works, then attempted but failed to have the CPO decision quashed in the [[High Court of Justice|High Court]].<ref name=highcourt>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/11424828/Tottenham-plans-for-new-stadium-given-massive-boost-as-business-looking-to-block-move-loses-High-Court-appeal.html|title= Tottenham plans for new stadium given massive boost as business looking to block move loses High Court appeal|work= [[Daily Telegraph]]|date= 20 February 2015|accessdate= 20 February 2015}}</ref> On 31 March 2015, the remaining plots on Paxton Road were acquired, allowing the development to proceed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/joint-statement-310315/ |title=Joint Statement |work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club|date= 31 March 2015|accessdate= 31 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/chairmanand39s-message-160515/ |title=Chairman'S Message|date= 16 May 2015 |work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club}}</ref>\n\nIt was first revealed in October 2013 that the club was considering a new plan for a multi-use stadium that can host American [[National Football League|NFL]] games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/tottenham-hotspurs-secret-plans-for-white-hart-lane-mega-stadium/8654598.article?blocktitle=News-feature&contentID=9529|title=Tottenham Hotspurs' secret plans for White Hart Lane mega stadium |date=24 October 2013 |first= Richard|last= Waite|work=The Architects' Journal }}</ref> On 8 July 2015, the club announced that it had reached an agreement with [[National Football League|NFL]] to hold a minimum of two NFL games a year in a 10-year partnership.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/11725998/Tottenham-close-to-signing-deal-with-NFL-to-stage-American-Football-matches-at-new-61000-seater-stadium.html |title=Tottenham sign deal with NFL to stage American Football matches at new 61,000-seater stadium |first=Jeremy|last= Wilson|date=8 Jul 2015 |work=The Telegraph }}</ref> The same day a new design team was also announced, alongside a revised project plan, with [[Populous (company)|Populous]] led by Christopher Lee responsible for the stadium design.<ref name=\"projectupdateJuly2015\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/new-scheme/project-update/#scheme-comparisons |title=Project Update |work=THFC |accessdate= 12 July 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714032108/http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/new-scheme/project-update/ |archivedate=14 July 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/events/business-of-sport/christopher-lee-architect-populous/ |title=Architect Christopher Lee from Populous talks modern stadium design |first=David |last=Edwards|work=The Telegraph |date=3 June 2016 |accessdate=31 January 2019 }}</ref> In December 2015, the revised plans were approved by Haringey Council, including the demolition of locally listed buildings.<ref name=\"haringey planning\">{{cite web |url=http://www.haringey.gov.uk/planning-and-building-control/planning/major-projects-and-regeneration/tottenham-hotspur-football-club-stadium-development |title=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club Stadium Development |work=Haringey London}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/35118953 Tottenham's revised stadium plans approved by Haringey Council ''BBC News'']. Retrieved 17 December 2015</ref> The Mayor of London also gave formal approval to the plans in February 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/new-tottenham-stadium-mayor-of-london-boris-johnson-gives-formal-approval-to-spurs-redevelopment-a3189306.html |title=New Tottenham stadium: Mayor of London Boris Johnson gives formal approval to Spurs redevelopment |first=Sam |last= Long |date= 25 February 2016 |work=Evening Standard }}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\n[[File:New White Hart Lane from above 2017-05. trimmed 2.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|Northern section of the new stadium (left) under construction in May 2017, with White Hart Lane (right) partially demolished. The new ground covers part of the old ground.]]\nBuilding work on the Northumberland Development Project started in September 2012, however, construction of the stadium itself did not commence until 2015 due to the CPO dispute. The stadium was constructed in two main phases so that White Hart Lane could still be used in the [[2016\u201317 Tottenham Hotspur F.C. season|2016\u201317 season]] while construction was still in progress. The first phase involved the building of the northern section of the stadium (including the North, West and East Stands), while the South Stand construction started in the second phase after White Hart Lane had been demolished. A large part of the land north of the existing stadium had been cleared by 2014 while the CPO dispute was ongoing.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jul/13/football-news-in-brief |title= Football news in brief |date= 13 July 2014 |work=The Guardian }}</ref> After the dispute was resolved, preliminary work on the basement began in the summer of 2015,<ref name=\"project update\">{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714032108/http://tottenhamhotspur.com/new-scheme/project-update/ |archivedate=14 July 2015 |title=Project Update |url=http://tottenhamhotspur.com/new-scheme/project-update/ |url-status=dead |work=Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref> with concrete and ground works for the foundation by Morrisroe starting in autumn 2015, based on earlier approved and amended plans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2016/02/25/final-go-ahead-for-400m-spurs-stadium/ |title=Final go-ahead for \u00a3400m Spurs stadium |date=25 February 2016 |work=Construction Enquirer |accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.morrisroe.co.uk/portfolio/tottenham-hotspur/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur Football Stadium |work=Morrisroe  |accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=\nhttp://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/ApplicationSearchServlet?PKID=280768 |title=Online Planning Services |work=Haringey London  |accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe new plan for the project was given final approval in February 2016, which allowed the construction of the main structure of the new stadium itself to start soon after. In order to facilitate the construction of the northern section of the stadium while matches of the final season were still being played at The Lane, the northeast corner of White Hart Lane was demolished in the summer of 2016 after the [[2015\u201316 Tottenham Hotspur F.C. season|2015\u201316 season]] had finished.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cartilagefreecaptain.sbnation.com/2016/5/6/11605462/tottenham-hotspur-confirms-upcoming-partial-demolition-of-white-hart-lane-stand |title=Tottenham Hotspur confirms upcoming partial demolition of White Hart Lane stand|first= Dustin |last=Menno| date= 6 May 2016|work=Cartilage Free Captain }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club/new-stadium/stadium-construction-update-latest-aerial-photos-170816/|title=Stadium Construction Update - Latest Aerial Photos|date= 17 August 2016 |work= Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref> From the basement to level 6, the construction of this section is in reinforced concrete.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/AttachmentShowServlet?ImageName=748344 |title=Environmental Statement |date=September 2015 |work=Haringey Council }}</ref> Three further levels above are constructed in steel frame. There are only six cores in reinforced concrete for vertical circulation of spectators instead of the eight expected of a stadium of this size as they needed to be constructed within the first phase of the stadium construction.<ref name=\"jones\"/> The South Stand constructed in the second phase has open staircases to the concourses.<ref name=\"access\"/>\n[[File:Tottenham Hotspur Stadium under construction - view from Park Lane.jpg|thumb|Stadium under construction in May 2018 with two steel \"trees\" supporting the South Stand erected and the cable net roof structure installed. Trays for the retractable pitch are observable under the podium in the foreground.]]\n\nThe demolition of the majority remaining White Hart Lane ground began the day after the last home match of the [[2016\u201317 Tottenham Hotspur F.C. season|2016\u201317 season]] was played, and the demolition was completed with all visible remnants of White Hart Lane removed by early August 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spurs release brilliant time-lapse video showing new stadium progress and how it will look|url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/spurs-new-stadium-building-ground-13434810|accessdate=17 October 2018|work=football.london|date=4 August 2017|first=Alasdair|last= Gold}}</ref> Piling work for Phase 2 of the stadium construction started in June 2017.<ref>{{cite |url=http://www.thstofficial.com/uploads/9/2/2/6/92268578/thfc_stadium_newsletter_june_17.pdf |title= Spurs Stadium Project |work=Tottenham Hotspur Supporters' Trust }}</ref> While the northern section constructed in the first phase is a largely concrete structure, the entire single-tier south stand has a steel frame to allow for a speedier construction.<ref name=\"jones\">{{cite web |url=https://populous.com/posts/home-sweet-home-tottenham-hotspurs-last-match-white-hart-lane/ |title=Home Sweet Home: Tottenham Hotspur's last match at White Hart Lane|date=17 May 2017 |first=Tom |last=Jones|work=Populous}}</ref> The two steel \"trees\" that support the  South Stand were erected in December 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tothelaneandback.com/2017/11/11/tottenham-deploy-trees-in-new-850m-stadium-to-take-the-weight-of-the-south-stand-which-will-be-the-largest-in-europe/ |title=Tottenham Deploy 'Trees' In New \u00a3850m Stadium To Take The Weight Of The South Stand Which Will Be The Largest In Europe|first= Thomas|last= Hein |date= 11 November 2017 |work= }}</ref> The compression ring that holds the cable net roof structure was completed in February 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club/new-stadium/new-stadium-update-commencement-of-roof-lift-080218/ |title=New Stadium Update: Commencement of Roof Lift|date= 8 February 2018 |work=Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref> and the roof structure raised in March 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/new-spurs-stadium-spectacular-feature-14331516 |title=Tottenham unveil spectacular feature for \u00a3850m new stadium which will delight the fans |first=Alasdair |last=Gold|date=26 March 2018|work=football.london }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tottenham Hotspur Stadium under construction February 2019.jpg|thumb|Stadium nearing completion in February 2019. Last section of metal cladding panels being installed.]]\nParts of the old White Hart Lane have been incorporated into the new stadium &ndash; crushed aggregate of the concrete foundation of White Hart Lane was mixed in with new concrete to create the floor of the concourse of the new stadium,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/03/08/crushed-aggies-from-white-hart-lane-form-new-spurs-stadium-floors/ |title=White Hart Lane crushed aggies form new Spurs stadium floors |first=Grant |last=Prior | date=8 March 2018 |work=Construction Enquirer }}</ref> and bricks from the East Stand were used for the Shelf Bar.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club/new-stadium/new-stadium-shelf-and-led-190418/ |title= New stadium - latest photos - Shelf Bar and LED | date=19 April 2018 |work =Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref>  A number of heritage plaques are placed around the stadium marking points of the old stadium, such as its centre.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/media/16058/fan-guide.pdf |title=The Tottenham Hotspur Stadium: Welcome Home - Your Guide |work=Tottenham Hotspur |accessdate=12 March 2019 }}</ref> The pitch was laid in early October 2018.<ref name=\"ouzia\"/> The exterior of the stadium is finished with 35,000 decorative tiles, 4,801 perforated metal panels and 2,505 glass panels.<ref name=gold2019>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/everything-know-spurs-new-stadium-16041502 |title=15 astonishing facts about Tottenham Hotspur's new stadium - Everything you need to know|first=Alasdair |last=Gold|work=football.london|date=28 March 2019 |accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref> The external cladding of the stadium was completed with the last few metal panels of the 'veil' installed in March 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/new-tottenham-stadium-nike-corner-15955550 |title=New Tottenham stadium: Naming rights & Nike, the corner space 'issue', test events and 55 photos |first=Alasdair|last= Gold|work=football.london|date= 11 March 2019 |accessdate=12 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Opening===\nThe club initially announced that it would hold four test events at the stadium in August and early September 2018.<ref name=\"independent_a8398106\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11447481/spurs-announce-test-events-for-new-stadium |title=Spurs announce Test Events for new stadium|date= 24 July 2018 |work=Sky Sports |accessdate=24 July 2018 }}</ref> The first two events would be attended only by club staff and officials,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/new-tottenham-stadium-open-date-15014554|title=New Tottenham stadium: Whether ground will be ready on time, test events & stunning new photos|first=Alasdair |last=Gold|date=11 August 2018|work=football.london |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/11/09/tottenham-staff-given-sneak-preview-spectacular-new-stadium/ |title=Tottenham staff given sneak preview of spectacular new stadium |first=Matt|last= Law|date=9 November 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> the following two would be games open to the public, with increasing levels of attendance necessary for the issuing of safety certificate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cartilagefreecaptain.sbnation.com/2018/7/24/17609148/tottenham-hotspur-new-stadium-test-events-august-september-academy-spurs-legends |title=Tottenham confirm two test events ahead of new stadium opening|first= Dustin|last= Menno|date=24 July 2018|work=Cartilage Free Captain |accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11590069/tottenham-stadium-qa-what-has-to-happen-before-they-move-in |title=Tottenham stadium Q&A: What has to happen before they move in? |date= 23 December 2018 |work=Sky Sports |accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref> However, issues with the critical safety systems due to faulty electrical wiring delayed the completion of the stadium,<ref name=\"october opening\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/08/13/tottenham-forced-delay-opening-new-stadium-issues-critical-safety/ |title=Tottenham forced to delay opening of new stadium until end of October after 'issues with critical safety systems |first=Jeremy |last=Wilson|date=13 August 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tottenham stadium delay down to 'faulty wiring', says Mace|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11480000/tottenham-stadium-delay-down-to-faulty-wiring-says-mace |date=23 August 2018|work=Sky Sports |accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref> and these two games were postponed to March 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/spurs-stadium-the-story-so-far/5096681.article |title=Spurs stadium: The story so far |work= Building |date=2 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019 }}</ref> A fan familiarisation event was held instead at the stadium in December 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tottenham stage 'fan familiarisation event' at new White Hart Lane stadium|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11583073/tottenham-stage-fan-familiarisation-event-at-new-stadium |work=Sky Sports |date= 17 December 2018 }}</ref> The first match, an under-18s fixture between [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Tottenham]] and [[Southampton F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Southampton]] held on 24 March, was attended by 28,987 fans and won by Tottenham 3\u20131, with the first ever goal at the stadium scored by J'Neil Bennett.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/new-tottenham-stadium-test-event-jneil-bennett-makes-history-as-spurs-u18s-beat-southampton-a4099496.html |title=New Tottenham stadium test event: J'Neil Bennett makes history as Spurs U18s beat Southampton |first=Vaishali|last= Bhardwaj |date=24 March 2019 |work=Evening Standard|accessdate=24 March 2019 }}</ref> The second, a Legends match against [[Inter Milan]] on 30 March, was attended by 41,244, but resulted in a 4\u20135 loss to the Inter Forever team.<ref name=\"opening\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47502366|title=Tottenham: New stadium to be used competitively in first week of April |date=8 March 2019 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate= 8 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11679895/spurs-legends-4-5-inter-forever-gazza-cameo-in-thriller-at-new-stadium |title=Spurs Legends 4-5 Inter Forever: Gazza cameo in thriller at new stadium |date=30 March 2019 |accessdate=20 March 2019 |work=Sky Sports }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2019/march/legends-thrill-fans-at-new-stadium |title=Legends Thrill Fans at New Stadium |date=30 March 2019 |accessdate=31 March 2019 |work=THFC }}</ref>\n\nThe opening was originally planned for the second home match against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in September 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44479264 |title=Premier League fixtures 2018-19: Man City visit Arsenal on opening weekend |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 June 2018 |accessdate=14 June 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44480283 |title=Tottenham: Liverpool the visitors for first game at new stadium |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 June 2018 |accessdate=14 June 2018 }}</ref> but delays to the opening of the stadium forced Tottenham to extend their temporary tenancy of [[Wembley Stadium]] for the [[2018\u201319 Tottenham Hotspur F.C. season|2018\u201319 season]] until April 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham-confirm-wembley-date-for-manchester-city-match-and-stadium-will-stage-champions-league-a3926521.html |title=Tottenham confirm Wembley date for Manchester City match and stadium will stage Champions League group stage |first=Dan |last=Kilpatrick |work=Evening Standard |date=3 September 2018 |accessdate=3 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"2019 opening\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/oct/26/tottenham-mauricio-pochettino-real-madrid-wembley-nfl-manchester-city |title=Tottenham confirm they will not play in new stadium until 2019 |first=Ed|last= Aarons|date=26 October 2018 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=26 October 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"burrows\" /> They also played their home game in the third round of the [[2018\u201319 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] at [[Stadium MK]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11491901/tottenham-given-permission-to-move-watford-carabao-cup-tie-to-milton-keynes |title= Tottenham given permission to move Watford Carabao Cup tie to Milton Keynes | date= 5 September 2018 |work=Sky Sports}}</ref>  The first NFL game was due to be [[Oakland Raiders]] against [[Seattle Seahawks]] on 14 October 2018 but this too was relocated to Wembley following the stadium delay.<ref name=\"october opening\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nfl-england-oak-sea-tottenham/raiders-face-seahawks-in-first-game-at-new-tottenham-stadium-idUSKBN1F10TL |title=Raiders face Seahawks in first game at new Tottenham stadium |date=12 January 2018 |work= Reuters |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>  The club shop was the first to open on 23 October 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/tottenham-hotspur/story/3676313/tottenham-open-biggest-club-shop-in-europe-at-new-stadium-no-confirmed-date-for-first-match |title=Tottenham open biggest club shop in Europe at new stadium, no confirmed date for first match |first=Ben|last= Pearce |work=ESPN}}</ref> The stadium opened with a ceremony on 3 April 2019 before its first competitive senior game, the Premier League match against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref name=\"burrows\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/tottenham-hotspur-fixtures-new-stadium-first-game-when-is-it-crystal-palace-fc-a8827321.html |title=Tottenham new stadium: Spurs confirm Crystal Palace as first fixture at new home|first=Ben |last=Burrows |date=17 March 2019 |work=The Independent |accessdate=17 March 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/tottenham-hotspur-stadium-opening-ceremony-spurs-pay-homage-to-regeneration-of-local-area-after-2011-a4108686.html |title=Tottenham Hotspur stadium opening ceremony: Spurs pay homage to regeneration of local area after 2011 riots |date=3 April 2019 |work=Evening Standard |accessdate=4 April 2019 |first= Jack |last=Rosser }}</ref> The match was won by Tottenham 2\u20130, with [[Son Heung-min]] scoring the first ever official goal at the new stadium.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/04/03/tottenhams-first-game-new-stadium-plus-man-city-chelsea-premier/ |title=Son Heung-min writes his name in Spurs folklore with first goal in Tottenham's new stadium | first1=Jason |last1=Burt|first2=Alan |last2=Tyers |work=The Telegraph |date=3 April 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Tottenham Hotspur 2\u20130 Crystal Palace |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47512149 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 April 2019 |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture and facilities==\n[[File:Tottenham Hotspur Stadium - view from High Road - June 2019.jpg|thumb|West entrance of stadium on Tottenham High Road]]\nThe stadium is an asymmetric bowl, with a capacity of 62,303.<ref name=\"furtherexpansion\">{{cite news|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2019/august/application-to-increase-stadium-capacity-approved/|title=Spurs stadium capacity increased to 62,214|date= 5 August 2019|publisher=Tottenham hotspur official website|accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=capacity /> The bowl shape of the stadium comes from the need to maximise hospitality facilities while the asymmetry is the result of the creation of a single-tier stand in the south.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/AttachmentShowServlet?ImageName=748760 |title=Tottenham Hotspur Design and Access Statement 2015: Design Response |work=Haringey Council |accessdate=27 July 2018 }}</ref> The stadium is around 48 m high, 250 m long on its north-south axis and about 200 metres wide east to west.<ref name=\"overview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/AttachmentShowServlet?ImageName=748755 |title=Tottenham Hotspur Design and Access Statement 2015: Overview |work=Haringey Council |accessdate=25 July 2018 }}</ref> There are 9 floors in the horseshoe-shaped northern section above the basement, and 5 floors in the south, with a [[gross internal area]] of 119,945 m<sup>2</sup>,<ref name=\"overview\"/> which is around four times the size of White Hart Lane.<ref name=washington>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/tottenham-stadium-follows-us-financing-model/2019/04/01/145a04ec-54a2-11e9-aa83-504f086bf5d6_story.html |title=Tottenham Stadium follows US financing model |first=Ronald |last=Blum\u2009|date= 1 April 2019 |accessdate=1 April 2019 |work=Washington Post}}</ref> The stadium covers an area of 43,000 m<sup>2</sup>, nearly twice the area of White Hart Lane (24,000  m<sup>2</sup>).<ref name=stadiumdb>{{cite web |url=http://stadiumdb.com/stadiums/eng/tottenham_hotspur_stadium |title=Tottenham Hotspur Stadium |work=StadiumDB.com |accessdate=29 February 2020 }}</ref> The front of the West Stand faces the High Road and features a projecting, angled, glazed box that encases an escalator and serves as the main entrance for guests and patrons. The projecting entrance, along with the facades of other buildings of the Tottenham Experience, present a traditional linear frontage along the High Road. A 9.5-m pavement is created in front of these buildings to improve the flow of the crowd on match day on the High Road. To the east, on Worcester Avenue, is a dedicated entrance for NFL events.<ref name=\"access\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/AttachmentShowServlet?ImageName=748452 |title=Tottenham Hotspur Design and Access Statement 2015: 7.1 Stadium Design Concept |work=Haringey Council }}</ref> There are two raised podiums for fans access, one to the north and one to the south. A large open public square, the size of [[Trafalgar Square]], has been created on the south podium as the main access point for home fans. The square has a number of ventilation shafts, and it may be used for sporting and community activities.<ref name=\"populous\"/><ref name=\"london.gov\">{{cite web |url=https://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/PAWS/media_id_285574/tottenham_hotspur_stadium_report.pdf |title=Northumberland Development Project (Tottenham Hotspur Stadium) |date=27 October 2015 |accessdate=20 April 2019 |work=Greater London Authority }}</ref> Away fans may enter from the northeast corner of the stadium via Worcester Avenue and the north podium. The South Stand features a 5-storey atrium behind a single 7,000 m<sup>2</sup> curved glazed facade.<ref name=\"plan\">{{cite web |url= http://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/AttachmentShowServlet?ImageName=748774 |title=Tottenham Hotspur Design and Access Statement 2015: Part 7.5 |work=Haringey Council Services }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tottenham Hotspur Stadium with The Tottenham Experience on High Road - February 2019.jpg|thumb|Frontage of the stadium and Tottenham Experience along the High Road]]\nThe bulk of the structure dominates the surrounding area, but the appearance of the mass of the building is modulated by different claddings of glass, metal panels and pre-cast concrete. The perforated metal panels serve as a screen but allow for natural ventilation and light for the open [[Physical plant|plant]] areas in the stadium, and they also act as a unifying sculptured element in the appearance of the stadium.  Regions of glazing not covered by the metal screen, including the main entrances and concourses, offices, Sky Lounge, as well the extensive glazed area to the south, allow for views into and out of the stadium.<ref name=\"plan\"/> The metal panels may be in an open or closed position, and they are lined with [[LED]] luminaires that glow on match nights.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/new-tottenham-stadium-feature-spurs-14564979 |title= Spurs unveil impressive feature that will transform the outside of their new \u00a3850m stadium |first=Alasdair |last=Gold|date= 24 April 2018|work=football.london |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe roof is a cable net structure, held in place by an elliptically-shaped compression ring.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club/new-stadium/new-stadium-update-commencement-of-roof-lift-080218/ |title=New Stadium Update: Commencement of Roof Lift|date= 8 February 2018 |work=Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref> The roof has a circumference of 720 metres, and it is clad in standing seam aluminium panels that end with extruded [[polycarbonate]] on the inside edge to allow light through onto the pitch but reduce the contrast of the shadow of the roof on the pitch.<ref name=\"plan\"/><ref name=gold2019 />  810 curved alumininum eave cassettes connect the roof to the wall. The pitch is lit by 324 LED floodlights, arranged in 54 groups of six and attached to the columns of the roofing system.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://luxreview.com/article/2018/03/pitch-lights-will-be-led-says-spurs |title=Pitch lights will be LED, says Spurs |date=6 March 2018|work=LUX |accessdate=12 July 2018 }}</ref> There are four large LED screens inside the stadium, the two on the south side are the largest of any stadium in Western Europe.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/spurs-new-stadium-completion-date-14660098 |title=New Spurs stadium: Latest photos, video and completion date as we walk around site |first=Alasdair |last=Gold|work=football.london|date= 17 May 2018 }}</ref> There are also two facade video displays on the outside of the stadium, three tiers of LED ribbon displays inside, and nearly 1,800 video screens in and around the stadium.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.daktronics.com/news/Pages/Tottenham-Hotspur-Selects-Daktronics-For-New-Stadium.aspx |title=Tottenham Hotspur Selects Daktronics To Provide LED Video Displays For New Stadium |work=Daktronics }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thestadiumbusiness.com/2018/03/27/daktronics-supply-led-displays-new-tottenham-stadium/ |title=Daktronics to supply LED displays for new Tottenham stadium |work=TheStadiumBusiness|date= 27 March 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/the-club/partners/our-suppliers/lg/ |title=LG |work=Tottenham Hotspur |accessdate=30 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe stadium is designed like a concert hall with good acoustics in mind so as to optimise the atmosphere on match day.<ref name=\"gq\"/> The corners of the stadium are enclosed and the stands are placed close to the pitch, with fans generating a \"wall of sound\" that can reverberate around the ground.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenhams-new-stadium-will-have-better-atmosphere-than-arsenals-emirates-says-spurs-director-a3429286.html |title=Tottenham's new stadium will have better atmosphere than Arsenal's Emirates, says Spurs director Donna-Maria Cullen|first=Tom |last=Dutton |date=29 December 2016 |work=Evening Standard}}</ref><ref name=\"clad\">{{cite web |url= http://www.cladglobal.com/news?codeid=329763 |title=White Hart Lane: Populous MD lifts the lid on the design of Tottenham's community-driven new stadium|first= Kim|last= Megson |date= 20 January 2017|work=Clad News }}</ref> The design extends to the shape and material of the roof and the seating, such as aluminium [[soffit]] lining to the roof, and aims to produce cleaner and quicker reverberation times that allow fans to sing in sync thereby producing chants that are louder and last longer.<ref name=\"gq\"/>  The stadium is also designed to maintain the character but noisier than White Hart Lane and facilitate a sense of \"home\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48076482 |title=Tottenham Hotspur: New stadium is like a town hall, architect says |date=27 April 2019 |work =BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://populous.com/make-it-loud-designing-for-atmosphere-at-new-tottenham-hotspur-stadium |title=Make it Loud: Designing for Atmosphere at New Tottenham Hotspur Stadium |date=April 15, 2019 |work=Populous}}</ref>\n\n===Stands===\n[[File:Tottenham Hotspur Stadium South Stand.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|The South Stand, also known as the Park Lane end, before the [[UEFA Champions League]] quarter-final with [[Manchester City F.C.]] on 9 April 2019, with fans displaying the club motto 'To Dare Is to Do'.]]\nAlthough the stadium is designed as a bowl, it still has four distinct stands.<ref name=\"gq\"/> The tiers of the stands are set at angles of up to 35 degrees, the maximum permissible in British stadium design,<ref name=white>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/03/22/tottenham-hotspurs-new-home-sets-benchmark-modern-stadia/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur\u2019s new home sets benchmark for modern stadia | first=Jim |last=White |date=22 March 2019|work=The Telegraph |accessdate=22 March 2019 }}</ref><ref name=hytner2019>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/mar/24/tottenham-new-stadium-mauricio-pochettino |title=Intimacy, awe and a salute to Gazza: Spurs throw open doors to new home |first=David |last=Hytner|date= 24 March 2019 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=24 March 2019 }}</ref> and all seats provide clear views of the pitch for the ticket holders.<ref name=\"access\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://cartilagefreecaptain.sbnation.com/2015/10/2/9437987/tottenham-hotspur-new-stadium-details-interior-bowl-drawings |title=Spurs' new stadium interior designed to enhance fan views|first= Matthew |last=Pachniuk |date= 2 October 2015 |work=Cartilage Free Captain|accessdate=26 March 2019}}</ref> The South Stand is designated the 'Home End', and it has a single tier which is the largest [[Spion Kop (stadiums)|single-tier stand]] in the country, with seating for 17,500 fans. It is 34.1m high with a 34 degree incline, has concourses on Level 1, 2, 3 and 4 and is accessible from the south atrium.<ref name=\"guide\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/media/6426/tottenhamhotspur-2018-19season-newstadium.pdf |title=Welcome to Our New Home |accessdate=11 January 2019 |work=Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref> The design of the South Stand is influenced by the \"Yellow Wall\" of [[Borussia Dortmund]]'s [[Westfalenstadion|Signal Iduna Park]] and the stand is intended to be the \"heart-beat\" of the stadium that can generate an intense atmosphere on match day.<ref name=\"gq\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/six-things-you-need-to-know-about-the-new-tottenham-stadium |title=Spurs stadium designers: \"We've built it like a concert hall\" |first= Stuart |last=McGurk |date=23 January 2017|work=GQ}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://populous.com/posts/behind-design-single-tier-stand-drive-atmosphere-tottenham-hotspurs-new-south-stand/ |title=Behind the Design: The Single-Tier Stand to Drive Atmosphere of Tottenham Hotspur's New South Stand |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180406230857/https://populous.com/posts/behind-design-single-tier-stand-drive-atmosphere-tottenham-hotspurs-new-south-stand/ |archivedate=6 April 2018 |date=21 December 2017 |work=Populous}}</ref><ref name=\"plan\"/> \n[[File:Home team dugout at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium.jpg|thumb|left|Home [[Technical area|dugout]] below the West Stand]]\nThe 35.5m high North Stand has three tiers with concourses on Level 1, 2, 4 and 5.<ref name=\"guide\"/> The East and West Stands are 33.8 m and 33.2 m high respectively, and have concourses on Level 1 and 5. Both stands have four tiers each, two of which are smaller and intended for [[Club seating|premium seating]].<ref name=\"guide\"/> There are around 8,000 of these premium seats as well as 70 private [[luxury box|loges]] and super loges for premium members and corporate hospitality.<ref name=stone>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47687411 |title=Tottenham: A glimpse inside Spurs' new \u00a31bn state-of-the-art stadium|first= Simon|last= Stone|work=BBC Sport|date=24 March 2019|accessdate=25 March 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/spurs/80756/new-spurs-stadium-tunnel-views-at-eyewatering-prices |title=New Spurs stadium: tunnel views at eyewatering prices |date=20 January 2017|work=The Week |accessdate=21 July 2018 }}</ref><ref name=moore>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2019/mar/30/new-spurs-stadium-review-tottenham-hotspur-lets-call-it-a-home-win |title=Spurs\u2019 new stadium: let\u2019s call it a home win |first=Rowan |last=Moore|date= 30 March 2019 |accessdate=7 April 2019|work=The Observer }}</ref> The seats of the stadium, initially numbered 62,062 but later increased twice to 62,303,<ref name=capacity /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/11277777/tottenhams-new-stadium-capacity-increased-to-62062|title=Spurs stadium capacity increased to 62,062|date= 5 March 2018|publisher=Sky Sports|accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref> are in navy blue,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://talksport.com/football/391399/tottenham-new-stadium-seats-ripped-out-building-blunder/ |title= Tottenham's new stadium to have 15,000 seats ripped out after building blunder |work=talkSPORT|date=27 June 2018 }}</ref> with 42,000 of these reserved for season ticket holders.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/may-article-import/2018/welcome-home-secure-your-seat-and-look-around-the-new-stadium/ |title=Welcome Home - Secure Your Seat and 'Look Around' the New Stadium |work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club }}</ref> The seats have a minimum width of 470mm (compared with the 455\u2013460 mm of the previous stadium), increasing to 520\u2013700 mm for premium seats, with legroom of between 780 to 858mm.<ref name=7facts /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thstofficial.com/thst-news/new-stadium-qa-thst-thfc-and-populous-13-july-2015 |title=New Stadium Q&A: THST, THFC and Populous - 13 July 2015 |date=16 July 2015|work=Tottenham Hotspur Supporters Trust |accessdate=14 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:View of North Stand in Tottenham Hotspur Stadium.jpg|thumb|The North Stand, seating for away fans is in the right corner. The Sky Bridge is above the North Stand.]]\nAway fans are allocated seats in the north east corner; 3,000 seats in the lower tier for Premier League games, while for domestic cups they may be allocated up to 15% of the capacity spread over three tiers.<ref name=7facts>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/seven-key-answers-spurs-new-12913685|title= Seven key answers about Spurs' new stadium including if White Hart Lane's cockerels will be saved |first=Alasdair |last= Gold|date= 19 April 2017 |work=football.london }}</ref>  The stands include areas with 7,500 seats that can be quickly turned into safe standing areas should there be a change in the legislation that banned standing in football stadiums.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/06/26/tottenhams-new-stadium-has-future-proofed-safe-standing/ |title=Tottenham's new stadium has been 'future-proofed' for safe standing |first=Sam |last=Dean |date=26 June 2018 |work=Daily Telegraph |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tottenham-hotspur-can-convert-to-safe-standing-within-an-hour-vc5hfpmsl |title=Tottenham Hotspur can convert to safe-standing within an hour |first=Martyn |last=Ziegler|work=The Times|date=27 July 2018 |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2018/june/club-s-future-proofed-areas-offer-new-concept-in-safe-standing-debate/|title=Club\u2019s future-proofed areas offer new concept in safe standing debate |date=25 June 2018 |accessdate=26 March 2019|work =Tottenham Hotspur F.C. }}</ref> A family area is located in the north west corner for those attending with their children. Disabled fans are catered for with 265 wheelchair bays, areas for assistance dogs as well as facilities for those with \"complex care requirements\".<ref name=stone /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://ask.tottenhamhotspur.com/hc/en-us/articles/209483865-Accessibility |title=Ask Spurs: Accessibility |work=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |accessdate=20 July 2019 }}</ref>  Accessible seating is available in all four stands, where the design allows for flexible seating for family groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/may-article-import/2018/welcome-home-secure-your-seat-and-look-around-the-new-stadium/ |title=Welcome Home - Secure Your Seat and 'Look Around' the New Stadium |date=12 March 2018 |work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |accessdate=13 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Pitches===\nThe association football pitch of the stadium has a standard dimension of 105m x 68m, same in size as the pitches at [[Old Trafford]] and Wembley Stadium, but 440 square metres larger than the pitch at White Hart Lane.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/15122/10989411/will-the-bigger-wembley-pitch-affect-tottenham-this-season |title= Will the bigger Wembley pitch affect Tottenham this season? |first= Adam |last=Smith|date= 16 August 2017 |work=Sky Sports}}</ref> The overall grass surface is 114.58\u00d779.84 metres, including the perimeter between the pitch and the stands. The distances between the stands and the pitch are minimised so as to enhance the atmosphere on match days &ndash; {{convert|7.97|m|ft|1}} on the east, north and west sides from the front of the stand to the pitch, and {{convert|4.985|m|ft|1}} at the south end of the pitch.<ref name=\"bowl\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/AttachmentShowServlet?ImageName=748767 |title=Tottenham Hotspur Design and Access Statement 2015 |work=Haringey Council }}</ref>\n\nIn order to keep the football pitch in optimum condition, there are two different surfaces &ndash; a [[Desso GrassMaster]] hybrid grass pitch for football, and a synthetic turf [[American football field|surface]] underneath to be used for NFL games, as well as concerts and other events.<ref name=\"bowl\"/><ref name=\"populous\">{{cite web|url=https://populous.com/project/tottenham-hotspur-football-club/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |work=Populous }}</ref> The football pitch can be retracted in a way similar to that of the [[Arizona Cardinals]]' [[State Farm Stadium|home stadium]], but it is the first in the world to split into three sections before retracting.<ref name=ingenia>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham-give-impressive-first-look-at-wordfirst-dividing-retractable-pitch-for-new-stadium-a3629321.html|title= Tottenham give impressive first look at 'world-first dividing retractable pitch' for new stadium|first=Alex|last= Young |date= 7 September 2017 |work=Evening Standard }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/09/07/tottenham-hotspur-will-have-worlds-first-dividing-retractable/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur will have world's first dividing retractable pitch, so they can host football and NFL |date=7 September 2017 |work=The Daily Telegraph }}</ref>  The pitch needed to split so as to accommodate the two columns that support the South Stand when retracting.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ingenia.org.uk/Ingenia/Articles/a57524c7-215a-484d-9ffb-94c16030f3fc |title=The football pitch in three pieces|first=Richard |last=Gray |work=Ingenia |date= December 2018 |accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> Each of the three sections weighs more than 3,000 tonnes, and is made up of 33 smaller trays, making a total of 99 trays, with a combined weight of 10,000 tonnes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/01/26/installation-work-starts-on-spurs-retractable-pitch/ |title=Installation work starts on Spurs retractable pitch |first=Grant |last=Prior |date=26 January 2018|work=Construction Enquirer}}</ref> The retracting pitch slides into the car park under the South Stand and the south podium, and the surface can be switched in between 25 minutes to an hour.<ref name=ingenia /><ref name=ibbetson /> The NFL pitch is placed 1.6 metres beneath the natural turf surface, and the change in height when the surface is switched also produces ideal sightlines for the front row for both codes (NFL team personnel tend to stand pitchside in allocated areas which would block the view of the front row if the pitch is not lower in NFL games).<ref name=ingenia /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/long-reads/tottenham-hotspur-white-hart-lane-new-stadium-football/ |title=Spurs are starting a stadium design revolution in Tottenham|first=Rob |last=Hastings |date= 24 January 2017|work=iNews|accessdate=20 July 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://eandt.theiet.org/content/articles/2019/11/dual-use-at-spurs-new-stadium-gives-nfl-a-london-base/ |title=Dual-use at Spurs\u2019 stadium gives NFL a London base |first= Crispin |last=Andrews|date=13 November 2019 |work= Engineering and Technology|accessdate=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Grow lights over the pitch at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium.jpg|thumb|[[Grow lights]] suspended on trusses over the pitch]]\nThe stadium features the world's first integrated grow lighting system over the pitch. [[Grow light]]s are suspended on six 70-metre trusses to encourage the growth of the grass in the shaded areas of the stadium, and they can be folded away under the North Stand when not in use.<ref name=\"conway\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45586929 |title=Spurs' new stadium 'will be greatest ever built' says chief engineer |first= Richard|last= Conway|date=26 September 2018 |work=BBC Sport }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/new-tottenham-stadium-pitch-structures-15125801 |title=Revealed: What the new metal structures fans have spotted at Spurs' new stadium are for |first=Alasdair |last=Gold |date=9 September 2018 |work=football.london }}</ref><ref name=\"ouzia\">{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/new-tottenham-stadium-pitch-laid-at-new-ground-spurs-unveil-world-first-technology-a3954946.html |title= New Tottenham stadium: Pitch is laid as Spurs unveil 'world-first' technology|first=Malik|last= Ouzia |work=The Evening Standard |date=5 October 2018 |accessdate=6 October 2018 }}</ref> The grass can also be maintained for up to 5 days with artificial lighting, air ventilation, dehumidification and irrigation systems when the pitch is retracted under the south podium.<ref name=ibbetson>{{cite web |url=https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/behind-the-scenes-look-at-tottenhams-retractable-pitch/10041699.article |title=Behind the scenes look at Tottenham\u2019s retractable pitch |date=4 April 2019 |first= Connor |last= Ibbetson |accessdate=8 May 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/events/business-of-sport/christopher-lee-architect-populous/ |title=Architect Christopher Lee from Populous talks modern stadium design|date=3 June 2016|first=David |last=Edwards |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stadia-magazine.com/videos/how-tottenham-hotspur-stadiums-smart-pitch-lighting-system-works.html |title=How Tottenham Hotspur Stadium\u2019s smart pitch lighting system works|work=Stadia Magazine |accessdate=21 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Facilities===\n[[File:Home dressing room at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium.jpg|thumb|left|Home [[dressing room]] at the stadium]]\nThe stadium provides separate facilities for football and NFL players; these include changing rooms, medical facilities, restaurants, [[hydrotherapy]] pools, warm-up areas, pre-match players' lounge, as well as lounges and creches for their families.<ref name=hayward /> It also caters for the different requirements of football and NFL media.<ref name=white /> There are a number of bars for fans on match day. In the South Stand is the Goal Line Bar, which at 65m is the longest in Europe. The White Hart and The Shelf are bars in the East Stand, while The Dispensary is found in the West Stand.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://new-stadium.tottenhamhotspur.com/season-tickets/our-feature-bars/home/ |title= Our Feature Bars |work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> The stadium offers a wide range of food and drinks outlets (65 at the club opening);<ref name=washington /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11683043/tottenhams-new-stadium-watch-the-opening-ceremony-live |title=Tottenham's new stadium: Watch the opening ceremony on Sky Sports|work=Sky Sports |date= 29 March 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019 }}</ref> in the South Stand is the 'Market Place' with a range of food and drink outlets, and a selection of food outlets are also available in other stands.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.compass-group.co.uk/media/news/levy-uk-and-tottenham-hotspur-announces-winning-food-and-drink-offering-for-new-stadium/ |title=Levy UK and Tottenham Hotspur announces winning food and drink offering for new stadium |date=21 June 2018|work=Compass |accessdate=12 July 2018 }}</ref><ref name=stone />  Other features include an in-house bakery and the world's first [[microbrewery]] in a stadium, which can produce one million pints of craft beer a year and deliver up to 10,000 pints a minute.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/01/20/tottenham-give-taster-new-stadium-micro-brewery/ |title=Tottenham give taster of new stadium... with its own micro brewery |first=Jason|last= Burt|date=20 January 2017 |work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=8 July 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2018/may/beavertown-to-open-microbrewery-at-clubs-new-stadium/ |title=Beavertown to open Microbrewery at Club's new stadium |date=30 May 2018 |work=Tottenham Hotspur |accessdate=13 July 2018 }}</ref> The stadium is the first cashless stadium in the country, it also offers stadium-wide connectivity for all the fans with more [[Wi-Fi]] access points and [[Bluetooth]] beacons as well as greater bandwidth than any other stadium.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/f8303438-571e-11e9-91f9-b6515a54c5b1 |title=Spurs stadium\u2019s wireless wonders |first=Chris|last= Nuttall |work=Financial Times |date=4 April 2019 |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://telecoms.com/496746/spurs-and-hpe-hope-to-show-how-stadium-wifi-should-be-done/ |title=Spurs and HPE hope to show how stadium wifi should be done |first=Scott|last= Bicheno |date=3 April 2019 |accessdate=4 April 2019 |work=Telecoms }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190418005264/en/Real-Wireless-Tottenham-Hotspur-Stadium-%E2%80%93-Best-Connected |title=Real Wireless: Tottenham Hotspur Stadium \u2013 the Best-Connected in the UK|date= 18 April 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2019 |work=Business Wire}}</ref> Some car parking spaces, but not for general admission fans, are provided underneath the stand and in the basement. A range of hospitality facilities in the East and West Stands are provided for those with premium memberships. These include two Sky Lounges on the top floor of the East and West Stands, with views over London and the pitch, the Sky Bridge, which is the world's first bridge to be suspended from the roof of a stadium, 65 suites of private loges and super loges, [[Michelin star]] level dining, and the Tunnel Club that allows its members to observe the players as they walk from the dressing room to the pitch through a glass-walled tunnel.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tunnel-club-michelincalibre-food-and-even-a-microbrewery-the-premium-side-of-tottenhams-new-stadium-a3445081.html |title=New Tottenham stadium: Tunnel Club, Michelin-calibre food and even a micro-brewery - The premium side of Tottenham's new stadium |first=Mark|last= Blunden |date= 20 January 2017 |work=Evening Standard |accessdate=11 July 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/new-spurs-stadium-roof-restaurant-13240166 |title=Details of new Spurs stadium's \u00a320m roof emerge with luxury restaurant that will 'hang from it' |first=Alasdair |last=Gold |date= 26 June 2017|work=football.london |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jan/20/tottenham-hotspur-new-stadium-cheese-white-hart-lane |title=Big cheeses: Tottenham\u2019s new stadium to give half-time snacks fancy flavour|first= Amy|last= Lawrence|date=20 January 2017 |accessdate=7 November 2018 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tottenham Hotspur Stadium - northwest corner February 2019.jpg|thumb|Northwest corner of stadium, with access to the north podium, the Paxton ticket office and a cafe]]\nThe stadium is intended to be active all year round as a sports and entertainment destination with conference and banqueting facilities. It offers visitor attractions such as a Sky Walk, whereby visitors may walk up the side of the stadium, right up to the roof which has a glass walkway around the golden cockerel over the South Stand where they may view the goal line from the roof, or abseil down to the south podium from a viewing deck.<ref name=\"plan\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dezeen.com/2019/04/03/tottenham-hotspur-stadium-football-club-design-populous/ |title=Populous completes \"best stadium in the world\" for Tottenham Hotspur |first=Tom |last=Ravenscroft |date= 3 April 2019 |work=De Zeen |accessdate=20 April 2019 }}</ref> The East Stand includes a double-height banquet hall that may be used for conference events.<ref name=\"populous\"/> To the south of the stadium, the raised podium forms a large open public square that may be used for a range of sporting and community activities. The Tottenham Experience, which includes a club shop, club archive and museum on Tottenham High Road, serves as the arrivals hub for visitors, where they may collect tickets and start a tour of the stadium. The museum is located in the Grade II listed Warmington House, and the new club shop is the largest in Europe, featuring a 100-seat auditorium area that may be used for pre-match experiences.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://i.tottenhamhotspur.com/hc/en-us/articles/209100129-Tottenham-Experience |title=Tottenham Experience |work=iSpurs |accessdate= 13 July 2018}}</ref> On the northwest corner is M cafe, a media room that may be open to the public and used as a cafe on non-match days.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/inside-tottenhams-stadium-10-brilliant-features-to-look-out-for-at-first-game-against-crystal-palace-a4108336.html |title=Inside Tottenham's stadium: 10 brilliant features to look out for at first game against Crystal Palace |first=Dan |last=Kilpatrick |date=3 April 2019 |accessdate=20 April 2019 |work= Evening Standard }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/new-spurs-stadium-photos-section-16573151 |title=New Spurs stadium: Photos and all you need to know from inside the latest section to open today|first=Alasdair |last=Gold|date= 12 July 2019 |work=football.london |accessdate=12 July 2019}}</ref> Other facilities may be offered in ancillary buildings surrounding the stadium, including a ticket office, and a planned extreme sports building as well as a community health centre.<ref name=\"populous\"/>\n\n===Statuary===\n\nA 4.5-m-tall and near-double-sized [[fibreglass]] replica of the spurs cockerel, originally created in 1909 to sit atop the west stand at White Hart Lane, was placed on the roof structure above the South Stand on 6 November 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://talksport.com/football/442641/tottenham-hotspur-new-stadium-update-golden-cockerel-spurs/ |title=ICONIC Tottenham new stadium update: Golden Cockerel arrives and is pictured on top of the South Stand |first=Billy |last=Hawkins|date=7 November 2018 |work=Talk Sport |accessdate =7 November 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2018/september/golden-cockerel-to-grace-new-stadium-roof/ |title=Golden Cockerel to grace new stadium roof |date= 10 September 2018|work=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |accessdate=22 August 2019 }}</ref> It is a faithful replica of the original, including dents caused by [[Paul Gascoigne]] when he shot at it with an [[air rifle]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://uk.sports.yahoo.com/news/story-paul-gascoigne-spurs-famous-cockerel-air-rifle-110956540.html |title=The story of Paul Gascoigne, Spurs' famous cockerel and an air rifle |first=Matt |last=Storey|work=Yahoo! Sport |date=10 September 2018 |accessdate =7 July 2019 }}</ref>  A statue of [[Bill Nicholson (footballer)|Bill Nicholson]] will be placed on the south west approach to the stadium; the old gate to the West Stand from White Hart Lane will also be placed here, and the statue of Nicholson will be positioned at its centre, recreating a historic photographic image of Nicholson.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news-archive-1/a-fitting-place-for-bill-in-new-stadium-plans/ |title=A fitting place for Bill in new stadium plans |work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |accessdate=21 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\nThe stadium is the home of Tottenham Hotspur, who play their Premier League and other cup home matches at the ground. The stadium is also used for other football events; in its first year, it was used for a live screening of the [[2019 UEFA Champions League Final]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/grief-was-shared-in-a-giant-gogglebox-experience-at-spurs-new-stadium-3md67bk6k |title=Grief was shared in a giant Gogglebox experience at Spurs\u2019 new stadium |first=Glenn |last=Ebrey |date=2 June 2019|work= The Sunday Times |accessdate=12 June 2019 }}</ref> select [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Under-23s]] games,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2019/august/under-23s-to-appreciate-and-cherish-new-stadium-match-on-friday/ |title=Under-23s to 'appreciate and cherish' new stadium match on Friday |date= 14 August 2019|work=Tottenham Hotspur |accessdate=10 September 2019 }}</ref> as well as the first North London derby in the [[FA Women's Super League]] between Tottenham and Arsenal held on 17 November 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48934921 |title=Women's Super League: Tottenham Hotspur Stadium to host Spurs v Arsenal in November|work=BBC Sports |date=10 July 2019 |accessdate=10 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe stadium is intended to be used for a number of purposes aside from association football, serving as the venue for NFL games and other events. It is can host up to 16 non-association football events a year, at least two of which will be NFL games, and up to six music concerts.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/tottenham-hotspur/story/3042015/tottenham-aiming-for-premier-leagues-best-atmosphere-at-new-stadium |title= Tottenham want Premier League's best atmosphere in building new stadium |date=20 January 2017|first=Dan |last=Kilpatrick |work=ESPN |accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref> \n===NFL London Games===\n{{main|NFL International Series}}\n[[File:Carolina Panthers logo at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium.jpg|thumb|Logo of [[Carolina Panthers]] at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium]]\nTottenham Hotspur Stadium is the first and only stadium to be designed specially for NFL games outside of North America.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/04/sport/nfl-london-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-spt-intl-gbr/index.html |title=Could London become a permanent home for the NFL?|first= George|last= Ramsay|work= CNN|date=4 October 2019}}</ref> The first game at the stadium took place on 6 October 2019 when the [[2019 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]] played against the [[2019 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]]. A record crowd of 60,463 watched the Raiders win a close game 24\u201321.<ref name=\"nflfirrst\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/american-football/49954966 |title=Oakland Raiders 24-21 Chicago Bears: Raiders win first NFL game at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium|first= Ben |last=Collins |work=BBC Sport|date=7 October 2019 |accessdate=7 October 2019}}</ref> The following week, the [[2019 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] hosted the [[2019 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]] on October 13.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/american-football/47967256 |title=NFL London: Schedule announced for Tottenham Stadium & Wembley games | work=BBC Sport |date= 17 April 2019|accessdate= 17 April 2019 }}</ref>\nA number of NFL events were held at the stadium before the first game; the trials for the first intake of the NFL Academy was launched at the stadium on 2 July 2019;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/jul/02/nfl-american-football-tottenham-london-academy-way-out-teenagers |title=NFL comes to London offering way out for trapped teenagers |first=Robert |last=Booth |date= 2 July 2019 |work=The Guardian|accessdate=7 July 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://talksport.com/sport/us-sports/567007/tottenham-hotspur-stadium-nfl-beckham/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur Stadium looks incredible in NFL mode with star wide receiver Odell Beckham Jr hailing the facilities as 'better than back home'|first =Josh |last=Fordham|date=2 July 2019|work=talkSport |accessdate=5 July 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://sportsvenuebusiness.com/index.php/2019/07/02/nfl-makes-its-debut-at-the-new-tottenham-hotspur-stadium/ |title=NFL Makes Its Debut at the New Tottenham Hotspur Stadium|work=Sports Venue Business |date=2 July 2019 |accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref> and the national NFL Flag Championship, [[flag football]] competition for UK schoolchildren aged 8\u201311, were the first such games held at the stadium on 3 July 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url= \nhttp://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001035148/article/nfl-flag-champions-crowned-at-tottenham-hotspur-stadium |title=NFL Flag champions crowned at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium|date=4 July 2019 |work=NFL | accessdate=5 July 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.silverandblackpride.com/2019/6/15/18680233/tahir-whitehead-to-represent-raiders-for-series-of-july-events-in-london |title=Tahir Whitehead to represent Raiders for series of July events in London|first= Levi |last=Damien|date=15 June 2019|work=SBNation }}</ref>\n\nThe first [[Touchdown|touchdown]] at the stadium was scored by [[Josh Jacobs]].\n\n===Rugby===\nThe [[rugby union]] club [[Saracens F.C.|Saracens]] will also play their annual showpiece game at the stadium for five years starting in 2020,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/47787038 |title=Saracens to play annual showpiece at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium |work=BBC |date=2 April 2019 |accessdate=2 April 2019 }}</ref> with the first game taking place between Saracens and [[Harlequin F.C.|Harlequins]] {{efn|Match was originally scheduled for 28 March 2020, but was postponed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/rugby/date-confirmed-for-saracens-vs-harlequins-at-tottenhams-new-stadium-a4186556.html |title=Date confirmed for Saracens vs Harlequins at Tottenham's new stadium |first=Simon |last= Collings |date=10 July 2019 |work=Evening Standard|accessdate=10 July 2019 }}</ref> The stadium will also host the [[European Rugby Champions Cup]] and [[European Rugby Challenge Cup|Challenge Cup]] finals in 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/new-tottenham-stadium-to-stage-rugby-cup-finals-in-2021-a4135906.html |title=New Tottenham stadium to stage rugby cup finals in 2021|first=Simon|last= Collings|work=Evening Standard |date=7 May 2019 |accessdate=7 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe first [[rugby league]] match at the stadium will be the [[2020 Kangaroo tour of England#Third Test|third and final test]] in the 2020 [[The Ashes (rugby league)|Ashes series]] between [[England national rugby league team|England]] and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] on 14 November 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/rugby-league/50329514 |title=Tottenham Hotspur Stadium to host final England v Australia Ashes test in 2020 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=7 November 2019 |website=[[BBC Online]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |access-date=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Concerts===\nThe first concerts scheduled at the stadium will be by [[Guns N' Roses]] to be held on 29\u201330 May 2020 as part of the European leg of their [[Guns N' Roses 2020 Tour]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/guns-n-roses-announce-london-show-on-2020-european-stadium-tour-2587075 |title=Guns N' Roses add second huge London show to 2020 European stadium tour |first=Nick |last= Reilly |date= 13 December 2019|work=NME |accessdate=21 December 2019 }}</ref>  [[Capital (radio network)|Capital]]'s music event [[Summertime Ball]] was planned to be held at the stadium on 6 June 2020 but cancelled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/spurs-confirm-major-event-stadium-17708662 |title= Spurs confirm major summer event at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium |first=Josh |last=Challies|date= 7 February 2020 |work=football.london |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/capital-summertime-ball-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-cancelled-a4392096.html |title=Capital\u2019s Summertime Ball at the Tottenham Hotspur Stadium cancelled as organisers react to threat of coronavirus |first=Harry|last=Fletcher |work=Evening Standard |date=19 March 2020 }}</ref> [[Lady Gaga]] will also perform at the stadium as part of [[The Chromatica Ball]] to support her new album ''[[Chromatica]]'' on 30 July 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/lady-gaga-the-chromatica-ball-tour-london-date-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-tickets-2620807 |title= Lady Gaga announces huge UK date on 'The Chromatica Ball Tour'|first=Sam |last=Moore|work=NME |date=5 March 2020|accessdate=5 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Boxing===\nThe stadium will host the very first bout between the English defending [[World Boxing Association|WBA (super)]], [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]], [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]], and [[International Boxing Organization|IBO]] world champion [[Anthony Joshua]] and Bulgarian IBF [[mandatory challenger]] [[Kubrat Pulev]] for the heavyweight world titles, on 20 June 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/51705419 |title=Anthony Joshua to fight Kubrat Pulev at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium |date=2 March 2020 |work=BBC |accessdate=2 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Attendance==\nThe stadium has a capacity of 62,303 (initially 62,062), but due to the need to segregate fans, the full capacity may never be reached for association football matches as some seats are deliberately kept unused.<ref name=goldopening>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/things-love-tottenham-new-stadium-16081735 |title=Three things we loved about Tottenham's new stadium and three things we didn't|first=Alasdair |last=Gold|date= 5 April 2019|work=football.london|accessdate=4 April 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"kilpatrick2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/smaller-than-emirates-stadium-why-tottenham-may-struggle-to-fill-62062-capacity-at-1bn-new-home-a4109196.html|title=Smaller than Emirates Stadium? Why Tottenham may struggle to fill 62,062 capacity at \u00a31bn new home |first=Dan|last= Kilpatrick|work=Evening Standard|date=4 April 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019 }}</ref>  Attendance is counted by the number of fans going through the gates rather than the number of tickets issued as is the case in some grounds such as the [[Emirates Stadium|Emirates]] as well as Spurs at Wembley where attendance figures may include season ticket holders who did not turn up for matches and unused free tickets.<ref name=\"kilpatrick2019\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsvibe.co.uk/2019/04/05/when-is-a-capacity-not-a-capacity-ask-spurs-or-arsenal/|title=When is a capacity not a capacity \u2013 Ask Spurs or Arsenal! |date=5 April 2019 |work=Sportsvibe |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45158878 |title=Football club attendances: Are fans getting the full picture? |first= Alistair |last=Magowan |date=12 September 2019|work=BBC Sport |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> The first match after its official opening, although sold out, was attended by 59,215 fans as some rows of seating were kept empty and some premium areas were not yet opened.<ref name=goldopening /><ref name=\"kilpatrick2019\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6337444-the-reason-why-tottenham-hotspur-did-not-have-full-capacity-for-first-match-at-new-stadium |title=The Reason Why Tottenham Hotspur Did Not Have Full Capacity for First Match at New Stadium|first=Tom |last=Gott|date=5 April 2019 |work=90Min |accessdate=6 April 2019}}</ref> Attendance in the first season at the stadium averaged at 59,175 from the 7 home matches played there, compared to 59,826 for all home matches that season, most of which were played at Wembley which has a higher capacity.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.footballwebpages.co.uk/premier-league/attendances |title=Premier League \u2013 Average Attendances \u2013 Home Matches |work=Football Web Pages |accessdate=4 September 2019 }}</ref> \n\nThe official stadium record attendance for a Tottenham game currently stands at 61,104 in the English Premier League match against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on 22 December 2019.<ref name=\"record attendance\" />  The previous highest attendance for any game was the first NFL game held at the stadium  on 6 October 2019 between [[Chicago Bears]] and [[Oakland Raiders]], which was watched by 60,463 spectators.<ref name=\"nflfirrst\"/>  It recorded the highest ever attendance for a [[FA Women's Super League|Women's Super League]] match at 38,262 in the match against [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal Women]] held on 17 November 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50363864 |title=Tottenham Hotspur Women 0 : 2 Arsenal Women |first=Tom |last=Garry|work=BBC |date=17 November 2019 |accessdate= 2 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Cost, finance and sponsorship==\n[[File:East entrance of Tottenham Hotspur Stadium on Worcester Avenue.jpg|thumb|East entrance on Worcester Avenue]]\nAn early estimate put Phase 2 of the development, that includes the construction of the stadium, at \u00a3305 million,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/09c-MRF-Stage-2-North-Tottenham-Project-Appraisal%20RTF.rtf |url-status=dead |title=Project Appraisal From - Stage 2: Investment Decision |website=London.gov.uk |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902032013/https://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/09c-MRF-Stage-2-North-Tottenham-Project-Appraisal%20RTF.rtf |archivedate=2 September 2012 }}</ref> but in July 2018, it was reported that the construction of the stadium itself was projected to cost \u00a3350\u2013\u00a3400 million, out of the estimated \u00a3850 million cost for the entire Northumberland Development Project.<ref name=\"kilpatrick\">{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/new-tottenham-stadium-not-possible-without-2011-london-riots-a3898956.html |title=New Tottenham stadium 'not possible' without 2011 London riots|first=Dan |last=Kilpatrick |work=The Evening Standard |date=30 July 2018}}</ref> The cost had increased due to the higher cost of import by at least 15% caused by the [[Brexit]] vote on the exchange rate,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/daniel-levy-new-tottenham-stadium-club-new-dawn-a4316696.html |title=Daniel Levy: Delivering new Tottenham stadium is end of the beginning for club's new dawn|first=James|last= Olley |date= 18 December 2019 |work=Evening Standard |accessdate=30 December 2019 }}</ref> changes to the build, overtime working, extra hirings and higher construction costs.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham-reveal-cost-of-new-stadium-has-risen-to-800m-due-to-brexit-a3484516.html |title=New Tottenham Stadium: Tottenham reveal cost of new ground has risen to \u00a3800 million |first=Tom |last=Collomosse|date= 8 March 2017 |work=Evening Standard }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/08/16/spurs-stadium-builders-earning-more-than-the-players/ |title= Spurs stadium builders \"earning more than the players\"|first=Grant |last=Prior|work=Construction Enquirer|date=16 August 2018|accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref> The cost of the project was widely reported to be over \u00a31.2 billion, although the club had insisted that the final cost would be less than a billion.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/09/21/tottenham-insist-suggestions-12bn-final-stadium-bill-inaccurate/ |title=Tottenham insist suggestions of \u00a31.2bn final stadium bill are inaccurate |first=Matt |last=Law|date=21 September 2018 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref> Just before the stadium opened in April 2019, the club chairman [[Daniel Levy (businessman)|Daniel Levy]] said that the cost is of the order of one billion.<ref name=\"gilmour\">{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11682615/daniel-levy-says-tottenham-will-become-one-of-biggest-clubs-in-the-world |title=Daniel Levy says Tottenham will become one of biggest clubs in the World|first =Paul|last=Gilmour|date=3 April 2019|work=Sky Sports|accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe project was financed through a combination of club's own resources, bank loans and club revenues.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47794989 |title=Tottenham: New stadium can make Spurs one of world's biggest clubs, says Chairman Daniel Levy |work=BBC |date=2 April 2019|accessdate=3 April 2019 }}</ref> A \u00a3200 million interim financing facility was arranged in December 2015 with three banks to finance the project.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.insideworldfootball.com/2017/06/01/spurs-secure-400m-bank-loan-complete-740m-stadium-build/ |title=Spurs secure \u00a3400m bank loan to complete \u00a3740m stadium build |date=1 June 2017 |work=Inside Football World }}</ref> This was replaced in May 2017 by a \u00a3400 million, five-year loan, deal with the banks to fund the remaining build.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham-announce-400-million-deal-to-help-finance-new-stadium-a3553746.html |title=New Tottenham stadium: Spurs announce \u00a3400million loan deal to help finance new stadium |first=Tom |last=Collomosse|date= 31 May 2017 |work=Evening Standard }}</ref> By this stage, \u00a3340 million had already been spent on land acquisition and the planning process, as well as the construction cost; \u00a3100 million of this came from the 2015 interim financing, with the rest from club resources.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/spurs-loans-idUSL8N1IX54A| title=LPC-Tottenham Hotspur nets \u00a3400m stadium loan |first=Alasdair |last=Reilly|date=31 May 2017 |work=Reuters }}</ref>  However, with costs spiralling, the club was forced to borrow an extra \u00a3237 million, raising the financing facility to \u00a3637m.<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/tottenham-new-stadium-wembley-pitch-opening-when-ready-spending-debt-vs-manchester-city-a8608226.html |title=New Tottenham stadium: Spurs forced to borrow another \u00a3237m as costs continue to spiral|first=Jack |last=Pitt-Brooke |date=30 October 2018 |work=The Independent |accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref> In order to reduce debt-servicing costs and improve annual cash flow, \u00a3525 million of the debt was refinanced by issuing [[Bond (finance)|bonds]] that will mature in 15 to 30 years' time.  The bond issue was arranged by [[Bank of America Merrill Lynch]], which also provided a \u00a3112m loan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/b5931cd8-da1a-11e9-8f9b-77216ebe1f17 |title= Tottenham secures financial future with stadium debt deal |first1=Murad|last1= Ahmed|first2= Robert |last2=Smith|work=The Financial Times|date=20 September 2019|accessdate=20 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2019/september/club-refinances-construction-debt/ |title=Club Refinances Construction Debt|date=20 September 2019|work=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |accessdate=20 September 2019 }}</ref> The club aims to pay for the stadium through a number of means: income from ticket sales is forecast to increase to \u00a3100 million per year, more than twice that earned from White Hart Lane;<ref name=hayward>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/03/24/tottenham-hotspurs-new-ground-eclipses-north-london-rivalsemirates/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur's new ground eclipses north London rivals' Emirates Stadium \u2013 it was worth the long wait |first=Paul |last=Hayward|date=25 March 2019 |work=The Telegraph|accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref> revenues from other sports hosted at the stadium with the NFL contributing \u00a310 million to the initial cost;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.us/tottenham-hotspur/story/3108630/nfl-helping-fund-new-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-sources?ICID=ref_fark |title=NFL helping fund new Tottenham Hotspur stadium - sources |publisher=ESPN |date=21 April 2017 |author=Dan Kilpatrick |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> increased hospitality and catering income,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cateringinsight.com/kccj-outfit-is-bringing-spurs-800000-during-each-game/ |title=KCCJ outfit is bringing Spurs \u00a3800,000 during each game |first=Clare |last= Nicholls |date=30 April 2019 |work=Catering Insight }}</ref> as well as sponsorship, merchandising, advertising, concession and digital rights, and broadcast revenues.<ref name=washington />\n\n===Partnership and deals===\nThe club has a number of partners at the stadium. Following on tradition, Heineken, who have previously held sponsorship deals, have been named as the beer sponsor for the new stadium.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/partners/heineken-named-as-official-beer-partner-for-tottenham-hotspur-iconic-new-stadium-180518/ |title=Heineken named as official beer partner for Tottenham Hotspur's Iconic new stadium |publisher=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |date=18 May 2018 |accessdate=7 June 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616180354/https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/partners/heineken-named-as-official-beer-partner-for-tottenham-hotspur-iconic-new-stadium-180518/ |archivedate=16 June 2018 }}</ref> The north London brewer Beavertown is the official craft beer supplier and it installed the world's first stadium-located microbrewery on the south east corner of the stadium.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/tottenham-hotspur-team-up-with-beavertown-to-create-worlds-first-microbrewery-in-a-football-stadium-a3851201.html |title=Tottenham Hotspur team up with Beavertown to create world's first microbrewery in a football stadium|first=Tom|last= Powell |date= 30 May 2018 |work= Evening Standard }}</ref> The company selected by the club to supply the advertising system in the new ground will be TGI.<ref>{{cite web |title=TGI to deliver perimeter advertising system at club's new world-class stadium |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club/new-stadium/tgi-to-deliver-perimeter-advertising-system-310518/ |publisher=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |date=31 May 2018 |accessdate=4 June 2018 }}</ref> Tottenham signed a contract with [[LG Corporation|LG]] to supply the new stadium with Ultra-premium TVs and digital signage.<ref>{{cite web |title=LG Chosen to Supply Ultra-Premium TVS and Digital Signage across new stadium |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club/new-stadium/lg-chosen-to-supply-ultra-premium-tvs-and-digital-signage-across-new-stadium-010618/ |publisher=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |date=1 June 2018 |accessdate=4 June 2018 }}</ref> [[Hewlett Packard Enterprise]] is the IT networking and wireless infrastructure partner for the new stadium.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news-archive-1/hewlett-packard-enterprise-to-support-technology-vision-for-new-stadium/ |title=Hewlett Packard Enterprise to support technology vision for new vision |date=11 July 2018 |work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |accessdate= 1 August 2018}}</ref> The concessions for food and drink in the stadium are run by [[Levy Restaurants|Levy]], a subsidiary of [[Compass Group|Compass]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2019/03/27/businesses-making-tottenham-hotspurs-new-1bn-stadium-envy-premier/ |title=The businesses making Tottenham Hotspur's new \u00a31bn stadium the envy of its Premier League rivals|first= Oliver|last= Gill |date=28 March 2019|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Naming rights===\nThe stadium is named Tottenham Hotspur Stadium until a [[Naming rights|naming-rights]] agreement is reached.<ref name=\"name\">{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/new-tottenham-stadium-will-be-called-the-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-if-clubs-starts-season-without-a3776636.html |title=New Tottenham stadium will be called the 'Tottenham Hotspur Stadium' if club starts season without naming-rights deal |first=Tom |last= Collomosse |date= 27 February 2018 |work=London Evening Standard |accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref> The club is looking for deals variously reported to be worth \u00a320m annually (\u00a3400 million for a 20-year deal or \u00a3200 million for ten years),<ref name=\"thenational_726821\"/><ref name=\"telegraph_2018-08-30\"/> or \u00a325 million in a 15-year deal (\u00a3375 million).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/12/18/tottenham-hold-world-record-25m-a-year-deal-sell-stadium-naming/ |title=Exclusive: Tottenham hold out for world record \u00a325m-a-year deal to sell stadium naming rights but no buyer imminent |first= Matt |last=Law|date=18 December 2019 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Economic impact===\nThe club estimates that the stadium would inject around \u00a3293 million a year into the community in Tottenham, and create more than 1,700 new jobs out of the total of 3,500 jobs to be created when the project is complete.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/03/sports/tottenham-hotspur-stadium.html |title=Tottenham Hotspur Stadium Opens: Is There Room for Everyone? |first=Rory|last= Smith|date=April 3, 2019|work=The New York Times |accessdate=10 April 2019 }}</ref><ref name=winter>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tottenham-hotspurs-new-stadium-should-be-a-source-of-pride-for-all-of-football-9c5r8gcsd |title=Tottenham Hotspur\u2019s new stadium should be a source of pride for all of football |first= Henry|last= Winter|date=26 March 2019|work=The Times|accessdate=10 April 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:Spurs stadium January 2020.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|View towards the South Stand]]\nThe new stadium has received generally positive comments from fans as well as sports and architecture writers alike.  [[Paul Hayward (journalist)|Paul Hayward]] of ''The Telegraph'' described it as \"imposing and extravagant, yes, but still true to Tottenham Hotspur\u2019s spirit and ''raison d'\u00eatre''\".<ref name=hayward />  ''[[The Observer]]'''s architecture critic [[Rowan Moore]], despite being unimpressed by the \"ugliness\" of its external appearance, chose it as one of the top five buildings of 2019,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2019/dec/29/rowan-moore-best-architecture-of-2019 |title=Rowan Moore\u2019s best architecture of 2019 |first=Rowan |last=Moore|date= 29 December 2019 |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref> arguing that the stadium is at its best as a venue for watching football, and that it has achieved \"the desired combination of magnificence and intimacy\".<ref name=moore /> Similarly David Hytner of ''[[The Guardian]]'' noted that while the stadium is significantly larger, it still has the \"feeling of intimacy\" due to the closeness of the stands to the pitch, and that the design of the stadium has managed to \"retain the feel of the old White Hart Lane\".<ref name=hytner2019 /> [[Henry Winter]] of ''[[The Times]]'' offered the opinion that the new stadium has shown the other clubs \"the quality of spec required\" for a new stadium, and one that can produce the loudest sound for the fans. He also noted the significance of the new stadium within the community in Tottenham by helping to regenerate a deprived area blighted by riots, becoming a stadium that is \"a must-see stop on those touring London\u2019s architectural splendours\" and one should be a source of pride \"for all in the game\".<ref name=winter /> \n\nIn a survey of 4,302 fans organised by Tottenham Hotspur Supporters' Trust, 95% were satisfied with their experience attending games at the new stadium, compared to 52% of fans who were satisfied while Tottenham were playing at Wembley Stadium. 84% of those were satisfied with the atmosphere at the stadium for league game, rising to 98% for European games.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/tottenham-fans-reveal-what-they-love-about-new-stadium-and-what-needs-to-improve-a4201546.html |title= Tottenham fans reveal what they love about new stadium... and what needs to improve |first= Simon |last=Collings |work=Evening Standard |date=31 July 2019 |accessdate=5 August 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thstofficial.com/uploads/9/2/2/6/92268578/thst_annual_fans_survey_2019.pdf |title=Fan Survey 2019 |date=July 2019|accessdate=5 August 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe stadium won the Supreme Award for Structural Engineering Excellence in the [[Structural Awards]] from the [[Institution of Structural Engineers]] in 2019. It also won in the Long Span Structures category.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.istructe.org/structuralawards/winners |title=2019 Winners |work=The Institution of Structural Engineers |accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref> Other awards it has received in 2019 include [[Architects' Journal]]'s Architecture Awards for 'Best Leisure Project',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/aj-architecture-awards-2019-winner-leisure/10045344.article |title=AJ Architecture Awards 2019 winner: Leisure |date=20 November 2019 |first= Will |last= Hurst |work=Architects' Journal |accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref> the [[Building (magazine)|Building Magazine]] Project of the Year,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.building-awards.com/2019-winners/ |title=Congratulations to our Building Awards 2019 Winners! |work=Building Awards |accessdate=24 November 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.building.co.uk/buildings/buildings-projects-of-the-year-2019/5103446.article |title=Building\u2019s Projects of the Year 2019 |first=Ike |last=Ijeh |date=23 December 2019|work=Building|accessdate=29 December 2019 }}</ref> Gold awards from the World Interior News (WIN) in the Branding and Wayfinding category as well as for its general concourse design in the Leisure and Entertainment Interiors category,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldinteriorsnewsawards.com/winners-2019/ |title= Results 2019: Interiors |work=WIN Awards |accessdate=24 November 2019 }}</ref> Bronze Award in the Leisure category of the World Architecture News Awards,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wanawards.com/results-2019/ |title=Results 2019 |date=24 October 2019 |work=WAN Awards |accessdate=24 November 2019 }}</ref> Local Authority Building Control (LABC) Building Excellence Award in the Best Inclusive Building category for Tottenham Experience,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.labc.co.uk/awards/grand-finals-2019-winners |title=LABC Grand Finals Winners and Highly Commended 2019 |work=LABC |accessdate=24 November 2019 }}</ref> and Structural Steel Design Awards for Project of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.steelconstruction.org/2019/10/02/2019-structural-steel-design-awards-winners-announced/ |title=2019 Structural Steel Design Awards winners announced |date= 2 October 2019 |work=SteelConstruction.org }}</ref>\n\n==In popular media==\nThe stadium is the subject of an episode of ''Richard Hammond's Big'' where the presenter [[Richard Hammond]] explores the biggest things he can find, broadcast in February 2020 on [[Discovery Channel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/daniel-levy-makes-big-claim-17776817 |title=Daniel Levy makes big claim about Tottenham Hotspur Stadium plus what's still to be finished|first=Alasdair |last= Gold| date=19 February 2020 |work=football.london |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nThe stadium is accessible via a number of [[London Overground]], [[London Underground]] and [[National Rail]] stations: [[Seven Sisters station|Seven Sisters]], [[Tottenham Hale station|Tottenham Hale]], [[Northumberland Park railway station|Northumberland Park]], and [[White Hart Lane railway station|White Hart Lane]] stations. The nearest station, at around 200 m away, is White Hart Lane, which is on the London Overground line from [[Liverpool Street station]].<ref name=transport />   The station ticket hall was rebuilt in 2019, and a Wembley-style walkway for fans from the station to the stadium is planned. The next nearest is [[Northumberland Park railway station|Northumberland Park]] and fans can reached the stadium via Park Lane. Both Seven Sisters and Tottenham Hale stations are stops along the [[Victoria line]] on [[London Underground]]. The walk to the stadium from Seven Sisters station takes around 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://i.tottenhamhotspur.com/hc/en-us/articles/209485005-New-Stadium-Getting-Here |title=New Stadium Getting Here|work=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |accessdate=10 April 2019 }}</ref>  White Hart Lane and Seven Sisters are popular stops for fans which can cause congestion after games on match days.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/passengers-criticise-overcrowding-on-tube-after-first-match-at-new-spurs-stadium-a4109021.html |title=TfL passengers 'like cattle' on London Underground after first match at new Tottenham stadium |first=Magda |last= Ibrahim |date= 4 April 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2019 }}</ref>\n \nThe stadium area is served by up to 144 buses an hour.<ref name=\"illustrative\"/> Bus routes that stop close to the ground are [[London Buses route 149|149]], [[London Buses route 259|259]], [[London Buses route 279|279]], [[London Buses route 349|349]], and [[London Buses route W3|W3]].<ref name=transport>{{cite web |url=https://moovitapp.com/index/en-gb/public_transportation-White_Hart_Lane_Stadium-London_and_South_East-efsite_4ac518f7f964a5209eaf20e3-2122 |title=How to get to White Hart Lane Stadium in Tottenham by Bus, Tube or National Rail |work=Moovit }}</ref> A number of buses routes however are subject to diversions on matchdays. The club also operates two high frequency shuttle bus services to the stadium, one from [[Alexandra Palace railway station|Alexandra Palace]] via [[Wood Green tube station|Wood Green]] (on [[Piccadilly line]]) and finishing at [[Haringey Sixth Form College]], and the other from Tottenham Hale to [[Duke's Aldridge Academy]].<ref name=\"illustrative\">{{cite web |url=http://new-stadium.tottenhamhotspur.com/transport/ |title=Transport |work=Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/the-stadium/plan-your-visit/getting-here/shuttle-bus-services/ |title=Shuttle Bus Services |work=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |accessdate=24 April 2019 }}</ref>  On match days, roads near the stadium are normally closed to traffic two to three hours before kick-off, and one to one and a half hours after the match.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://i.tottenhamhotspur.com/hc/en-us/articles/360001254109-Road-Closures |title=Road Closures Local Information |accessdate=4 April 2019 |work=Ask Spurs}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://talksport.com/football/507748/tottenham-hotspur-stadium-latest-update-haringey-council-road-traffic-order/ |title=FINALLY Tottenham Hotspur Stadium latest: Fans believe stadium could be opened NEXT WEEK as Haringey council pass Road Traffic Order for March 16 |first=Joe |last=Coleman |date=8 March 2019|work=talkSport|accessdate=20 April 2019 }}</ref> Car parking in the area is controlled on match days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.haringey.gov.uk/parking-roads-and-travel/parking/controlled-parking-zones-cpzs/tottenham-event-day-cpz/tottenham-event-day-cpz-map |title=Tottenham Event Day CPZ map |work=Haringey Council |accessdate=8 April 2019 }}</ref> Tottenham has also started an arrangement with Big Green Coaches to provide match-day travel for fans to get to and from matches. A number of major towns in and around South East England are chosen as pickup points and supporters are dropped off at a designated coach parking facility near the Stadium, and are collected from the same area with coaches departing around an hour after the final whistle back to their collection points.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://spurs.biggreencoach.co.uk/ |title=Regional Coach Network |work=Big Green Coach |accessdate=18 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of stadiums in the United Kingdom by capacity]]\n* [[Potential London NFL franchise]]\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons Category}}\n* [http://new-stadium.tottenhamhotspur.com/ Official Tottenham Hotspur website]\n\n{{Tottenham Hotspur F.C.}}\n{{Premier League venues}}\n{{IStructE Supreme Award laureates}}\n{{NFL Stadiums}}\n{{Portal bar|London|English football|American football}}\n\n[[Category:Tottenham Hotspur F.C.]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in London]]\n[[Category:Football venues in London]]\n[[Category:Premier League venues]]\n[[Category:American football venues in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:National Football League venues]]\n[[Category:NFL International Series]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Football stadium in London}}\n{{Infobox stadium\n| stadium_name      = Tottenham Hotspur Stadium\n| location           = [[Tottenham]] <br />[[London]], [[N postcode area|N17]]\n| image             = Tottenham Hotspur Stadium June 2019, view from East.jpg\n| image_size        = 280\n| caption           = View of the stadium from the east\n| coordinates       = {{coord|51|36|16|N|0|03|59|W|region:GB|display=it}}\n|publictransit      = {{rail-interchange|london|overground}} {{rws|White Hart Lane}}<br>{{rail-interchange|gb|rail}} {{rws|Northumberland Park}}<br>{{rail-interchange|london|underground}} {{rws|Seven Sisters}}\n| fullname          = Tottenham Hotspur Stadium\n| nickname          =\n| owner             = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n| operator          = Tottenham Hotspur\n| construction_cost = \u00a31 billion (entire project)<ref name=\"gilmour\"/>\n| built             = 2016\u20132019\n| opened            = 3 April 2019\n| dimensions        = {{convert|105|x|68|m|yd|1}}\n| surface           = [[Desso GrassMaster]] (football)<br>Turf Nation (NFL)<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Turf Nation |magazine=Stadia |url=http://www.stadia-magazine.com/directory.php?CompanyID=1033}}</ref>\n| status            = \n| architect         = [[Populous (company)|Populous]]\n| general_contractor = [[Mace (construction company)|Mace]] \n| structural engineer = [[BuroHappold Engineering|BuroHappold]]<ref name=\"architects\">{{cite web |url=https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/buildings/populouss-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-awe-inspiring/10041690.article |title=Populous\u2019s Tottenham Hotspur Stadium \u2013 awe inspiring |date=4 April 2019 |first=Rupert|last= Bickersteth |work=Architects Journal |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref><br /> [[Schlaich Bergermann Partner|Schlaich Bergermann]] (roof)<ref name=\"architects\" /><br />SCX (retractable pitch)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/behind-the-scenes-look-at-tottenhams-retractable-pitch/10041699.article |title= Behind the scenes look at Tottenham\u2019s retractable pitch |date=4 April 2019 |first= Connor |last= Ibbetson|work=New Civil Engineer |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n| seating_capacity  = 62,303<ref name=capacity>{{cite news|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/the-stadium/local/|title=Local: Information for local residents and businesses|publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n| record_attendance  = 61,104 (vs. [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], 22 December 2019)<ref name=\"record attendance\">{{cite news |url=https://www.premierleague.com/match/46782 |title=Spurs v Chelsea  |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=22 December 2019 }}</ref><br />60,463 (NFL)<ref name=\"nflfirrst\"/>\n}}\n\nThe '''Tottenham Hotspur Stadium''' is the home of [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in north London, replacing the club's previous stadium, [[White Hart Lane]]. It has a capacity of 62,303,<ref name=capacity /> making it one of the [[List of football stadiums in England|largest]] stadiums in the [[Premier League]] and the largest club stadium in London.<ref name=white /> It is designed to be a [[multi-purpose stadium]] and features the world's first dividing, retractable football pitch, which reveals a synthetic turf pitch underneath for [[NFL International Series|NFL London Games]], concerts and other events. \n\nThe construction of the stadium was initiated as the centrepiece of the [[Northumberland Development Project]], intended to be the catalyst for a 20-year regeneration plan for [[Tottenham]]. The project covers the site of the now demolished ground of White Hart Lane and areas adjacent to it. The project was first conceived in 2007 and announced in 2008, but the plan was revised several times, and the construction of the stadium, beset by disputes and delays, did not commence until 2015. The stadium subsequently opened on 3 April 2019 with a ceremony before the first Premier League game held at the stadium.\n\nThe name \"Tottenham Hotspur Stadium\" is temporary, the intention being to sell the [[naming rights]], so that it will be named after a sponsor.<ref name=\"name\"/><ref name=\"thenational_726821\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thenational.ae/sport/comment/the-penny-finally-drops-as-tottenham-deal-with-spiralling-costs-of-move-back-to-white-hart-lane-1.726821 |title=The penny finally drops as Tottenham deal with spiralling costs of move back to White Hart Lane |first=Steve |last=Luckings|date=3 May 2018|work=The National|accessdate=14 July 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph_2018-08-30\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/08/30/tottenham-hotspurstruggle-200m-naming-deal-new-stadium/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur struggle for \u00a3200m naming deal for new stadium |first=Tom |last=Morgan |date=30 August 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph }}</ref> The stadium is occasionally referred to as '''New White Hart Lane''' by fans and some in the media.<ref name=\"independent_a8398106\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/tottenham-premier-league-fixtures-wembley-stadium-vs-fulham-first-game-white-hart-lane-liverpool-a8398106.html|title= Tottenham announce stay at Wembley Stadium and reveal first game at new White Hart Lane against Liverpool |first=Jack |last=de Menezes|date=14 June 2018|work=The Independent |accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Flavius |first1=Kevin |title=Tottenham Confirm New White Hart Lane Will Not Be Ready to Host Matches Until Next Year |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6206967-tottenham-confirm-new-white-hart-lane-will-not-be-ready-to-host-matches-until-next-year |website=90MIN |accessdate=30 October 2018 |date=26 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mannion |first1=Damian |title=PITCH PERFECT Tottenham stadium news: Pitch being laid at new White Hart Lane ground and fans can watch it live |url=https://talksport.com/football/428677/tottenham-stadium-news-pitch-being-laid-new-white-hart-lane/ |website=talkSPORT |accessdate=30 October 2018 |date=2 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wallace |first1=Sam |title=Workers on Spurs' new White Hart Lane stadium 'off their heads on cocaine' during construction |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/09/20/spurs-stadium-workers-heads-cocaine-alcohol-construction/ |accessdate=30 October 2018 |work=The Telegraph |date=20 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{See|White Hart Lane|Northumberland Development Project}}\n===Early grounds===\n[[File:Aerial view Tottenham Hotspur Football Club -trimmed.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|Aerial view of [[White Hart Lane]], demolished in 2017. Great part of the area in view was redeveloped in the new stadium project.]]\n\nTottenham Hotspur was formed in 1882, and early matches of the club were played on public land at [[Tottenham Marshes]].<ref name=Goodwin>{{cite book |first=Bob |last=Goodwin |title=Tottenham Hotspur: The Complete Record |publisher=Derby Books |edition=2 |year=2007 |isbn=978-1-85983-846-4}}</ref> As their matches became more popular with the public and the number of spectators increased, the club decided to move to an enclosed ground allowing it to charge an entrance fee and control the crowd. In 1888, the club rented a pitch at Asplins Farm, next to the railway line at [[Northumberland Park, London|Northumberland Park]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S07SDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT24&lpg=PT24#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=People's History of Tottenham Hotspur: How Spurs Fans Shaped the Identity of One of the World's Most Famous Clubs|authors= Martin Cloake, Alan Fisher |publisher=Pitch Publishing |date=15 August 2016 |chapter=Chapter 2: Enclosure Changed the Game Forever}}</ref> However, the ground soon became overcrowded, and in 1899 the club moved to a piece of land owned by the brewery company [[Charringtons]] to the east of [[Tottenham High Road]] behind the White Hart pub.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/tottenham-hotspur-spurs-white-hart-lane-farewell-goodbye-diego-maradon-johan-cruyff-a7733846.html|title=White Hart Lane has seen Diego Maradona and Johan Cruyff, but after 118 years Tottenham have outgrown it|first=Martin |last=Cloake |date=13 May 2017|work=The Independent}}</ref> This became the [[White Hart Lane]] ground.\n\nThe club acquired the freehold of the ground, as well as additional land at the northern (Paxton Road) end, in 1905.<ref name=\"haringey\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/AttachmentShowServlet?ImageName=236039 |title=Northumberland Development Project, Tottenham|date=October 2009 |publisher=Haringey Council}}</ref><ref name=\"stadium history\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/the-stadium/history/ |title= History of White Hart Lane |work=Tottenham Hotspur}}</ref> Starting in 1909, a new stadium with stands designed by [[Archibald Leitch]] was built over a period of two and a half decades. The stadium had a capacity of nearly 80,000 by 1934. Over the years, the stadium underwent a number of changes and seating replaced the standing areas, which reduced the capacity to about 50,000 in 1979. Significant standing areas, however, still existed, including the long stretch of raised standing terrace favoured by fans on the East Stand known as The Shelf.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/the-shelf-at-tottenham-once-made-white-hart-lane-londons-most-hostile-stadium-a3537971.html |title=The Shelf at Tottenham once made White Hart Lane London's most hostile stadium |first=Tony |last=Evans | date= 13 May 2017 |work=Evening Standard}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in the early 1980s, the White Hart Lane ground was redeveloped, and in order to comply with the recommendation of the [[Taylor Report]] of 1989, it was then turned into an all-seater stadium. The capacity of the stadium was reduced to around 36,000 by the time the refurbishment was completed in 1998. The capacity was, by then, lower than the grounds of other major English clubs, with many of these clubs also planning to expand further. As revenues from gate receipts in that period formed a substantial part of the club's income (before it became dominated by TV broadcast rights deals),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-36412394 |title=Premier League finances enter new era, says Deloitte |first= Bill|last= Wilson|work=BBC }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jun/06/premier-league-finances-club-guide-2016-17 |title=Premier League finances: the full club-by-club breakdown and verdict |first=David |last=Conn|date=6 June 2018 |work=The Guardian|accessdate= 9 December 2018 }}</ref> Tottenham began to explore ways of increasing the stadium capacity to allow it to more effectively compete financially with rival clubs.<ref name=\"east stand\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spurs1882.org/misc/WHL_EastStand2001_PlanningStatement.pdf |title=Proposed New East Stand Redevelopment for Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |date=June 2001 |work=Spurs Since 1882}}</ref>\n\nOver the years, a number of schemes were considered; these included rebuilding the East Stand as a three-tier structure, and moving to different stadiums and locations such as [[Picketts Lock]] and the [[Olympic Stadium (London)|Olympic Stadium]] at [[Stratford, London]].<ref name=\"east stand\"/> These plans however failed to come to fruition,<ref>{{cite news |title =Spurs plan down the Tube |first=Raoul |last=Simons |work=Evening Standard |date=30 July 2003 |url= https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/spurs-plan-down-the-tube-6985469.html }}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-12424549 West Ham chosen as preferred Olympic Stadium tenant BBC Sport online] Retrieved 12 February 2011</ref> except for a proposal to redevelop the existing site that became the [[Northumberland Development Project]].<ref name=\"Collett\">{{cite web |url= https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-england-tottenham/spurs-commit-to-new-stadium-in-tottenham-idUKTRE80U12620120131 |title=Spurs commit to new stadium in Tottenham|first=Mike|last= Collett|date=31 January 2012 |work=Reuters }}</ref>\n\n===Planning===\nThe club first announced in 2007 that redevelopment of the current site was one of the options under consideration.<ref name=young>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/new-tottenham-stadium-guide-pictures-video-capacity-cost-opening-date-and-what-we-know-so-far-a4047846.html |title=New Tottenham stadium guide: Opening date, pictures, video, capacity, cost and more |first=Alex |last= Young |date=24 January 2019 |work=Evening Standard |accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/articles/stadiumupdate060508.html|title=Stadium Update|publisher=Tottenhamhotspur.com|date=6 May 2008|accessdate=25 May 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509062202/http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/articles/stadiumupdate060508.html |archivedate=9 May 2008 }}</ref> In April 2008, the club revealed that it was considering the acquisition of the Wingate Trading Estate immediately adjacent to the north of White Hart Lane for building the stadium.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/0,,2271881,00.html |title=Spurs consider White Hart Lane exit for 55,000-seat stadium|work=The Guardian|date= 9 April 2008 |first=David|last= Hytner}}</ref> In October 2008, the Northumberland Development Project, that included the construction of a stadium, as well as a club museum, homes, shops and other facilities, was announced.<ref name=\"confirmed\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/tottenham-hotspur-confirms-northumberland-development-project-301008/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur Confirms Northumberland Development Project|date= 30 October 2008 |work=Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref><ref name=\"image released\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/t/tottenham_hotspur/7784290.stm|title=Spurs reveal images of new ground|publisher=BBC Sport|date=15 December 2008|accessdate=16 December 2008}}</ref> The early plan was for Tottenham to move into the new stadium, while it was partially built, at the beginning of the 2012\u201313 season, with the stadium  completed by the end of the following season. However, the project was delayed, with the plan undergoing a number of revisions and the completion date pushed back several times.<ref name=stadiumplans2013>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamjournal.co.uk/news/tottenham_hotspur_stadium_plan_drops_hotel_for_college_and_more_flats_1_1187677 |title=Tottenham Hotspur stadium plan drops hotel for college and more flats |work=Tottenahm and Wood Green Journal |date=25 January 2012 |accessdate= 29 May 2013|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221012501/http://www.tottenhamjournal.co.uk/news/tottenham_hotspur_stadium_plan_drops_hotel_for_college_and_more_flats_1_1187677 |archivedate= 21 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29144491 |title=Tottenham stadium delay means club face season away from home BBC Sport website 10 December 2014|accessdate= 20 February 2015|work=BBC}}</ref> The club also did not fully commit itself to building the stadium in Tottenham until January 2012, after it had lost its bid for the [[Olympic Stadium (London)|Olympic Stadium]] to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref name=\"Collett\"/>\n\nThe first plan of the project, with a 58,000-capacity stadium, was released in April 2009 for public consultation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/5084823/Tottenhams-new-stadium-could-have-an-ice-rink.html |title=Tottenham's new stadium could have an ice rink |first= Richard|last= Bright|date=1 April 2009 |work=The Telegraph }}</ref> In October 2009, the planning application for a 56,000-seat stadium, designed by [[KSS Design Group]], and other buildings was then submitted.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/t/tottenham_hotspur/8326735.stm |title=Spurs aim for new stadium by 2012 |work=BBC |first=Sam |last=Sheringham|date=26 October 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/make-and-kss-to-design-spurs-stadium/3127797.article |title=Make and KSS to design Spurs stadium |first= Sarah |last=Richardson|date=18 November 2008|work=Building }}</ref> The proposal, which included the demolition of eight locally listed buildings and two nationally listed buildings, was criticised by conservation groups including [[English Heritage]], as well as the Government's advisory body on architecture, the [[Commission for Architecture and the Built Environment]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/spurs-try-again-as-400m-stadium-plan-is-ruled-offside-6471651.html |title=Spurs try again as \u00a3400m stadium plan is ruled offside |first=Felix |last=Allen |date= 20 May 2010 |work= Evening Standard}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/tottenham/article7131149.ece |title= Tottenham's plans to redevelop White Hart Lane shown red card |work=Times online|accessdate= 22 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528094547/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/tottenham/article7131149.ece |archivedate=28 May 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.savebritainsheritage.org/campaigns/item/50/15-historic-buildings-set-for-demolition-under-Spurs-stadium-plans |title=15 historic buildings set for demolition under Spurs stadium plans |work=SAVE Britain Heritage }}</ref> In response to the objections, a revised plan, that retained some of the listed buildings, was resubmitted in May 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/9498772/premier-league-tottenham-press-ahead-with-stadium-plans |title=Premier League: Tottenham press ahead with stadium plans |first= Lyall |last=Thomas|date= 2 October 2014 |work=Sky Sports }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/7744297/Tottenham-redesign-new-stadium-to-preserve-listed-buildings.html |title=Tottenham redesign new stadium to preserve listed buildings |first=John |last=Ley |date= 20 May 2010 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=15 June 2018 }}</ref> This plan was accepted by Haringey Council on 30 September 2010, and later by the [[Mayor of London]], [[Boris Johnson]], as well as the government.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/8160140/Tottenham-given-go-ahead-to-redevelop-White-Hart-lane-by-Mayor-of-London-Boris-Johnson.html |title=Tottenham given go ahead to redevelop White Hart Lane by Mayor of London Boris Johnson |date=25 November 2010|work=The Telegraph}}</ref><ref name=NDPPressrelease>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/futureplans/news/stadium-plans-011010.html |title=Stadium Plans |work=THFC Official website|accessdate= 15 June 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101003104828/http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/futureplans/news/stadium-plans-011010.html |archivedate= 3 October 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/new-stadium-plans-update1-091210/|title=New Stadium Plans Update|date= 9 December 2010 |work=Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref> However, only part of this plan, the construction of Lilywhite House, was implemented.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club-announcement-160215/ |title=Club Announcement|date= 16 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Northumnerland Development Project.svg|thumb|upright=0.8|The layout for the [[Northumberland Development Project]]]]\nIn August 2011, a [[2011 England riots|major riot]] erupted in a deprived area of Tottenham. [[Haringey Council]], keen to keep the economically-important club within the community, issued planning permission for the project on 20 September 2011,<ref name=\"kilpatrick\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/articles/northumberland-development-project-update-200911.html |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124142051/http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/articles/northumberland-development-project-update-200911.html |archivedate=24 November 2011 | title=Northumberland Development Project Update |work= Tottenhamhotspur.com|accessdate= 20 September 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/14996725 |title=Tottenham sign planning agreement to build new stadium |date = 20 September 2011 |work=BBC}}</ref> and a week later removed the demand for community infrastructure payments usually required for such a project.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-15095674|title=Club reveal next stage plans for Northumberland Development Tottenham stadium: Club offered White Hart Lane deal|publisher=BBC |date=28 September 2011|accessdate=18 November 2011}}</ref> In a joint statement with Haringey Council in January 2012, Tottenham announced that it would stay in North Tottenham and work with the council to rejuvenate the area.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.enfieldindependent.co.uk/news/tottenhamhotspurstadiumplans/9502824.Spurs_confirm_intention_to_stay_in_Tottenham_and_help_rejuvenate_the_area/ |title= Spurs confirm intention to stay in Tottenham and help rejuvenate the area|first=Bruce |last=Thain|work=Enfield Independent |date=31 January 2012 }}</ref> In this scheme, the Northumberland Development Project would serve as the catalyst for a 20-year regeneration program planned by the Haringey Council.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.haringey.gov.uk/sites/haringeygovuk/files/a_plan_for_tottenham.pdf |title=A Plan Tottenham |work=Haringey Council |date=2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"projectupdateJuly2015\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/tottenham-in-1-billion-turnaround-9214361.html |title=Tottenham in \u00a31 billion turnaround |work= London Evening Standard |date=25 March 2014 |first=Robert |last=Bevan }}</ref> In March 2012, Haringey Council approved of plans to hand over council-owned land in the redevelopment area, including part of Wingate Trading Estate, as well as Paxton Road and Bill Nicholson Way, to Spurs. It also agreed on a Compulsory Purchase Order (CPO) to buy the remaining properties on Paxton Road that had yet to sell.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.tottenhamjournal.co.uk/news/spurs_granted_right_to_remove_final_business_in_the_way_of_new_ground_1_1334278|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20130215060058/http://www.tottenhamjournal.co.uk/news/spurs_granted_right_to_remove_final_business_in_the_way_of_new_ground_1_1334278|title=Spurs granted right to remove final business in the way of new ground|first= Tim |last=Lamden|date= March 29, 2012 |archivedate=15 February 2013 |work=Tottenham and Wood Green Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://cartilagefreecaptain.sbnation.com/2012/3/29/2911018/another-obstacle-between-tottenham-hotspur-and-their-new-stadium-falls |title=Another Obstacle Between Tottenham Hotspur and Their New Stadium Falls |author=Bryan A.|date= 29 March 2012 |work=Cartilage Free Captain}}</ref> After a long delay, the Secretary of State for the [[Department for Communities and Local Government]], [[Eric Pickles]], confirmed the CPO on 11 July 2014.<ref name=\"DCMS\">{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-scheme-gets-the-green-light|title=New Tottenham Hotspur stadium scheme gets the green light|date=11 July 2014|publisher=Department for Communities and Local Government|accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/northumberland-development-project-cpo-confirmed-110714/|title=Northumberland Development Project - CPO Confirmed|date=11 July 2014|publisher=Tottenham Hotspur|accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref> The owner of the remaining business with two plots on the development site, Archway Sheet Metal Works, then attempted but failed to have the CPO decision quashed in the [[High Court of Justice|High Court]].<ref name=highcourt>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/11424828/Tottenham-plans-for-new-stadium-given-massive-boost-as-business-looking-to-block-move-loses-High-Court-appeal.html|title= Tottenham plans for new stadium given massive boost as business looking to block move loses High Court appeal|work= [[Daily Telegraph]]|date= 20 February 2015|accessdate= 20 February 2015}}</ref> On 31 March 2015, the remaining plots on Paxton Road were acquired, allowing the development to proceed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/joint-statement-310315/ |title=Joint Statement |work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club|date= 31 March 2015|accessdate= 31 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/chairmanand39s-message-160515/ |title=Chairman'S Message|date= 16 May 2015 |work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club}}</ref>\n\nIt was first revealed in October 2013 that the club was considering a new plan for a multi-use stadium that can host American [[National Football League|NFL]] games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/tottenham-hotspurs-secret-plans-for-white-hart-lane-mega-stadium/8654598.article?blocktitle=News-feature&contentID=9529|title=Tottenham Hotspurs' secret plans for White Hart Lane mega stadium |date=24 October 2013 |first= Richard|last= Waite|work=The Architects' Journal }}</ref> On 8 July 2015, the club announced that it had reached an agreement with [[National Football League|NFL]] to hold a minimum of two NFL games a year in a 10-year partnership.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/11725998/Tottenham-close-to-signing-deal-with-NFL-to-stage-American-Football-matches-at-new-61000-seater-stadium.html |title=Tottenham sign deal with NFL to stage American Football matches at new 61,000-seater stadium |first=Jeremy|last= Wilson|date=8 Jul 2015 |work=The Telegraph }}</ref> The same day a new design team was also announced, alongside a revised project plan, with [[Populous (company)|Populous]] led by Christopher Lee responsible for the stadium design.<ref name=\"projectupdateJuly2015\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/new-scheme/project-update/#scheme-comparisons |title=Project Update |work=THFC |accessdate= 12 July 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714032108/http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/new-scheme/project-update/ |archivedate=14 July 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/events/business-of-sport/christopher-lee-architect-populous/ |title=Architect Christopher Lee from Populous talks modern stadium design |first=David |last=Edwards|work=The Telegraph |date=3 June 2016 |accessdate=31 January 2019 }}</ref> In December 2015, the revised plans were approved by Haringey Council, including the demolition of locally listed buildings.<ref name=\"haringey planning\">{{cite web |url=http://www.haringey.gov.uk/planning-and-building-control/planning/major-projects-and-regeneration/tottenham-hotspur-football-club-stadium-development |title=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club Stadium Development |work=Haringey London}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/35118953 Tottenham's revised stadium plans approved by Haringey Council ''BBC News'']. Retrieved 17 December 2015</ref> The Mayor of London also gave formal approval to the plans in February 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/new-tottenham-stadium-mayor-of-london-boris-johnson-gives-formal-approval-to-spurs-redevelopment-a3189306.html |title=New Tottenham stadium: Mayor of London Boris Johnson gives formal approval to Spurs redevelopment |first=Sam |last= Long |date= 25 February 2016 |work=Evening Standard }}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\n[[File:New White Hart Lane from above 2017-05. trimmed 2.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|Northern section of the new stadium (left) under construction in May 2017, with White Hart Lane (right) partially demolished. The new ground covers part of the old ground.]]\nBuilding work on the Northumberland Development Project started in September 2012, however, construction of the stadium itself did not commence until 2015 due to the CPO dispute. The stadium was constructed in two main phases so that White Hart Lane could still be used in the [[2016\u201317 Tottenham Hotspur F.C. season|2016\u201317 season]] while construction was still in progress. The first phase involved the building of the northern section of the stadium (including the North, West and East Stands), while the South Stand construction started in the second phase after White Hart Lane had been demolished. A large part of the land north of the existing stadium had been cleared by 2014 while the CPO dispute was ongoing.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jul/13/football-news-in-brief |title= Football news in brief |date= 13 July 2014 |work=The Guardian }}</ref> After the dispute was resolved, preliminary work on the basement began in the summer of 2015,<ref name=\"project update\">{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714032108/http://tottenhamhotspur.com/new-scheme/project-update/ |archivedate=14 July 2015 |title=Project Update |url=http://tottenhamhotspur.com/new-scheme/project-update/ |url-status=dead |work=Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref> with concrete and ground works for the foundation by Morrisroe starting in autumn 2015, based on earlier approved and amended plans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2016/02/25/final-go-ahead-for-400m-spurs-stadium/ |title=Final go-ahead for \u00a3400m Spurs stadium |date=25 February 2016 |work=Construction Enquirer |accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.morrisroe.co.uk/portfolio/tottenham-hotspur/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur Football Stadium |work=Morrisroe  |accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=\nhttp://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/ApplicationSearchServlet?PKID=280768 |title=Online Planning Services |work=Haringey London  |accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe new plan for the project was given final approval in February 2016, which allowed the construction of the main structure of the new stadium itself to start soon after. In order to facilitate the construction of the northern section of the stadium while matches of the final season were still being played at The Lane, the northeast corner of White Hart Lane was demolished in the summer of 2016 after the [[2015\u201316 Tottenham Hotspur F.C. season|2015\u201316 season]] had finished.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cartilagefreecaptain.sbnation.com/2016/5/6/11605462/tottenham-hotspur-confirms-upcoming-partial-demolition-of-white-hart-lane-stand |title=Tottenham Hotspur confirms upcoming partial demolition of White Hart Lane stand|first= Dustin |last=Menno| date= 6 May 2016|work=Cartilage Free Captain }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club/new-stadium/stadium-construction-update-latest-aerial-photos-170816/|title=Stadium Construction Update - Latest Aerial Photos|date= 17 August 2016 |work= Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref> From the basement to level 6, the construction of this section is in reinforced concrete.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/AttachmentShowServlet?ImageName=748344 |title=Environmental Statement |date=September 2015 |work=Haringey Council }}</ref> Three further levels above are constructed in steel frame. There are only six cores in reinforced concrete for vertical circulation of spectators instead of the eight expected of a stadium of this size as they needed to be constructed within the first phase of the stadium construction.<ref name=\"jones\"/> The South Stand constructed in the second phase has open staircases to the concourses.<ref name=\"access\"/>\n[[File:Tottenham Hotspur Stadium under construction - view from Park Lane.jpg|thumb|Stadium under construction in May 2018 with two steel \"trees\" supporting the South Stand erected and the cable net roof structure installed. Trays for the retractable pitch are observable under the podium in the foreground.]]\n\nThe demolition of the majority remaining White Hart Lane ground began the day after the last home match of the [[2016\u201317 Tottenham Hotspur F.C. season|2016\u201317 season]] was played, and the demolition was completed with all visible remnants of White Hart Lane removed by early August 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spurs release brilliant time-lapse video showing new stadium progress and how it will look|url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/spurs-new-stadium-building-ground-13434810|accessdate=17 October 2018|work=football.london|date=4 August 2017|first=Alasdair|last= Gold}}</ref> Piling work for Phase 2 of the stadium construction started in June 2017.<ref>{{cite |url=http://www.thstofficial.com/uploads/9/2/2/6/92268578/thfc_stadium_newsletter_june_17.pdf |title= Spurs Stadium Project |work=Tottenham Hotspur Supporters' Trust }}</ref> While the northern section constructed in the first phase is a largely concrete structure, the entire single-tier south stand has a steel frame to allow for a speedier construction.<ref name=\"jones\">{{cite web |url=https://populous.com/posts/home-sweet-home-tottenham-hotspurs-last-match-white-hart-lane/ |title=Home Sweet Home: Tottenham Hotspur's last match at White Hart Lane|date=17 May 2017 |first=Tom |last=Jones|work=Populous}}</ref> The two steel \"trees\" that support the  South Stand were erected in December 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tothelaneandback.com/2017/11/11/tottenham-deploy-trees-in-new-850m-stadium-to-take-the-weight-of-the-south-stand-which-will-be-the-largest-in-europe/ |title=Tottenham Deploy 'Trees' In New \u00a3850m Stadium To Take The Weight Of The South Stand Which Will Be The Largest In Europe|first= Thomas|last= Hein |date= 11 November 2017 |work= }}</ref> The compression ring that holds the cable net roof structure was completed in February 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club/new-stadium/new-stadium-update-commencement-of-roof-lift-080218/ |title=New Stadium Update: Commencement of Roof Lift|date= 8 February 2018 |work=Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref> and the roof structure raised in March 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/new-spurs-stadium-spectacular-feature-14331516 |title=Tottenham unveil spectacular feature for \u00a3850m new stadium which will delight the fans |first=Alasdair |last=Gold|date=26 March 2018|work=football.london }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tottenham Hotspur Stadium under construction February 2019.jpg|thumb|Stadium nearing completion in February 2019. Last section of metal cladding panels being installed.]]\nParts of the old White Hart Lane have been incorporated into the new stadium &ndash; crushed aggregate of the concrete foundation of White Hart Lane was mixed in with new concrete to create the floor of the concourse of the new stadium,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/03/08/crushed-aggies-from-white-hart-lane-form-new-spurs-stadium-floors/ |title=White Hart Lane crushed aggies form new Spurs stadium floors |first=Grant |last=Prior | date=8 March 2018 |work=Construction Enquirer }}</ref> and bricks from the East Stand were used for the Shelf Bar.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club/new-stadium/new-stadium-shelf-and-led-190418/ |title= New stadium - latest photos - Shelf Bar and LED | date=19 April 2018 |work =Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref>  A number of heritage plaques are placed around the stadium marking points of the old stadium, such as its centre.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/media/16058/fan-guide.pdf |title=The Tottenham Hotspur Stadium: Welcome Home - Your Guide |work=Tottenham Hotspur |accessdate=12 March 2019 }}</ref> The pitch was laid in early October 2018.<ref name=\"ouzia\"/> The exterior of the stadium is finished with 35,000 decorative tiles, 4,801 perforated metal panels and 2,505 glass panels.<ref name=gold2019>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/everything-know-spurs-new-stadium-16041502 |title=15 astonishing facts about Tottenham Hotspur's new stadium - Everything you need to know|first=Alasdair |last=Gold|work=football.london|date=28 March 2019 |accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref> The external cladding of the stadium was completed with the last few metal panels of the 'veil' installed in March 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/new-tottenham-stadium-nike-corner-15955550 |title=New Tottenham stadium: Naming rights & Nike, the corner space 'issue', test events and 55 photos |first=Alasdair|last= Gold|work=football.london|date= 11 March 2019 |accessdate=12 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Opening===\nThe club initially announced that it would hold four test events at the stadium in August and early September 2018.<ref name=\"independent_a8398106\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11447481/spurs-announce-test-events-for-new-stadium |title=Spurs announce Test Events for new stadium|date= 24 July 2018 |work=Sky Sports |accessdate=24 July 2018 }}</ref> The first two events would be attended only by club staff and officials,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/new-tottenham-stadium-open-date-15014554|title=New Tottenham stadium: Whether ground will be ready on time, test events & stunning new photos|first=Alasdair |last=Gold|date=11 August 2018|work=football.london |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/11/09/tottenham-staff-given-sneak-preview-spectacular-new-stadium/ |title=Tottenham staff given sneak preview of spectacular new stadium |first=Matt|last= Law|date=9 November 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> the following two would be games open to the public, with increasing levels of attendance necessary for the issuing of safety certificate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cartilagefreecaptain.sbnation.com/2018/7/24/17609148/tottenham-hotspur-new-stadium-test-events-august-september-academy-spurs-legends |title=Tottenham confirm two test events ahead of new stadium opening|first= Dustin|last= Menno|date=24 July 2018|work=Cartilage Free Captain |accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11590069/tottenham-stadium-qa-what-has-to-happen-before-they-move-in |title=Tottenham stadium Q&A: What has to happen before they move in? |date= 23 December 2018 |work=Sky Sports |accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref> However, issues with the critical safety systems due to faulty electrical wiring delayed the completion of the stadium,<ref name=\"october opening\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/08/13/tottenham-forced-delay-opening-new-stadium-issues-critical-safety/ |title=Tottenham forced to delay opening of new stadium until end of October after 'issues with critical safety systems |first=Jeremy |last=Wilson|date=13 August 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tottenham stadium delay down to 'faulty wiring', says Mace|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11480000/tottenham-stadium-delay-down-to-faulty-wiring-says-mace |date=23 August 2018|work=Sky Sports |accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref> and these two games were postponed to March 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/spurs-stadium-the-story-so-far/5096681.article |title=Spurs stadium: The story so far |work= Building |date=2 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019 }}</ref> A fan familiarisation event was held instead at the stadium in December 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tottenham stage 'fan familiarisation event' at new White Hart Lane stadium|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11583073/tottenham-stage-fan-familiarisation-event-at-new-stadium |work=Sky Sports |date= 17 December 2018 }}</ref> The first match, an under-18s fixture between [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Tottenham]] and [[Southampton F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Southampton]] held on 24 March, was attended by 28,987 fans and won by Tottenham 3\u20131, with the first ever goal at the stadium scored by J'Neil Bennett.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/new-tottenham-stadium-test-event-jneil-bennett-makes-history-as-spurs-u18s-beat-southampton-a4099496.html |title=New Tottenham stadium test event: J'Neil Bennett makes history as Spurs U18s beat Southampton |first=Vaishali|last= Bhardwaj |date=24 March 2019 |work=Evening Standard|accessdate=24 March 2019 }}</ref> The second, a Legends match against [[Inter Milan]] on 30 March, was attended by 41,244, but resulted in a 4\u20135 loss to the Inter Forever team.<ref name=\"opening\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47502366|title=Tottenham: New stadium to be used competitively in first week of April |date=8 March 2019 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate= 8 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11679895/spurs-legends-4-5-inter-forever-gazza-cameo-in-thriller-at-new-stadium |title=Spurs Legends 4-5 Inter Forever: Gazza cameo in thriller at new stadium |date=30 March 2019 |accessdate=20 March 2019 |work=Sky Sports }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2019/march/legends-thrill-fans-at-new-stadium |title=Legends Thrill Fans at New Stadium |date=30 March 2019 |accessdate=31 March 2019 |work=THFC }}</ref>\n\nThe opening was originally planned for the second home match against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in September 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44479264 |title=Premier League fixtures 2018-19: Man City visit Arsenal on opening weekend |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 June 2018 |accessdate=14 June 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44480283 |title=Tottenham: Liverpool the visitors for first game at new stadium |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 June 2018 |accessdate=14 June 2018 }}</ref> but delays to the opening of the stadium forced Tottenham to extend their temporary tenancy of [[Wembley Stadium]] for the [[2018\u201319 Tottenham Hotspur F.C. season|2018\u201319 season]] until April 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham-confirm-wembley-date-for-manchester-city-match-and-stadium-will-stage-champions-league-a3926521.html |title=Tottenham confirm Wembley date for Manchester City match and stadium will stage Champions League group stage |first=Dan |last=Kilpatrick |work=Evening Standard |date=3 September 2018 |accessdate=3 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"2019 opening\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/oct/26/tottenham-mauricio-pochettino-real-madrid-wembley-nfl-manchester-city |title=Tottenham confirm they will not play in new stadium until 2019 |first=Ed|last= Aarons|date=26 October 2018 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=26 October 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"burrows\" /> They also played their home game in the third round of the [[2018\u201319 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] at [[Stadium MK]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11491901/tottenham-given-permission-to-move-watford-carabao-cup-tie-to-milton-keynes |title= Tottenham given permission to move Watford Carabao Cup tie to Milton Keynes | date= 5 September 2018 |work=Sky Sports}}</ref>  The first NFL game was due to be [[Oakland Raiders]] against [[Seattle Seahawks]] on 14 October 2018 but this too was relocated to Wembley following the stadium delay.<ref name=\"october opening\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nfl-england-oak-sea-tottenham/raiders-face-seahawks-in-first-game-at-new-tottenham-stadium-idUSKBN1F10TL |title=Raiders face Seahawks in first game at new Tottenham stadium |date=12 January 2018 |work= Reuters |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>  The club shop was the first to open on 23 October 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/tottenham-hotspur/story/3676313/tottenham-open-biggest-club-shop-in-europe-at-new-stadium-no-confirmed-date-for-first-match |title=Tottenham open biggest club shop in Europe at new stadium, no confirmed date for first match |first=Ben|last= Pearce |work=ESPN}}</ref> The stadium opened with a ceremony on 3 April 2019 before its first competitive senior game, the Premier League match against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref name=\"burrows\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/tottenham-hotspur-fixtures-new-stadium-first-game-when-is-it-crystal-palace-fc-a8827321.html |title=Tottenham new stadium: Spurs confirm Crystal Palace as first fixture at new home|first=Ben |last=Burrows |date=17 March 2019 |work=The Independent |accessdate=17 March 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/tottenham-hotspur-stadium-opening-ceremony-spurs-pay-homage-to-regeneration-of-local-area-after-2011-a4108686.html |title=Tottenham Hotspur stadium opening ceremony: Spurs pay homage to regeneration of local area after 2011 riots |date=3 April 2019 |work=Evening Standard |accessdate=4 April 2019 |first= Jack |last=Rosser }}</ref> The match was won by Tottenham 2\u20130, with [[Son Heung-min]] scoring the first ever official goal at the new stadium.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/04/03/tottenhams-first-game-new-stadium-plus-man-city-chelsea-premier/ |title=Son Heung-min writes his name in Spurs folklore with first goal in Tottenham's new stadium | first1=Jason |last1=Burt|first2=Alan |last2=Tyers |work=The Telegraph |date=3 April 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Tottenham Hotspur 2\u20130 Crystal Palace |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47512149 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 April 2019 |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture and facilities==\n[[File:Tottenham Hotspur Stadium - view from High Road - June 2019.jpg|thumb|West entrance of stadium on Tottenham High Road]]\nThe stadium is an asymmetric bowl, with a capacity of 62,303.<ref name=\"furtherexpansion\">{{cite news|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2019/august/application-to-increase-stadium-capacity-approved/|title=Spurs stadium capacity increased to 62,214|date= 5 August 2019|publisher=Tottenham hotspur official website|accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=capacity /> The bowl shape of the stadium comes from the need to maximise hospitality facilities while the asymmetry is the result of the creation of a single-tier stand in the south.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/AttachmentShowServlet?ImageName=748760 |title=Tottenham Hotspur Design and Access Statement 2015: Design Response |work=Haringey Council |accessdate=27 July 2018 }}</ref> The stadium is around 48 m high, 250 m long on its north-south axis and about 200 metres wide east to west.<ref name=\"overview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/AttachmentShowServlet?ImageName=748755 |title=Tottenham Hotspur Design and Access Statement 2015: Overview |work=Haringey Council |accessdate=25 July 2018 }}</ref> There are 9 floors in the horseshoe-shaped northern section above the basement, and 5 floors in the south, with a [[gross internal area]] of 119,945 m<sup>2</sup>,<ref name=\"overview\"/> which is around four times the size of White Hart Lane.<ref name=washington>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/tottenham-stadium-follows-us-financing-model/2019/04/01/145a04ec-54a2-11e9-aa83-504f086bf5d6_story.html |title=Tottenham Stadium follows US financing model |first=Ronald |last=Blum\u2009|date= 1 April 2019 |accessdate=1 April 2019 |work=Washington Post}}</ref> The stadium covers an area of 43,000 m<sup>2</sup>, nearly twice the area of White Hart Lane (24,000  m<sup>2</sup>).<ref name=stadiumdb>{{cite web |url=http://stadiumdb.com/stadiums/eng/tottenham_hotspur_stadium |title=Tottenham Hotspur Stadium |work=StadiumDB.com |accessdate=29 February 2020 }}</ref> The front of the West Stand faces the High Road and features a projecting, angled, glazed box that encases an escalator and serves as the main entrance for guests and patrons. The projecting entrance, along with the facades of other buildings of the Tottenham Experience, present a traditional linear frontage along the High Road. A 9.5-m pavement is created in front of these buildings to improve the flow of the crowd on match day on the High Road. To the east, on Worcester Avenue, is a dedicated entrance for NFL events.<ref name=\"access\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/AttachmentShowServlet?ImageName=748452 |title=Tottenham Hotspur Design and Access Statement 2015: 7.1 Stadium Design Concept |work=Haringey Council }}</ref> There are two raised podiums for fans access, one to the north and one to the south. A large open public square, the size of [[Trafalgar Square]], has been created on the south podium as the main access point for home fans. The square has a number of ventilation shafts, and it may be used for sporting and community activities.<ref name=\"populous\"/><ref name=\"london.gov\">{{cite web |url=https://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/PAWS/media_id_285574/tottenham_hotspur_stadium_report.pdf |title=Northumberland Development Project (Tottenham Hotspur Stadium) |date=27 October 2015 |accessdate=20 April 2019 |work=Greater London Authority }}</ref> Away fans may enter from the northeast corner of the stadium via Worcester Avenue and the north podium. The South Stand features a 5-storey atrium behind a single 7,000 m<sup>2</sup> curved glazed facade.<ref name=\"plan\">{{cite web |url= http://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/AttachmentShowServlet?ImageName=748774 |title=Tottenham Hotspur Design and Access Statement 2015: Part 7.5 |work=Haringey Council Services }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tottenham Hotspur Stadium with The Tottenham Experience on High Road - February 2019.jpg|thumb|Frontage of the stadium and Tottenham Experience along the High Road]]\nThe bulk of the structure dominates the surrounding area, but the appearance of the mass of the building is modulated by different claddings of glass, metal panels and pre-cast concrete. The perforated metal panels serve as a screen but allow for natural ventilation and light for the open [[Physical plant|plant]] areas in the stadium, and they also act as a unifying sculptured element in the appearance of the stadium.  Regions of glazing not covered by the metal screen, including the main entrances and concourses, offices, Sky Lounge, as well the extensive glazed area to the south, allow for views into and out of the stadium.<ref name=\"plan\"/> The metal panels may be in an open or closed position, and they are lined with [[LED]] luminaires that glow on match nights.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/new-tottenham-stadium-feature-spurs-14564979 |title= Spurs unveil impressive feature that will transform the outside of their new \u00a3850m stadium |first=Alasdair |last=Gold|date= 24 April 2018|work=football.london |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe roof is a cable net structure, held in place by an elliptically-shaped compression ring.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club/new-stadium/new-stadium-update-commencement-of-roof-lift-080218/ |title=New Stadium Update: Commencement of Roof Lift|date= 8 February 2018 |work=Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref> The roof has a circumference of 720 metres, and it is clad in standing seam aluminium panels that end with extruded [[polycarbonate]] on the inside edge to allow light through onto the pitch but reduce the contrast of the shadow of the roof on the pitch.<ref name=\"plan\"/><ref name=gold2019 />  810 curved alumininum eave cassettes connect the roof to the wall. The pitch is lit by 324 LED floodlights, arranged in 54 groups of six and attached to the columns of the roofing system.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://luxreview.com/article/2018/03/pitch-lights-will-be-led-says-spurs |title=Pitch lights will be LED, says Spurs |date=6 March 2018|work=LUX |accessdate=12 July 2018 }}</ref> There are four large LED screens inside the stadium, the two on the south side are the largest of any stadium in Western Europe.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/spurs-new-stadium-completion-date-14660098 |title=New Spurs stadium: Latest photos, video and completion date as we walk around site |first=Alasdair |last=Gold|work=football.london|date= 17 May 2018 }}</ref> There are also two facade video displays on the outside of the stadium, three tiers of LED ribbon displays inside, and nearly 1,800 video screens in and around the stadium.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.daktronics.com/news/Pages/Tottenham-Hotspur-Selects-Daktronics-For-New-Stadium.aspx |title=Tottenham Hotspur Selects Daktronics To Provide LED Video Displays For New Stadium |work=Daktronics }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thestadiumbusiness.com/2018/03/27/daktronics-supply-led-displays-new-tottenham-stadium/ |title=Daktronics to supply LED displays for new Tottenham stadium |work=TheStadiumBusiness|date= 27 March 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/the-club/partners/our-suppliers/lg/ |title=LG |work=Tottenham Hotspur |accessdate=30 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe stadium is designed like a concert hall with good acoustics in mind so as to optimise the atmosphere on match day.<ref name=\"gq\"/> The corners of the stadium are enclosed and the stands are placed close to the pitch, with fans generating a \"wall of sound\" that can reverberate around the ground.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenhams-new-stadium-will-have-better-atmosphere-than-arsenals-emirates-says-spurs-director-a3429286.html |title=Tottenham's new stadium will have better atmosphere than Arsenal's Emirates, says Spurs director Donna-Maria Cullen|first=Tom |last=Dutton |date=29 December 2016 |work=Evening Standard}}</ref><ref name=\"clad\">{{cite web |url= http://www.cladglobal.com/news?codeid=329763 |title=White Hart Lane: Populous MD lifts the lid on the design of Tottenham's community-driven new stadium|first= Kim|last= Megson |date= 20 January 2017|work=Clad News }}</ref> The design extends to the shape and material of the roof and the seating, such as aluminium [[soffit]] lining to the roof, and aims to produce cleaner and quicker reverberation times that allow fans to sing in sync thereby producing chants that are louder and last longer.<ref name=\"gq\"/>  The stadium is also designed to maintain the character but noisier than White Hart Lane and facilitate a sense of \"home\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48076482 |title=Tottenham Hotspur: New stadium is like a town hall, architect says |date=27 April 2019 |work =BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://populous.com/make-it-loud-designing-for-atmosphere-at-new-tottenham-hotspur-stadium |title=Make it Loud: Designing for Atmosphere at New Tottenham Hotspur Stadium |date=April 15, 2019 |work=Populous}}</ref>\n\n===Stands===\n[[File:Tottenham Hotspur Stadium South Stand.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|The South Stand, also known as the Park Lane end, before the [[UEFA Champions League]] quarter-final with [[Manchester City F.C.]] on 9 April 2019, with fans displaying the club motto 'To Dare Is to Do'.]]\nAlthough the stadium is designed as a bowl, it still has four distinct stands.<ref name=\"gq\"/> The tiers of the stands are set at angles of up to 35 degrees, the maximum permissible in British stadium design,<ref name=white>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/03/22/tottenham-hotspurs-new-home-sets-benchmark-modern-stadia/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur\u2019s new home sets benchmark for modern stadia | first=Jim |last=White |date=22 March 2019|work=The Telegraph |accessdate=22 March 2019 }}</ref><ref name=hytner2019>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/mar/24/tottenham-new-stadium-mauricio-pochettino |title=Intimacy, awe and a salute to Gazza: Spurs throw open doors to new home |first=David |last=Hytner|date= 24 March 2019 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=24 March 2019 }}</ref> and all seats provide clear views of the pitch for the ticket holders.<ref name=\"access\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://cartilagefreecaptain.sbnation.com/2015/10/2/9437987/tottenham-hotspur-new-stadium-details-interior-bowl-drawings |title=Spurs' new stadium interior designed to enhance fan views|first= Matthew |last=Pachniuk |date= 2 October 2015 |work=Cartilage Free Captain|accessdate=26 March 2019}}</ref> The South Stand is designated the 'Home End', and it has a single tier which is the largest [[Spion Kop (stadiums)|single-tier stand]] in the country, with seating for 17,500 fans. It is 34.1m high with a 34 degree incline, has concourses on Level 1, 2, 3 and 4 and is accessible from the south atrium.<ref name=\"guide\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/media/6426/tottenhamhotspur-2018-19season-newstadium.pdf |title=Welcome to Our New Home |accessdate=11 January 2019 |work=Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref> The design of the South Stand is influenced by the \"Yellow Wall\" of [[Borussia Dortmund]]'s [[Westfalenstadion|Signal Iduna Park]] and the stand is intended to be the \"heart-beat\" of the stadium that can generate an intense atmosphere on match day.<ref name=\"gq\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/six-things-you-need-to-know-about-the-new-tottenham-stadium |title=Spurs stadium designers: \"We've built it like a concert hall\" |first= Stuart |last=McGurk |date=23 January 2017|work=GQ}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://populous.com/posts/behind-design-single-tier-stand-drive-atmosphere-tottenham-hotspurs-new-south-stand/ |title=Behind the Design: The Single-Tier Stand to Drive Atmosphere of Tottenham Hotspur's New South Stand |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180406230857/https://populous.com/posts/behind-design-single-tier-stand-drive-atmosphere-tottenham-hotspurs-new-south-stand/ |archivedate=6 April 2018 |date=21 December 2017 |work=Populous}}</ref><ref name=\"plan\"/> \n[[File:Home team dugout at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium.jpg|thumb|left|Home [[Technical area|dugout]] below the West Stand]]\nThe 35.5m high North Stand has three tiers with concourses on Level 1, 2, 4 and 5.<ref name=\"guide\"/> The East and West Stands are 33.8 m and 33.2 m high respectively, and have concourses on Level 1 and 5. Both stands have four tiers each, two of which are smaller and intended for [[Club seating|premium seating]].<ref name=\"guide\"/> There are around 8,000 of these premium seats as well as 70 private [[luxury box|loges]] and super loges for premium members and corporate hospitality.<ref name=stone>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47687411 |title=Tottenham: A glimpse inside Spurs' new \u00a31bn state-of-the-art stadium|first= Simon|last= Stone|work=BBC Sport|date=24 March 2019|accessdate=25 March 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/spurs/80756/new-spurs-stadium-tunnel-views-at-eyewatering-prices |title=New Spurs stadium: tunnel views at eyewatering prices |date=20 January 2017|work=The Week |accessdate=21 July 2018 }}</ref><ref name=moore>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2019/mar/30/new-spurs-stadium-review-tottenham-hotspur-lets-call-it-a-home-win |title=Spurs\u2019 new stadium: let\u2019s call it a home win |first=Rowan |last=Moore|date= 30 March 2019 |accessdate=7 April 2019|work=The Observer }}</ref> The seats of the stadium, initially numbered 62,062 but later increased twice to 62,303,<ref name=capacity /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/11277777/tottenhams-new-stadium-capacity-increased-to-62062|title=Spurs stadium capacity increased to 62,062|date= 5 March 2018|publisher=Sky Sports|accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref> are in navy blue,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://talksport.com/football/391399/tottenham-new-stadium-seats-ripped-out-building-blunder/ |title= Tottenham's new stadium to have 15,000 seats ripped out after building blunder |work=talkSPORT|date=27 June 2018 }}</ref> with 42,000 of these reserved for season ticket holders.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/may-article-import/2018/welcome-home-secure-your-seat-and-look-around-the-new-stadium/ |title=Welcome Home - Secure Your Seat and 'Look Around' the New Stadium |work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club }}</ref> The seats have a minimum width of 470mm (compared with the 455\u2013460 mm of the previous stadium), increasing to 520\u2013700 mm for premium seats, with legroom of between 780 to 858mm.<ref name=7facts /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thstofficial.com/thst-news/new-stadium-qa-thst-thfc-and-populous-13-july-2015 |title=New Stadium Q&A: THST, THFC and Populous - 13 July 2015 |date=16 July 2015|work=Tottenham Hotspur Supporters Trust |accessdate=14 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:View of North Stand in Tottenham Hotspur Stadium.jpg|thumb|The North Stand, seating for away fans is in the right corner. The Sky Bridge is above the North Stand.]]\nAway fans are allocated seats in the north east corner; 3,000 seats in the lower tier for Premier League games, while for domestic cups they may be allocated up to 15% of the capacity spread over three tiers.<ref name=7facts>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/seven-key-answers-spurs-new-12913685|title= Seven key answers about Spurs' new stadium including if White Hart Lane's cockerels will be saved |first=Alasdair |last= Gold|date= 19 April 2017 |work=football.london }}</ref>  The stands include areas with 7,500 seats that can be quickly turned into safe standing areas should there be a change in the legislation that banned standing in football stadiums.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/06/26/tottenhams-new-stadium-has-future-proofed-safe-standing/ |title=Tottenham's new stadium has been 'future-proofed' for safe standing |first=Sam |last=Dean |date=26 June 2018 |work=Daily Telegraph |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tottenham-hotspur-can-convert-to-safe-standing-within-an-hour-vc5hfpmsl |title=Tottenham Hotspur can convert to safe-standing within an hour |first=Martyn |last=Ziegler|work=The Times|date=27 July 2018 |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2018/june/club-s-future-proofed-areas-offer-new-concept-in-safe-standing-debate/|title=Club\u2019s future-proofed areas offer new concept in safe standing debate |date=25 June 2018 |accessdate=26 March 2019|work =Tottenham Hotspur F.C. }}</ref> A family area is located in the north west corner for those attending with their children. Disabled fans are catered for with 265 wheelchair bays, areas for assistance dogs as well as facilities for those with \"complex care requirements\".<ref name=stone /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://ask.tottenhamhotspur.com/hc/en-us/articles/209483865-Accessibility |title=Ask Spurs: Accessibility |work=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |accessdate=20 July 2019 }}</ref>  Accessible seating is available in all four stands, where the design allows for flexible seating for family groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/may-article-import/2018/welcome-home-secure-your-seat-and-look-around-the-new-stadium/ |title=Welcome Home - Secure Your Seat and 'Look Around' the New Stadium |date=12 March 2018 |work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |accessdate=13 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Pitches===\nThe association football pitch of the stadium has a standard dimension of 105m x 68m, same in size as the pitches at [[Old Trafford]] and Wembley Stadium, but 440 square metres larger than the pitch at White Hart Lane.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/15122/10989411/will-the-bigger-wembley-pitch-affect-tottenham-this-season |title= Will the bigger Wembley pitch affect Tottenham this season? |first= Adam |last=Smith|date= 16 August 2017 |work=Sky Sports}}</ref> The overall grass surface is 114.58\u00d779.84 metres, including the perimeter between the pitch and the stands. The distances between the stands and the pitch are minimised so as to enhance the atmosphere on match days &ndash; {{convert|7.97|m|ft|1}} on the east, north and west sides from the front of the stand to the pitch, and {{convert|4.985|m|ft|1}} at the south end of the pitch.<ref name=\"bowl\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planningservices.haringey.gov.uk/portal/servlets/AttachmentShowServlet?ImageName=748767 |title=Tottenham Hotspur Design and Access Statement 2015 |work=Haringey Council }}</ref>\n\nIn order to keep the football pitch in optimum condition, there are two different surfaces &ndash; a [[Desso GrassMaster]] hybrid grass pitch for football, and a synthetic turf [[American football field|surface]] underneath to be used for NFL games, as well as concerts and other events.<ref name=\"bowl\"/><ref name=\"populous\">{{cite web|url=https://populous.com/project/tottenham-hotspur-football-club/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |work=Populous }}</ref> The football pitch can be retracted in a way similar to that of the [[Arizona Cardinals]]' [[State Farm Stadium|home stadium]], but it is the first in the world to split into three sections before retracting.<ref name=ingenia>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham-give-impressive-first-look-at-wordfirst-dividing-retractable-pitch-for-new-stadium-a3629321.html|title= Tottenham give impressive first look at 'world-first dividing retractable pitch' for new stadium|first=Alex|last= Young |date= 7 September 2017 |work=Evening Standard }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/09/07/tottenham-hotspur-will-have-worlds-first-dividing-retractable/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur will have world's first dividing retractable pitch, so they can host football and NFL |date=7 September 2017 |work=The Daily Telegraph }}</ref>  The pitch needed to split so as to accommodate the two columns that support the South Stand when retracting.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ingenia.org.uk/Ingenia/Articles/a57524c7-215a-484d-9ffb-94c16030f3fc |title=The football pitch in three pieces|first=Richard |last=Gray |work=Ingenia |date= December 2018 |accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> Each of the three sections weighs more than 3,000 tonnes, and is made up of 33 smaller trays, making a total of 99 trays, with a combined weight of 10,000 tonnes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/01/26/installation-work-starts-on-spurs-retractable-pitch/ |title=Installation work starts on Spurs retractable pitch |first=Grant |last=Prior |date=26 January 2018|work=Construction Enquirer}}</ref> The retracting pitch slides into the car park under the South Stand and the south podium, and the surface can be switched in between 25 minutes to an hour.<ref name=ingenia /><ref name=ibbetson /> The NFL pitch is placed 1.6 metres beneath the natural turf surface, and the change in height when the surface is switched also produces ideal sightlines for the front row for both codes (NFL team personnel tend to stand pitchside in allocated areas which would block the view of the front row if the pitch is not lower in NFL games).<ref name=ingenia /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/long-reads/tottenham-hotspur-white-hart-lane-new-stadium-football/ |title=Spurs are starting a stadium design revolution in Tottenham|first=Rob |last=Hastings |date= 24 January 2017|work=iNews|accessdate=20 July 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://eandt.theiet.org/content/articles/2019/11/dual-use-at-spurs-new-stadium-gives-nfl-a-london-base/ |title=Dual-use at Spurs\u2019 stadium gives NFL a London base |first= Crispin |last=Andrews|date=13 November 2019 |work= Engineering and Technology|accessdate=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Grow lights over the pitch at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium.jpg|thumb|[[Grow lights]] suspended on trusses over the pitch]]\nThe stadium features the world's first integrated grow lighting system over the pitch. [[Grow light]]s are suspended on six 70-metre trusses to encourage the growth of the grass in the shaded areas of the stadium, and they can be folded away under the North Stand when not in use.<ref name=\"conway\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45586929 |title=Spurs' new stadium 'will be greatest ever built' says chief engineer |first= Richard|last= Conway|date=26 September 2018 |work=BBC Sport }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/new-tottenham-stadium-pitch-structures-15125801 |title=Revealed: What the new metal structures fans have spotted at Spurs' new stadium are for |first=Alasdair |last=Gold |date=9 September 2018 |work=football.london }}</ref><ref name=\"ouzia\">{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/new-tottenham-stadium-pitch-laid-at-new-ground-spurs-unveil-world-first-technology-a3954946.html |title= New Tottenham stadium: Pitch is laid as Spurs unveil 'world-first' technology|first=Malik|last= Ouzia |work=The Evening Standard |date=5 October 2018 |accessdate=6 October 2018 }}</ref> The grass can also be maintained for up to 5 days with artificial lighting, air ventilation, dehumidification and irrigation systems when the pitch is retracted under the south podium.<ref name=ibbetson>{{cite web |url=https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/behind-the-scenes-look-at-tottenhams-retractable-pitch/10041699.article |title=Behind the scenes look at Tottenham\u2019s retractable pitch |date=4 April 2019 |first= Connor |last= Ibbetson |accessdate=8 May 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/events/business-of-sport/christopher-lee-architect-populous/ |title=Architect Christopher Lee from Populous talks modern stadium design|date=3 June 2016|first=David |last=Edwards |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stadia-magazine.com/videos/how-tottenham-hotspur-stadiums-smart-pitch-lighting-system-works.html |title=How Tottenham Hotspur Stadium\u2019s smart pitch lighting system works|work=Stadia Magazine |accessdate=21 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Facilities===\n[[File:Home dressing room at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium.jpg|thumb|left|Home [[dressing room]] at the stadium]]\nThe stadium provides separate facilities for football and NFL players; these include changing rooms, medical facilities, restaurants, [[hydrotherapy]] pools, warm-up areas, pre-match players' lounge, as well as lounges and creches for their families.<ref name=hayward /> It also caters for the different requirements of football and NFL media.<ref name=white /> There are a number of bars for fans on match day. In the South Stand is the Goal Line Bar, which at 65m is the longest in Europe. The White Hart and The Shelf are bars in the East Stand, while The Dispensary is found in the West Stand.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://new-stadium.tottenhamhotspur.com/season-tickets/our-feature-bars/home/ |title= Our Feature Bars |work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> The stadium offers a wide range of food and drinks outlets (65 at the club opening);<ref name=washington /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11683043/tottenhams-new-stadium-watch-the-opening-ceremony-live |title=Tottenham's new stadium: Watch the opening ceremony on Sky Sports|work=Sky Sports |date= 29 March 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019 }}</ref> in the South Stand is the 'Market Place' with a range of food and drink outlets, and a selection of food outlets are also available in other stands.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.compass-group.co.uk/media/news/levy-uk-and-tottenham-hotspur-announces-winning-food-and-drink-offering-for-new-stadium/ |title=Levy UK and Tottenham Hotspur announces winning food and drink offering for new stadium |date=21 June 2018|work=Compass |accessdate=12 July 2018 }}</ref><ref name=stone />  Other features include an in-house bakery and the world's first [[microbrewery]] in a stadium, which can produce one million pints of craft beer a year and deliver up to 10,000 pints a minute.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/01/20/tottenham-give-taster-new-stadium-micro-brewery/ |title=Tottenham give taster of new stadium... with its own micro brewery |first=Jason|last= Burt|date=20 January 2017 |work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=8 July 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2018/may/beavertown-to-open-microbrewery-at-clubs-new-stadium/ |title=Beavertown to open Microbrewery at Club's new stadium |date=30 May 2018 |work=Tottenham Hotspur |accessdate=13 July 2018 }}</ref> The stadium is the first cashless stadium in the country, it also offers stadium-wide connectivity for all the fans with more [[Wi-Fi]] access points and [[Bluetooth]] beacons as well as greater bandwidth than any other stadium.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/f8303438-571e-11e9-91f9-b6515a54c5b1 |title=Spurs stadium\u2019s wireless wonders |first=Chris|last= Nuttall |work=Financial Times |date=4 April 2019 |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://telecoms.com/496746/spurs-and-hpe-hope-to-show-how-stadium-wifi-should-be-done/ |title=Spurs and HPE hope to show how stadium wifi should be done |first=Scott|last= Bicheno |date=3 April 2019 |accessdate=4 April 2019 |work=Telecoms }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190418005264/en/Real-Wireless-Tottenham-Hotspur-Stadium-%E2%80%93-Best-Connected |title=Real Wireless: Tottenham Hotspur Stadium \u2013 the Best-Connected in the UK|date= 18 April 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2019 |work=Business Wire}}</ref> Some car parking spaces, but not for general admission fans, are provided underneath the stand and in the basement. A range of hospitality facilities in the East and West Stands are provided for those with premium memberships. These include two Sky Lounges on the top floor of the East and West Stands, with views over London and the pitch, the Sky Bridge, which is the world's first bridge to be suspended from the roof of a stadium, 65 suites of private loges and super loges, [[Michelin star]] level dining, and the Tunnel Club that allows its members to observe the players as they walk from the dressing room to the pitch through a glass-walled tunnel.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tunnel-club-michelincalibre-food-and-even-a-microbrewery-the-premium-side-of-tottenhams-new-stadium-a3445081.html |title=New Tottenham stadium: Tunnel Club, Michelin-calibre food and even a micro-brewery - The premium side of Tottenham's new stadium |first=Mark|last= Blunden |date= 20 January 2017 |work=Evening Standard |accessdate=11 July 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/new-spurs-stadium-roof-restaurant-13240166 |title=Details of new Spurs stadium's \u00a320m roof emerge with luxury restaurant that will 'hang from it' |first=Alasdair |last=Gold |date= 26 June 2017|work=football.london |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jan/20/tottenham-hotspur-new-stadium-cheese-white-hart-lane |title=Big cheeses: Tottenham\u2019s new stadium to give half-time snacks fancy flavour|first= Amy|last= Lawrence|date=20 January 2017 |accessdate=7 November 2018 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tottenham Hotspur Stadium - northwest corner February 2019.jpg|thumb|Northwest corner of stadium, with access to the north podium, the Paxton ticket office and a cafe]]\nThe stadium is intended to be active all year round as a sports and entertainment destination with conference and banqueting facilities. It offers visitor attractions such as a Sky Walk, whereby visitors may walk up the side of the stadium, right up to the roof which has a glass walkway around the golden cockerel over the South Stand where they may view the goal line from the roof, or abseil down to the south podium from a viewing deck.<ref name=\"plan\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dezeen.com/2019/04/03/tottenham-hotspur-stadium-football-club-design-populous/ |title=Populous completes \"best stadium in the world\" for Tottenham Hotspur |first=Tom |last=Ravenscroft |date= 3 April 2019 |work=De Zeen |accessdate=20 April 2019 }}</ref> The East Stand includes a double-height banquet hall that may be used for conference events.<ref name=\"populous\"/> To the south of the stadium, the raised podium forms a large open public square that may be used for a range of sporting and community activities. The Tottenham Experience, which includes a club shop, club archive and museum on Tottenham High Road, serves as the arrivals hub for visitors, where they may collect tickets and start a tour of the stadium. The museum is located in the Grade II listed Warmington House, and the new club shop is the largest in Europe, featuring a 100-seat auditorium area that may be used for pre-match experiences.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://i.tottenhamhotspur.com/hc/en-us/articles/209100129-Tottenham-Experience |title=Tottenham Experience |work=iSpurs |accessdate= 13 July 2018}}</ref> On the northwest corner is M cafe, a media room that may be open to the public and used as a cafe on non-match days.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/inside-tottenhams-stadium-10-brilliant-features-to-look-out-for-at-first-game-against-crystal-palace-a4108336.html |title=Inside Tottenham's stadium: 10 brilliant features to look out for at first game against Crystal Palace |first=Dan |last=Kilpatrick |date=3 April 2019 |accessdate=20 April 2019 |work= Evening Standard }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/new-spurs-stadium-photos-section-16573151 |title=New Spurs stadium: Photos and all you need to know from inside the latest section to open today|first=Alasdair |last=Gold|date= 12 July 2019 |work=football.london |accessdate=12 July 2019}}</ref> Other facilities may be offered in ancillary buildings surrounding the stadium, including a ticket office, and a planned extreme sports building as well as a community health centre.<ref name=\"populous\"/>\n\n===Statuary===\n\nA 4.5-m-tall and near-double-sized [[fibreglass]] replica of the spurs cockerel, originally created in 1909 to sit atop the west stand at White Hart Lane, was placed on the roof structure above the South Stand on 6 November 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://talksport.com/football/442641/tottenham-hotspur-new-stadium-update-golden-cockerel-spurs/ |title=ICONIC Tottenham new stadium update: Golden Cockerel arrives and is pictured on top of the South Stand |first=Billy |last=Hawkins|date=7 November 2018 |work=Talk Sport |accessdate =7 November 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2018/september/golden-cockerel-to-grace-new-stadium-roof/ |title=Golden Cockerel to grace new stadium roof |date= 10 September 2018|work=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |accessdate=22 August 2019 }}</ref> It is a faithful replica of the original, including dents caused by [[Paul Gascoigne]] when he shot at it with an [[air rifle]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://uk.sports.yahoo.com/news/story-paul-gascoigne-spurs-famous-cockerel-air-rifle-110956540.html |title=The story of Paul Gascoigne, Spurs' famous cockerel and an air rifle |first=Matt |last=Storey|work=Yahoo! Sport |date=10 September 2018 |accessdate =7 July 2019 }}</ref>  A statue of [[Bill Nicholson (footballer)|Bill Nicholson]] will be placed on the south west approach to the stadium; the old gate to the West Stand from White Hart Lane will also be placed here, and the statue of Nicholson will be positioned at its centre, recreating a historic photographic image of Nicholson.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news-archive-1/a-fitting-place-for-bill-in-new-stadium-plans/ |title=A fitting place for Bill in new stadium plans |work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |accessdate=21 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\nThe stadium is the home of Tottenham Hotspur, who play their Premier League and other cup home matches at the ground. The stadium is also used for other football events; in its first year, it was used for a live screening of the [[2019 UEFA Champions League Final]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/grief-was-shared-in-a-giant-gogglebox-experience-at-spurs-new-stadium-3md67bk6k |title=Grief was shared in a giant Gogglebox experience at Spurs\u2019 new stadium |first=Glenn |last=Ebrey |date=2 June 2019|work= The Sunday Times |accessdate=12 June 2019 }}</ref> select [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Under-23s]] games,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2019/august/under-23s-to-appreciate-and-cherish-new-stadium-match-on-friday/ |title=Under-23s to 'appreciate and cherish' new stadium match on Friday |date= 14 August 2019|work=Tottenham Hotspur |accessdate=10 September 2019 }}</ref> as well as the first North London derby in the [[FA Women's Super League]] between Tottenham and Arsenal held on 17 November 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48934921 |title=Women's Super League: Tottenham Hotspur Stadium to host Spurs v Arsenal in November|work=BBC Sports |date=10 July 2019 |accessdate=10 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe stadium is intended to be used for a number of purposes aside from association football, serving as the venue for NFL games and other events. It is can host up to 16 non-association football events a year, at least two of which will be NFL games, and up to six music concerts.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/tottenham-hotspur/story/3042015/tottenham-aiming-for-premier-leagues-best-atmosphere-at-new-stadium |title= Tottenham want Premier League's best atmosphere in building new stadium |date=20 January 2017|first=Dan |last=Kilpatrick |work=ESPN |accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref> \n===NFL London Games===\n{{main|NFL International Series}}\n[[File:Carolina Panthers logo at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium.jpg|thumb|Logo of [[Carolina Panthers]] at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium]]\nTottenham Hotspur Stadium is the first and only stadium to be designed specially for NFL games outside of North America.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/04/sport/nfl-london-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-spt-intl-gbr/index.html |title=Could London become a permanent home for the NFL?|first= George|last= Ramsay|work= CNN|date=4 October 2019}}</ref> The first game at the stadium took place on 6 October 2019 when the [[2019 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]] played against the [[2019 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]]. A record crowd of 60,463 watched the Raiders win a close game 24\u201321.<ref name=\"nflfirrst\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/american-football/49954966 |title=Oakland Raiders 24-21 Chicago Bears: Raiders win first NFL game at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium|first= Ben |last=Collins |work=BBC Sport|date=7 October 2019 |accessdate=7 October 2019}}</ref> The following week, the [[2019 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] hosted the [[2019 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]] on October 13.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/american-football/47967256 |title=NFL London: Schedule announced for Tottenham Stadium & Wembley games | work=BBC Sport |date= 17 April 2019|accessdate= 17 April 2019 }}</ref>\nA number of NFL events were held at the stadium before the first game; the trials for the first intake of the NFL Academy was launched at the stadium on 2 July 2019;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/jul/02/nfl-american-football-tottenham-london-academy-way-out-teenagers |title=NFL comes to London offering way out for trapped teenagers |first=Robert |last=Booth |date= 2 July 2019 |work=The Guardian|accessdate=7 July 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://talksport.com/sport/us-sports/567007/tottenham-hotspur-stadium-nfl-beckham/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur Stadium looks incredible in NFL mode with star wide receiver Odell Beckham Jr hailing the facilities as 'better than back home'|first =Josh |last=Fordham|date=2 July 2019|work=talkSport |accessdate=5 July 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://sportsvenuebusiness.com/index.php/2019/07/02/nfl-makes-its-debut-at-the-new-tottenham-hotspur-stadium/ |title=NFL Makes Its Debut at the New Tottenham Hotspur Stadium|work=Sports Venue Business |date=2 July 2019 |accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref> and the national NFL Flag Championship, [[flag football]] competition for UK schoolchildren aged 8\u201311, were the first such games held at the stadium on 3 July 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url= \nhttp://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001035148/article/nfl-flag-champions-crowned-at-tottenham-hotspur-stadium |title=NFL Flag champions crowned at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium|date=4 July 2019 |work=NFL | accessdate=5 July 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.silverandblackpride.com/2019/6/15/18680233/tahir-whitehead-to-represent-raiders-for-series-of-july-events-in-london |title=Tahir Whitehead to represent Raiders for series of July events in London|first= Levi |last=Damien|date=15 June 2019|work=SBNation }}</ref>\n\nThe first [[Touchdown|touchdown]] at the stadium was scored by [[Josh Jacobs]].\n\n===Rugby===\nThe [[rugby union]] club [[Saracens F.C.|Saracens]] will also play their annual showpiece game at the stadium for five years starting in 2020,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/47787038 |title=Saracens to play annual showpiece at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium |work=BBC |date=2 April 2019 |accessdate=2 April 2019 }}</ref> with the first game taking place between Saracens and [[Harlequin F.C.|Harlequins]] {{efn|Match was originally scheduled for 28 March 2020, but was postponed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/rugby/date-confirmed-for-saracens-vs-harlequins-at-tottenhams-new-stadium-a4186556.html |title=Date confirmed for Saracens vs Harlequins at Tottenham's new stadium |first=Simon |last= Collings |date=10 July 2019 |work=Evening Standard|accessdate=10 July 2019 }}</ref> The stadium will also host the [[European Rugby Champions Cup]] and [[European Rugby Challenge Cup|Challenge Cup]] finals in 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/new-tottenham-stadium-to-stage-rugby-cup-finals-in-2021-a4135906.html |title=New Tottenham stadium to stage rugby cup finals in 2021|first=Simon|last= Collings|work=Evening Standard |date=7 May 2019 |accessdate=7 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe first [[rugby league]] match at the stadium will be the [[2020 Kangaroo tour of England#Third Test|third and final test]] in the 2020 [[The Ashes (rugby league)|Ashes series]] between [[England national rugby league team|England]] and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] on 14 November 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/rugby-league/50329514 |title=Tottenham Hotspur Stadium to host final England v Australia Ashes test in 2020 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=7 November 2019 |website=[[BBC Online]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |access-date=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Concerts===\nThe first concerts scheduled at the stadium will be by [[Guns N' Roses]] to be held on 29\u201330 May 2020 as part of the European leg of their [[Guns N' Roses 2020 Tour]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/guns-n-roses-announce-london-show-on-2020-european-stadium-tour-2587075 |title=Guns N' Roses add second huge London show to 2020 European stadium tour |first=Nick |last= Reilly |date= 13 December 2019|work=NME |accessdate=21 December 2019 }}</ref>  [[Capital (radio network)|Capital]]'s music event [[Summertime Ball]] was planned to be held at the stadium on 6 June 2020 but cancelled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/spurs-confirm-major-event-stadium-17708662 |title= Spurs confirm major summer event at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium |first=Josh |last=Challies|date= 7 February 2020 |work=football.london |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/capital-summertime-ball-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-cancelled-a4392096.html |title=Capital\u2019s Summertime Ball at the Tottenham Hotspur Stadium cancelled as organisers react to threat of coronavirus |first=Harry|last=Fletcher |work=Evening Standard |date=19 March 2020 }}</ref> [[Lady Gaga]] will also perform at the stadium as part of [[The Chromatica Ball]] to support her new album ''[[Chromatica]]'' on 30 July 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/lady-gaga-the-chromatica-ball-tour-london-date-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-tickets-2620807 |title= Lady Gaga announces huge UK date on 'The Chromatica Ball Tour'|first=Sam |last=Moore|work=NME |date=5 March 2020|accessdate=5 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Boxing===\nThe stadium will host the very first bout between the English defending [[World Boxing Association|WBA (super)]], [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]], [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]], and [[International Boxing Organization|IBO]] world champion [[Anthony Joshua]] and Bulgarian IBF [[mandatory challenger]] [[Kubrat Pulev]] for the heavyweight world titles, on 20 June 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/51705419 |title=Anthony Joshua to fight Kubrat Pulev at Tottenham Hotspur Stadium |date=2 March 2020 |work=BBC |accessdate=2 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Attendance==\nThe stadium has a capacity of 62,303 (initially 62,062), but due to the need to segregate fans, the full capacity may never be reached for association football matches as some seats are deliberately kept unused.<ref name=goldopening>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/things-love-tottenham-new-stadium-16081735 |title=Three things we loved about Tottenham's new stadium and three things we didn't|first=Alasdair |last=Gold|date= 5 April 2019|work=football.london|accessdate=4 April 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"kilpatrick2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/smaller-than-emirates-stadium-why-tottenham-may-struggle-to-fill-62062-capacity-at-1bn-new-home-a4109196.html|title=Smaller than Emirates Stadium? Why Tottenham may struggle to fill 62,062 capacity at \u00a31bn new home |first=Dan|last= Kilpatrick|work=Evening Standard|date=4 April 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019 }}</ref>  Attendance is counted by the number of fans going through the gates rather than the number of tickets issued as is the case in some grounds such as the [[Emirates Stadium|Emirates]] as well as Spurs at Wembley where attendance figures may include season ticket holders who did not turn up for matches and unused free tickets.<ref name=\"kilpatrick2019\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsvibe.co.uk/2019/04/05/when-is-a-capacity-not-a-capacity-ask-spurs-or-arsenal/|title=When is a capacity not a capacity \u2013 Ask Spurs or Arsenal! |date=5 April 2019 |work=Sportsvibe |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45158878 |title=Football club attendances: Are fans getting the full picture? |first= Alistair |last=Magowan |date=12 September 2019|work=BBC Sport |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> The first match after its official opening, although sold out, was attended by 59,215 fans as some rows of seating were kept empty and some premium areas were not yet opened.<ref name=goldopening /><ref name=\"kilpatrick2019\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6337444-the-reason-why-tottenham-hotspur-did-not-have-full-capacity-for-first-match-at-new-stadium |title=The Reason Why Tottenham Hotspur Did Not Have Full Capacity for First Match at New Stadium|first=Tom |last=Gott|date=5 April 2019 |work=90Min |accessdate=6 April 2019}}</ref> Attendance in the first season at the stadium averaged at 59,175 from the 7 home matches played there, compared to 59,826 for all home matches that season, most of which were played at Wembley which has a higher capacity.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.footballwebpages.co.uk/premier-league/attendances |title=Premier League \u2013 Average Attendances \u2013 Home Matches |work=Football Web Pages |accessdate=4 September 2019 }}</ref> \n\nThe official stadium record attendance for a Tottenham game currently stands at 61,104 in the English Premier League match against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on 22 December 2019.<ref name=\"record attendance\" />  The previous highest attendance for any game was the first NFL game held at the stadium  on 6 October 2019 between [[Chicago Bears]] and [[Oakland Raiders]], which was watched by 60,463 spectators.<ref name=\"nflfirrst\"/>  It recorded the highest ever attendance for a [[FA Women's Super League|Women's Super League]] match at 38,262 in the match against [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal Women]] held on 17 November 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50363864 |title=Tottenham Hotspur Women 0 : 2 Arsenal Women |first=Tom |last=Garry|work=BBC |date=17 November 2019 |accessdate= 2 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Cost, finance and sponsorship==\n[[File:East entrance of Tottenham Hotspur Stadium on Worcester Avenue.jpg|thumb|East entrance on Worcester Avenue]]\nAn early estimate put Phase 2 of the development, that includes the construction of the stadium, at \u00a3305 million,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/09c-MRF-Stage-2-North-Tottenham-Project-Appraisal%20RTF.rtf |url-status=dead |title=Project Appraisal From - Stage 2: Investment Decision |website=London.gov.uk |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902032013/https://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/09c-MRF-Stage-2-North-Tottenham-Project-Appraisal%20RTF.rtf |archivedate=2 September 2012 }}</ref> but in July 2018, it was reported that the construction of the stadium itself was projected to cost \u00a3350\u2013\u00a3400 million, out of the estimated \u00a3850 million cost for the entire Northumberland Development Project.<ref name=\"kilpatrick\">{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/new-tottenham-stadium-not-possible-without-2011-london-riots-a3898956.html |title=New Tottenham stadium 'not possible' without 2011 London riots|first=Dan |last=Kilpatrick |work=The Evening Standard |date=30 July 2018}}</ref> The cost had increased due to the higher cost of import by at least 15% caused by the [[Brexit]] vote on the exchange rate,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/daniel-levy-new-tottenham-stadium-club-new-dawn-a4316696.html |title=Daniel Levy: Delivering new Tottenham stadium is end of the beginning for club's new dawn|first=James|last= Olley |date= 18 December 2019 |work=Evening Standard |accessdate=30 December 2019 }}</ref> changes to the build, overtime working, extra hirings and higher construction costs.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham-reveal-cost-of-new-stadium-has-risen-to-800m-due-to-brexit-a3484516.html |title=New Tottenham Stadium: Tottenham reveal cost of new ground has risen to \u00a3800 million |first=Tom |last=Collomosse|date= 8 March 2017 |work=Evening Standard }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/08/16/spurs-stadium-builders-earning-more-than-the-players/ |title= Spurs stadium builders \"earning more than the players\"|first=Grant |last=Prior|work=Construction Enquirer|date=16 August 2018|accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref> The cost of the project was widely reported to be over \u00a31.2 billion, although the club had insisted that the final cost would be less than a billion.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/09/21/tottenham-insist-suggestions-12bn-final-stadium-bill-inaccurate/ |title=Tottenham insist suggestions of \u00a31.2bn final stadium bill are inaccurate |first=Matt |last=Law|date=21 September 2018 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref> Just before the stadium opened in April 2019, the club chairman [[Daniel Levy (businessman)|Daniel Levy]] said that the cost is of the order of one billion.<ref name=\"gilmour\">{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/11682615/daniel-levy-says-tottenham-will-become-one-of-biggest-clubs-in-the-world |title=Daniel Levy says Tottenham will become one of biggest clubs in the World|first =Paul|last=Gilmour|date=3 April 2019|work=Sky Sports|accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe project was financed through a combination of club's own resources, bank loans and club revenues.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47794989 |title=Tottenham: New stadium can make Spurs one of world's biggest clubs, says Chairman Daniel Levy |work=BBC |date=2 April 2019|accessdate=3 April 2019 }}</ref> A \u00a3200 million interim financing facility was arranged in December 2015 with three banks to finance the project.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.insideworldfootball.com/2017/06/01/spurs-secure-400m-bank-loan-complete-740m-stadium-build/ |title=Spurs secure \u00a3400m bank loan to complete \u00a3740m stadium build |date=1 June 2017 |work=Inside Football World }}</ref> This was replaced in May 2017 by a \u00a3400 million, five-year loan, deal with the banks to fund the remaining build.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham-announce-400-million-deal-to-help-finance-new-stadium-a3553746.html |title=New Tottenham stadium: Spurs announce \u00a3400million loan deal to help finance new stadium |first=Tom |last=Collomosse|date= 31 May 2017 |work=Evening Standard }}</ref> By this stage, \u00a3340 million had already been spent on land acquisition and the planning process, as well as the construction cost; \u00a3100 million of this came from the 2015 interim financing, with the rest from club resources.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/spurs-loans-idUSL8N1IX54A| title=LPC-Tottenham Hotspur nets \u00a3400m stadium loan |first=Alasdair |last=Reilly|date=31 May 2017 |work=Reuters }}</ref>  However, with costs spiralling, the club was forced to borrow an extra \u00a3237 million, raising the financing facility to \u00a3637m.<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/tottenham-new-stadium-wembley-pitch-opening-when-ready-spending-debt-vs-manchester-city-a8608226.html |title=New Tottenham stadium: Spurs forced to borrow another \u00a3237m as costs continue to spiral|first=Jack |last=Pitt-Brooke |date=30 October 2018 |work=The Independent |accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref> In order to reduce debt-servicing costs and improve annual cash flow, \u00a3525 million of the debt was refinanced by issuing [[Bond (finance)|bonds]] that will mature in 15 to 30 years' time.  The bond issue was arranged by [[Bank of America Merrill Lynch]], which also provided a \u00a3112m loan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/b5931cd8-da1a-11e9-8f9b-77216ebe1f17 |title= Tottenham secures financial future with stadium debt deal |first1=Murad|last1= Ahmed|first2= Robert |last2=Smith|work=The Financial Times|date=20 September 2019|accessdate=20 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2019/september/club-refinances-construction-debt/ |title=Club Refinances Construction Debt|date=20 September 2019|work=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |accessdate=20 September 2019 }}</ref> The club aims to pay for the stadium through a number of means: income from ticket sales is forecast to increase to \u00a3100 million per year, more than twice that earned from White Hart Lane;<ref name=hayward>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/03/24/tottenham-hotspurs-new-ground-eclipses-north-london-rivalsemirates/ |title=Tottenham Hotspur's new ground eclipses north London rivals' Emirates Stadium \u2013 it was worth the long wait |first=Paul |last=Hayward|date=25 March 2019 |work=The Telegraph|accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref> revenues from other sports hosted at the stadium with the NFL contributing \u00a310 million to the initial cost;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.us/tottenham-hotspur/story/3108630/nfl-helping-fund-new-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-sources?ICID=ref_fark |title=NFL helping fund new Tottenham Hotspur stadium - sources |publisher=ESPN |date=21 April 2017 |author=Dan Kilpatrick |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> increased hospitality and catering income,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cateringinsight.com/kccj-outfit-is-bringing-spurs-800000-during-each-game/ |title=KCCJ outfit is bringing Spurs \u00a3800,000 during each game |first=Clare |last= Nicholls |date=30 April 2019 |work=Catering Insight }}</ref> as well as sponsorship, merchandising, advertising, concession and digital rights, and broadcast revenues.<ref name=washington />\n\n===Partnership and deals===\nThe club has a number of partners at the stadium. Following on tradition, Heineken, who have previously held sponsorship deals, have been named as the beer sponsor for the new stadium.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/partners/heineken-named-as-official-beer-partner-for-tottenham-hotspur-iconic-new-stadium-180518/ |title=Heineken named as official beer partner for Tottenham Hotspur's Iconic new stadium |publisher=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |date=18 May 2018 |accessdate=7 June 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616180354/https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/partners/heineken-named-as-official-beer-partner-for-tottenham-hotspur-iconic-new-stadium-180518/ |archivedate=16 June 2018 }}</ref> The north London brewer Beavertown is the official craft beer supplier and it installed the world's first stadium-located microbrewery on the south east corner of the stadium.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/tottenham-hotspur-team-up-with-beavertown-to-create-worlds-first-microbrewery-in-a-football-stadium-a3851201.html |title=Tottenham Hotspur team up with Beavertown to create world's first microbrewery in a football stadium|first=Tom|last= Powell |date= 30 May 2018 |work= Evening Standard }}</ref> The company selected by the club to supply the advertising system in the new ground will be TGI.<ref>{{cite web |title=TGI to deliver perimeter advertising system at club's new world-class stadium |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club/new-stadium/tgi-to-deliver-perimeter-advertising-system-310518/ |publisher=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |date=31 May 2018 |accessdate=4 June 2018 }}</ref> Tottenham signed a contract with [[LG Corporation|LG]] to supply the new stadium with Ultra-premium TVs and digital signage.<ref>{{cite web |title=LG Chosen to Supply Ultra-Premium TVS and Digital Signage across new stadium |url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club/new-stadium/lg-chosen-to-supply-ultra-premium-tvs-and-digital-signage-across-new-stadium-010618/ |publisher=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |date=1 June 2018 |accessdate=4 June 2018 }}</ref> [[Hewlett Packard Enterprise]] is the IT networking and wireless infrastructure partner for the new stadium.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news-archive-1/hewlett-packard-enterprise-to-support-technology-vision-for-new-stadium/ |title=Hewlett Packard Enterprise to support technology vision for new vision |date=11 July 2018 |work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club |accessdate= 1 August 2018}}</ref> The concessions for food and drink in the stadium are run by [[Levy Restaurants|Levy]], a subsidiary of [[Compass Group|Compass]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2019/03/27/businesses-making-tottenham-hotspurs-new-1bn-stadium-envy-premier/ |title=The businesses making Tottenham Hotspur's new \u00a31bn stadium the envy of its Premier League rivals|first= Oliver|last= Gill |date=28 March 2019|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Naming rights===\nThe stadium is named Tottenham Hotspur Stadium until a [[Naming rights|naming-rights]] agreement is reached.<ref name=\"name\">{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/new-tottenham-stadium-will-be-called-the-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-if-clubs-starts-season-without-a3776636.html |title=New Tottenham stadium will be called the 'Tottenham Hotspur Stadium' if club starts season without naming-rights deal |first=Tom |last= Collomosse |date= 27 February 2018 |work=London Evening Standard |accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref> The club is looking for deals variously reported to be worth \u00a320m annually (\u00a3400 million for a 20-year deal or \u00a3200 million for ten years),<ref name=\"thenational_726821\"/><ref name=\"telegraph_2018-08-30\"/> or \u00a325 million in a 15-year deal (\u00a3375 million).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/12/18/tottenham-hold-world-record-25m-a-year-deal-sell-stadium-naming/ |title=Exclusive: Tottenham hold out for world record \u00a325m-a-year deal to sell stadium naming rights but no buyer imminent |first= Matt |last=Law|date=18 December 2019 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Economic impact===\nThe club estimates that the stadium would inject around \u00a3293 million a year into the community in Tottenham, and create more than 1,700 new jobs out of the total of 3,500 jobs to be created when the project is complete.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/03/sports/tottenham-hotspur-stadium.html |title=Tottenham Hotspur Stadium Opens: Is There Room for Everyone? |first=Rory|last= Smith|date=April 3, 2019|work=The New York Times |accessdate=10 April 2019 }}</ref><ref name=winter>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tottenham-hotspurs-new-stadium-should-be-a-source-of-pride-for-all-of-football-9c5r8gcsd |title=Tottenham Hotspur\u2019s new stadium should be a source of pride for all of football |first= Henry|last= Winter|date=26 March 2019|work=The Times|accessdate=10 April 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:Spurs stadium January 2020.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|View towards the South Stand]]\nThe new stadium has received generally positive comments from fans as well as sports and architecture writers alike.  [[Paul Hayward (journalist)|Paul Hayward]] of ''The Telegraph'' described it as \"imposing and extravagant, yes, but still true to Tottenham Hotspur\u2019s spirit and ''raison d'\u00eatre''\".<ref name=hayward />  ''[[The Observer]]'''s architecture critic [[Rowan Moore]], despite being unimpressed by the \"ugliness\" of its external appearance, chose it as one of the top five buildings of 2019,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2019/dec/29/rowan-moore-best-architecture-of-2019 |title=Rowan Moore\u2019s best architecture of 2019 |first=Rowan |last=Moore|date= 29 December 2019 |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref> arguing that the stadium is at its best as a venue for watching football, and that it has achieved \"the desired combination of magnificence and intimacy\".<ref name=moore /> Similarly David Hytner of ''[[The Guardian]]'' noted that while the stadium is significantly larger, it still has the \"feeling of intimacy\" due to the closeness of the stands to the pitch, and that the design of the stadium has managed to \"retain the feel of the old White Hart Lane\".<ref name=hytner2019 /> [[Henry Winter]] of ''[[The Times]]'' offered the opinion that the new stadium has shown the other clubs \"the quality of spec required\" for a new stadium, and one that can produce the loudest sound for the fans. He also noted the significance of the new stadium within the community in Tottenham by helping to regenerate a deprived area blighted by riots, becoming a stadium that is \"a must-see stop on those touring London\u2019s architectural splendours\" and one should be a source of pride \"for all in the game\".<ref name=winter /> \n\nIn a survey of 4,302 fans organised by Tottenham Hotspur Supporters' Trust, 95% were satisfied with their experience attending games at the new stadium, compared to 52% of fans who were satisfied while Tottenham were playing at Wembley Stadium. 84% of those were satisfied with the atmosphere at the stadium for league game, rising to 98% for European games.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/tottenham-fans-reveal-what-they-love-about-new-stadium-and-what-needs-to-improve-a4201546.html |title= Tottenham fans reveal what they love about new stadium... and what needs to improve |first= Simon |last=Collings |work=Evening Standard |date=31 July 2019 |accessdate=5 August 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thstofficial.com/uploads/9/2/2/6/92268578/thst_annual_fans_survey_2019.pdf |title=Fan Survey 2019 |date=July 2019|accessdate=5 August 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe stadium won the Supreme Award for Structural Engineering Excellence in the [[Structural Awards]] from the [[Institution of Structural Engineers]] in 2019. It also won in the Long Span Structures category.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.istructe.org/structuralawards/winners |title=2019 Winners |work=The Institution of Structural Engineers |accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref> Other awards it has received in 2019 include [[Architects' Journal]]'s Architecture Awards for 'Best Leisure Project',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/aj-architecture-awards-2019-winner-leisure/10045344.article |title=AJ Architecture Awards 2019 winner: Leisure |date=20 November 2019 |first= Will |last= Hurst |work=Architects' Journal |accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref> the [[Building (magazine)|Building Magazine]] Project of the Year,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.building-awards.com/2019-winners/ |title=Congratulations to our Building Awards 2019 Winners! |work=Building Awards |accessdate=24 November 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.building.co.uk/buildings/buildings-projects-of-the-year-2019/5103446.article |title=Building\u2019s Projects of the Year 2019 |first=Ike |last=Ijeh |date=23 December 2019|work=Building|accessdate=29 December 2019 }}</ref> Gold awards from the World Interior News (WIN) in the Branding and Wayfinding category as well as for its general concourse design in the Leisure and Entertainment Interiors category,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldinteriorsnewsawards.com/winners-2019/ |title= Results 2019: Interiors |work=WIN Awards |accessdate=24 November 2019 }}</ref> Bronze Award in the Leisure category of the World Architecture News Awards,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wanawards.com/results-2019/ |title=Results 2019 |date=24 October 2019 |work=WAN Awards |accessdate=24 November 2019 }}</ref> Local Authority Building Control (LABC) Building Excellence Award in the Best Inclusive Building category for Tottenham Experience,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.labc.co.uk/awards/grand-finals-2019-winners |title=LABC Grand Finals Winners and Highly Commended 2019 |work=LABC |accessdate=24 November 2019 }}</ref> and Structural Steel Design Awards for Project of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.steelconstruction.org/2019/10/02/2019-structural-steel-design-awards-winners-announced/ |title=2019 Structural Steel Design Awards winners announced |date= 2 October 2019 |work=SteelConstruction.org }}</ref>\n\n==In popular media==\nThe stadium is the subject of an episode of ''Richard Hammond's Big'' where the presenter [[Richard Hammond]] explores the biggest things he can find, broadcast in February 2020 on [[Discovery Channel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/news/daniel-levy-makes-big-claim-17776817 |title=Daniel Levy makes big claim about Tottenham Hotspur Stadium plus what's still to be finished|first=Alasdair |last= Gold| date=19 February 2020 |work=football.london |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nThe stadium is accessible via a number of [[London Overground]], [[London Underground]] and [[National Rail]] stations: [[Seven Sisters station|Seven Sisters]], [[Tottenham Hale station|Tottenham Hale]], [[Northumberland Park railway station|Northumberland Park]], and [[White Hart Lane railway station|White Hart Lane]] stations. The nearest station, at around 200 m away, is White Hart Lane, which is on the London Overground line from [[Liverpool Street station]].<ref name=transport />   The station ticket hall was rebuilt in 2019, and a Wembley-style walkway for fans from the station to the stadium is planned. The next nearest is [[Northumberland Park railway station|Northumberland Park]] and fans can reached the stadium via Park Lane. Both Seven Sisters and Tottenham Hale stations are stops along the [[Victoria line]] on [[London Underground]]. The walk to the stadium from Seven Sisters station takes around 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://i.tottenhamhotspur.com/hc/en-us/articles/209485005-New-Stadium-Getting-Here |title=New Stadium Getting Here|work=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |accessdate=10 April 2019 }}</ref>  White Hart Lane and Seven Sisters are popular stops for fans which can cause congestion after games on match days.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/passengers-criticise-overcrowding-on-tube-after-first-match-at-new-spurs-stadium-a4109021.html |title=TfL passengers 'like cattle' on London Underground after first match at new Tottenham stadium |first=Magda |last= Ibrahim |date= 4 April 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2019 }}</ref>\n \nThe stadium area is served by up to 144 buses an hour.<ref name=\"illustrative\"/> Bus routes that stop close to the ground are [[London Buses route 149|149]], [[London Buses route 259|259]], [[London Buses route 279|279]], [[London Buses route 349|349]], and [[London Buses route W3|W3]].<ref name=transport>{{cite web |url=https://moovitapp.com/index/en-gb/public_transportation-White_Hart_Lane_Stadium-London_and_South_East-efsite_4ac518f7f964a5209eaf20e3-2122 |title=How to get to White Hart Lane Stadium in Tottenham by Bus, Tube or National Rail |work=Moovit }}</ref> A number of buses routes however are subject to diversions on matchdays. The club also operates two high frequency shuttle bus services to the stadium, one from [[Alexandra Palace railway station|Alexandra Palace]] via [[Wood Green tube station|Wood Green]] (on [[Piccadilly line]]) and finishing at [[Haringey Sixth Form College]], and the other from Tottenham Hale to [[Duke's Aldridge Academy]].<ref name=\"illustrative\">{{cite web |url=http://new-stadium.tottenhamhotspur.com/transport/ |title=Transport |work=Tottenham Hotspur }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/the-stadium/plan-your-visit/getting-here/shuttle-bus-services/ |title=Shuttle Bus Services |work=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |accessdate=24 April 2019 }}</ref>  On match days, roads near the stadium are normally closed to traffic two to three hours before kick-off, and one to one and a half hours after the match.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://i.tottenhamhotspur.com/hc/en-us/articles/360001254109-Road-Closures |title=Road Closures Local Information |accessdate=4 April 2019 |work=Ask Spurs}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://talksport.com/football/507748/tottenham-hotspur-stadium-latest-update-haringey-council-road-traffic-order/ |title=FINALLY Tottenham Hotspur Stadium latest: Fans believe stadium could be opened NEXT WEEK as Haringey council pass Road Traffic Order for March 16 |first=Joe |last=Coleman |date=8 March 2019|work=talkSport|accessdate=20 April 2019 }}</ref> Car parking in the area is controlled on match days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.haringey.gov.uk/parking-roads-and-travel/parking/controlled-parking-zones-cpzs/tottenham-event-day-cpz/tottenham-event-day-cpz-map |title=Tottenham Event Day CPZ map |work=Haringey Council |accessdate=8 April 2019 }}</ref> Tottenham has also started an arrangement with Big Green Coaches to provide match-day travel for fans to get to and from matches. A number of major towns in and around South East England are chosen as pickup points and supporters are dropped off at a designated coach parking facility near the Stadium, and are collected from the same area with coaches departing around an hour after the final whistle back to their collection points.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://spurs.biggreencoach.co.uk/ |title=Regional Coach Network |work=Big Green Coach |accessdate=18 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of stadiums in the United Kingdom by capacity]]\n* [[Potential London NFL franchise]]\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons Category}}\n* [http://new-stadium.tottenhamhotspur.com/ Official Tottenham Hotspur website]\n\n{{Tottenham Hotspur F.C.}}\n{{Premier League venues}}\n{{IStructE Supreme Award laureates}}\n{{NFL Stadiums}}\n{{Portal bar|London|English football|American football}}\n\n[[Category:Tottenham Hotspur F.C.]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in London]]\n[[Category:Football venues in London]]\n[[Category:Premier League venues]]\n[[Category:American football venues in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:National Football League venues]]\n[[Category:NFL International Series]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Yuterodn87", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tottenham_Hotspur_Stadium"}
{"title_page": "List of reportedly haunted locations", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Redirect|Haunting|other uses|The Haunting (disambiguation){{!}}The Haunting}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use American English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n\n{{Paranormal |state=collapsed}}\nThis is a '''list of reportedly haunted locations''' throughout the world, that are said to be haunted by [[ghost]]s or other [[supernatural]] beings, including [[demon]]s. Reports of haunted locations are part of ghostlore, which is a form of [[folklore]].\n\n==Argentina==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n* '''[[Cinco Saltos]]''' in [[R\u00edo Negro (Argentina)|R\u00edo Negro]] has been reported to have a number of ghosts, most of them reportedly the result of [[witchcraft]].{{cn|date=May 2019}} In 2009, an intact corpse of an 8- to 12-year-old girl who had died in the 1930s was found in a cemetery [[ossuary]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www1.rionegro.com.ar/arch200310/s01g02.html |title=Pol\u00e9mica por una momia de Cinco Saltos|publisher=RioNegro.com.ar |date=1 October 2003 |accessdate=28 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Australia==\n<!-- Note to editors: There have reason sighting in austrailia is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:Ararat Lunatic Asylum - Aradale Psychiatric Hospital.jpg|thumb|[[Aradale Mental Hospital|Ararat Lunatic Asylum]]]]\n* The '''''Buratimos''''' is the wreck of a former [[U.S. Navy]] ship from World War II, that occurred off the coast of [[Western Australia]] in 1964.<ref>Jack Wong Sue and Barry Sue. ''Ghost of the Buratimos''. (Revised edition: Perth, 2005)</ref>\n*'''[[Aradale Mental Hospital|Ararat Lunatic Asylum]]''', or Aradale, is the largest abandoned [[History of psychiatric institutions|lunatic asylum]] in Australia. Opened in 1867, Aradale was reserved for many of the incurable mental patients in Victoria during the 1800s. An estimated 13,000 people died here during 140 years of operation.\n* Thirteen people were executed at the '''[[Ballarat Gaol]]''' in [[Ballarat]]. The remains of seven criminals are still on the grounds. The Ballarat Ghost Tours operate nightly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eerietours.com.au |title=Eerietours.com.au |publisher=Eerietours.com.au |date= |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref>\n*'''[[Beechworth Asylum|Beechworth Lunatic Asylum]]''' in [[Beechworth, Victoria]] is reportedly haunted by several ghosts of departed patients. Open from 1867 to 1995, it has appeared in several books, television shows, and documentaries, including ''A.C.T. Paranormal''. Ghost tours run nightly.<ref>[http://www.beechworth.com.au/Beechworth-Tours/Beechworth-Tours/Beechworth-Ghost-Tours-Bookings.html Beechworth Ghost Tours - Information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217024800/http://beechworth.com.au/Beechworth-Tours/Beechworth-Tours/Beechworth-Ghost-Tours-Bookings.html |date=17 February 2011 }} Accessed 6/9/08</ref>\n* '''[[Brisbane City Hall]]''' in [[Brisbane|Brisbane, Australia]] has several stories of deaths spanning the eras before and after its construction. During construction, workmen were said to have died while laying the foundations, which were on top of a former swamp. It is also said that the area was once a significant Aboriginal site&nbsp;\u2013 either a meeting place or campground. One story relates the death of a maintenance man, or lift attendant, who either fell to his death down the lift well or was crushed by the lift&nbsp;\u2013 this story likely results from a suicide from the clock tower that occurred in 1935.{{cn|date=May 2019}} Another story claims an American soldier was stabbed to death during World War II during a fight. Staff have reported the sounds of an argument from the Red Cross Tea Room, and there are many reports of sounds and unusual activity in the areas surrounding these deaths. A third story claims the apparition of a woman is regularly seen traversing the main stairs in the lobby, and to look out over the foyer&nbsp;\u2013 a story which likely results from another suicide from City Hall's Clock Tower in 1937, although recent photos of the stairwell exhibit a possible apparition.{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n[[File:The BuzzSaw viewed from the entrance to Dreamworld..jpg|thumb|200px|[[BuzzSaw (roller coaster)|BuzzSaw roller coaster]] in Dreamworld.]]\n* '''[[Dreamworld (Australian theme park)|Dreamworld]]''' is a theme park in [[Coomera, Queensland]]. One building inside the grounds of the theme park, where the reality television series ''[[Big Brother Australia]]'' is produced, has been reported to be haunted since the show's first season in 2001. Numerous production staff claim to have witnessed the presence of a young girl, as well as a child's voice and fog appearing late at night and early in the morning.<ref>{{cite web | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130902213833/http://www.bigbrother.com.au/news/8715707/the-big-brother-housemate-youve-yet-to-meet | url = http://www.bigbrother.com.au/news/8715707/the-big-brother-housemate-youve-yet-to-meet | title = The Big Brother Housemate You\u2019ve Yet To Meet ... | archivedate = 2 September 2013 | date = 31 August 2013 | accessdate = 17 February 2015}}</ref> Additionally, theme park employees have spoken about sightings of a ghost nicknamed [[Jack Darke]], named after a [[gold prospecting|gold prospector]] who was claimed to have been killed by a buzzsaw in 1897.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9jVxSdym8Kg | title = Dreamworld Ghost Video | date = 18 August 2011}}</ref>\n*'''[[Fremantle Arts Centre]]''' in [[Fremantle]], [[Western Australia]] was originally built as a psychiatric hospital - Fremantle Lunatic Asylum - it has seen much overcrowding, abuse and death. It was built using convict labour between 1861 and 1868. Cold spots are commonly felt, sounds of crying, laughter and yelling have been heard. Some people have reported the feeling of being kissed on the cheek by unseen persons. A lot of the activity takes place on the first floor where doors open and close and objects move by themselves. One of the apparitions that is seen, a woman whose daughter had been kidnapped was admitted to the asylum due to her deep depression, committed suicide by throwing herself through the first floor window. It is said she can be seen about the building as she still searches in hopes of finding her daughter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theparanormalguide.com/1/post/2014/04/fremantle-arts-centre.html|title=Fremantle Arts Centre|website=The Paranormal Guide|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n*'''[[Fremantle Prison]]''' in [[Fremantle]], [[Western Australia]] is a former prison built in 1855 primarily by convicts using limestone quarried on-site. Initially used for [[Convicts in Australia|convicts]] transported from Britain, it was transferred to the colonial government in 1886 for use for locally-sentenced prisoners. At least 43 men and 1 woman were executed between 1886 and 1964. There have been many reports of sightings of apparitions and unexplainable occurrences.\n*'''[[Monte Cristo Homestead]]''' in [[Junee, New South Wales]] was the site of seven deaths during the 1800s, and is reported{{By whom|date=October 2012}} to be the most haunted house in Australia. Various ghost groups have reported sightings there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.montecristo.com.au/ |title=Monte Cristo Homestead, Australia's Most Haunted House&nbsp;\u2013 Ghost Tours |publisher=Montecristo.com.au |date= |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref>\n* '''[[North Head Quarantine Station]]''' in [[Manly, New South Wales]] housed victims of a number of diseases including [[smallpox]] and the [[Spanish influenza|Spanish flu]] between 1833 and 1984. It was the site of over 500 deaths. A number of ghost tours are run on the grounds, which includes a large cemetery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quarantinestation.com.au/Ghost-Tours/overview-ghost-paranormal-tours.html|title=(Quarantine Station Ghost Tours)|author=Kelly|publisher=|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref>\n*'''[[Port Arthur, Tasmania|Port Arthur]]''' in [[Tasmania]] operates nightly ghost tours.\n*The '''[[Princess Theatre, Melbourne|Princess Theatre Melbourne]]'''  has reported several ghosts since the building opened in 1886. The theatre's best known \"inhabitant\" is Frederick Baker, whose stage name was [[Frederick Federici]], a talented bass-baritone singer who died during March 1888 whilst singing the role of [[Mephistopheles]] in [[Faust (opera)|''Faust'']]&nbsp;\u2013 and who was seen by the rest of the cast taking his bows with them soon thereafter. For years the theater kept a seat vacant in the [[dress circle]] for Federici (only ceasing the practice on economic grounds), and his appearance in the dress circle during rehearsals for a new show is considered a good omen.\n* [[Campbelltown, New South Wales|Campbelltown]] NSW [[Fisher's ghost]] is a popular Australian ghost story or folk tale dating to the early 19th century. On 17 June 1826 an English-born Australian farmer from Campbelltown named Frederick Fisher (born 28 August 1792 in London) suddenly disappeared. \n* [[Macquarie Fields]] NSW south west of Sydney train station where numerous people have accounted hearing a girl crying. LAte at night, when it\u2019s still, and last trains have pulled out, \u201cfaint crying\u201d can be heard carried on the breeze at Macquarie Fields station.\n\n* [[Northern Beaches]] NSW the Wakehurst Parkway is busy road north of Sydney is not the type of place you would usually associate with the supernatural, but the Wakehurst Parkway has for years been linked with reported sightings of a mysterious female figure, with claims the apparition has even appeared in the back seat of people\u2019s cars before disappearing.\n\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/rewind/txt/s1184926.htm |title=Rewind (ABC TV): The theater ghost |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=29 August 2004 |accessdate=11 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523025416/http://www.abc.net.au/tv/rewind/txt/s1184926.htm |archive-date=23 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Bangladesh==\n{{main|Ghosts in Bengali culture#Alleged haunted places}}\n* '''[[Dhaka]] Airport Road''': The segment of the road between Nikunjo and Biman office is reported by believers to be haunted by a lady at night, supposedly causing accidents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/weekend/2015/oct/29/urban-legends-where-they-roam-restless|title=Urban legends: Where they roam restless|website=dhakatribune.com|access-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Dhaka Golf Heights, Banani, [[Dhaka]]''': Claimed by believers to be haunted by a crying baby, and feelings of being watched are reported.<ref name=\"dhakatribune.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/weekend/2015/oct/29/urban-legends-where-they-roam-restless|title=Urban legends: Where they roam restless|website=www.dhakatribune.com|access-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Under-construction apartment in Old DOHS, Banani, [[Dhaka]]''': Said to have ties to [[Satanism]]. Lanes 4 and 5 are reputed to have been built on top of graves.<ref name=\"daily-sun.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/86647/HAUNTED-TALES:-IN-CONVERSATION-WITH-%E2%80%98DHAKA-PARANORMAL-SOCIETY%E2%80%99|title=HAUNTED TALES: IN CONVERSATION WITH \u2018DHAKA PARANORMAL SOCIETY\u2019|website=daily-sun.com|access-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Purbo Nayatola Rail Crossing, [[Dhaka]]''': Reported by believers to be haunted by a woman frantically looking for her missing infant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/weekend/2015/oct/29/urban-legends-where-they-roam-restless#sthash.KHLIvOWN.dpuf|title=Urban legends: Where they roam restless|website=dhakatribune.com|access-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n* '''[[Shahidullah Hall]] Pond, Dhaka''': The old pond adjoining Shahidullah Hall at [[Dhaka University]] campus is believed to be haunted by people who drowned in the pond.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u09b6\u09b9\u09c0\u09a6\u09c1\u09b2\u09cd\u09b2\u09be\u09b9 \u09b9\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b0\u09b9\u09b8\u09cd\u09af\u09ae\u09af\u09bc \u09aa\u09c1\u0995\u09c1\u09b0|url=http://www.bd-pratidin.com/campus/2015/04/12/74534|access-date=22 October 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Farmhouse in [[Narsingdi District|Narsingdi]]''': This farmhouse, over a couple of hundred years old, contains twin ponds called ''Bhobani'' and ''Rukshar'', and rumours claim of a Hindu cremation ground on site of one of the ponds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/weekend/2014/jan/31/paranormal-activity|title=Paranormal activity|website=dhakatribune.com|access-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Highway Near Mirsharai, [[Chittagong]]''': The highway connecting Dhaka and Chittagong near Mirsharai, Chittagong is claimed by believers to be haunted by a [[vanishing hitchhiker]] at night.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghoststoriesworld.com/haunted-places-in-bangladesh/the-highway-near-mirsharai-chittagong|title=The highway near Mirsharai Chittagong - Haunted Places in Bangladesh|last=Writer|first=Ghost|website=Ghoststoriesworld.com|access-date=3 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117220400/http://www.ghoststoriesworld.com/haunted-places-in-bangladesh/the-highway-near-mirsharai-chittagong|archive-date=17 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* '''Pakri Beach, [[Chittagong]]''': This silver sand beach has a reputation of being haunted. Reported hauntings range from mysterious footsteps and disembodied screams to an apparition of an old sailor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghoststoriesworld.com/haunted-places-in-bangladesh/parki-beach-chittagong-ghost-stories|title=Parki Beach Chittagong Ghost stories, Apparitions of old sailors|last=Writer|first=Ghost|website=Ghoststoriesworld.com|access-date=3 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304220145/http://www.ghoststoriesworld.com/haunted-places-in-bangladesh/parki-beach-chittagong-ghost-stories|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Sunrise at Kuakata beach.JPG|thumbnail|200px|Kuakata Beach, Barisal]]\n* ''' [[Kuakata|Kuakata Beach, Barisal]]''': [[Rakhine people|Rakhaine]] settlers claim this beach to be haunted. Believers also claim of a large, wooden, gold-laden boat in the surrounding forest area that is supposedly cursed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://remit2homeblog.wordpress.com/2013/12/30/kuakata-the-daughter-of-the-ocean-sagar-kanya/|title=Kuakata: The daughter of the ocean (Sagar Kanya)|last=Blog|first=Klinnk|website=Remit2Home|access-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Farmhouse in [[Comilla]]''': A huge farmhouse in Comilla is reported to be haunted by [[Shadow people|black shadows]] assaulting people at night.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/brush-with-the-paranormal-49233|title=Brush with the paranormal|website=The Daily Star|access-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Barbados==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Chase Vault]]''' is a [[burial vault (tomb)|burial vault]] in the cemetery of the [[Christ Church Parish Church]] in [[Oistins]], [[Christ Church Parish, Barbados|Christ Church]], [[Barbados]] best known for a widespread but unverified legend of \"mysterious moving [[coffin]]s\". According to the story, each time the heavily sealed vault was opened during the early 19th century for burial of a family member, all of the lead coffins had changed position. The facts of the story are unverified, and skeptics call the tale \"historically dubious.\" The tale appears to have originated from anecdotes told by Thomas H. Orderson, Rector of Christ Church during the 1800s, and subsequently repeated in [[James Edward Alexander]]'s 1833 ''Transatlantic Sketches.''<ref name=\"Alexander1833\">{{Cite book|author=Sir James Edward Alexander|title=Transatlantic sketches, comprising visits to the most interesting scenes in North and South America, and the West Indies|url=https://archive.org/details/transatlanticske01alexrich|year=1833|publisher=R. Bentley|pages=[https://archive.org/details/transatlanticske01alexrich/page/162 162]\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Percy1833\">{{Cite book|author=Reuben Percy|title=The Mirror of literature, amusement, and instruction|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_7boRAAAAYAAJ|year=1833|publisher=J. Limbird|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_7boRAAAAYAAJ/page/n71 51]\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Clark1999\">{{Cite book|author=Jerome Clark|title=Unexplained!: Strange Sightings, Incredible Occurrences & Puzzling Physical Phenomena|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=szFLs6pQmsQC&pg=PA573|year=1999|publisher=Visible Ink Press|isbn=978-1-57859-070-4|pages=573\u2013}}</ref><ref>Nickell, Joe; 1982. \"Barbados' restless coffins laid to rest\". ''[[Fate Magazine|Fate]]'', Part I, 35.4 (April): 50\u201356; Part II, 35.5 (May): 79\u201386</ref><ref name=\"Nickell2001\">{{Cite book|author=Joe Nickell|title=Real-Life X-Files: Investigating the Paranormal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Bm-EjjG3AwC|accessdate=14 May 2012|date=24 October 2001|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=978-0-8131-2210-6}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated125\">{{Cite book\n| last = Dils\n| first = Tracy\n| title = \"Real-Life Scary Places\":Terrifying True Tales\n| publisher = Willowisp Press\n| year = 1985\n| location = [[St. Petersburg, Florida]]\n| page = [https://archive.org/details/reallifescarypla0000dils/page/125 125]\n| isbn = 0-87406-794-4\n| url = https://archive.org/details/reallifescarypla0000dils/page/125\n}}</ref><ref name=\"ghost-story1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghost-story.co.uk/stories/thechasevault.html |title=Ghost Story.uk |publisher=Ghost-story.co.uk |date= |accessdate=18 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Brazil==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n* The '''[[wmbr:|Grande Hotel Trilogia]]''' in [[Cambuquira]], [[Minas Gerais]] is allegedly haunted and appeared on episode 16 of the 1st season of [[Ghost Hunters International]].\n* The '''[[Joelma Building]][[br]]{{dn|date=March 2020}}''' (now the Pra\u00e7a da Bandeira Building) in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] is allegedly haunted by victims of the fire that started on 1 February 1974, after an air conditioning unit on the twelfth floor overheated; centered on the \"Mystery of the Thirteen Souls\", individuals who died within an elevator as they were trying to escape the fire, and are haunting the building.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Carolina Iskandarian Do G1, em S\u00e3o Paulo |url=http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/SaoPaulo/0,,MUL330153-5605,00.html |title=G1 Edi\u00e7\u00e3o S\u00e3o Paulo&nbsp;\u2013 NOT\u00cdCIAS&nbsp;\u2013 Lugares 'mal-assombrados' viram lenda em SP |publisher=G1.globo.com |date= |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Cambodia==\n*'''[[Kampong Chhnang Province|Kampong Chhnang]]''': The famous \"ghost house\" in Cambodia.<ref name=\"Indochina\"/>\n\n==Canada==\n{{Main|List of reportedly haunted locations in Canada}}\nSeveral sites in Canada are reputedly haunted, including '''[[Citadel Hill (Fort George)]]''' in Halifax, '''[[The Algonquin Resort St. Andrews By-The-Sea]]''' in New Brunswick, '''[[Banff Springs Hotel]]''' in Alberta, '''[[Darke Hall]]''' at '''[[University of Regina]]''' in Saskatchewan, '''[[Fairmont Royal York]]''' in Toronto, '''[[Fort Garry Hotel]]''' in Winnipeg, '''[[Hotel Macdonald]]''' in Edmonton, '''[[Craigdarroch Castle]]''' in Victoria, '''[[Plains of Abraham]]''' in Quebec City and '''[[Bytown Museum]]''' in Ottawa.\n\n==China==\n{{main|List of reportedly haunted locations in China}}\n[[File:Front elevation, 81 Chaonei, Beijing.jpg|thumb|Western (front) elevation of [[Chaonei No. 81]] during 2014]]\nSeveral sites in China are reportedly haunted, including '''[[Chaonei No. 81]]''', an abandoned mansion in Beijing's [[Chaoyangmen]] neighborhood, and the '''[[Wukang Mansion]]''', formerly known as the ''Normandie Apartment'', in [[Shanghai]] (named after the [[World War I]] battleship Normandie).\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Colombia==\n{{Main|List of reportedly haunted locations in Colombia}}\n\n==Czech Republic==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Zv\u00edkov Castle]]''': Until 1597 there are stories about a Zv\u00edkovsk\u00fd Rar\u00e1\u0161ek (Rarach is a supernatural being common in Slavic folklore, similar to an imp or trickster) which haunts people in the ancient tower, Markomanka. This tower has stones engraved with unknown symbols, and was built during the [[Marcomanni]] rule over [[Bohemia]], in the 1st century BC and 2nd century AD. It was integrated into Zv\u00edkov castle hundreds of years later. Strange events occur here frequently, including weird photos, technical problems, unpredictable behaviour of animals, spontaneous extinguishing of fires, electromagnetic anomalies, and the presence of ghosts. In Czech media it's a popular subject of investigation. Other areas of the castle are also haunted; it is said to be dangerous to sleep in the main tower, as anyone who does supposedly dies within a year. Another monster common in Czech culture, [[fire hound]]s are also part of the myths surrounding the castle. It is said that these spectral dogs (in some accounts they are depicted with burning eyes) are guarding a hidden tunnel underneath Zv\u00edkov.<ref>{{cite web |author=Galileo Corporation s.r.o. |url=http://www.hrad-zvikov.eu/points-of-interest/hliza-tower/ |title=Ofici\u00e1ln\u00ed str\u00e1nky hradu Zv\u00edkov - Hl\u00edza tower |publisher=Hrad-zvikov.eu |accessdate=26 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325192456/http://www.hrad-zvikov.eu/points-of-interest/hliza-tower/ |archivedate=25 March 2014  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.castlesandmanorhouses.com/summary.php?Category=Visit&Type=%28All+Properties%29&Country=%28All+Countries%29&Parameter=ByCountry |title=List of (All Properties) to Visit in (All Countries) |publisher=Castlesandmanorhouses.com |date= |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blesk.cz/clanek/celebrity/10200/zvikovsky-rarasek-trapi-filmare.html |title=Zv\u00edkovsk\u00fd rar\u00e1\u0161ek tr\u00e1p\u00ed filma\u0159e |publisher=Blesk.cz |date= |accessdate=26 March 2014 |language=Czech}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tajemnamista.cz/magazin/64-zvikovska-vez-markomanka-dodnes-vyhrozuje-smrti |title=Zv\u00edkovsk\u00e1 v\u011b\u017e Markomanka: Dodnes vyhro\u017euje smrt\u00ed! |publisher=Tajemn\u00e1 m\u00edsta |accessdate=26 March 2014 |language=Czech |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327234202/http://www.tajemnamista.cz/magazin/64-zvikovska-vez-markomanka-dodnes-vyhrozuje-smrti |archivedate=27 March 2014  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://paranormal.komis-site.eu/zvikov-tajemna-vez-markomanka/ |title=Zv\u00edkov \u2013 Tajemn\u00e1 v\u011b\u017e Markomanka \u00ab Paranormal |publisher=Paranormal.komis-site.eu |date=24 January 2013 |accessdate=26 March 2014 |language=Czech}}</ref>\n\n==Denmark==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Dragsholm Castle]]''' in [[Zealand]] is said to be haunted by the ghost of [[James Hepburn, 4th Earl of Bothwell]], imprisoned there for about five years until his death during 1578.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guide-to-castles-of-europe.com/dragsholm-castle.html |title=Guide to castles of Europe |accessdate=31 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Egypt==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:WhiteDesertEgypt@FarafraOasis2007jan6-93 byDanielCsorfoly.JPG|thumb|Farafra Desert]]\n*'''[[Baron Empain Palace]]''': Tourists have reportedly heard voices throughout the palace late at night. Guards and police have reported seeing ghostly apparitions of people who were once residents of the palace, wandering the outside lawn at midnight.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\">{{cite book\n |page=359\n |title=Encyclopedia of Haunted Places: Ghostly Locales from Around the World\n |author=Jeff Belanger\n |publisher= New Page Books\n |year=2005\n |ISBN=1564147991}}</ref>\n*'''[[Farafra, Egypt|Farafra Desert]]''': The ghost of [[Akhenaten]] is said to wander the Farafra Desert (also known as the White Desert) of Egypt, reported by dozens of tourists and [[nomads]]. Legend says this is because Akhenaten abolished the Egyptian gods when he became Pharaoh, angering the religious followers and priests of Egypt. Upon his death, the priests are believed to have cursed him to wander the deserts forever as punishment.<ref>{{cite book\n |page=1\n |title=The Ghost of Akhenaten\n |author=Moyra Caldecott\n |publisher=Mushroom Publishing\n |year=2003\n |ISBN=1-84319-024-9}}</ref>\n*'''[[Pyramids of Giza]]''': A man in early 20th-century clothing has been seen by visitors, rumored to be the ghost of [[Howard Carter]]. Various employees and tourists have reported seeing an [[orb (optics)|orb]] apparition of an Egyptian Pharaoh, floating away from the pyramids towards the Valley of the Kings.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n*'''[[Valley of the Kings]]''': Eyewitnesses have reported seeing the vision of an Egyptian Pharaoh in the Valley of the Kings, wearing his golden collar, headdress, and riding a fiery [[chariot]] with black phantom horses.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n\n==Finland==\n[[File:Alexander Theatre Helsinki 2011-09-03 1.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Alexander Theatre]]]]\n*'''[[Alexander Theatre]]''' in [[Helsinki]] is reportedly haunted by the ghost of an officer. The ghost moved to Helsinki as the tiles to build Alexander Theatre were relocated from [[\u00c5land]]. Some have suggested that the officer died in the [[Crimea War]] and has been there ever since.<ref name=Fin>[http://www.nopsatravels.com/kummitusten-helsinki/#kohde2 Kummitusten Helsinki ] Retrieved 22 December 2015</ref>\n*'''[[Finnish National Theatre]]''' in Helsinki is reportedly haunted by at least three ghosts - an unknown ''Grey Lady'' and the ghosts of actors [[Aarne Lepp\u00e4nen]] and [[Urho Somersalmi]].<ref name=Fin/>\n*'''Haihara Manor''' in [[Tampere]] is haunted by ''The Blue Maid'', former maid of the manor.<ref>[http://www.tampere.fi/english/culturalaffairs/locations/haihara/history.html City of Tampere - History] Retrieved 22 December 2015</ref>\n*'''Mustio Manor''' in the village of Mustio reportedly is a location with several ghosts.<ref>[http://www.mustionlinna.fi/en/museum-a-park/museum-a-park/museum-guided-tour Museum & Guided Tour of Mustion Linna Website ] Retrieved 22 December 2015</ref>\n*'''[[Nummela Sanatorium]]''', an abandoned hospital in the village of [[R\u00f6ykk\u00e4]] is told about rumors of paranormal phenomena, like the windows of the building show mysterious lights, and on the edge of the roof there is a woman who suicides by jumping down. There is also a rumor that the hospital might be haunted by the spirit of a girl who died there at a young age.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iltalehti.fi/matkajutut/a/2016102122496652|title=Hui, kummituksia! Suomalaiskohteet, joihin liittyy hurjia aavetarinoita|work=Iltalehti|author=Marianne Zitting|date=24 October 2016|accessdate=27 March 2019|language=fi}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nurmijarvenuutiset.fi/artikkeli/4532-hurjia-kummitusjuttuja|title=Hurjia kummitusjuttuja|work=Nurmij\u00e4rven uutiset|author=|date=12 November 2010|accessdate=27 March 2019|language=fi}}</ref>\n*'''Svenska Klubben''' (The Swedish Club) house in [[Kruununhaka]], Helsinki, is haunted by the ''Grey Madame''. She is rumoured to be the former lady of the house who had an affair with her chauffeur. She is known to swing the chandeliers, play piano and walk around the house.<ref>[http://www.mtv.fi/lifestyle/koti/artikkeli/urho-vaeltaa-teatterissa-kirves-kadessaan-lahde-kierrokselle-helsingin-kuuluisiin-kummitustaloihin/5219666 MTV Lifestyle] Retrieved 22 December 2015</ref>\n*'''[[Turku City Library]]''' employees have reportedly had paranormal experiences in the basement of the library. The ghost is assumed to be a former librarian.{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n*'''[[Villa Kleineh]]''', a historical villa in Helsinki currently used by the Dutch embassy, reportedly hosts a ghost called ''The White Lady''.<ref name=\"HT 2013\">{{cite web | author=HT | title=Villa Kleineh opens on Restaurant Day to serve cuisine hollandaise | website=News from Finland \"Helsinki Times\" | date=14 November 2013 | url=http://www.helsinkitimes.fi/eat-and-drink/8389-villa-kleineh-opens-on-restaurant-day-to-serve-cuisine-hollandaise.html | access-date=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==France==\n{{Main|List of reportedly haunted locations in France}}\n[[File:Logis chateau chateaubriant 01.jpg|thumb|[[Ch\u00e2teau de Ch\u00e2teaubriant]]]]\n\nSeveral sites in France are reputedly haunted, including the '''[[Ch\u00e2teau de Brissac]]''', the '''[[Ch\u00e2teau de Tr\u00e9cesson]]''' in Brittany, the '''[[Catacombs of Paris|Catacombs]] ''' and '''[[P\u00e8re Lachaise Cemetery|Cemetery of P\u00e8re Lachaise]]''' in Paris, '''[[Mont Saint-Michel]]''', and the '''[[Ch\u00e2teau de Ch\u00e2teaubriant]]''' in western [[France]].\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Germany==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''Berlin''': The [[Reichstag building]] has been reported to be haunted by numerous ghosts of famous German politicians.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n*'''[[Heidelberg]]''': The ''Hexenturm'' ([[Witches Tower]]) and the [[Nazi]] Amphitheatre are both said to be haunted by various ghosts.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n*'''[[Frankenstein Castle]]''': Frankenstein Castle ({{lang-de|Burg Frankenstein}}) is a real [[hilltop castle]] in the [[Odenwald]], overlooking the city of [[Darmstadt]], and allegedly an inspiration for [[Mary Shelley]] when she wrote her monster novel ''[[Frankenstein]]''. The [[SyFy]] TV show ''[[Ghost Hunters International]]'' aired an entire episode about the castle and testified it had \"... significant paranormal activity\".<ref>[http://www.syfy.com/ghosthuntersinternational/episodes/season/s01/episode/e107/frankenstein_s_castle SyFy - Ghost Hunters International Website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140420024220/http://www.syfy.com/ghosthuntersinternational/episodes/season/s01/episode/e107/frankenstein_s_castle |date=20 April 2014 }} Retrieved 19 April 2014</ref>\n*'''Lichtenegg Castle''': The ghost of a lady in a white dress is said to be seen standing in front of the entrance to the ruins at midnight. She will, usually, sit down on a flat rock covered with moss.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n[[File:Nordkirchen-Hauptgebaeude-von-Venusinsel-DSC 5912.jpg|thumb|Northern front of Schloss Nordkirchen.]]\n*'''[[Schloss Nordkirchen]]''': The castle was built between 1703 and 1734. According to the legend, at full moon and on certain foggy nights, a few people have reported seeing a luxurious [[carriage]] with stallions running through the grounds.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n*'''[[Wolfsegg, Bavaria]]''', '''Wolfsegg Castle''': This 14th-century castle was supposed to be a sanctuary for travellers. The folklore of this haunting originated from the 1500s, when Ulrich von Laaber hired two young farmers to kill his wife, Klara von Helfenstein, after discovering she was having an affair.  Soon thereafter, Ulrich and his sons also died suddenly. There have been reports of strange noises coming out of a cave area near the castle. Several expeditions into the cave, uncovering numerous animal skeletons, leading locals to decide the noises had come from hunters who were hiding their prey. While the cave noises might have been solved, this has not been the case of the haunting of the \"White Woman\" who is still restlessly making her rounds of the castle.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n*'''[[W\u00fcrzburg]]''': There is supposedly the ghost of a dead [[nun]] walking through the halls of Praemonstratenser Abbey. The ghost is said to be that of Maria Renata Von Mossau, accused of mixing herbs into everyone's food in order to bewitch them. The nun was taken to be executed only three days after her sentencing in court. She was first decapitated, and then burned and her ashes scattered. To this day, there are reports of her walking down the hallways and holding a bouquet of roses while picking off the petals, leaving a trail across the grounds.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n\n==India==\n{{main|List of reportedly haunted locations in India}}\n[[File:South-Park-Street-Cemetery-1.jpg|thumb|South Park Street Cemetery.]]\nSeveral sites in India are reported to be haunted, including [[South Park Street Cemetery]] in West Bengal on [[Park Street, Kolkata]], and [[Morgan House, Kalimpong|Morgan House]], [[Bhangarh_Fort|Bhangar Fort]], [[Rajasthan]], a colonial-era mansion in [[Kalimpong]] that is considered to be one of the most haunted locations in [[India]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/5-haunted-hotels-of-india-hotel-taj-mahal-palace-mumbai-hotel-brij-raj-bhavan-kota-morgan-house-tourist-lodge-kalimpong/1/532827.html|title=Dare to stay at these haunted hotels of India?|access-date=26 June 2017}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Indonesia==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:Basement of Lawang Sewu 2011.JPG|thumb|The basement of the Building B of Lawang Sewu, a former prison. It is one of the rooms where ghost sightings have been reported.]]\n*'''[[Dr. Cipto Mangunkusumo Hospital]]''': The government run hospital located at [[Salemba]], [[Jakarta]]. It is rumored to be haunted by a [[vengeful spirit]] of a fenale nurse named ''Suster Ngesot'' (Limping Nurse).<ref>{{cite web|language=thai|url=https://en.brilio.net/scary/tragic-death-of-suster-ngesot-haunt-hospitals-in-indonesia-160808s.html|title=Tragic death of Suster Ngesot leaves her haunting old hospitals|date=11 August 2016|accessdate=9 March 2020|work=https://en.brilio.net|first=Victoria|last=Tunggono}}</ref>\n*'''[[Jakarta History Museum]]''': This historical building once served as the administrative headquarters of the [[Dutch East Indies]]. The front square of the building was often used as a place of executions for criminals. During nighttime there are reports of sighting of a headless ghost, Dutch colonial lady, and mysterious sounds coming from the underground prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hipwee.com/travel/kisah-misteri-yang-tersembunyi-di-museum-fatahillah-dijamin-kamu-bakal-merinding-dibuatnya/|title=Kisah Misteri yang Tersembunyi di Museum Fatahillah. Dijamin Kamu Bakal Merinding Dibuatnya!|first=Andina|last=Rahayu|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnnindonesia.com/gaya-hidup/20141213145342-269-17920/riwayat-penjara-terpendam-di-kota-tua-jakarta/|title=Riwayat Penjara Terpendam di Kota Tua Jakarta|publisher=}}</ref>\n*'''[[Jeruk Purut Cemetery]]''': A cemetery in [[Jakarta]] said to be haunted by the ghost of a decapitated pastor, which carries its head around with it, and is followed by a large black dog. The story was used as the inspiration for the 2006 movie, ''[[Hantu Jeruk Purut]]''.<ref>{{cite news\n | last1 = \n | first1 = \n | year = \n | date=27 March 2010\n | title = Ghost tales underline Jakartan love for absurdities\n | work = The Jakarta Post\n | location = Jakarta\n | url = http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2010/03/27/ghost-tales-underline-jakartan-love-absurdities.html\n | accessdate=28 October 2011\n | ref = {{harvid|The Jakarta Post 2010, Ghost tales underline}}\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n |last1=Sembiring \n |first1=Dalih \n |last2=Siregar \n |first2=Lisa \n |date=14 August 2009 \n |title=Spirits In the Night: A Guide to Jakarta's Ghosts \n |work=The Jakarta Globe \n |location=Jakarta \n |url=http://jakartaglobe.id/archive/spirits-in-the-night-a-guide-to-jakartas-ghosts\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524155032/http://jakartaglobe.id/archive/spirits-in-the-night-a-guide-to-jakartas-ghosts\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=24 May 2018\n |accessdate=28 October 2011 \n |ref={{harvid|Sembiring and Siregar 2009, Spirits in the night}} \n}}</ref>\n*'''Kampung Gajah''': Opened in 2010, Kampung Gajah was once an amusement park in Lembang, West Bandung Regency until the company that once ran the amusement park filed bankruptcy. The park was permanently closed in 2018. After the closure of the park, many ghost hunters started to use the former site of the amusement park for ghost hunting. One of local YouTuber from West Bandung once visited the former site and reported some abnormal incidents like the camera suddenly goes off twice and drone problems.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liputan6.com/lifestyle/read/4111815/taman-rekreasi-kampung-gajah-berubah-jadi-wisata-horor|title=Taman Rekreasi Kampung Gajah Berubah Jadi Wisata Horor|publisher=}}</ref>\n*'''[[Lawang Sewu]]''': Literally meaning a \"thousand doors\" in Javanese, it is a former Dutch colonial building located in Semarang, in central Java. Many ghost sightings have been reported here, including a ghost of a Dutch lady as well as headless ghouls. During one of the ghost hunting television programs, a ghost was purportedly caught on camera.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bym4TXmuy-o |title=Dunia Lain Lawang Sewu}}</ref>\n*'''[[Parangtritis]]''': This popular tourist beach located in southern coast of [[Special Region of Yogyakarta|Yogyakarta]] contains legend regarding the foundation of the [[Mataram Sultanate]]. It was said that here [[Sutawijaya|Panembahan Senopati]], the founder of Mataram Sultanate made a spiritual pact with [[Nyai Roro Kidul]], the ruler of Java's southern sea for the well-being of Mataram. Every year, the ''Labuhan'' ceremony is held there and in neighboring Parangkusumo beach to commemorate the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wisatalicious.com/pantai-parangtritis-yogyakarta-keindahan-yang-berbalut-misteri/|title=Pantai Parangtritis Yogyakarta, Keindahan Yang Berbalut Misteri - Wisatalicious|website=wisatalicious.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.okezone.com/read/2014/03/16/510/956019/cerita-ratu-kidul-kesemsem-panembahan-senopati|title=Cerita Ratu Kidul|publisher=}}</ref>\n*'''[[Pelabuhan Ratu]]''': Legend says that [[Nyai Roro Kidul]] (Nyai is a [[Javanese language|Javanese]] and [[Sundanese language|Sundanese]] honorific for Madame), the Queen of the South Sea and daughter of King Prabu Siliwangi, is supposed to have committed suicide by jumping off the cliff into the sea. Rumors say that if someone wears green when swimming (the Queen's favourite color), he or she will be pulled by her ghost into the sea. Room 308 at the [[Samudra Beach Hotel]] is set aside for the Queen's ghost.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mikalina.com/Texts/pelabuhanratu_indonesia.htm |title=Pelabuhanratu (Indonesia) \u2013 A resort with a ghost |accessdate=20 December 2006 |last=Janssen |first=Peter |publisher=MysticAsia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061124200111/http://www.mikalina.com/Texts/pelabuhanratu_indonesia.htm |archivedate=24 November 2006  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://indahnesia.com/indonesia/JAWSAM/samudra_beach.php |title=Room No. 308 still retains its mystery |accessdate=20 December 2006 |last=Khouw |first=Ida Indawati |publisher=The Jakarta Post}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n*'''Saidah Tower''': An abandoned 30-storey building located in [[East Jakarta]] was once owned by [[Arab Indonesian]] wealthy family of same name. The building was abandoned in 2007 because of the building structure problems.<ref name=Merdeka1>[http://www.merdeka.com/peristiwa/bagaimana-nasib-menara-saidah-ke-depan.html Situs Merdeka.com: Bagaimana nasib Menara Saidah ke depan?]. Dipublikasikan 26 Mei 2012. Diakses 2 Juni 2013</ref> Many locals believed the former building was haunted since 2009.<ref>https://www.hipwee.com/travel/kisah-misteri-menara-saidah-bangunan-tinggi-yang-katanya-jadi-istananya-para-arwah/</ref>\n\n==Ireland==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:IMG KinnittyCastle0973.jpg|thumb|Kinnitty Castle]]\n[[File:Malahide Castle - magic door.JPG|thumb|Malahide Castle]]\n[[File:The Stewards House Killakee.jpg|thumb|Stewards House, Montpelier Hill]]\n*'''[[Charles Fort (Ireland)|Charles Fort]]''': Haunted by a 17th-century bride known as \"The White Lady of Kinsale\".<ref>{{cite web|author=JackMc |url=http://www.europeanghostsandhauntings.com/2011/12/white-lady-of-kinsale-charles-fort-near.html |title=White Lady of Kinsale - Charles Fort near Kinsale, Ireland |publisher=European Ghosts and Hauntings |date=3 December 2011 |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n*'''[[Charleville Castle]]''': This castle is haunted by the third [[Earl of Charleville]]'s younger daughter, Harriet. She lost her life after falling from the main staircase of this building at the age of eight, in April 1861.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghost-story.co.uk/index.php/most-haunted/191-charleville-castle-tullamore-ireland |title=Charleville Castle, Tullamore, Ireland |publisher=Ghost-story.co.uk |date= |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref> It was featured on ''[[Scariest Places on Earth]]'', ''[[Most Haunted]]'', and ''Ghost Hunters International''.\n*'''Drumbeg Manor''' in Inver, Donegal: Considered to be one of the most haunted places in all Europe. Apparitions and strange events are reported to have taken place within the manor, and on its grounds. Stories say that a screaming woman can be heard, as well as the appearance of a man in a white suit walking the halls.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.paranormaldatabase.com/ireland/cork.php?pageNum_paradata=2&totalRows_paradata=116 | title=Ghosts, Hauntings and Legends |accessdate=14 March 2012}}</ref>\n*'''[[Ducketts Grove]]''': The mansion was owned by the Duckett family for 300 years, and is said to be haunted by a [[Banshee|Banshee Ghost]]. On 17 March 2011, the [[SyFy]] show ''Destination Truth'' featured a four-hour live investigation for the season finale to find out the mystery of the ruins.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.syfy.com/destinationtruth/episodes/season/4.5/episode/409/destination_truth_live_event| title=Destination Truth: Duckett's Grove|accessdate=22 May 2012}}</ref>\n*'''[[Kilmainham Gaol]]''': This former prison has paranormal activities of lights which often turn themselves on and off in the prison's chapel, unseen forces pushing people over, apparitional footsteps, the feeling of being watched by spirits, as well as unexplained bangs and disembodied voices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hauntedrooms.co.uk/kilmainham-gaol |title=Kilmainham Gaol - Dublin, Ireland |publisher=HauntedRooms.co.uk |date= |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n*'''[[Kinnitty Castle]]''': This Gothic castle sits on a plot that once housed [[Druid]]s and [[Bards]]. It has witnessed a long and turbulent history, and is reportedly the home of many ghosts, the most popular of which is the Phantom Monk of [[Kinnitty]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hauntedrooms.co.uk/kinnitty-castle-hotel-co-offaly-ireland| title=Ghosts of Kinnitty Castle Hotel |accessdate=12 July 2012}}</ref> It was featured on ''Most Haunted''.\n*'''[[Malahide Castle]]''': This castle is haunted by Lord Galtrim, Sir Walter Hussey, the son of the Baron of Galtrim. Killed in battle on his wedding day during the 15th century, his apparition roams the castle at night, groaning in pain, while pointing at the spear wound in his side. There is also Lady Matilda \"Maud\" Plunkett. Her spirit appears to workers and guests as she did on the day of her marriage to the Lord Chief Justice. Maud would chase his spirit through the corridors. The third spirit is Puck, a jester who fell in love with [[Gear\u00f3id M\u00f3r FitzGerald, 8th Earl of Kildare|Gerard FitzGerald]]'s daughter, Lady Eleanor, who was detained at the castle by Henry VIII for inciting rebellions. One snowy night in December, Puck was found stabbed through the heart, still wearing his jester suit and cap. Before his death, he swore that he would haunt here until a master with a bride from the people ruled this castle. However, he promised not to harm any male Talbot who slept here. Numerous visitors have reported seeing the jester's face on some photos taken here. The White Lady is the fourth apparition here. The White Lady is a painting of a very beautiful, but unknown, lady which hangs on the castle's Great Wall. It is said that she would leave her painting at times and wander through the grounds at night. The fifth and final spirit is [[Miles Corbet]]. He was given this castle and the surrounding property by Oliver Cromwell. During the Restoration, Miles was made to pay for his crimes, and was hanged. It is reported that his apparition appears as a whole soldier in armour which then suddenly fall into pieces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.strangilla.com/the-haunted-castles-in-existence/|title=Haunted Weekends, Haunted Hotels & Haunted Castles|work=Haunted Rooms|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n*'''[[Montpelier Hill]]''': The Stewards House, or Killakee House, was built around 1765 by the Conolly family as a hunting lodge. The house has a reputation for being haunted. Stories tell of a particularly large ghostly [[black cat]]. The best documented account occurred between 1968 and 1970 when the ''[[Evening Herald]]'' and ''[[Evening Press]]'' newspapers carried a number of reports regarding a Mrs. Margaret O'Brien and her husband Nicholas, a retired [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na|Garda]] [[superintendent (police)|superintendent]], who were converting the house into an arts centre. During the conversion, tradesmen employed on the work site began complaining of ghosts. One night, a friend of the O'Briens, artist Tom McAssey, and two workmen were confronted by a spectral figure and a black cat with glowing red eyes. McAssey painted a portrait of the cat which hung in the house for several years afterwards. Although locals were skeptical of the reports, further apparitions were reported, most notably that of an Indian gentleman, and of two nuns called Blessed Margaret and Holy Mary who had taken part in black masses on Montpelier Hill. There were also reports of incorporeal ringing bells and [[poltergeist]] activity. In 1970, an [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]] television crew recorded a documentary about the house. In the documentary, a [[clairvoyant]] called Sheila St. Clair communicated with the spirits of the house through [[automatic writing]]. In 1971, a plumber working in the house discovered a grave with a skeleton of a small figure, most likely that of a child or, perhaps, the body of the dwarf alleged to have been sacrificed by the members of the Hell Fire Club. The house operated as a restaurant in the 1990s before closing in 2001; it is now a private residence.<ref>{{cite book |last=O'Farrell |first=Padraic |title=Irish Ghost Stories |year=2004 |publisher=Gill & Macmillan |location=Dublin |isbn=978-0-7171-3633-9 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Walsh |first=Dave |title=Haunted Dublin |year=2008 |publisher=Nonsuch Publishing |location=Dublin |isbn=978-1-84588-932-6 }}</ref><ref name=\"Walsh_21\">Walsh, p. 21.</ref>\n*'''[[Leap Castle]]''': Many people were imprisoned and executed in this castle, and it is supposedly haunted by several spirits.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.castles.org/castles/Europe/Western_Europe/Ireland/Leap/Leap.htm |title=The Reference of the Castle |accessdate=14 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505062516/http://www.castles.org/castles/Europe/Western_Europe/Ireland/Leap/Leap.htm |archivedate=5 May 2012  }}</ref> It was featured on ''Scariest Places on Earth'' and ''Most Haunted''.\n*'''Renyle House Hotel''' in [[Galway]]: Haunted by former anonymous remaining guests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hauntedrooms.co.uk/renyle-house-hotel|title=Haunted Weekends, Haunted Hotels & Haunted Castles|work=Haunted Rooms|accessdate=4 October 2014}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*'''[[Ross Castle]]''': Guests often wake at night hearing disembodied voices and doors banging and shutting on their own. An apparitional spirit who roams here is Richard Nugent's daughter, Sabina. Her lover, Orwin drowned himself. A second apparitional spirit who roams here is Orwin's father, Myles \"The Slasher\" O'Reilly. This Irish soldier spent his last night here before dying in a battle in 1644.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ross-castle.com/en/history/ghosts |title=Ross Castle B&B - Ghosts |publisher=Ross-castle.com |date= |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n*'''[[St. Michan's Church]]''': This church is haunted by disembodied whispering voices from mummies entombed in the [[burial vault (tomb)|vault]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Strickler |first=Lon |url=http://www.phantomsandmonsters.com/2010/01/haunted-earth-mummies-of-st-michans.html |title=Pulse of the Paranormal |publisher=Phantoms and Monsters |date=26 January 2010 |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n*'''[[Shelbourne Hotel]]''': This hotel is believed to be haunted by a seven-year-old girl from the 18th century, named Mary Masters, who had lived in the row of houses which once stood where the hotel is now. She died due to cholera during 1791. Her apparition roams the halls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hauntedrooms.co.uk/shelbourne-hotel-dublin-ireland |title=Shelbourne Hotel, Dublin, Ireland |publisher=HauntedRooms.co.uk |date= |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n*'''[[Wicklow Gaol]]''': a prison for over 200 years, it is claimed to be haunted by many former prisoners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ghostcatcherie.wordpress.com/2009/09/19/wicklow-gaol-the-gates-of-hell-september-2009-2/|title=Wicklow Gaol, \u2018The Gates of Hell\u2019, September 2009|date=19 September 2009|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Italy==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Colosseum]]''': Known also as the '''Flavian Amphitheatre''', was reported to be haunted according to some witnesses and researchers' testimonies. Visitors have described observing ghostly figures wandering the staircases. There have been reports of hearing the cheers and screams from a crowd while no sign of people in the particular section. The vaults were, reportedly, active by the spirits of [[gladiator]]s waiting to fight, [[actor]]s waiting to perform, and prisoners becoming prepared for execution. Several accounts of cold touches or pushes have been felt by both tourists and employees. Sounds of animals have also been heard within the vaults.<ref>{{cite web|last=J.Lynch |first=Gordon |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cFRsQu4LgHgC&pg=PA213&dq=Colosseum+haunted&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjCm_mWjI_OAhUB6iYKHcKDD6oQ6AEIIjAB#v=onepage&q=Colosseum%20haunted&f=false |title=Famous Ghosts and Haunted Places|publisher=Rosen Publishing Group Inc. |date=2012 |accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref>\n* The castle of '''Montebello''', in [[Montebello di Torriana]] (in the [[province of Rimini]]), is famous for the medieval legend that tells that an [[Albinism|albino]] (in the [[Middle Ages]], albino people were thought to be incarnations of [[Satan]]) girl nicknamed \"Azzurrina\" ([[Italian language|Italian]] feminine [[diminutive]] for \"azzurro\", \"light [[blue]]\", the colour of her eyes), born about in 1370 and mysteriously vanished on 21 June 1375 ([[solstice]] day), while her father, ''Signore'' (\"Lord\") of Montebello, was fighting in a battle. According to the legend, Azzurrina's ghost appears in the castle every five years from that day, on solstice day. The legend provided fame for the town of Montebello di Torriana and much tourism to the castle, especially on 21 June.\n*'''[[Poveglia]]''': This island, near Venice, was once a sanctuary to refugees during the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] [[Ottoman wars in Europe|conflicts]], and a hospice for sick patients throughout the centuries. It was detailed, from witnesses, haunted by many victims of the [[Bubonic plague|plague]].  In 1922, the island became home to a mental hospital, where a doctor, reportedly, experimented on patients with crude [[lobotomy|lobotomies]]. He later threw himself from the hospital tower after claiming he had been driven mad by the spirits of the island. The island has been featured on the paranormal shows ''[[Ghost Adventures]]'' and ''[[Scariest Places on Earth]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/italy/10767781/Worlds-most-haunted-island-up-for-auction.html|title = 'World's most haunted island' up for auction|last = Kington|first = Tom|date = 15 April 2014|work = |accessdate = 16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/24658/strange-geographies-happy-haunted-island-poveglia|title=Strange Geographies: The Happy, Haunted Island of Poveglia|work=Mental Floss}}</ref>\n*'''[[Teatro Massimo]]''' in [[Palermo]].{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n\n==Japan==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:Suicide Forest.jpg|thumb|Aokigahara in Yamanashi Prefecture]]\n*'''[[Hoichi the Earless|Amiidaji]]''' (Temple of [[Amitabha|Amida]]): In the [[Shimonoseki Strait]], it is the location of a legendary haunting. It is said that the blind [[Biwa h\u014dshi]] Hoichi, a resident of the temple, was visited every night by the ghost of a dead samurai, and made to play the biwa in the cemetery. When the priest of the temple learned this, he had the [[heart sutra]] painted on every part of Hoichi's body apart from his ears. When the samurai returned to take Hoichi to the cemetery, he could only see Hoichi's ears, so he took them instead, leaving Hoichi earless, resulting his nickname, \"Mimi-Nashi Hoichi\" ([[H\u014dichi the Earless]]). This legend was famously retold by [[Lafcadio Hearn]] in his book ''[[Kwaidan: Stories and Studies of Strange Things]]'', which was adapted as part of [[Masaki Kobayashi]]'s movie ''[[Kwaidan]]''.<ref>{{cite book |author=Professor Solomon |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=coxRQh_ONfIC&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=Hoichi+Dan-no-ura |title=Japan in a Nutshell}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/shi/kwaidan/kwai03.htm |title=The Story Of Mimi-Nashi-Hoichi |publisher=Sacred-texts.com |date= |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref>\n*'''[[Aokigahara]]''': The forest at the bottom of [[Mt. Fuji]] is a popular location for [[suicide]]. This results in a widespread belief that it is haunted. It was featured by an episode of ''Destination Truth'' on the SyFy Channel.<ref name=\"Iwasaka 1994\">Iwasaka, Michiko and [[Toelken, Barre]]. ''Ghosts and the Japanese: Cultural Experiences in Japanese Death Legends'', Utah State University Press, 1994. {{ISBN|0-87421-179-4}}.</ref>\n* '''Okiku's Well''': The well at [[Himeji Castle]] is often said to be haunted by the ghost of [[Banch\u014d Sarayashiki|Okiku]]. She is supposed to rise from the well at night and count to nine before shrieking and returning to the well.<ref name=\"Iwasaka 1994\"/>\n\n==Jordan==\n*'''[[Petra]]''': The residence of [[djinn]]s, supernatural beings in [[Islam]] according to the [[Bedouin]]'s saying.<ref>{{IMDb title|1603573|\"Destination Truth\" Ghost of Petra/The Lizard Man (TV Episode 2010)}}</ref>\n\n==Malaysia==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:Newlands-the-home-of-Agnes-Newton-Keith-Sabah-Borneo.JPG|thumb|right|[[Agnes Keith House]] in [[Sandakan]], [[Sabah]], Malaysia. Pictured in 2007.]]\n[[File:Kinarut Sabah TheKinarutMansion-06.jpg|thumb|right|[[Kinarut Mansion]] ruins as pictured in 2012.]]\n[[File:Highland Towers 2008.JPG|thumb|Remains of the Highland Towers during 2008.]]\n*'''[[Agnes Keith House]]''': A house built in the site of a former house for British colonial officials. Reportedly haunted with a female apparition based on the experience by the house former owners including a known American author named [[Agnes Newton Keith]]. The house has now turned into a museum in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hmetro.com.my/nuansa/2017/05/232562/kisah-misteri-penuh-sejarah|title=Kisah misteri penuh sejarah|trans-title=A mystery story full of history|author=Rodly Fadly|language=Malay|publisher=[[Harian Metro]]|date=26 May 2017|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thepatriots.asia/misteri-kisah-seram-rumah-agam-agnes-keith-sandakan/|title=Misteri Kisah Seram Rumah Agam Agnes Keith|trans-title=Mysteries of Agnes Keith House|author=Suhelmi A Majik|language=Malay|publisher=The Patriots|date=9 May 2019|accessdate=14 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190614110302/https://www.thepatriots.asia/misteri-kisah-seram-rumah-agam-agnes-keith-sandakan/|archivedate=14 June 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*'''[[Bukit Tunku]]''': Previously known as Kenny Hills, Bukit Tunku is a leafy area with British colonial houses. There's a report of a phantom motorcycle and a ghost of woman standing in the middle of the road. Local taxi drivers usually refuse to pick up women and children at night.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2013/11/24/haunted-by-the-supernatural/|title=Haunted by the supernatural|author=Hariati Azizan|publisher=The Star|date=24 November 2013|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"most haunted\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldofbuzz.com/9-of-the-most-haunted-places-in-malaysia/|title=9 Of The Most Haunted Places In Malaysia|publisher=World of Buzz|date=31 October 2015|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"most haunted MY\">{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.tv/my/features/we-dare-you-visit-10-most-haunted-places-in-malaysia/|title=These are the 10 most haunted places in Malaysia|author=Tshiung Han See|publisher=Stuff|date=17 October 2016|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Genting Highlands]]''': Some apartments like Amber Court and Ria Apartment are reportedly haunted as well as [[First World Hotel]], which 6,118 of its rooms are reportedly haunted due to gambling related suicides.<ref name=\"most haunted\"/><ref name=\"most haunted MY\"/>\n*'''[[Highland Towers collapse|Highland Towers]]''': After a tragedy that killed 48 residents, the remaining towers was reportedly haunted as claimed by the nearest residents who live not far from there.<ref name=\"most haunted\"/><ref name=\"most haunted MY\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2013/12/12/ghostly-town-in-many-ways-site-draws-fair-share-of-stories/|title=Highland Towers: Ghostly town in many ways|author=Shalini Ravindran|publisher=The Star|date=12 December 2013|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n*'''[[Kinarut Mansion]]''': A former German [[manor house]] in the [[Graeco-Roman]] style. Local population living near the area of the mansion ruins claimed the place is haunted with \"[[Hantu Tinggi]]\", a type of Malay ghost in the form of tall tree who usually disguised as a normal tree in the heavily forest area.<ref name=\"Kinarut Mansion haunted\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bharian.com.my/node/69724|title=Rumah 'hantu tinggi' bongkar sejarah industri getah Sabah|trans-title=House of 'tall ghost' unravel the history of the Sabah rubber industry|author=Suzianah Jiffar|language=Malay|publisher=[[Berita Harian]]|date=24 July 2015|accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref> Other passerby claimed to have seen a fast moving apparition and hearing the eerie voice of [[pontianak (folklore)|pontianak]], a Malay female ghost at night which were also supported by media crews who covering information about the mansion when they felt \"something\" was following them through their walk in the area.<ref name=\"Kinarut Mansion haunted\"/>\n*'''[[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]]''': The main international airport of [[Malaysia]] stands on former [[Elaeis|oil palm]] fields. Nighttime employees often see sightings and hear mysterious sounds. There are also reports of [[demonic possession|possession]] of airline staffs and airport securities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.thesundaily.my/node/429380|title=(Video) Horror at KLIA|publisher=The Sun|date=22 February 2017|accessdate=26 October 2018}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*'''Masjid Kampung Tedong''': A new [[masjid]] in Kampung Tedong, [[Melaka]], in May 2016, [[CCTV]] cameras can capture two wooden boards that can move itself similar to [[poltergeist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thairath.co.th/content/643182|script-title=th:\u0e42\u0e0b\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e25\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e19! \u0e04\u0e25\u0e34\u0e1b\u0e41\u0e1c\u0e07\u0e01\u0e31\u0e49\u0e19\u0e43\u0e19\u0e21\u0e31\u0e2a\u0e22\u0e34\u0e14\u0e21\u0e32\u0e40\u0e25\u0e40\u0e0b\u0e35\u0e22 \u0e40\u0e25\u0e37\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e44\u0e1b\u0e21\u0e32\u0e44\u0e14\u0e49\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e07|language=Thai|publisher=Thai Rath|date=21 June 2017|accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref>\n*'''Mimaland''': Located in [[Gombak]], [[Selangor]], Mimaland used to be a largest theme park in Malaysia until its closing in 1994 due to giant water slide incident that killed a Singaporean tourist. Locals often reported paranormal activities around the former site of the theme park.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/leisure/2016/12/09/mimaland-taman-tema-gah-kini-jadi-tempat-berhantu/|title=Mimaland, taman tema gah kini jadi tempat berhantu?|author=Nizha Periaswamy|language=Malay|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=9 December 2016|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/exclusive/2017/04/235211/memories-mimaland-abandoned-over-20-years-msias-first-theme-park-still|title=Memories of Mimaland: Abandoned for over 20 years, M'sia's first theme park still draws visitors \u2013 some, for all the wrong reasons|author=Fernando Fong|publisher=New Straits Times|date=30 April 2017|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref>\n*'''Tambun Inn''': Located in [[Ipoh]], it is one of the top tourist destinations in Malaysia, and is reported to be haunted by many ghostly apparitions. Some of these accounts mention lights turning on and off, sounds of whispers and eerie cries, as well as a report of the ghost of an old woman spotted within the vicinity of the inn.<ref name=\"most haunted MY\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.articlesphere.com/Article/Scary-Creatures-of-the-Night--Scariest-Hotels-in-the-World/165029|title=Scary Creatures of the Night: Scariest Hotels in the World|author=Joe Owens|publisher=Article Sphere|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Tawau Hills Park]]''': Located in the town of [[Tawau]] in [[Sabah]], this forest park is a popular tourist destination in Tawau. Home of the tallest tropical tree in the world, the yellow meranti (''shorea faguetiana''). People are not advised to go to the park at night, as the location is said (by the town residents) to be haunted.\n*'''Kuala Lumpur - Karak Highway ''': Located in Karak , This highway has some horror stories like example : Yellow Beetle sightings , A 'ghost' boy that finding his mother and anything else . However the mystery of this highway are still unsolved.\n\n==Mexico==\n{{Main|List of reportedly haunted locations in Mexico}}\n[[File:Metro Panteones Entrance.jpg|thumb|Entrance to [[Metro Panteones]].]]\nSeveral sites in Mexico are reputedly haunted, including the '''[[Palace of the Inquisition]]''' and the '''[[Plaza de las Tres Culturas]]''' in the City of Mexico, '''[[Hospicio Caba\u00f1as]]''' in Guadalajara, '''[[Mapim\u00ed Silent Zone]]''' in the state of Durango, '''[[Chautla Hacienda]]''' in [[Puebla]], and the ancient Mayan city of '''[[Chichen Itza]]''' on the Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Monaco==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n* A yacht once belonging to [[Errol Flynn]], the {{USS|Zaca|IX-73|6}}, is berthed here and is supposed to be haunted. Witnesses have reported seeing Errol Flynn's ghost pacing aboard. Others have described the sounds of voices and laughter as if a wild party were happening on board.<ref>Richard Winer and Nancy Osborn-Ishmael, (1980), More Haunted Houses, Bantam Books, pp. 69\u201372</ref>\n\n==Myanmar (formerly Burma)==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Keng Tung]]''': Kyaing Tong New Hotel was once a palace, it is now a reportedly haunted hotel.<ref name=\"Indochina\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indochinapioneer.com/4-check-in-points-to-drop-by-for-your-halloween-vacation-in-sea/|title=4 Check-in points to drop by for your Halloween vacation in Southeast Asia|publisher=Indochina Pioneer|date=3 October 2017|accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e07\u0e15\u0e38\u0e07-\u0e19\u0e04\u0e23\u0e41\u0e2b\u0e48\u0e07\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07|url=https://www.thairath.co.th/content/488032|work=[[Thairath]]|language=thai|date=21 March 2015|first=\u0e25\u0e21|last=\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e25\u0e35\u0e48\u0e22\u0e19\u0e17\u0e34\u0e28}}</ref>\n\n==Netherlands==\n{{unsourced|section|date=December 2018}}\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:Anne Frank House 02.JPG|thumb|200px|Anne Frank House]]\n[[File:Kasteel Waardenburg P1120541.jpg|thumb|Kasteel Waardenburg]]\n*'''[[Anne Frank House]]''', in [[Amsterdam]] is the former home of Anne Frank, the Dutch/Jewish girl who wrote the world-famous [[The Diary of a Young Girl]] the [[Second World War]]. In this war, Anne and her family had to hide from the Germans, they did that in the now called [[Anne Frank House]]. Which, back in World War 2, was her father's office. Anne, her sister, and her mother later died in concentration camps. People nowadays say that they feel cold spots in the house, have the feeling of being watched and the staff sometimes hear sounds coming from the secret annex. They{{who|date=December 2018}} say that if you stand outside of the house at midnight you can see a little girl hanging out of the window. Many{{who|date=December 2018}} say the girl is Anne.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} \n*'''[[Singraven]], or Singraven Manor''' is an estate in [[Overijssel]], a province in The Netherlands. In the sixteenth century, Singraven Manor became the residence of some Franciscan nuns for a short time. One of the nuns got bricked up alive, and after that, many strange things started to happen. After the new owner arrived he was unexplainably set on fire by an oil lamp. People{{who|date=December 2018}} say that the bricked up nun is still haunting the estate today.\n*'''[[Hoensbroek Castle]]''', is a castle in the province of [[Limburg (Netherlands)|Limburg]]. In this castle there is said to be a ghost called the blue lady. Her official name was Anna Catherina and she died on 5 November 1760. People say that she is looking for her 2 children who died at an early age. The children where supposedly buried inside the castle walls while she was not informed.\n*'''[[Kasteel Waardenburg]]''', or the Waardenburg castle is a castle in the province of [[Gelderland]]. This castle is said to be one of the most haunted places in The Netherlands. People feel like they are being watched, hear footsteps and whispers, see things move and feel cold spots. people say that in medieval times the wizard who lived in the castle made a pact with the devil, that he could do and get whatever he wanted for a period of seven years and after that he would be taken by the devil. Till this day there are 2 bloodstains that cannot be washed off on one of the castle walls.{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n*'''[[Blokhuispoort]]''', is an old building complex in the city of [[Leeuwarden]]. Blokhuispoort was originally built in 1499 as a citadel. Then it became a fortress, a court and execution place and from 1580 till 2007 it served as a prison. Nowadays it holds little businesses can hire workspace, a museum, a restaurant and the city's library. People have seen objects move on their own, shadow people, doors closing on their own and locked doors opening, voices, people being touched and footsteps.\n*'''[[Huissen#Haunted house|Binnenveld mansion]]''', is a [[rijksmonument]] located in [[Huissen]], in the province of [[Gelderland]]. The [[mansion]] is better known as the '[[haunted house]] of Huissen'. This building stood in the front area during the [[Battle of Arnhem]] (a major battle of [[World War II]]). According to locals, this house would be haunted.<ref>[https://www.gelderlander.nl/betuwe/spookhuis-huissen-op-wereldkaart~ad3a0724/ Spookhuis Huissen op wereldkaart]</ref><ref>[http://www.verhalenbank.nl/items/show/49977 Nederlandse verhalenbank]</ref>\n\n==New Zealand==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Larnach Castle]]''', on [[Otago Peninsula]], is said to be haunted by at least one, and possibly two ghosts: that of Kate, daughter of the mansion's original owner, [[William Larnach]]; and that of Larnach's first wife, Eliza.<ref>[http://www.nzghosts.co.nz/Otago1.htm Otago 1] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140405155418/http://www.nzghosts.co.nz/Otago1.htm |date=5 April 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internationalghostsandhauntings.com/2012/01/haunted-larnach-castle-dunedin-new.html|title=Haunted Larnach Castle - Dunedin, New Zealand|accessdate=4 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006093855/http://www.internationalghostsandhauntings.com/2012/01/haunted-larnach-castle-dunedin-new.html|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref><ref>\"[http://www.nzherald.co.nz/travel/news/article.cfm?c_id=7&objectid=10544960 Otago:Eerie episodes haunt Kiwi castle]\", ''New Zealand Herald''</ref>\n*The '''[[Vulcan Hotel (Saint Bathans)|Vulcan Hotel]]''', in [[Saint Bathans, New Zealand|Saint Bathans]], [[Otago]] is reputedly haunted by the ghost of a nineteenth century prostitute, \"The Rose\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/close-up/ghost-st-bathans-video-4499388|title=TVNZ - One News - The Ghost of St Bathans|work=TVNZ|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.nzghosts.co.nz/Otago1.htm New Zealand Ghosts - St Bathans] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140405155418/http://www.nzghosts.co.nz/Otago1.htm |date=5 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Norway==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n* '''Lier Sykehus''': An old insane asylum situated in [[Drammen]], Norway, where people claim to have seen ghosts, shadows and apparitions.<ref name=Klikk>{{cite web|title=The most haunted places|url=http://www.klikk.no/produkthjemmesider/vimenn/article399714.ece|publisher=Klikk.no|date=15 January 2009<!--|archiveurl=http://translate.google.com/translate?sl=auto&tl=en&js=n&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.klikk.no%2Fprodukthjemmesider%2Fvimenn%2Farticle399714.ece--> |accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Oman==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Bahla]]''': A town located in Oman. In neighboring Gulf countries and Oman itself, there are rumors of Bahla being home to [[jinn]]s, which are same as [[genies]] in English.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB3386FB348BF25&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Nl.newsbank.com |publisher=Nl.newsbank.com |date=26 June 1988 |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Pakistan==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:The Mohata Palace.jpg|thumb|[[Mohatta Palace]]]]\n* The '''[[Koh-i-Chiltan]]''' peak: This mountain in Balochistan is described, according to a local myth and the legend associated with it, as being haunted by the \"... spirits of forty babies.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/10974/pg10974.html |title=Chiltan Mount and a frugal pair |publisher=Gutenberg.org |date= |accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref>\n* The '''[[Mohatta Palace]]''' in [[Karachi]]: Said to be haunted by ghosts of the [[British Raj]] era. Museum guides have reportedly seen various objects which have moved from their original place, or shifted about while guards have claimed to have \"felt\" the presence of certain spirits during the night.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://karachi.metblogs.com/2006/06/29/a-bit-of-culture-in-a-piece-of-history/ |title=A bit of culture in a piece of history |publisher=Karachi Metblogs |date= |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jang.com.pk/thenews/jul2012-weekly/nos-22-07-2012/kol.htm|title=The mystery of Mohatta\u2019s secret tunnel|work=The News|date=22 July 2012|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Panama==\n*'''[[Coiba]]''': The largest island in the [[Central American]] region.  It used to be a prison for prisoners in the era of the dictator [[Manuel Noriega]] was a very scary place at night. Until a former stronger boxer, [[Roberto Dur\u00e1n]] said that he is not alone in the night.<ref>https://insidecostarica.com/2015/11/17/coiba-island-haunted-prison-paradise-central-americas-largest-island/</ref>\n\n==Peru==\n*'''[[Lima]]''': A paranormal event was recorded on security camera  in a co-working space in Lima,Peru.The place has been a notorious site for paranormal anomalies and has been haunted ever since. The location is close to an ancient temple, where human sacrifices occurred. Locals claim that this is the source of all haunted events. Multiple situations in which doors and servers move and unexplained sources of lights appeared during the night .\n\n==Philippines==\n{{Main|List of reportedly haunted locations in the Philippines}}\n[[File:Manila Cityhall.jpg|thumb|[[Manila City Hall]], one of the several locations in the country considered by believers to be haunted]]\nSeveral sites in the Philippine Islands are reportedly haunted, including the historic '''[[Fort Santiago]]''' in Manila, the abandoned '''[[Diplomat Hotel (Baguio)|Diplomat Hotel]]''' in the northern city of Baguio, and '''[[Silliman University]]''' in Dumaguete of the Visayan Islands.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Poland==\n* An [[:pl:Kosocicka_8|unfinished house at Kosocicka St]]. in [[Krak\u00f3w]].<ref>{{cite web|title=W tych miejscach a\u017c strach si\u0119 ba\u0107!|url=http://www.radiokrakow.pl/galerie/w-tych-miejscach-az-strach-sie-bac/2/|publisher=radiokrakow.pl|accessdate=14 April 2017|language=pl}}</ref> According to the story known by locals, the house was located on former cemetery ground. Construction started in the 1970s as an investment made by two brothers, but stopped after one of them killed the other in the house. After that the property was bought by another owner, who, for unknown reason, committed suicide in the house at night, at the 3rd floor. Locals claims that ghosts appear in the house.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Karolina Gawlik|title=Tajemnica nawiedzonego domu. \"Ofiar b\u0119dzie wi\u0119cej\"|url=http://krakow.onet.pl/nawiedzony-dom-na-ul-kosocickiej-w-krakowie/fvj98r|accessdate=14 April 2017|language=pl}}</ref>\n* Abandoned hospital in [[Olesno]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dragon|first1=Miros\u0142aw|title=W szpitalu w Ole\u015bnie straszy|url=http://www.nto.pl/wiadomosci/olesno/art/4088121,w-szpitalu-w-olesnie-straszy,id,t.html|publisher=Nowa Trybuna Opolska|language=pl}}</ref>\n* Haunted house in Jele\u0144 (part of [[Jaworzno]] city). Several families left this place, complaining of noises in the night and items thrown about by a [[poltergeist]]. The current owner offers adventure seekers an opportunity to stay in the house overnight (however, only groups of at least two people are accepted).<ref>{{cite web|author1=Anna Zielonka|title=Jaworzno: w domu w Jeleniu straszy. W\u0142a\u015bciciel otworzy\u0142 go dla chc\u0105cych prze\u017cy\u0107 przygod\u0119|url=http://www.dziennikzachodni.pl/wiadomosci/jaworzno/a/jaworzno-w-domu-w-jeleniu-straszy-wlasciciel-otworzyl-go-dla-chcacych-przezyc-przygode,11437458/|publisher=Dziennik Zachodni|accessdate=14 April 2017|page=pl}}</ref>\n\n==Portugal==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n* The '''[[Beau-S\u00e9jour Palace]]''', in [[Lisbon]], is said to be haunted by the Baron of Gl\u00f3ria, who lived in the palace during the 19th century. Employees working at the palace report moving and disappearing objects and windows opening and closing abruptly. Visitors to the gardens also report hearing the ringing of non-existent bells.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://umonline.uminho.pt/uploads/clipping/NOT_70313/4324873243248732.pdf |title=Por Que \u00c9 Que Acreditamos Em Fantasmas? |publisher=P\u00fablico |date=8 December 2012 |accessdate=3 September 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521200158/http://umonline.uminho.pt/uploads/clipping/NOT_70313/4324873243248732.pdf |archivedate=21 May 2014  }}</ref>\n* Visitors at the '''Bela Vista Hotel''', in [[Portim\u00e3o]], report hearing unexplainable wailings and bangs on the walls at night. The ghost of the previous owner of the hotel is said to haunt room 108, where she reportedly died.<ref name=\"ben\">{{Cite web|url=http://blog.benetton.com/portugal/2012/10/31/casas-assombradas-de-portugal/ |title=Casas Assombradas de Portugal |publisher=Benetton.com |date=31 October 2012 |accessdate=3 September 2013}}</ref>\n* The '''Castelinho de S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o do Estoril''', in [[Estoril]], is said to be haunted by the ghost of a little blind girl who accidentally fell to her death in a nearby cliff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consultoriodeastrologia.blogs.sapo.pt/1183691.html |title=Est\u00e1 algu\u00e9m a\u00ed? Guia de casas assombradas em Portugal! |publisher=Sapo.pt |date=26 October 2012 |accessdate=3 September 2013}}</ref>\n* The '''Quinta das Conchas''', in [[Lisbon]], is believed to be haunted by the ghost of a woman from [[S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe]] who's reported to have been kept in a cage for several years by Francisco Mantero Belard, the owner of the house in the early 20th century.<ref name=\"ben\"/>\n* The '''Quinta da Juncosa''', in [[Penafiel Municipality|Penafiel]], is said to be haunted by the Baron of Lages and his family. Suspecting that his wife was unfaithful to him, the baron reportedly tied her to one of his horse's legs and dragged her across the floor, killing her. After finding that she was innocent, he proceeded to kill his children and commit suicide. Locals have reported seeing the ghost of the baron several times over the years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://diariodigital.sapo.pt/news.asp?id_news=583100 |title=Vanessa Fidalgo ca\u00e7a os fantasmas de Portugal |publisher=Di\u00e1rio Digital |date=19 July 2012 |accessdate=3 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018232529/http://diariodigital.sapo.pt/news.asp?id_news=583100 |archive-date=18 October 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Romania==\n{{Main|List of reportedly haunted locations in Romania}}\n[[File:Anexa castelul Banffy.JPG|thumb|[[Bon\u021bida B\u00e1nffy Castle|B\u00e1nffy Castle]] in renovation]]\nSeveral sites in Romania are reputedly haunted, including historic '''[[Bon\u021bida B\u00e1nffy Castle|B\u00e1nffy Castle]]''' in [[Bon\u021bida]] and the '''[[Hoia Forest]]'''.\n{{clear right}}\n\n==Russia==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:Moscow Kremlin at night (7990921836).jpg|thumb|Moscow Kremlin]]\n*'''[[Moscow Kremlin]]''': Said to be haunted by the Soviet leaders Lenin and Stalin along with other historical figures.<ref><span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://www.unexplainable.net/ghost-paranormal/the-ghosts-of-the-soviet-union.php The Kremlin] </span> from Articlesphere.com</ref>\n{{clear right}}\n\n==Singapore==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Bedok]]''': A planning area in the south-eastern coast of Singapore, which is famous for its paranormal activities. There are numerous reports of suicide or [[murder-suicide]] around the residential areas. The most famous paranormal activity in the area is the ghost of a woman and her 3-years-old kid. She allegedly died by jumping from the HDB, after throwing her kid.<ref>{{cite web|title=This Bedok ghost story based on real events will send chills down your spine|url=https://goodyfeed.com/this-bedok-ghost-story-based-on-real-events-will-send-chills-down-your-spine/|first=Low|last=Kay Hwa}}</ref> \n*'''[[Changi Hospital|Old Changi Hospital]]''': The vacated hospital compound was popular with movie-makers after the [[Singapore Land Authority]] commenced short term rental of the buildings and is often listed as one of Singapore's most haunted locations due to its history. A former British military hospital, its reputation as a haunted location likely stems from the [[Japanese occupation of Singapore|Japanese occupation]], when the ''[[Kempeitai]]'' used its premises as a prison camp and reportedly turned some of the rooms into a torture chamber.<ref>{{cite news|title=Places in Singapore with a dark past|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/places-in-singapore-with-a-dark-past|work=[[The Straits Times]]|date=10 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=4 Haunted Places In Singapore So Spooky That Even The Ghosts Also Scared \u2013 Part 1|url=https://discoversg.com/2016/03/28/haunted-places-singapore-part-1/|publisher=Discover SG|first=Youliang|last=Teo|date=28 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Saving A Sexier Island: Notes from an Old Singapore|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8qE9CgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=[[Marshall Cavendish]]|date=2015|first=Neil|last=Humphreys|author-link=Neil Humphreys}}</ref>\n*'''[[East Coast Park]]''': One night a couple was strolling around the area at night. It was at this tower where a group of thugs attacked them, knocking the boyfriend unconscious and killing the girlfriend after violating her. After this particular incident, there have been people claiming to have seen a female figure near the tower; while there have even been alleged screams of help resonating from the area.<ref>{{cite news|title=Haunted by unsolved murder of girlfriend 25 years ago|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/haunted-by-unsolved-murder-of-girlfriend-25-years-ago|work=[[The Straits Times]]|date=19 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"All Singapore Stuff - Real Singapore News 2014\">{{cite web | title=The Haunted Amber Beacon Tower at East Coast Park | website=All Singapore Stuff - Real Singapore News | date=10 June 2014 | url=https://www.allsingaporestuff.com/article/haunted-amber-beacon-tower-east-coast-park | access-date=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Pasir Ris Park]]''': One of the white sand beaches of Singapore. It is a place where it has been reported that a haunted place is a hotspot where women commit suicide. Nowadays, it is very popular among the ghost hunters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sea-globe.com/paranormal-ghosts-singapore-southeast-asia-globe/|title=Singapore\u2019s ghost hunters|work=Southeast Asia Globe|first= David|last= Hutt|date=9 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==South Africa==\n{{main|List of reportedly haunted locations in South Africa}}\nSeveral locations in South Africa are reputedly haunted, including the [[Erasmus Castle]] in Pretoria and the [[Grey High School]] in Port Elizabeth.\n\n==South Korea==\n*''' Gonjiam Psychiatric Hospital''': Famous for its very dark past among ghost hunters in [[Seoul]]. This abandoned hospital in [[Gwangju, Gyeonggi]] is claimed to be the most haunted place in Korea. The once psychiatric hospital is home to many rumors of ghosts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/gonjiam-psychiatric-hospital|title=Gonjiam Psychiatric Hospital|work=atlasobscura.com}}</ref>\n*'''Yeongdeok House''': An abandoned house on the hill of [[Yeongdeok County|Yeongdeok]] the seaside county, in the past used to be a [[Korean food|seafood restaurant]]. It is now a deserted house reputed as a haunted place. Believed to be the ghosts of teenage soldiers who died a number of Jangsa landing operation, a part of [[battle of Inchon]].<ref name=\"\u0e1c\u0e35\"/>\n*'''[[Korean Folk Village]]''': The most popular tourist attraction is located [[Yongin]], [[Gyeonggi province]] has been reported to have witnessed [[Gwisin]] a [[vengeful ghost]] in the [[Korean folklore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.traveller.com.au/tourists-terror-at-virgin-ghosts-25g9b|work=traveller.com|title=Tourists' terror at 'virgin ghosts'|date=6 September 2012|accessdate=25 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Spain==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:Palacio de Linares - 01.jpg|thumb|[[Palace of Linares]]]]\n*'''[[Palace of Linares]]''' in [[Madrid]]: Built between 1872 and 1890 for the Marquis of Linares Jos\u00e9 de Murga. According to legend this place is the most haunted in Spain. Supposedly, a little girl appears in the mansion, the Marquis fathered her with his sister and they murdered her in order to hide their incestuous relationship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.madridvillaycorte.es/palacio-linares.php |title=Palacio de Linares |last1=Diehl Busch |first1=Mar\u00eda Dolores |last2=Casta\u00f1eda Velazquez |first2=Rafael |date= |website=Madrid, Villa y Corte |publisher=Ma. Dolores Diehl Busch |accessdate= 24 December 2014|language=Spanish |trans-title=Palace of linares}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ikerjimenez.com/reportajes/palaciodelinares/ |title= Una noche en el Palacio de Linares |last1=V\u00e1zquez |first1=Santiago |date= |website=ikerjimenez.com |publisher=Iker J\u00edmenez |accessdate=24 December 2014|language=Spanish |trans-title=A night in the Palace of linares }}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Sweden==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''Borgvattnets Pr\u00e4stg\u00e5rd''': The rectory of the small village of [[Borgvattnet]] in [[J\u00e4mtland]], northern [[Sweden]], where there have been reports of hauntings since the early 1920s. On December 2, 1947, [[Bishop]] Torsten Bohlin revealed plans to ''\"order a scientific investigation of the vicarage after several years of ghosts\"''. [[The Church of Sweden]] confirmed ghosts and the village of Borgvattnet immediately became world famous.  Today, the rectory is open to the public, and people can spend nights in the house for a small fee (which benefits the village).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.borgvattnet.eu|title=Borgvattnets Pr\u00e4stg\u00e5rd|website=www.borgvattnet.eu}}</ref>\n\n==Switzerland==\n* '''The house located in Junkerngasse no 54''' in [[Bern]] is said to be haunted. The origin of this belief is unknown. According to a story, around 12 and 1 am, the windows open and a headless woman appears, laughing in a creepy way. One Story tells that a woman dressed in black appears walking along the rooms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bernerzeitung.ch/region/bern/Zu-Besuch-im-Gespensterhaus-an-der-Junkerngasse/story/24871239|title=Bern: Zu Besuch im \"Gespensterhaus\" an der Junkerngasse -  News Region: Bern & Region - bernerzeitung.ch|work=bernerzeitung.ch/|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Taiwan==\n* '''Chiayi Min-Hsiung Haunted House:''' Located in [[Chiayi City]], it was once the residence of the Liu family. It is probably one of the most recognized haunted house in Taiwan.<ref name=\"ipeen.com.tw\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ipeen.com.tw/comment/165581|title=\u5609\u7fa9\u6c11\u96c4\u9b3c\u5c4b(\u5289\u5bb6\u53e4\u539d)---\u7df4\u5fc3\u81df\u4e4b\u65c5@Guinevere\uff0diPeen \u611b\u8a55\u7db2|website=iPeen \u611b\u8a55\u7db2|access-date=13 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Thailand==\n{{multiple image\n | align             = right\n | direction         = horizontal\n | background color  = \n | total_width       = 299\n | image1            = ThaiGovHouse 001.jpg\n | caption1          = \n | image2            = Wat Kudi Dao, Ayutthaya 0311.jpg\n | caption2          = \n | footer            = [[Government House of Thailand]] (''left'') and [[Wat Kudi Dao]], a part of [[Ayutthaya Historical Park]] (''right'').\n}}\n{{main|List of reportedly haunted locations in Thailand}}\n\nMany sites in Thailand are reputedly haunted, including [[Government House of Thailand]], [[Phitsanulok Mansion]], [[Lumphini Park]], [[Sathorn Unique Tower]] (Bangkok), [[Ayutthaya Historical Park]], and [[Mahidol University]] in central, or [[Ko Lipe|Lipe]] in southern etc.\n\n==United Arab Emirates==\n*'''[[Al Jazirah Al Hamra]]''': An abandoned fishing village near [[Ras al-Khaimah]] which is believed to be haunted by the presence of supernatural ''[[jinn]]s''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/national-day/our-guide-to-the-living-ghost-town-jazirat-al-hamra-ras-al-khaimah|title=Our guide to the living ghost town Jazirat Al Hamra, Ras Al Khaimah|work=The National|date=27 November 2014|accessdate=30 October 2015|first=Anna|last=Zacharias}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://khaleejtimes.com/wknd/editors-picks/Dubai-residents-recount-their-scariest-moments|title=Dubai residents recount their scariest moments|work=Khaleej Times|first=Rohit|last=Nair|date=30 October 2015|accessdate=30 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/xpress/dubai/news/revealed-uae-s-most-haunted-places-1.1609108 |title=Revealed: UAE\u2019s most \u2018haunted\u2019 places |work=Gulf News |date=28 October 2015 |accessdate=30 October 2015 |first=Abhishek |last=Sengupta |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151030065202/http://gulfnews.com/xpress/dubai/news/revealed-uae-s-most-haunted-places-1.1609108 |archivedate=30 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==United Kingdom==\n{{Main|Reportedly haunted locations in the United Kingdom}}\n{{multiple image\n | align             = right\n | direction         = horizontal\n | background color  = \n | total_width       = 299\n | image1            = Tower of London at night 3.jpg\n | caption1          = \n | image2            = Glamis Castle - geograph.org.uk - 916029.jpg\n | caption2          = \n | footer            = Tower of London (''left'') and Glamis Castle (''right'').\n}}\nMany sites in the UK are reputedly haunted, including the [[Tower of London]], [[50 Berkeley Square]] (London), [[Belgrave Hall]], [[Arundel Castle]], [[Speke Hall]], and [[Bruce Castle]] in England, and [[Ardrossan Castle]], [[Fyvie Castle]], [[Glamis Castle]], and [[Stirling Castle]] in Scotland.\n\n==United States==\n{{Main|List of reportedly haunted locations in the United States}}\n{{multiple image\n | align             = right\n | direction         = horizontal\n | background color  = \n | total_width       = 299\n | image1            = Octagon House (Washington, D.C.) in 2012.JPG\n | caption1          = \n | image2            = Winchester Mystery House (entrance).jpg\n | caption2          = \n | footer            = The Octagon in Washington, D.C. (''left''), and Winchester Mystery House in California (''right'').\n}}\nMany sites in the United States are reputedly haunted, including [[Dudleytown (Cornwall)|Dudleytown]] in Connecticut, the [[Cherry Hill (Albany, New York)|Cherry Hill Estate]] and [[112 Ocean Avenue|112 Ocean Avenue House]], (a.k.a. the Amityville Horror House) in New York, Williamsburg, Virginia also has many reportedly haunted areas, including old Colonial Williamsburg, as well as several domestic sightings in neighborhoods such as First Colony and Monticello Woods '''[[Cliveden (Benjamin Chew House)|Cliveden Manor]]''', the '''[[First Bank of the United States]]''', '''[[Fort Mifflin]]''', '''[[Library Company of Philadelphia|Library Hall]]''', '''[[Pennsylvania Hospital]]''', and '''[[Powel House]]''' in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], the [[The Octagon House (Washington, D.C.)|Octagon House]] (1801) and the [[White House]] in [[Washington, D.C.]],\nand '''[[El Adobe de Capistrano]]''' in California.\n{{clear right}}\n\n==Vietnam==\n*'''300 Kim M\u00e3''' in [[Hanoi]] is a building which was proposed to be the Bulgarian Embassy in Vietnam, but was abandoned for an unknown reason. After a murder near this building, the story of mysterious phenomenas including the ghost of a Western man is popularised across the nation. Now it is the property of [[Vietnamese government]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soha.vn/xa-hoi/ngoi-nha-ma-300-kim-ma-cham-den-tan-cung-bi-an-20150804091956978.htm|title=\"Ng\u00f4i nh\u00e0 ma\" 300 Kim M\u00e3: Ch\u1ea1m \u0111\u1ebfn t\u1eadn c\u00f9ng b\u00ed \u1ea9n|language=Vietnamese|publisher=Soha|date=12 August 2015|accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[C\u00f4n \u0110\u1ea3o]]''': The unfinished stone bridge in the deep jungle named \"Ma Thi\u00ean L\u00e3nh Bridge\" is called by the locals \"Ghost Bridge\", which is a bridge built by over [[C\u00f4n \u0110\u1ea3o Prison|300 prisoners]] who suffered a lot and died [[France\u2013Vietnam relations|under French control]]. One villager saw a long haired male ghost in a white shirt and black pants watch him while he was drinking with a friend, and then disappear. And a female villager said she saw a woman wearing a white dress standing on a bridge alone at the dawn. She knew instantly that it was a [[hungry ghost]]. One woman says she had come across a ghost of two boys without a shirt. They forced her to give them dessert.<ref name=\"\u0e1c\u0e35\">{{IMDb title|3253618|I Wouldn't Go in There}}</ref>\n*'''The Hui Mansion (now [[Ho Chi Minh City Museum of Fine Arts]])''': One of the most mysterious places in [[Ho Chi Minh City]], located at 97 Ph\u00f3 \u0110\u1ee9c Ch\u00ednh Street, [[District 1, Ho Chi Minh City|District 1]]. People believe that the mansion is haunted by the ghost of Mr. Hui Bon Hoa's [[leprosy]] daughter.<ref name=\"Indochina\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://saigoneer.com/saigon-culture/1922-saigon-urban-legends-the-ghost-of-the-fine-arts-museum|title=Saigon Urban Legends: The Ghost of the Fine Arts Museum|author=Dang Bui|publisher=Saigoneer|date=8 May 2014|accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Category see also|Reportedly haunted locations}}\n{{Commons category|Ghosts}}\n<!-- Note to editors: Entries should be in alphabetical order. -->\n*[[Ghost hunting]]\n*[[Haunted house]]\n*[[List of ghosts]]\n*[[List of ghost films]]\n*[[List of Ghost Adventures episodes|List of ''Ghost Adventures'' episodes]] (includes lists of reportedly haunted locations mostly in the United States that have been investigated)\n*[[List of Ghost Hunters episodes|List of ''Ghost Hunters'' episodes]] (includes lists of reportedly haunted locations in the United States that have been investigated)\n*[[List of Most Haunted episodes|List of ''Most Haunted'' episodes]] (includes lists of reportedly haunted locations in the United Kingdom and Ireland that have been investigated)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Ghosts|state=expanded}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haunted locations in the world}}\n[[Category:Lists of places]]\n[[Category:Reportedly haunted locations by country| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of reportedly haunted locations| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Redirect|Haunting|other uses|The Haunting (disambiguation){{!}}The Haunting}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use American English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n\n{{Paranormal |state=collapsed}}\nThis is a '''list of reportedly haunted locations''' throughout the world, that are said to be haunted by [[ghost]]s or other [[supernatural]] beings, including [[demon]]s. Reports of haunted locations are part of ghostlore, which is a form of [[folklore]].\n\n==Argentina==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n* '''[[Cinco Saltos]]''' in [[R\u00edo Negro (Argentina)|R\u00edo Negro]] has been reported to have a number of ghosts, most of them reportedly the result of [[witchcraft]].{{cn|date=May 2019}} In 2009, an intact corpse of an 8- to 12-year-old girl who had died in the 1930s was found in a cemetery [[ossuary]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www1.rionegro.com.ar/arch200310/s01g02.html |title=Pol\u00e9mica por una momia de Cinco Saltos|publisher=RioNegro.com.ar |date=1 October 2003 |accessdate=28 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Australia==\n<!-- Note to editors: There have reason sighting in austrailia is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:Ararat Lunatic Asylum - Aradale Psychiatric Hospital.jpg|thumb|[[Aradale Mental Hospital|Ararat Lunatic Asylum]]]]\n* The '''''Buratimos''''' is the wreck of a former [[U.S. Navy]] ship from World War II, that occurred off the coast of [[Western Australia]] in 1964.<ref>Jack Wong Sue and Barry Sue. ''Ghost of the Buratimos''. (Revised edition: Perth, 2005)</ref>\n*'''[[Aradale Mental Hospital|Ararat Lunatic Asylum]]''', or Aradale, is the largest abandoned [[History of psychiatric institutions|lunatic asylum]] in Australia. Opened in 1867, Aradale was reserved for many of the incurable mental patients in Victoria during the 1800s. An estimated 13,000 people died here during 140 years of operation.\n* Thirteen people were executed at the '''[[Ballarat Gaol]]''' in [[Ballarat]]. The remains of seven criminals are still on the grounds. The Ballarat Ghost Tours operate nightly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eerietours.com.au |title=Eerietours.com.au |publisher=Eerietours.com.au |date= |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref>\n*'''[[Beechworth Asylum|Beechworth Lunatic Asylum]]''' in [[Beechworth, Victoria]] is reportedly haunted by several ghosts of departed patients. Open from 1867 to 1995, it has appeared in several books, television shows, and documentaries, including ''A.C.T. Paranormal''. Ghost tours run nightly.<ref>[http://www.beechworth.com.au/Beechworth-Tours/Beechworth-Tours/Beechworth-Ghost-Tours-Bookings.html Beechworth Ghost Tours - Information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217024800/http://beechworth.com.au/Beechworth-Tours/Beechworth-Tours/Beechworth-Ghost-Tours-Bookings.html |date=17 February 2011 }} Accessed 6/9/08</ref>\n* '''[[Brisbane City Hall]]''' in [[Brisbane|Brisbane, Australia]] has several stories of deaths spanning the eras before and after its construction. During construction, workmen were said to have died while laying the foundations, which were on top of a former swamp. It is also said that the area was once a significant Aboriginal site&nbsp;\u2013 either a meeting place or campground. One story relates the death of a maintenance man, or lift attendant, who either fell to his death down the lift well or was crushed by the lift&nbsp;\u2013 this story likely results from a suicide from the clock tower that occurred in 1935.{{cn|date=May 2019}} Another story claims an American soldier was stabbed to death during World War II during a fight. Staff have reported the sounds of an argument from the Red Cross Tea Room, and there are many reports of sounds and unusual activity in the areas surrounding these deaths. A third story claims the apparition of a woman is regularly seen traversing the main stairs in the lobby, and to look out over the foyer&nbsp;\u2013 a story which likely results from another suicide from City Hall's Clock Tower in 1937, although recent photos of the stairwell exhibit a possible apparition.{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n[[File:The BuzzSaw viewed from the entrance to Dreamworld..jpg|thumb|200px|[[BuzzSaw (roller coaster)|BuzzSaw roller coaster]] in Dreamworld.]]\n* '''[[Dreamworld (Australian theme park)|Dreamworld]]''' is a theme park in [[Coomera, Queensland]]. One building inside the grounds of the theme park, where the reality television series ''[[Big Brother Australia]]'' is produced, has been reported to be haunted since the show's first season in 2001. Numerous production staff claim to have witnessed the presence of a young girl, as well as a child's voice and fog appearing late at night and early in the morning.<ref>{{cite web | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130902213833/http://www.bigbrother.com.au/news/8715707/the-big-brother-housemate-youve-yet-to-meet | url = http://www.bigbrother.com.au/news/8715707/the-big-brother-housemate-youve-yet-to-meet | title = The Big Brother Housemate You\u2019ve Yet To Meet ... | archivedate = 2 September 2013 | date = 31 August 2013 | accessdate = 17 February 2015}}</ref> Additionally, theme park employees have spoken about sightings of a ghost nicknamed [[Jack Darke]], named after a [[gold prospecting|gold prospector]] who was claimed to have been killed by a buzzsaw in 1897.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9jVxSdym8Kg | title = Dreamworld Ghost Video | date = 18 August 2011}}</ref>\n*'''[[Fremantle Arts Centre]]''' in [[Fremantle]], [[Western Australia]] was originally built as a psychiatric hospital - Fremantle Lunatic Asylum - it has seen much overcrowding, abuse and death. It was built using convict labour between 1861 and 1868. Cold spots are commonly felt, sounds of crying, laughter and yelling have been heard. Some people have reported the feeling of being kissed on the cheek by unseen persons. A lot of the activity takes place on the first floor where doors open and close and objects move by themselves. One of the apparitions that is seen, a woman whose daughter had been kidnapped was admitted to the asylum due to her deep depression, committed suicide by throwing herself through the first floor window. It is said she can be seen about the building as she still searches in hopes of finding her daughter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theparanormalguide.com/1/post/2014/04/fremantle-arts-centre.html|title=Fremantle Arts Centre|website=The Paranormal Guide|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n*'''[[Fremantle Prison]]''' in [[Fremantle]], [[Western Australia]] is a former prison built in 1855 primarily by convicts using limestone quarried on-site. Initially used for [[Convicts in Australia|convicts]] transported from Britain, it was transferred to the colonial government in 1886 for use for locally-sentenced prisoners. At least 43 men and 1 woman were executed between 1886 and 1964. There have been many reports of sightings of apparitions and unexplainable occurrences.\n*'''[[Monte Cristo Homestead]]''' in [[Junee, New South Wales]] was the site of seven deaths during the 1800s, and is reported{{By whom|date=October 2012}} to be the most haunted house in Australia. Various ghost groups have reported sightings there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.montecristo.com.au/ |title=Monte Cristo Homestead, Australia's Most Haunted House&nbsp;\u2013 Ghost Tours |publisher=Montecristo.com.au |date= |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref>\n* '''[[North Head Quarantine Station]]''' in [[Manly, New South Wales]] housed victims of a number of diseases including [[smallpox]] and the [[Spanish influenza|Spanish flu]] between 1833 and 1984. It was the site of over 500 deaths. A number of ghost tours are run on the grounds, which includes a large cemetery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quarantinestation.com.au/Ghost-Tours/overview-ghost-paranormal-tours.html|title=(Quarantine Station Ghost Tours)|author=Kelly|publisher=|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref>\n*'''[[Port Arthur, Tasmania|Port Arthur]]''' in [[Tasmania]] operates nightly ghost tours.\n*The '''[[Princess Theatre, Melbourne|Princess Theatre Melbourne]]'''  has reported several ghosts since the building opened in 1886. The theatre's best known \"inhabitant\" is Frederick Baker, whose stage name was [[Frederick Federici]], a talented bass-baritone singer who died during March 1888 whilst singing the role of [[Mephistopheles]] in [[Faust (opera)|''Faust'']]&nbsp;\u2013 and who was seen by the rest of the cast taking his bows with them soon thereafter. For years the theater kept a seat vacant in the [[dress circle]] for Federici (only ceasing the practice on economic grounds), and his appearance in the dress circle during rehearsals for a new show is considered a good omen.\n* [[Campbelltown, New South Wales|Campbelltown]] NSW [[Fisher's ghost]] is a popular Australian ghost story or folk tale dating to the early 19th century. On 17 June 1826 an English-born Australian farmer from Campbelltown named Frederick Fisher (born 28 August 1792 in London) suddenly disappeared. \n* [[Macquarie Fields]] NSW south west of Sydney train station where numerous people have accounted hearing a girl crying. LAte at night, when it\u2019s still, and last trains have pulled out, \u201cfaint crying\u201d can be heard carried on the breeze at Macquarie Fields station.\n\n* [[Northern Beaches]] NSW the Wakehurst Parkway is busy road north of Sydney is not the type of place you would usually associate with the supernatural, but the Wakehurst Parkway has for years been linked with reported sightings of a mysterious female figure, with claims the apparition has even appeared in the back seat of people\u2019s cars before disappearing.\n\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/rewind/txt/s1184926.htm |title=Rewind (ABC TV): The theater ghost |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=29 August 2004 |accessdate=11 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523025416/http://www.abc.net.au/tv/rewind/txt/s1184926.htm |archive-date=23 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Bangladesh==\n{{main|Ghosts in Bengali culture#Alleged haunted places}}\n* '''[[Dhaka]] Airport Road''': The segment of the road between Nikunjo and Biman office is reported by believers to be haunted by a lady at night, supposedly causing accidents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/weekend/2015/oct/29/urban-legends-where-they-roam-restless|title=Urban legends: Where they roam restless|website=dhakatribune.com|access-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Dhaka Golf Heights, Banani, [[Dhaka]]''': Claimed by believers to be haunted by a crying baby, and feelings of being watched are reported.<ref name=\"dhakatribune.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/weekend/2015/oct/29/urban-legends-where-they-roam-restless|title=Urban legends: Where they roam restless|website=www.dhakatribune.com|access-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Under-construction apartment in Old DOHS, Banani, [[Dhaka]]''': Said to have ties to [[Satanism]]. Lanes 4 and 5 are reputed to have been built on top of graves.<ref name=\"daily-sun.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/86647/HAUNTED-TALES:-IN-CONVERSATION-WITH-%E2%80%98DHAKA-PARANORMAL-SOCIETY%E2%80%99|title=HAUNTED TALES: IN CONVERSATION WITH \u2018DHAKA PARANORMAL SOCIETY\u2019|website=daily-sun.com|access-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Purbo Nayatola Rail Crossing, [[Dhaka]]''': Reported by believers to be haunted by a woman frantically looking for her missing infant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/weekend/2015/oct/29/urban-legends-where-they-roam-restless#sthash.KHLIvOWN.dpuf|title=Urban legends: Where they roam restless|website=dhakatribune.com|access-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n* '''[[Shahidullah Hall]] Pond, Dhaka''': The old pond adjoining Shahidullah Hall at [[Dhaka University]] campus is believed to be haunted by people who drowned in the pond.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u09b6\u09b9\u09c0\u09a6\u09c1\u09b2\u09cd\u09b2\u09be\u09b9 \u09b9\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b0\u09b9\u09b8\u09cd\u09af\u09ae\u09af\u09bc \u09aa\u09c1\u0995\u09c1\u09b0|url=http://www.bd-pratidin.com/campus/2015/04/12/74534|access-date=22 October 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Farmhouse in [[Narsingdi District|Narsingdi]]''': This farmhouse, over a couple of hundred years old, contains twin ponds called ''Bhobani'' and ''Rukshar'', and rumours claim of a Hindu cremation ground on site of one of the ponds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/weekend/2014/jan/31/paranormal-activity|title=Paranormal activity|website=dhakatribune.com|access-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Highway Near Mirsharai, [[Chittagong]]''': The highway connecting Dhaka and Chittagong near Mirsharai, Chittagong is claimed by believers to be haunted by a [[vanishing hitchhiker]] at night.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghoststoriesworld.com/haunted-places-in-bangladesh/the-highway-near-mirsharai-chittagong|title=The highway near Mirsharai Chittagong - Haunted Places in Bangladesh|last=Writer|first=Ghost|website=Ghoststoriesworld.com|access-date=3 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117220400/http://www.ghoststoriesworld.com/haunted-places-in-bangladesh/the-highway-near-mirsharai-chittagong|archive-date=17 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* '''Pakri Beach, [[Chittagong]]''': This silver sand beach has a reputation of being haunted. Reported hauntings range from mysterious footsteps and disembodied screams to an apparition of an old sailor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghoststoriesworld.com/haunted-places-in-bangladesh/parki-beach-chittagong-ghost-stories|title=Parki Beach Chittagong Ghost stories, Apparitions of old sailors|last=Writer|first=Ghost|website=Ghoststoriesworld.com|access-date=3 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304220145/http://www.ghoststoriesworld.com/haunted-places-in-bangladesh/parki-beach-chittagong-ghost-stories|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Sunrise at Kuakata beach.JPG|thumbnail|200px|Kuakata Beach, Barisal]]\n* ''' [[Kuakata|Kuakata Beach, Barisal]]''': [[Rakhine people|Rakhaine]] settlers claim this beach to be haunted. Believers also claim of a large, wooden, gold-laden boat in the surrounding forest area that is supposedly cursed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://remit2homeblog.wordpress.com/2013/12/30/kuakata-the-daughter-of-the-ocean-sagar-kanya/|title=Kuakata: The daughter of the ocean (Sagar Kanya)|last=Blog|first=Klinnk|website=Remit2Home|access-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Farmhouse in [[Comilla]]''': A huge farmhouse in Comilla is reported to be haunted by [[Shadow people|black shadows]] assaulting people at night.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/brush-with-the-paranormal-49233|title=Brush with the paranormal|website=The Daily Star|access-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Barbados==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Chase Vault]]''' is a [[burial vault (tomb)|burial vault]] in the cemetery of the [[Christ Church Parish Church]] in [[Oistins]], [[Christ Church Parish, Barbados|Christ Church]], [[Barbados]] best known for a widespread but unverified legend of \"mysterious moving [[coffin]]s\". According to the story, each time the heavily sealed vault was opened during the early 19th century for burial of a family member, all of the lead coffins had changed position. The facts of the story are unverified, and skeptics call the tale \"historically dubious.\" The tale appears to have originated from anecdotes told by Thomas H. Orderson, Rector of Christ Church during the 1800s, and subsequently repeated in [[James Edward Alexander]]'s 1833 ''Transatlantic Sketches.''<ref name=\"Alexander1833\">{{Cite book|author=Sir James Edward Alexander|title=Transatlantic sketches, comprising visits to the most interesting scenes in North and South America, and the West Indies|url=https://archive.org/details/transatlanticske01alexrich|year=1833|publisher=R. Bentley|pages=[https://archive.org/details/transatlanticske01alexrich/page/162 162]\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Percy1833\">{{Cite book|author=Reuben Percy|title=The Mirror of literature, amusement, and instruction|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_7boRAAAAYAAJ|year=1833|publisher=J. Limbird|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_7boRAAAAYAAJ/page/n71 51]\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Clark1999\">{{Cite book|author=Jerome Clark|title=Unexplained!: Strange Sightings, Incredible Occurrences & Puzzling Physical Phenomena|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=szFLs6pQmsQC&pg=PA573|year=1999|publisher=Visible Ink Press|isbn=978-1-57859-070-4|pages=573\u2013}}</ref><ref>Nickell, Joe; 1982. \"Barbados' restless coffins laid to rest\". ''[[Fate Magazine|Fate]]'', Part I, 35.4 (April): 50\u201356; Part II, 35.5 (May): 79\u201386</ref><ref name=\"Nickell2001\">{{Cite book|author=Joe Nickell|title=Real-Life X-Files: Investigating the Paranormal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Bm-EjjG3AwC|accessdate=14 May 2012|date=24 October 2001|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=978-0-8131-2210-6}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated125\">{{Cite book\n| last = Dils\n| first = Tracy\n| title = \"Real-Life Scary Places\":Terrifying True Tales\n| publisher = Willowisp Press\n| year = 1985\n| location = [[St. Petersburg, Florida]]\n| page = [https://archive.org/details/reallifescarypla0000dils/page/125 125]\n| isbn = 0-87406-794-4\n| url = https://archive.org/details/reallifescarypla0000dils/page/125\n}}</ref><ref name=\"ghost-story1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghost-story.co.uk/stories/thechasevault.html |title=Ghost Story.uk |publisher=Ghost-story.co.uk |date= |accessdate=18 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Brazil==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n* The '''[[wmbr:|Grande Hotel Trilogia]]''' in [[Cambuquira]], [[Minas Gerais]] is allegedly haunted and appeared on episode 16 of the 1st season of [[Ghost Hunters International]].\n* The '''[[Joelma Building]][[br]]{{dn|date=March 2020}}''' (now the Pra\u00e7a da Bandeira Building) in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] is allegedly haunted by victims of the fire that started on 1 February 1974, after an air conditioning unit on the twelfth floor overheated; centered on the \"Mystery of the Thirteen Souls\", individuals who died within an elevator as they were trying to escape the fire, and are haunting the building.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Carolina Iskandarian Do G1, em S\u00e3o Paulo |url=http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/SaoPaulo/0,,MUL330153-5605,00.html |title=G1 Edi\u00e7\u00e3o S\u00e3o Paulo&nbsp;\u2013 NOT\u00cdCIAS&nbsp;\u2013 Lugares 'mal-assombrados' viram lenda em SP |publisher=G1.globo.com |date= |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Cambodia==\n*'''[[Kampong Chhnang Province|Kampong Chhnang]]''': The famous \"ghost house\" in Cambodia.<ref name=\"Indochina\"/>\n\n==Canada==\n{{Main|List of reportedly haunted locations in Canada}}\nSeveral sites in Canada are reputedly haunted, including '''[[Citadel Hill (Fort George)]]''' in Halifax, '''[[The Algonquin Resort St. Andrews By-The-Sea]]''' in New Brunswick, '''[[Banff Springs Hotel]]''' in Alberta, '''[[Darke Hall]]''' at '''[[University of Regina]]''' in Saskatchewan, '''[[Fairmont Royal York]]''' in Toronto, '''[[Fort Garry Hotel]]''' in Winnipeg, '''[[Hotel Macdonald]]''' in Edmonton, '''[[Craigdarroch Castle]]''' in Victoria, '''[[Plains of Abraham]]''' in Quebec City and '''[[Bytown Museum]]''' in Ottawa.\n\n==China==\n{{main|List of reportedly haunted locations in China}}\n[[File:Front elevation, 81 Chaonei, Beijing.jpg|thumb|Western (front) elevation of [[Chaonei No. 81]] during 2014]]\nSeveral sites in China are reputedly haunted, including '''[[Chaonei No. 81]]''', an abandoned mansion in Beijing's [[Chaoyangmen]] neighborhood, and the '''[[Wukang Mansion]]''', formerly known as the ''Normandie Apartment'', in [[Shanghai]] (named after the [[World War I]] battleship Normandie).\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Colombia==\n{{Main|List of reportedly haunted locations in Colombia}}\n\n==Czech Republic==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Zv\u00edkov Castle]]''': Until 1597 there are stories about a Zv\u00edkovsk\u00fd Rar\u00e1\u0161ek (Rarach is a supernatural being common in Slavic folklore, similar to an imp or trickster) which haunts people in the ancient tower, Markomanka. This tower has stones engraved with unknown symbols, and was built during the [[Marcomanni]] rule over [[Bohemia]], in the 1st century BC and 2nd century AD. It was integrated into Zv\u00edkov castle hundreds of years later. Strange events occur here frequently, including weird photos, technical problems, unpredictable behaviour of animals, spontaneous extinguishing of fires, electromagnetic anomalies, and the presence of ghosts. In Czech media it's a popular subject of investigation. Other areas of the castle are also haunted; it is said to be dangerous to sleep in the main tower, as anyone who does supposedly dies within a year. Another monster common in Czech culture, [[fire hound]]s are also part of the myths surrounding the castle. It is said that these spectral dogs (in some accounts they are depicted with burning eyes) are guarding a hidden tunnel underneath Zv\u00edkov.<ref>{{cite web |author=Galileo Corporation s.r.o. |url=http://www.hrad-zvikov.eu/points-of-interest/hliza-tower/ |title=Ofici\u00e1ln\u00ed str\u00e1nky hradu Zv\u00edkov - Hl\u00edza tower |publisher=Hrad-zvikov.eu |accessdate=26 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325192456/http://www.hrad-zvikov.eu/points-of-interest/hliza-tower/ |archivedate=25 March 2014  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.castlesandmanorhouses.com/summary.php?Category=Visit&Type=%28All+Properties%29&Country=%28All+Countries%29&Parameter=ByCountry |title=List of (All Properties) to Visit in (All Countries) |publisher=Castlesandmanorhouses.com |date= |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blesk.cz/clanek/celebrity/10200/zvikovsky-rarasek-trapi-filmare.html |title=Zv\u00edkovsk\u00fd rar\u00e1\u0161ek tr\u00e1p\u00ed filma\u0159e |publisher=Blesk.cz |date= |accessdate=26 March 2014 |language=Czech}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tajemnamista.cz/magazin/64-zvikovska-vez-markomanka-dodnes-vyhrozuje-smrti |title=Zv\u00edkovsk\u00e1 v\u011b\u017e Markomanka: Dodnes vyhro\u017euje smrt\u00ed! |publisher=Tajemn\u00e1 m\u00edsta |accessdate=26 March 2014 |language=Czech |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327234202/http://www.tajemnamista.cz/magazin/64-zvikovska-vez-markomanka-dodnes-vyhrozuje-smrti |archivedate=27 March 2014  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://paranormal.komis-site.eu/zvikov-tajemna-vez-markomanka/ |title=Zv\u00edkov \u2013 Tajemn\u00e1 v\u011b\u017e Markomanka \u00ab Paranormal |publisher=Paranormal.komis-site.eu |date=24 January 2013 |accessdate=26 March 2014 |language=Czech}}</ref>\n\n==Denmark==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Dragsholm Castle]]''' in [[Zealand]] is said to be haunted by the ghost of [[James Hepburn, 4th Earl of Bothwell]], imprisoned there for about five years until his death during 1578.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guide-to-castles-of-europe.com/dragsholm-castle.html |title=Guide to castles of Europe |accessdate=31 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Egypt==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:WhiteDesertEgypt@FarafraOasis2007jan6-93 byDanielCsorfoly.JPG|thumb|Farafra Desert]]\n*'''[[Baron Empain Palace]]''': Tourists have reportedly heard voices throughout the palace late at night. Guards and police have reported seeing ghostly apparitions of people who were once residents of the palace, wandering the outside lawn at midnight.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\">{{cite book\n |page=359\n |title=Encyclopedia of Haunted Places: Ghostly Locales from Around the World\n |author=Jeff Belanger\n |publisher= New Page Books\n |year=2005\n |ISBN=1564147991}}</ref>\n*'''[[Farafra, Egypt|Farafra Desert]]''': The ghost of [[Akhenaten]] is said to wander the Farafra Desert (also known as the White Desert) of Egypt, reported by dozens of tourists and [[nomads]]. Legend says this is because Akhenaten abolished the Egyptian gods when he became Pharaoh, angering the religious followers and priests of Egypt. Upon his death, the priests are believed to have cursed him to wander the deserts forever as punishment.<ref>{{cite book\n |page=1\n |title=The Ghost of Akhenaten\n |author=Moyra Caldecott\n |publisher=Mushroom Publishing\n |year=2003\n |ISBN=1-84319-024-9}}</ref>\n*'''[[Pyramids of Giza]]''': A man in early 20th-century clothing has been seen by visitors, rumored to be the ghost of [[Howard Carter]]. Various employees and tourists have reported seeing an [[orb (optics)|orb]] apparition of an Egyptian Pharaoh, floating away from the pyramids towards the Valley of the Kings.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n*'''[[Valley of the Kings]]''': Eyewitnesses have reported seeing the vision of an Egyptian Pharaoh in the Valley of the Kings, wearing his golden collar, headdress, and riding a fiery [[chariot]] with black phantom horses.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n\n==Finland==\n[[File:Alexander Theatre Helsinki 2011-09-03 1.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Alexander Theatre]]]]\n*'''[[Alexander Theatre]]''' in [[Helsinki]] is reportedly haunted by the ghost of an officer. The ghost moved to Helsinki as the tiles to build Alexander Theatre were relocated from [[\u00c5land]]. Some have suggested that the officer died in the [[Crimea War]] and has been there ever since.<ref name=Fin>[http://www.nopsatravels.com/kummitusten-helsinki/#kohde2 Kummitusten Helsinki ] Retrieved 22 December 2015</ref>\n*'''[[Finnish National Theatre]]''' in Helsinki is reportedly haunted by at least three ghosts - an unknown ''Grey Lady'' and the ghosts of actors [[Aarne Lepp\u00e4nen]] and [[Urho Somersalmi]].<ref name=Fin/>\n*'''Haihara Manor''' in [[Tampere]] is haunted by ''The Blue Maid'', former maid of the manor.<ref>[http://www.tampere.fi/english/culturalaffairs/locations/haihara/history.html City of Tampere - History] Retrieved 22 December 2015</ref>\n*'''Mustio Manor''' in the village of Mustio reportedly is a location with several ghosts.<ref>[http://www.mustionlinna.fi/en/museum-a-park/museum-a-park/museum-guided-tour Museum & Guided Tour of Mustion Linna Website ] Retrieved 22 December 2015</ref>\n*'''[[Nummela Sanatorium]]''', an abandoned hospital in the village of [[R\u00f6ykk\u00e4]] is told about rumors of paranormal phenomena, like the windows of the building show mysterious lights, and on the edge of the roof there is a woman who suicides by jumping down. There is also a rumor that the hospital might be haunted by the spirit of a girl who died there at a young age.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iltalehti.fi/matkajutut/a/2016102122496652|title=Hui, kummituksia! Suomalaiskohteet, joihin liittyy hurjia aavetarinoita|work=Iltalehti|author=Marianne Zitting|date=24 October 2016|accessdate=27 March 2019|language=fi}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nurmijarvenuutiset.fi/artikkeli/4532-hurjia-kummitusjuttuja|title=Hurjia kummitusjuttuja|work=Nurmij\u00e4rven uutiset|author=|date=12 November 2010|accessdate=27 March 2019|language=fi}}</ref>\n*'''Svenska Klubben''' (The Swedish Club) house in [[Kruununhaka]], Helsinki, is haunted by the ''Grey Madame''. She is rumoured to be the former lady of the house who had an affair with her chauffeur. She is known to swing the chandeliers, play piano and walk around the house.<ref>[http://www.mtv.fi/lifestyle/koti/artikkeli/urho-vaeltaa-teatterissa-kirves-kadessaan-lahde-kierrokselle-helsingin-kuuluisiin-kummitustaloihin/5219666 MTV Lifestyle] Retrieved 22 December 2015</ref>\n*'''[[Turku City Library]]''' employees have reportedly had paranormal experiences in the basement of the library. The ghost is assumed to be a former librarian.{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n*'''[[Villa Kleineh]]''', a historical villa in Helsinki currently used by the Dutch embassy, reportedly hosts a ghost called ''The White Lady''.<ref name=\"HT 2013\">{{cite web | author=HT | title=Villa Kleineh opens on Restaurant Day to serve cuisine hollandaise | website=News from Finland \"Helsinki Times\" | date=14 November 2013 | url=http://www.helsinkitimes.fi/eat-and-drink/8389-villa-kleineh-opens-on-restaurant-day-to-serve-cuisine-hollandaise.html | access-date=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==France==\n{{Main|List of reportedly haunted locations in France}}\n[[File:Logis chateau chateaubriant 01.jpg|thumb|[[Ch\u00e2teau de Ch\u00e2teaubriant]]]]\n\nSeveral sites in France are reputedly haunted, including the '''[[Ch\u00e2teau de Brissac]]''', the '''[[Ch\u00e2teau de Tr\u00e9cesson]]''' in Brittany, the '''[[Catacombs of Paris|Catacombs]] ''' and '''[[P\u00e8re Lachaise Cemetery|Cemetery of P\u00e8re Lachaise]]''' in Paris, '''[[Mont Saint-Michel]]''', and the '''[[Ch\u00e2teau de Ch\u00e2teaubriant]]''' in western [[France]].\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Germany==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''Berlin''': The [[Reichstag building]] has been reported to be haunted by numerous ghosts of famous German politicians.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n*'''[[Heidelberg]]''': The ''Hexenturm'' ([[Witches Tower]]) and the [[Nazi]] Amphitheatre are both said to be haunted by various ghosts.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n*'''[[Frankenstein Castle]]''': Frankenstein Castle ({{lang-de|Burg Frankenstein}}) is a real [[hilltop castle]] in the [[Odenwald]], overlooking the city of [[Darmstadt]], and allegedly an inspiration for [[Mary Shelley]] when she wrote her monster novel ''[[Frankenstein]]''. The [[SyFy]] TV show ''[[Ghost Hunters International]]'' aired an entire episode about the castle and testified it had \"... significant paranormal activity\".<ref>[http://www.syfy.com/ghosthuntersinternational/episodes/season/s01/episode/e107/frankenstein_s_castle SyFy - Ghost Hunters International Website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140420024220/http://www.syfy.com/ghosthuntersinternational/episodes/season/s01/episode/e107/frankenstein_s_castle |date=20 April 2014 }} Retrieved 19 April 2014</ref>\n*'''Lichtenegg Castle''': The ghost of a lady in a white dress is said to be seen standing in front of the entrance to the ruins at midnight. She will, usually, sit down on a flat rock covered with moss.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n[[File:Nordkirchen-Hauptgebaeude-von-Venusinsel-DSC 5912.jpg|thumb|Northern front of Schloss Nordkirchen.]]\n*'''[[Schloss Nordkirchen]]''': The castle was built between 1703 and 1734. According to the legend, at full moon and on certain foggy nights, a few people have reported seeing a luxurious [[carriage]] with stallions running through the grounds.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n*'''[[Wolfsegg, Bavaria]]''', '''Wolfsegg Castle''': This 14th-century castle was supposed to be a sanctuary for travellers. The folklore of this haunting originated from the 1500s, when Ulrich von Laaber hired two young farmers to kill his wife, Klara von Helfenstein, after discovering she was having an affair.  Soon thereafter, Ulrich and his sons also died suddenly. There have been reports of strange noises coming out of a cave area near the castle. Several expeditions into the cave, uncovering numerous animal skeletons, leading locals to decide the noises had come from hunters who were hiding their prey. While the cave noises might have been solved, this has not been the case of the haunting of the \"White Woman\" who is still restlessly making her rounds of the castle.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n*'''[[W\u00fcrzburg]]''': There is supposedly the ghost of a dead [[nun]] walking through the halls of Praemonstratenser Abbey. The ghost is said to be that of Maria Renata Von Mossau, accused of mixing herbs into everyone's food in order to bewitch them. The nun was taken to be executed only three days after her sentencing in court. She was first decapitated, and then burned and her ashes scattered. To this day, there are reports of her walking down the hallways and holding a bouquet of roses while picking off the petals, leaving a trail across the grounds.<ref name=\"autogenerated359\"/>\n\n==India==\n{{main|List of reportedly haunted locations in India}}\n[[File:South-Park-Street-Cemetery-1.jpg|thumb|South Park Street Cemetery.]]\nSeveral sites in India are reported to be haunted, including [[South Park Street Cemetery]] in West Bengal on [[Park Street, Kolkata]], and [[Morgan House, Kalimpong|Morgan House]], [[Bhangarh_Fort|Bhangar Fort]], [[Rajasthan]], a colonial-era mansion in [[Kalimpong]] that is considered to be one of the most haunted locations in [[India]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/5-haunted-hotels-of-india-hotel-taj-mahal-palace-mumbai-hotel-brij-raj-bhavan-kota-morgan-house-tourist-lodge-kalimpong/1/532827.html|title=Dare to stay at these haunted hotels of India?|access-date=26 June 2017}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Indonesia==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:Basement of Lawang Sewu 2011.JPG|thumb|The basement of the Building B of Lawang Sewu, a former prison. It is one of the rooms where ghost sightings have been reported.]]\n*'''[[Dr. Cipto Mangunkusumo Hospital]]''': The government run hospital located at [[Salemba]], [[Jakarta]]. It is rumored to be haunted by a [[vengeful spirit]] of a fenale nurse named ''Suster Ngesot'' (Limping Nurse).<ref>{{cite web|language=thai|url=https://en.brilio.net/scary/tragic-death-of-suster-ngesot-haunt-hospitals-in-indonesia-160808s.html|title=Tragic death of Suster Ngesot leaves her haunting old hospitals|date=11 August 2016|accessdate=9 March 2020|work=https://en.brilio.net|first=Victoria|last=Tunggono}}</ref>\n*'''[[Jakarta History Museum]]''': This historical building once served as the administrative headquarters of the [[Dutch East Indies]]. The front square of the building was often used as a place of executions for criminals. During nighttime there are reports of sighting of a headless ghost, Dutch colonial lady, and mysterious sounds coming from the underground prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hipwee.com/travel/kisah-misteri-yang-tersembunyi-di-museum-fatahillah-dijamin-kamu-bakal-merinding-dibuatnya/|title=Kisah Misteri yang Tersembunyi di Museum Fatahillah. Dijamin Kamu Bakal Merinding Dibuatnya!|first=Andina|last=Rahayu|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnnindonesia.com/gaya-hidup/20141213145342-269-17920/riwayat-penjara-terpendam-di-kota-tua-jakarta/|title=Riwayat Penjara Terpendam di Kota Tua Jakarta|publisher=}}</ref>\n*'''[[Jeruk Purut Cemetery]]''': A cemetery in [[Jakarta]] said to be haunted by the ghost of a decapitated pastor, which carries its head around with it, and is followed by a large black dog. The story was used as the inspiration for the 2006 movie, ''[[Hantu Jeruk Purut]]''.<ref>{{cite news\n | last1 = \n | first1 = \n | year = \n | date=27 March 2010\n | title = Ghost tales underline Jakartan love for absurdities\n | work = The Jakarta Post\n | location = Jakarta\n | url = http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2010/03/27/ghost-tales-underline-jakartan-love-absurdities.html\n | accessdate=28 October 2011\n | ref = {{harvid|The Jakarta Post 2010, Ghost tales underline}}\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n |last1=Sembiring \n |first1=Dalih \n |last2=Siregar \n |first2=Lisa \n |date=14 August 2009 \n |title=Spirits In the Night: A Guide to Jakarta's Ghosts \n |work=The Jakarta Globe \n |location=Jakarta \n |url=http://jakartaglobe.id/archive/spirits-in-the-night-a-guide-to-jakartas-ghosts\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524155032/http://jakartaglobe.id/archive/spirits-in-the-night-a-guide-to-jakartas-ghosts\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=24 May 2018\n |accessdate=28 October 2011 \n |ref={{harvid|Sembiring and Siregar 2009, Spirits in the night}} \n}}</ref>\n*'''Kampung Gajah''': Opened in 2010, Kampung Gajah was once an amusement park in Lembang, West Bandung Regency until the company that once ran the amusement park filed bankruptcy. The park was permanently closed in 2018. After the closure of the park, many ghost hunters started to use the former site of the amusement park for ghost hunting. One of local YouTuber from West Bandung once visited the former site and reported some abnormal incidents like the camera suddenly goes off twice and drone problems.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liputan6.com/lifestyle/read/4111815/taman-rekreasi-kampung-gajah-berubah-jadi-wisata-horor|title=Taman Rekreasi Kampung Gajah Berubah Jadi Wisata Horor|publisher=}}</ref>\n*'''[[Lawang Sewu]]''': Literally meaning a \"thousand doors\" in Javanese, it is a former Dutch colonial building located in Semarang, in central Java. Many ghost sightings have been reported here, including a ghost of a Dutch lady as well as headless ghouls. During one of the ghost hunting television programs, a ghost was purportedly caught on camera.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bym4TXmuy-o |title=Dunia Lain Lawang Sewu}}</ref>\n*'''[[Parangtritis]]''': This popular tourist beach located in southern coast of [[Special Region of Yogyakarta|Yogyakarta]] contains legend regarding the foundation of the [[Mataram Sultanate]]. It was said that here [[Sutawijaya|Panembahan Senopati]], the founder of Mataram Sultanate made a spiritual pact with [[Nyai Roro Kidul]], the ruler of Java's southern sea for the well-being of Mataram. Every year, the ''Labuhan'' ceremony is held there and in neighboring Parangkusumo beach to commemorate the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wisatalicious.com/pantai-parangtritis-yogyakarta-keindahan-yang-berbalut-misteri/|title=Pantai Parangtritis Yogyakarta, Keindahan Yang Berbalut Misteri - Wisatalicious|website=wisatalicious.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.okezone.com/read/2014/03/16/510/956019/cerita-ratu-kidul-kesemsem-panembahan-senopati|title=Cerita Ratu Kidul|publisher=}}</ref>\n*'''[[Pelabuhan Ratu]]''': Legend says that [[Nyai Roro Kidul]] (Nyai is a [[Javanese language|Javanese]] and [[Sundanese language|Sundanese]] honorific for Madame), the Queen of the South Sea and daughter of King Prabu Siliwangi, is supposed to have committed suicide by jumping off the cliff into the sea. Rumors say that if someone wears green when swimming (the Queen's favourite color), he or she will be pulled by her ghost into the sea. Room 308 at the [[Samudra Beach Hotel]] is set aside for the Queen's ghost.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mikalina.com/Texts/pelabuhanratu_indonesia.htm |title=Pelabuhanratu (Indonesia) \u2013 A resort with a ghost |accessdate=20 December 2006 |last=Janssen |first=Peter |publisher=MysticAsia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061124200111/http://www.mikalina.com/Texts/pelabuhanratu_indonesia.htm |archivedate=24 November 2006  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://indahnesia.com/indonesia/JAWSAM/samudra_beach.php |title=Room No. 308 still retains its mystery |accessdate=20 December 2006 |last=Khouw |first=Ida Indawati |publisher=The Jakarta Post}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n*'''Saidah Tower''': An abandoned 30-storey building located in [[East Jakarta]] was once owned by [[Arab Indonesian]] wealthy family of same name. The building was abandoned in 2007 because of the building structure problems.<ref name=Merdeka1>[http://www.merdeka.com/peristiwa/bagaimana-nasib-menara-saidah-ke-depan.html Situs Merdeka.com: Bagaimana nasib Menara Saidah ke depan?]. Dipublikasikan 26 Mei 2012. Diakses 2 Juni 2013</ref> Many locals believed the former building was haunted since 2009.<ref>https://www.hipwee.com/travel/kisah-misteri-menara-saidah-bangunan-tinggi-yang-katanya-jadi-istananya-para-arwah/</ref>\n\n==Ireland==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:IMG KinnittyCastle0973.jpg|thumb|Kinnitty Castle]]\n[[File:Malahide Castle - magic door.JPG|thumb|Malahide Castle]]\n[[File:The Stewards House Killakee.jpg|thumb|Stewards House, Montpelier Hill]]\n*'''[[Charles Fort (Ireland)|Charles Fort]]''': Haunted by a 17th-century bride known as \"The White Lady of Kinsale\".<ref>{{cite web|author=JackMc |url=http://www.europeanghostsandhauntings.com/2011/12/white-lady-of-kinsale-charles-fort-near.html |title=White Lady of Kinsale - Charles Fort near Kinsale, Ireland |publisher=European Ghosts and Hauntings |date=3 December 2011 |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n*'''[[Charleville Castle]]''': This castle is haunted by the third [[Earl of Charleville]]'s younger daughter, Harriet. She lost her life after falling from the main staircase of this building at the age of eight, in April 1861.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghost-story.co.uk/index.php/most-haunted/191-charleville-castle-tullamore-ireland |title=Charleville Castle, Tullamore, Ireland |publisher=Ghost-story.co.uk |date= |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref> It was featured on ''[[Scariest Places on Earth]]'', ''[[Most Haunted]]'', and ''Ghost Hunters International''.\n*'''Drumbeg Manor''' in Inver, Donegal: Considered to be one of the most haunted places in all Europe. Apparitions and strange events are reported to have taken place within the manor, and on its grounds. Stories say that a screaming woman can be heard, as well as the appearance of a man in a white suit walking the halls.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.paranormaldatabase.com/ireland/cork.php?pageNum_paradata=2&totalRows_paradata=116 | title=Ghosts, Hauntings and Legends |accessdate=14 March 2012}}</ref>\n*'''[[Ducketts Grove]]''': The mansion was owned by the Duckett family for 300 years, and is said to be haunted by a [[Banshee|Banshee Ghost]]. On 17 March 2011, the [[SyFy]] show ''Destination Truth'' featured a four-hour live investigation for the season finale to find out the mystery of the ruins.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.syfy.com/destinationtruth/episodes/season/4.5/episode/409/destination_truth_live_event| title=Destination Truth: Duckett's Grove|accessdate=22 May 2012}}</ref>\n*'''[[Kilmainham Gaol]]''': This former prison has paranormal activities of lights which often turn themselves on and off in the prison's chapel, unseen forces pushing people over, apparitional footsteps, the feeling of being watched by spirits, as well as unexplained bangs and disembodied voices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hauntedrooms.co.uk/kilmainham-gaol |title=Kilmainham Gaol - Dublin, Ireland |publisher=HauntedRooms.co.uk |date= |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n*'''[[Kinnitty Castle]]''': This Gothic castle sits on a plot that once housed [[Druid]]s and [[Bards]]. It has witnessed a long and turbulent history, and is reportedly the home of many ghosts, the most popular of which is the Phantom Monk of [[Kinnitty]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hauntedrooms.co.uk/kinnitty-castle-hotel-co-offaly-ireland| title=Ghosts of Kinnitty Castle Hotel |accessdate=12 July 2012}}</ref> It was featured on ''Most Haunted''.\n*'''[[Malahide Castle]]''': This castle is haunted by Lord Galtrim, Sir Walter Hussey, the son of the Baron of Galtrim. Killed in battle on his wedding day during the 15th century, his apparition roams the castle at night, groaning in pain, while pointing at the spear wound in his side. There is also Lady Matilda \"Maud\" Plunkett. Her spirit appears to workers and guests as she did on the day of her marriage to the Lord Chief Justice. Maud would chase his spirit through the corridors. The third spirit is Puck, a jester who fell in love with [[Gear\u00f3id M\u00f3r FitzGerald, 8th Earl of Kildare|Gerard FitzGerald]]'s daughter, Lady Eleanor, who was detained at the castle by Henry VIII for inciting rebellions. One snowy night in December, Puck was found stabbed through the heart, still wearing his jester suit and cap. Before his death, he swore that he would haunt here until a master with a bride from the people ruled this castle. However, he promised not to harm any male Talbot who slept here. Numerous visitors have reported seeing the jester's face on some photos taken here. The White Lady is the fourth apparition here. The White Lady is a painting of a very beautiful, but unknown, lady which hangs on the castle's Great Wall. It is said that she would leave her painting at times and wander through the grounds at night. The fifth and final spirit is [[Miles Corbet]]. He was given this castle and the surrounding property by Oliver Cromwell. During the Restoration, Miles was made to pay for his crimes, and was hanged. It is reported that his apparition appears as a whole soldier in armour which then suddenly fall into pieces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.strangilla.com/the-haunted-castles-in-existence/|title=Haunted Weekends, Haunted Hotels & Haunted Castles|work=Haunted Rooms|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n*'''[[Montpelier Hill]]''': The Stewards House, or Killakee House, was built around 1765 by the Conolly family as a hunting lodge. The house has a reputation for being haunted. Stories tell of a particularly large ghostly [[black cat]]. The best documented account occurred between 1968 and 1970 when the ''[[Evening Herald]]'' and ''[[Evening Press]]'' newspapers carried a number of reports regarding a Mrs. Margaret O'Brien and her husband Nicholas, a retired [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na|Garda]] [[superintendent (police)|superintendent]], who were converting the house into an arts centre. During the conversion, tradesmen employed on the work site began complaining of ghosts. One night, a friend of the O'Briens, artist Tom McAssey, and two workmen were confronted by a spectral figure and a black cat with glowing red eyes. McAssey painted a portrait of the cat which hung in the house for several years afterwards. Although locals were skeptical of the reports, further apparitions were reported, most notably that of an Indian gentleman, and of two nuns called Blessed Margaret and Holy Mary who had taken part in black masses on Montpelier Hill. There were also reports of incorporeal ringing bells and [[poltergeist]] activity. In 1970, an [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]] television crew recorded a documentary about the house. In the documentary, a [[clairvoyant]] called Sheila St. Clair communicated with the spirits of the house through [[automatic writing]]. In 1971, a plumber working in the house discovered a grave with a skeleton of a small figure, most likely that of a child or, perhaps, the body of the dwarf alleged to have been sacrificed by the members of the Hell Fire Club. The house operated as a restaurant in the 1990s before closing in 2001; it is now a private residence.<ref>{{cite book |last=O'Farrell |first=Padraic |title=Irish Ghost Stories |year=2004 |publisher=Gill & Macmillan |location=Dublin |isbn=978-0-7171-3633-9 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Walsh |first=Dave |title=Haunted Dublin |year=2008 |publisher=Nonsuch Publishing |location=Dublin |isbn=978-1-84588-932-6 }}</ref><ref name=\"Walsh_21\">Walsh, p. 21.</ref>\n*'''[[Leap Castle]]''': Many people were imprisoned and executed in this castle, and it is supposedly haunted by several spirits.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.castles.org/castles/Europe/Western_Europe/Ireland/Leap/Leap.htm |title=The Reference of the Castle |accessdate=14 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505062516/http://www.castles.org/castles/Europe/Western_Europe/Ireland/Leap/Leap.htm |archivedate=5 May 2012  }}</ref> It was featured on ''Scariest Places on Earth'' and ''Most Haunted''.\n*'''Renyle House Hotel''' in [[Galway]]: Haunted by former anonymous remaining guests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hauntedrooms.co.uk/renyle-house-hotel|title=Haunted Weekends, Haunted Hotels & Haunted Castles|work=Haunted Rooms|accessdate=4 October 2014}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*'''[[Ross Castle]]''': Guests often wake at night hearing disembodied voices and doors banging and shutting on their own. An apparitional spirit who roams here is Richard Nugent's daughter, Sabina. Her lover, Orwin drowned himself. A second apparitional spirit who roams here is Orwin's father, Myles \"The Slasher\" O'Reilly. This Irish soldier spent his last night here before dying in a battle in 1644.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ross-castle.com/en/history/ghosts |title=Ross Castle B&B - Ghosts |publisher=Ross-castle.com |date= |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n*'''[[St. Michan's Church]]''': This church is haunted by disembodied whispering voices from mummies entombed in the [[burial vault (tomb)|vault]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Strickler |first=Lon |url=http://www.phantomsandmonsters.com/2010/01/haunted-earth-mummies-of-st-michans.html |title=Pulse of the Paranormal |publisher=Phantoms and Monsters |date=26 January 2010 |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n*'''[[Shelbourne Hotel]]''': This hotel is believed to be haunted by a seven-year-old girl from the 18th century, named Mary Masters, who had lived in the row of houses which once stood where the hotel is now. She died due to cholera during 1791. Her apparition roams the halls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hauntedrooms.co.uk/shelbourne-hotel-dublin-ireland |title=Shelbourne Hotel, Dublin, Ireland |publisher=HauntedRooms.co.uk |date= |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n*'''[[Wicklow Gaol]]''': a prison for over 200 years, it is claimed to be haunted by many former prisoners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ghostcatcherie.wordpress.com/2009/09/19/wicklow-gaol-the-gates-of-hell-september-2009-2/|title=Wicklow Gaol, \u2018The Gates of Hell\u2019, September 2009|date=19 September 2009|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Italy==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Colosseum]]''': Known also as the '''Flavian Amphitheatre''', was reported to be haunted according to some witnesses and researchers' testimonies. Visitors have described observing ghostly figures wandering the staircases. There have been reports of hearing the cheers and screams from a crowd while no sign of people in the particular section. The vaults were, reportedly, active by the spirits of [[gladiator]]s waiting to fight, [[actor]]s waiting to perform, and prisoners becoming prepared for execution. Several accounts of cold touches or pushes have been felt by both tourists and employees. Sounds of animals have also been heard within the vaults.<ref>{{cite web|last=J.Lynch |first=Gordon |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cFRsQu4LgHgC&pg=PA213&dq=Colosseum+haunted&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjCm_mWjI_OAhUB6iYKHcKDD6oQ6AEIIjAB#v=onepage&q=Colosseum%20haunted&f=false |title=Famous Ghosts and Haunted Places|publisher=Rosen Publishing Group Inc. |date=2012 |accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref>\n* The castle of '''Montebello''', in [[Montebello di Torriana]] (in the [[province of Rimini]]), is famous for the medieval legend that tells that an [[Albinism|albino]] (in the [[Middle Ages]], albino people were thought to be incarnations of [[Satan]]) girl nicknamed \"Azzurrina\" ([[Italian language|Italian]] feminine [[diminutive]] for \"azzurro\", \"light [[blue]]\", the colour of her eyes), born about in 1370 and mysteriously vanished on 21 June 1375 ([[solstice]] day), while her father, ''Signore'' (\"Lord\") of Montebello, was fighting in a battle. According to the legend, Azzurrina's ghost appears in the castle every five years from that day, on solstice day. The legend provided fame for the town of Montebello di Torriana and much tourism to the castle, especially on 21 June.\n*'''[[Poveglia]]''': This island, near Venice, was once a sanctuary to refugees during the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] [[Ottoman wars in Europe|conflicts]], and a hospice for sick patients throughout the centuries. It was detailed, from witnesses, haunted by many victims of the [[Bubonic plague|plague]].  In 1922, the island became home to a mental hospital, where a doctor, reportedly, experimented on patients with crude [[lobotomy|lobotomies]]. He later threw himself from the hospital tower after claiming he had been driven mad by the spirits of the island. The island has been featured on the paranormal shows ''[[Ghost Adventures]]'' and ''[[Scariest Places on Earth]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/italy/10767781/Worlds-most-haunted-island-up-for-auction.html|title = 'World's most haunted island' up for auction|last = Kington|first = Tom|date = 15 April 2014|work = |accessdate = 16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/24658/strange-geographies-happy-haunted-island-poveglia|title=Strange Geographies: The Happy, Haunted Island of Poveglia|work=Mental Floss}}</ref>\n*'''[[Teatro Massimo]]''' in [[Palermo]].{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n\n==Japan==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:Suicide Forest.jpg|thumb|Aokigahara in Yamanashi Prefecture]]\n*'''[[Hoichi the Earless|Amiidaji]]''' (Temple of [[Amitabha|Amida]]): In the [[Shimonoseki Strait]], it is the location of a legendary haunting. It is said that the blind [[Biwa h\u014dshi]] Hoichi, a resident of the temple, was visited every night by the ghost of a dead samurai, and made to play the biwa in the cemetery. When the priest of the temple learned this, he had the [[heart sutra]] painted on every part of Hoichi's body apart from his ears. When the samurai returned to take Hoichi to the cemetery, he could only see Hoichi's ears, so he took them instead, leaving Hoichi earless, resulting his nickname, \"Mimi-Nashi Hoichi\" ([[H\u014dichi the Earless]]). This legend was famously retold by [[Lafcadio Hearn]] in his book ''[[Kwaidan: Stories and Studies of Strange Things]]'', which was adapted as part of [[Masaki Kobayashi]]'s movie ''[[Kwaidan]]''.<ref>{{cite book |author=Professor Solomon |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=coxRQh_ONfIC&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=Hoichi+Dan-no-ura |title=Japan in a Nutshell}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/shi/kwaidan/kwai03.htm |title=The Story Of Mimi-Nashi-Hoichi |publisher=Sacred-texts.com |date= |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref>\n*'''[[Aokigahara]]''': The forest at the bottom of [[Mt. Fuji]] is a popular location for [[suicide]]. This results in a widespread belief that it is haunted. It was featured by an episode of ''Destination Truth'' on the SyFy Channel.<ref name=\"Iwasaka 1994\">Iwasaka, Michiko and [[Toelken, Barre]]. ''Ghosts and the Japanese: Cultural Experiences in Japanese Death Legends'', Utah State University Press, 1994. {{ISBN|0-87421-179-4}}.</ref>\n* '''Okiku's Well''': The well at [[Himeji Castle]] is often said to be haunted by the ghost of [[Banch\u014d Sarayashiki|Okiku]]. She is supposed to rise from the well at night and count to nine before shrieking and returning to the well.<ref name=\"Iwasaka 1994\"/>\n\n==Jordan==\n*'''[[Petra]]''': The residence of [[djinn]]s, supernatural beings in [[Islam]] according to the [[Bedouin]]'s saying.<ref>{{IMDb title|1603573|\"Destination Truth\" Ghost of Petra/The Lizard Man (TV Episode 2010)}}</ref>\n\n==Malaysia==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:Newlands-the-home-of-Agnes-Newton-Keith-Sabah-Borneo.JPG|thumb|right|[[Agnes Keith House]] in [[Sandakan]], [[Sabah]], Malaysia. Pictured in 2007.]]\n[[File:Kinarut Sabah TheKinarutMansion-06.jpg|thumb|right|[[Kinarut Mansion]] ruins as pictured in 2012.]]\n[[File:Highland Towers 2008.JPG|thumb|Remains of the Highland Towers during 2008.]]\n*'''[[Agnes Keith House]]''': A house built in the site of a former house for British colonial officials. Reportedly haunted with a female apparition based on the experience by the house former owners including a known American author named [[Agnes Newton Keith]]. The house has now turned into a museum in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hmetro.com.my/nuansa/2017/05/232562/kisah-misteri-penuh-sejarah|title=Kisah misteri penuh sejarah|trans-title=A mystery story full of history|author=Rodly Fadly|language=Malay|publisher=[[Harian Metro]]|date=26 May 2017|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thepatriots.asia/misteri-kisah-seram-rumah-agam-agnes-keith-sandakan/|title=Misteri Kisah Seram Rumah Agam Agnes Keith|trans-title=Mysteries of Agnes Keith House|author=Suhelmi A Majik|language=Malay|publisher=The Patriots|date=9 May 2019|accessdate=14 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190614110302/https://www.thepatriots.asia/misteri-kisah-seram-rumah-agam-agnes-keith-sandakan/|archivedate=14 June 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*'''[[Bukit Tunku]]''': Previously known as Kenny Hills, Bukit Tunku is a leafy area with British colonial houses. There's a report of a phantom motorcycle and a ghost of woman standing in the middle of the road. Local taxi drivers usually refuse to pick up women and children at night.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2013/11/24/haunted-by-the-supernatural/|title=Haunted by the supernatural|author=Hariati Azizan|publisher=The Star|date=24 November 2013|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"most haunted\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldofbuzz.com/9-of-the-most-haunted-places-in-malaysia/|title=9 Of The Most Haunted Places In Malaysia|publisher=World of Buzz|date=31 October 2015|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"most haunted MY\">{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.tv/my/features/we-dare-you-visit-10-most-haunted-places-in-malaysia/|title=These are the 10 most haunted places in Malaysia|author=Tshiung Han See|publisher=Stuff|date=17 October 2016|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Genting Highlands]]''': Some apartments like Amber Court and Ria Apartment are reportedly haunted as well as [[First World Hotel]], which 6,118 of its rooms are reportedly haunted due to gambling related suicides.<ref name=\"most haunted\"/><ref name=\"most haunted MY\"/>\n*'''[[Highland Towers collapse|Highland Towers]]''': After a tragedy that killed 48 residents, the remaining towers was reportedly haunted as claimed by the nearest residents who live not far from there.<ref name=\"most haunted\"/><ref name=\"most haunted MY\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2013/12/12/ghostly-town-in-many-ways-site-draws-fair-share-of-stories/|title=Highland Towers: Ghostly town in many ways|author=Shalini Ravindran|publisher=The Star|date=12 December 2013|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n*'''[[Kinarut Mansion]]''': A former German [[manor house]] in the [[Graeco-Roman]] style. Local population living near the area of the mansion ruins claimed the place is haunted with \"[[Hantu Tinggi]]\", a type of Malay ghost in the form of tall tree who usually disguised as a normal tree in the heavily forest area.<ref name=\"Kinarut Mansion haunted\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bharian.com.my/node/69724|title=Rumah 'hantu tinggi' bongkar sejarah industri getah Sabah|trans-title=House of 'tall ghost' unravel the history of the Sabah rubber industry|author=Suzianah Jiffar|language=Malay|publisher=[[Berita Harian]]|date=24 July 2015|accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref> Other passerby claimed to have seen a fast moving apparition and hearing the eerie voice of [[pontianak (folklore)|pontianak]], a Malay female ghost at night which were also supported by media crews who covering information about the mansion when they felt \"something\" was following them through their walk in the area.<ref name=\"Kinarut Mansion haunted\"/>\n*'''[[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]]''': The main international airport of [[Malaysia]] stands on former [[Elaeis|oil palm]] fields. Nighttime employees often see sightings and hear mysterious sounds. There are also reports of [[demonic possession|possession]] of airline staffs and airport securities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.thesundaily.my/node/429380|title=(Video) Horror at KLIA|publisher=The Sun|date=22 February 2017|accessdate=26 October 2018}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*'''Masjid Kampung Tedong''': A new [[masjid]] in Kampung Tedong, [[Melaka]], in May 2016, [[CCTV]] cameras can capture two wooden boards that can move itself similar to [[poltergeist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thairath.co.th/content/643182|script-title=th:\u0e42\u0e0b\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e25\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e19! \u0e04\u0e25\u0e34\u0e1b\u0e41\u0e1c\u0e07\u0e01\u0e31\u0e49\u0e19\u0e43\u0e19\u0e21\u0e31\u0e2a\u0e22\u0e34\u0e14\u0e21\u0e32\u0e40\u0e25\u0e40\u0e0b\u0e35\u0e22 \u0e40\u0e25\u0e37\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e44\u0e1b\u0e21\u0e32\u0e44\u0e14\u0e49\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e07|language=Thai|publisher=Thai Rath|date=21 June 2017|accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref>\n*'''Mimaland''': Located in [[Gombak]], [[Selangor]], Mimaland used to be a largest theme park in Malaysia until its closing in 1994 due to giant water slide incident that killed a Singaporean tourist. Locals often reported paranormal activities around the former site of the theme park.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/leisure/2016/12/09/mimaland-taman-tema-gah-kini-jadi-tempat-berhantu/|title=Mimaland, taman tema gah kini jadi tempat berhantu?|author=Nizha Periaswamy|language=Malay|publisher=Free Malaysia Today|date=9 December 2016|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/exclusive/2017/04/235211/memories-mimaland-abandoned-over-20-years-msias-first-theme-park-still|title=Memories of Mimaland: Abandoned for over 20 years, M'sia's first theme park still draws visitors \u2013 some, for all the wrong reasons|author=Fernando Fong|publisher=New Straits Times|date=30 April 2017|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref>\n*'''Tambun Inn''': Located in [[Ipoh]], it is one of the top tourist destinations in Malaysia, and is reported to be haunted by many ghostly apparitions. Some of these accounts mention lights turning on and off, sounds of whispers and eerie cries, as well as a report of the ghost of an old woman spotted within the vicinity of the inn.<ref name=\"most haunted MY\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.articlesphere.com/Article/Scary-Creatures-of-the-Night--Scariest-Hotels-in-the-World/165029|title=Scary Creatures of the Night: Scariest Hotels in the World|author=Joe Owens|publisher=Article Sphere|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Tawau Hills Park]]''': Located in the town of [[Tawau]] in [[Sabah]], this forest park is a popular tourist destination in Tawau. Home of the tallest tropical tree in the world, the yellow meranti (''shorea faguetiana''). People are not advised to go to the park at night, as the location is said (by the town residents) to be haunted.\n*'''Kuala Lumpur - Karak Highway ''': Located in Karak , This highway has some horror stories like example : Yellow Beetle sightings , A 'ghost' boy that finding his mother and anything else . However the mystery of this highway are still unsolved.\n\n==Mexico==\n{{Main|List of reportedly haunted locations in Mexico}}\n[[File:Metro Panteones Entrance.jpg|thumb|Entrance to [[Metro Panteones]].]]\nSeveral sites in Mexico are reputedly haunted, including the '''[[Palace of the Inquisition]]''' and the '''[[Plaza de las Tres Culturas]]''' in the City of Mexico, '''[[Hospicio Caba\u00f1as]]''' in Guadalajara, '''[[Mapim\u00ed Silent Zone]]''' in the state of Durango, '''[[Chautla Hacienda]]''' in [[Puebla]], and the ancient Mayan city of '''[[Chichen Itza]]''' on the Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Monaco==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n* A yacht once belonging to [[Errol Flynn]], the {{USS|Zaca|IX-73|6}}, is berthed here and is supposed to be haunted. Witnesses have reported seeing Errol Flynn's ghost pacing aboard. Others have described the sounds of voices and laughter as if a wild party were happening on board.<ref>Richard Winer and Nancy Osborn-Ishmael, (1980), More Haunted Houses, Bantam Books, pp. 69\u201372</ref>\n\n==Myanmar (formerly Burma)==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Keng Tung]]''': Kyaing Tong New Hotel was once a palace, it is now a reportedly haunted hotel.<ref name=\"Indochina\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indochinapioneer.com/4-check-in-points-to-drop-by-for-your-halloween-vacation-in-sea/|title=4 Check-in points to drop by for your Halloween vacation in Southeast Asia|publisher=Indochina Pioneer|date=3 October 2017|accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e07\u0e15\u0e38\u0e07-\u0e19\u0e04\u0e23\u0e41\u0e2b\u0e48\u0e07\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07|url=https://www.thairath.co.th/content/488032|work=[[Thairath]]|language=thai|date=21 March 2015|first=\u0e25\u0e21|last=\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e25\u0e35\u0e48\u0e22\u0e19\u0e17\u0e34\u0e28}}</ref>\n\n==Netherlands==\n{{unsourced|section|date=December 2018}}\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:Anne Frank House 02.JPG|thumb|200px|Anne Frank House]]\n[[File:Kasteel Waardenburg P1120541.jpg|thumb|Kasteel Waardenburg]]\n*'''[[Anne Frank House]]''', in [[Amsterdam]] is the former home of Anne Frank, the Dutch/Jewish girl who wrote the world-famous [[The Diary of a Young Girl]] the [[Second World War]]. In this war, Anne and her family had to hide from the Germans, they did that in the now called [[Anne Frank House]]. Which, back in World War 2, was her father's office. Anne, her sister, and her mother later died in concentration camps. People nowadays say that they feel cold spots in the house, have the feeling of being watched and the staff sometimes hear sounds coming from the secret annex. They{{who|date=December 2018}} say that if you stand outside of the house at midnight you can see a little girl hanging out of the window. Many{{who|date=December 2018}} say the girl is Anne.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} \n*'''[[Singraven]], or Singraven Manor''' is an estate in [[Overijssel]], a province in The Netherlands. In the sixteenth century, Singraven Manor became the residence of some Franciscan nuns for a short time. One of the nuns got bricked up alive, and after that, many strange things started to happen. After the new owner arrived he was unexplainably set on fire by an oil lamp. People{{who|date=December 2018}} say that the bricked up nun is still haunting the estate today.\n*'''[[Hoensbroek Castle]]''', is a castle in the province of [[Limburg (Netherlands)|Limburg]]. In this castle there is said to be a ghost called the blue lady. Her official name was Anna Catherina and she died on 5 November 1760. People say that she is looking for her 2 children who died at an early age. The children where supposedly buried inside the castle walls while she was not informed.\n*'''[[Kasteel Waardenburg]]''', or the Waardenburg castle is a castle in the province of [[Gelderland]]. This castle is said to be one of the most haunted places in The Netherlands. People feel like they are being watched, hear footsteps and whispers, see things move and feel cold spots. people say that in medieval times the wizard who lived in the castle made a pact with the devil, that he could do and get whatever he wanted for a period of seven years and after that he would be taken by the devil. Till this day there are 2 bloodstains that cannot be washed off on one of the castle walls.{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n*'''[[Blokhuispoort]]''', is an old building complex in the city of [[Leeuwarden]]. Blokhuispoort was originally built in 1499 as a citadel. Then it became a fortress, a court and execution place and from 1580 till 2007 it served as a prison. Nowadays it holds little businesses can hire workspace, a museum, a restaurant and the city's library. People have seen objects move on their own, shadow people, doors closing on their own and locked doors opening, voices, people being touched and footsteps.\n*'''[[Huissen#Haunted house|Binnenveld mansion]]''', is a [[rijksmonument]] located in [[Huissen]], in the province of [[Gelderland]]. The [[mansion]] is better known as the '[[haunted house]] of Huissen'. This building stood in the front area during the [[Battle of Arnhem]] (a major battle of [[World War II]]). According to locals, this house would be haunted.<ref>[https://www.gelderlander.nl/betuwe/spookhuis-huissen-op-wereldkaart~ad3a0724/ Spookhuis Huissen op wereldkaart]</ref><ref>[http://www.verhalenbank.nl/items/show/49977 Nederlandse verhalenbank]</ref>\n\n==New Zealand==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Larnach Castle]]''', on [[Otago Peninsula]], is said to be haunted by at least one, and possibly two ghosts: that of Kate, daughter of the mansion's original owner, [[William Larnach]]; and that of Larnach's first wife, Eliza.<ref>[http://www.nzghosts.co.nz/Otago1.htm Otago 1] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140405155418/http://www.nzghosts.co.nz/Otago1.htm |date=5 April 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internationalghostsandhauntings.com/2012/01/haunted-larnach-castle-dunedin-new.html|title=Haunted Larnach Castle - Dunedin, New Zealand|accessdate=4 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006093855/http://www.internationalghostsandhauntings.com/2012/01/haunted-larnach-castle-dunedin-new.html|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref><ref>\"[http://www.nzherald.co.nz/travel/news/article.cfm?c_id=7&objectid=10544960 Otago:Eerie episodes haunt Kiwi castle]\", ''New Zealand Herald''</ref>\n*The '''[[Vulcan Hotel (Saint Bathans)|Vulcan Hotel]]''', in [[Saint Bathans, New Zealand|Saint Bathans]], [[Otago]] is reputedly haunted by the ghost of a nineteenth century prostitute, \"The Rose\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/close-up/ghost-st-bathans-video-4499388|title=TVNZ - One News - The Ghost of St Bathans|work=TVNZ|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.nzghosts.co.nz/Otago1.htm New Zealand Ghosts - St Bathans] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140405155418/http://www.nzghosts.co.nz/Otago1.htm |date=5 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Norway==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n* '''Lier Sykehus''': An old insane asylum situated in [[Drammen]], Norway, where people claim to have seen ghosts, shadows and apparitions.<ref name=Klikk>{{cite web|title=The most haunted places|url=http://www.klikk.no/produkthjemmesider/vimenn/article399714.ece|publisher=Klikk.no|date=15 January 2009<!--|archiveurl=http://translate.google.com/translate?sl=auto&tl=en&js=n&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.klikk.no%2Fprodukthjemmesider%2Fvimenn%2Farticle399714.ece--> |accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Oman==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Bahla]]''': A town located in Oman. In neighboring Gulf countries and Oman itself, there are rumors of Bahla being home to [[jinn]]s, which are same as [[genies]] in English.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB3386FB348BF25&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Nl.newsbank.com |publisher=Nl.newsbank.com |date=26 June 1988 |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Pakistan==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:The Mohata Palace.jpg|thumb|[[Mohatta Palace]]]]\n* The '''[[Koh-i-Chiltan]]''' peak: This mountain in Balochistan is described, according to a local myth and the legend associated with it, as being haunted by the \"... spirits of forty babies.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/10974/pg10974.html |title=Chiltan Mount and a frugal pair |publisher=Gutenberg.org |date= |accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref>\n* The '''[[Mohatta Palace]]''' in [[Karachi]]: Said to be haunted by ghosts of the [[British Raj]] era. Museum guides have reportedly seen various objects which have moved from their original place, or shifted about while guards have claimed to have \"felt\" the presence of certain spirits during the night.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://karachi.metblogs.com/2006/06/29/a-bit-of-culture-in-a-piece-of-history/ |title=A bit of culture in a piece of history |publisher=Karachi Metblogs |date= |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jang.com.pk/thenews/jul2012-weekly/nos-22-07-2012/kol.htm|title=The mystery of Mohatta\u2019s secret tunnel|work=The News|date=22 July 2012|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Panama==\n*'''[[Coiba]]''': The largest island in the [[Central American]] region.  It used to be a prison for prisoners in the era of the dictator [[Manuel Noriega]] was a very scary place at night. Until a former stronger boxer, [[Roberto Dur\u00e1n]] said that he is not alone in the night.<ref>https://insidecostarica.com/2015/11/17/coiba-island-haunted-prison-paradise-central-americas-largest-island/</ref>\n\n==Peru==\n*'''[[Lima]]''': A paranormal event was recorded on security camera  in a co-working space in Lima,Peru.The place has been a notorious site for paranormal anomalies and has been haunted ever since. The location is close to an ancient temple, where human sacrifices occurred. Locals claim that this is the source of all haunted events. Multiple situations in which doors and servers move and unexplained sources of lights appeared during the night .\n\n==Philippines==\n{{Main|List of reportedly haunted locations in the Philippines}}\n[[File:Manila Cityhall.jpg|thumb|[[Manila City Hall]], one of the several locations in the country considered by believers to be haunted]]\nSeveral sites in the Philippine Islands are reportedly haunted, including the historic '''[[Fort Santiago]]''' in Manila, the abandoned '''[[Diplomat Hotel (Baguio)|Diplomat Hotel]]''' in the northern city of Baguio, and '''[[Silliman University]]''' in Dumaguete of the Visayan Islands.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Poland==\n* An [[:pl:Kosocicka_8|unfinished house at Kosocicka St]]. in [[Krak\u00f3w]].<ref>{{cite web|title=W tych miejscach a\u017c strach si\u0119 ba\u0107!|url=http://www.radiokrakow.pl/galerie/w-tych-miejscach-az-strach-sie-bac/2/|publisher=radiokrakow.pl|accessdate=14 April 2017|language=pl}}</ref> According to the story known by locals, the house was located on former cemetery ground. Construction started in the 1970s as an investment made by two brothers, but stopped after one of them killed the other in the house. After that the property was bought by another owner, who, for unknown reason, committed suicide in the house at night, at the 3rd floor. Locals claims that ghosts appear in the house.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Karolina Gawlik|title=Tajemnica nawiedzonego domu. \"Ofiar b\u0119dzie wi\u0119cej\"|url=http://krakow.onet.pl/nawiedzony-dom-na-ul-kosocickiej-w-krakowie/fvj98r|accessdate=14 April 2017|language=pl}}</ref>\n* Abandoned hospital in [[Olesno]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dragon|first1=Miros\u0142aw|title=W szpitalu w Ole\u015bnie straszy|url=http://www.nto.pl/wiadomosci/olesno/art/4088121,w-szpitalu-w-olesnie-straszy,id,t.html|publisher=Nowa Trybuna Opolska|language=pl}}</ref>\n* Haunted house in Jele\u0144 (part of [[Jaworzno]] city). Several families left this place, complaining of noises in the night and items thrown about by a [[poltergeist]]. The current owner offers adventure seekers an opportunity to stay in the house overnight (however, only groups of at least two people are accepted).<ref>{{cite web|author1=Anna Zielonka|title=Jaworzno: w domu w Jeleniu straszy. W\u0142a\u015bciciel otworzy\u0142 go dla chc\u0105cych prze\u017cy\u0107 przygod\u0119|url=http://www.dziennikzachodni.pl/wiadomosci/jaworzno/a/jaworzno-w-domu-w-jeleniu-straszy-wlasciciel-otworzyl-go-dla-chcacych-przezyc-przygode,11437458/|publisher=Dziennik Zachodni|accessdate=14 April 2017|page=pl}}</ref>\n\n==Portugal==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n* The '''[[Beau-S\u00e9jour Palace]]''', in [[Lisbon]], is said to be haunted by the Baron of Gl\u00f3ria, who lived in the palace during the 19th century. Employees working at the palace report moving and disappearing objects and windows opening and closing abruptly. Visitors to the gardens also report hearing the ringing of non-existent bells.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://umonline.uminho.pt/uploads/clipping/NOT_70313/4324873243248732.pdf |title=Por Que \u00c9 Que Acreditamos Em Fantasmas? |publisher=P\u00fablico |date=8 December 2012 |accessdate=3 September 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521200158/http://umonline.uminho.pt/uploads/clipping/NOT_70313/4324873243248732.pdf |archivedate=21 May 2014  }}</ref>\n* Visitors at the '''Bela Vista Hotel''', in [[Portim\u00e3o]], report hearing unexplainable wailings and bangs on the walls at night. The ghost of the previous owner of the hotel is said to haunt room 108, where she reportedly died.<ref name=\"ben\">{{Cite web|url=http://blog.benetton.com/portugal/2012/10/31/casas-assombradas-de-portugal/ |title=Casas Assombradas de Portugal |publisher=Benetton.com |date=31 October 2012 |accessdate=3 September 2013}}</ref>\n* The '''Castelinho de S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o do Estoril''', in [[Estoril]], is said to be haunted by the ghost of a little blind girl who accidentally fell to her death in a nearby cliff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consultoriodeastrologia.blogs.sapo.pt/1183691.html |title=Est\u00e1 algu\u00e9m a\u00ed? Guia de casas assombradas em Portugal! |publisher=Sapo.pt |date=26 October 2012 |accessdate=3 September 2013}}</ref>\n* The '''Quinta das Conchas''', in [[Lisbon]], is believed to be haunted by the ghost of a woman from [[S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe]] who's reported to have been kept in a cage for several years by Francisco Mantero Belard, the owner of the house in the early 20th century.<ref name=\"ben\"/>\n* The '''Quinta da Juncosa''', in [[Penafiel Municipality|Penafiel]], is said to be haunted by the Baron of Lages and his family. Suspecting that his wife was unfaithful to him, the baron reportedly tied her to one of his horse's legs and dragged her across the floor, killing her. After finding that she was innocent, he proceeded to kill his children and commit suicide. Locals have reported seeing the ghost of the baron several times over the years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://diariodigital.sapo.pt/news.asp?id_news=583100 |title=Vanessa Fidalgo ca\u00e7a os fantasmas de Portugal |publisher=Di\u00e1rio Digital |date=19 July 2012 |accessdate=3 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018232529/http://diariodigital.sapo.pt/news.asp?id_news=583100 |archive-date=18 October 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Romania==\n{{Main|List of reportedly haunted locations in Romania}}\n[[File:Anexa castelul Banffy.JPG|thumb|[[Bon\u021bida B\u00e1nffy Castle|B\u00e1nffy Castle]] in renovation]]\nSeveral sites in Romania are reputedly haunted, including historic '''[[Bon\u021bida B\u00e1nffy Castle|B\u00e1nffy Castle]]''' in [[Bon\u021bida]] and the '''[[Hoia Forest]]'''.\n{{clear right}}\n\n==Russia==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:Moscow Kremlin at night (7990921836).jpg|thumb|Moscow Kremlin]]\n*'''[[Moscow Kremlin]]''': Said to be haunted by the Soviet leaders Lenin and Stalin along with other historical figures.<ref><span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://www.unexplainable.net/ghost-paranormal/the-ghosts-of-the-soviet-union.php The Kremlin] </span> from Articlesphere.com</ref>\n{{clear right}}\n\n==Singapore==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''[[Bedok]]''': A planning area in the south-eastern coast of Singapore, which is famous for its paranormal activities. There are numerous reports of suicide or [[murder-suicide]] around the residential areas. The most famous paranormal activity in the area is the ghost of a woman and her 3-years-old kid. She allegedly died by jumping from the HDB, after throwing her kid.<ref>{{cite web|title=This Bedok ghost story based on real events will send chills down your spine|url=https://goodyfeed.com/this-bedok-ghost-story-based-on-real-events-will-send-chills-down-your-spine/|first=Low|last=Kay Hwa}}</ref> \n*'''[[Changi Hospital|Old Changi Hospital]]''': The vacated hospital compound was popular with movie-makers after the [[Singapore Land Authority]] commenced short term rental of the buildings and is often listed as one of Singapore's most haunted locations due to its history. A former British military hospital, its reputation as a haunted location likely stems from the [[Japanese occupation of Singapore|Japanese occupation]], when the ''[[Kempeitai]]'' used its premises as a prison camp and reportedly turned some of the rooms into a torture chamber.<ref>{{cite news|title=Places in Singapore with a dark past|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/places-in-singapore-with-a-dark-past|work=[[The Straits Times]]|date=10 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=4 Haunted Places In Singapore So Spooky That Even The Ghosts Also Scared \u2013 Part 1|url=https://discoversg.com/2016/03/28/haunted-places-singapore-part-1/|publisher=Discover SG|first=Youliang|last=Teo|date=28 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Saving A Sexier Island: Notes from an Old Singapore|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8qE9CgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=[[Marshall Cavendish]]|date=2015|first=Neil|last=Humphreys|author-link=Neil Humphreys}}</ref>\n*'''[[East Coast Park]]''': One night a couple was strolling around the area at night. It was at this tower where a group of thugs attacked them, knocking the boyfriend unconscious and killing the girlfriend after violating her. After this particular incident, there have been people claiming to have seen a female figure near the tower; while there have even been alleged screams of help resonating from the area.<ref>{{cite news|title=Haunted by unsolved murder of girlfriend 25 years ago|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/haunted-by-unsolved-murder-of-girlfriend-25-years-ago|work=[[The Straits Times]]|date=19 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"All Singapore Stuff - Real Singapore News 2014\">{{cite web | title=The Haunted Amber Beacon Tower at East Coast Park | website=All Singapore Stuff - Real Singapore News | date=10 June 2014 | url=https://www.allsingaporestuff.com/article/haunted-amber-beacon-tower-east-coast-park | access-date=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Pasir Ris Park]]''': One of the white sand beaches of Singapore. It is a place where it has been reported that a haunted place is a hotspot where women commit suicide. Nowadays, it is very popular among the ghost hunters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sea-globe.com/paranormal-ghosts-singapore-southeast-asia-globe/|title=Singapore\u2019s ghost hunters|work=Southeast Asia Globe|first= David|last= Hutt|date=9 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==South Africa==\n{{main|List of reportedly haunted locations in South Africa}}\nSeveral locations in South Africa are reputedly haunted, including the [[Erasmus Castle]] in Pretoria and the [[Grey High School]] in Port Elizabeth.\n\n==South Korea==\n*''' Gonjiam Psychiatric Hospital''': Famous for its very dark past among ghost hunters in [[Seoul]]. This abandoned hospital in [[Gwangju, Gyeonggi]] is claimed to be the most haunted place in Korea. The once psychiatric hospital is home to many rumors of ghosts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/gonjiam-psychiatric-hospital|title=Gonjiam Psychiatric Hospital|work=atlasobscura.com}}</ref>\n*'''Yeongdeok House''': An abandoned house on the hill of [[Yeongdeok County|Yeongdeok]] the seaside county, in the past used to be a [[Korean food|seafood restaurant]]. It is now a deserted house reputed as a haunted place. Believed to be the ghosts of teenage soldiers who died a number of Jangsa landing operation, a part of [[battle of Inchon]].<ref name=\"\u0e1c\u0e35\"/>\n*'''[[Korean Folk Village]]''': The most popular tourist attraction is located [[Yongin]], [[Gyeonggi province]] has been reported to have witnessed [[Gwisin]] a [[vengeful ghost]] in the [[Korean folklore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.traveller.com.au/tourists-terror-at-virgin-ghosts-25g9b|work=traveller.com|title=Tourists' terror at 'virgin ghosts'|date=6 September 2012|accessdate=25 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Spain==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n[[File:Palacio de Linares - 01.jpg|thumb|[[Palace of Linares]]]]\n*'''[[Palace of Linares]]''' in [[Madrid]]: Built between 1872 and 1890 for the Marquis of Linares Jos\u00e9 de Murga. According to legend this place is the most haunted in Spain. Supposedly, a little girl appears in the mansion, the Marquis fathered her with his sister and they murdered her in order to hide their incestuous relationship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.madridvillaycorte.es/palacio-linares.php |title=Palacio de Linares |last1=Diehl Busch |first1=Mar\u00eda Dolores |last2=Casta\u00f1eda Velazquez |first2=Rafael |date= |website=Madrid, Villa y Corte |publisher=Ma. Dolores Diehl Busch |accessdate= 24 December 2014|language=Spanish |trans-title=Palace of linares}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ikerjimenez.com/reportajes/palaciodelinares/ |title= Una noche en el Palacio de Linares |last1=V\u00e1zquez |first1=Santiago |date= |website=ikerjimenez.com |publisher=Iker J\u00edmenez |accessdate=24 December 2014|language=Spanish |trans-title=A night in the Palace of linares }}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Sweden==\n<!-- Note to editors: There is consensus that entries must cite external references or they will be removed. Entries should also be in alphabetical order. -->\n*'''Borgvattnets Pr\u00e4stg\u00e5rd''': The rectory of the small village of [[Borgvattnet]] in [[J\u00e4mtland]], northern [[Sweden]], where there have been reports of hauntings since the early 1920s. On December 2, 1947, [[Bishop]] Torsten Bohlin revealed plans to ''\"order a scientific investigation of the vicarage after several years of ghosts\"''. [[The Church of Sweden]] confirmed ghosts and the village of Borgvattnet immediately became world famous.  Today, the rectory is open to the public, and people can spend nights in the house for a small fee (which benefits the village).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.borgvattnet.eu|title=Borgvattnets Pr\u00e4stg\u00e5rd|website=www.borgvattnet.eu}}</ref>\n\n==Switzerland==\n* '''The house located in Junkerngasse no 54''' in [[Bern]] is said to be haunted. The origin of this belief is unknown. According to a story, around 12 and 1 am, the windows open and a headless woman appears, laughing in a creepy way. One Story tells that a woman dressed in black appears walking along the rooms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bernerzeitung.ch/region/bern/Zu-Besuch-im-Gespensterhaus-an-der-Junkerngasse/story/24871239|title=Bern: Zu Besuch im \"Gespensterhaus\" an der Junkerngasse -  News Region: Bern & Region - bernerzeitung.ch|work=bernerzeitung.ch/|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Taiwan==\n* '''Chiayi Min-Hsiung Haunted House:''' Located in [[Chiayi City]], it was once the residence of the Liu family. It is probably one of the most recognized haunted house in Taiwan.<ref name=\"ipeen.com.tw\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ipeen.com.tw/comment/165581|title=\u5609\u7fa9\u6c11\u96c4\u9b3c\u5c4b(\u5289\u5bb6\u53e4\u539d)---\u7df4\u5fc3\u81df\u4e4b\u65c5@Guinevere\uff0diPeen \u611b\u8a55\u7db2|website=iPeen \u611b\u8a55\u7db2|access-date=13 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Thailand==\n{{multiple image\n | align             = right\n | direction         = horizontal\n | background color  = \n | total_width       = 299\n | image1            = ThaiGovHouse 001.jpg\n | caption1          = \n | image2            = Wat Kudi Dao, Ayutthaya 0311.jpg\n | caption2          = \n | footer            = [[Government House of Thailand]] (''left'') and [[Wat Kudi Dao]], a part of [[Ayutthaya Historical Park]] (''right'').\n}}\n{{main|List of reportedly haunted locations in Thailand}}\n\nMany sites in Thailand are reputedly haunted, including [[Government House of Thailand]], [[Phitsanulok Mansion]], [[Lumphini Park]], [[Sathorn Unique Tower]] (Bangkok), [[Ayutthaya Historical Park]], and [[Mahidol University]] in central, or [[Ko Lipe|Lipe]] in southern etc.\n\n==United Arab Emirates==\n*'''[[Al Jazirah Al Hamra]]''': An abandoned fishing village near [[Ras al-Khaimah]] which is believed to be haunted by the presence of supernatural ''[[jinn]]s''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/national-day/our-guide-to-the-living-ghost-town-jazirat-al-hamra-ras-al-khaimah|title=Our guide to the living ghost town Jazirat Al Hamra, Ras Al Khaimah|work=The National|date=27 November 2014|accessdate=30 October 2015|first=Anna|last=Zacharias}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://khaleejtimes.com/wknd/editors-picks/Dubai-residents-recount-their-scariest-moments|title=Dubai residents recount their scariest moments|work=Khaleej Times|first=Rohit|last=Nair|date=30 October 2015|accessdate=30 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/xpress/dubai/news/revealed-uae-s-most-haunted-places-1.1609108 |title=Revealed: UAE\u2019s most \u2018haunted\u2019 places |work=Gulf News |date=28 October 2015 |accessdate=30 October 2015 |first=Abhishek |last=Sengupta |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151030065202/http://gulfnews.com/xpress/dubai/news/revealed-uae-s-most-haunted-places-1.1609108 |archivedate=30 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==United Kingdom==\n{{Main|Reportedly haunted locations in the United Kingdom}}\n{{multiple image\n | align             = right\n | direction         = horizontal\n | background color  = \n | total_width       = 299\n | image1            = Tower of London at night 3.jpg\n | caption1          = \n | image2            = Glamis Castle - geograph.org.uk - 916029.jpg\n | caption2          = \n | footer            = Tower of London (''left'') and Glamis Castle (''right'').\n}}\nMany sites in the UK are reputedly haunted, including the [[Tower of London]], [[50 Berkeley Square]] (London), [[Belgrave Hall]], [[Arundel Castle]], [[Speke Hall]], and [[Bruce Castle]] in England, and [[Ardrossan Castle]], [[Fyvie Castle]], [[Glamis Castle]], and [[Stirling Castle]] in Scotland.\n\n==United States==\n{{Main|List of reportedly haunted locations in the United States}}\n{{multiple image\n | align             = right\n | direction         = horizontal\n | background color  = \n | total_width       = 299\n | image1            = Octagon House (Washington, D.C.) in 2012.JPG\n | caption1          = \n | image2            = Winchester Mystery House (entrance).jpg\n | caption2          = \n | footer            = The Octagon in Washington, D.C. (''left''), and Winchester Mystery House in California (''right'').\n}}\nMany sites in the United States are reputedly haunted, including [[Dudleytown (Cornwall)|Dudleytown]] in Connecticut, the [[Cherry Hill (Albany, New York)|Cherry Hill Estate]] and [[112 Ocean Avenue|112 Ocean Avenue House]], (a.k.a. the Amityville Horror House) in New York, Williamsburg, Virginia also has many reportedly haunted areas, including old Colonial Williamsburg, as well as several domestic sightings in neighborhoods such as First Colony and Monticello Woods '''[[Cliveden (Benjamin Chew House)|Cliveden Manor]]''', the '''[[First Bank of the United States]]''', '''[[Fort Mifflin]]''', '''[[Library Company of Philadelphia|Library Hall]]''', '''[[Pennsylvania Hospital]]''', and '''[[Powel House]]''' in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], the [[The Octagon House (Washington, D.C.)|Octagon House]] (1801) and the [[White House]] in [[Washington, D.C.]],\nand '''[[El Adobe de Capistrano]]''' in California.\n{{clear right}}\n\n==Vietnam==\n*'''300 Kim M\u00e3''' in [[Hanoi]] is a building which was proposed to be the Bulgarian Embassy in Vietnam, but was abandoned for an unknown reason. After a murder near this building, the story of mysterious phenomenas including the ghost of a Western man is popularised across the nation. Now it is the property of [[Vietnamese government]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soha.vn/xa-hoi/ngoi-nha-ma-300-kim-ma-cham-den-tan-cung-bi-an-20150804091956978.htm|title=\"Ng\u00f4i nh\u00e0 ma\" 300 Kim M\u00e3: Ch\u1ea1m \u0111\u1ebfn t\u1eadn c\u00f9ng b\u00ed \u1ea9n|language=Vietnamese|publisher=Soha|date=12 August 2015|accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[C\u00f4n \u0110\u1ea3o]]''': The unfinished stone bridge in the deep jungle named \"Ma Thi\u00ean L\u00e3nh Bridge\" is called by the locals \"Ghost Bridge\", which is a bridge built by over [[C\u00f4n \u0110\u1ea3o Prison|300 prisoners]] who suffered a lot and died [[France\u2013Vietnam relations|under French control]]. One villager saw a long haired male ghost in a white shirt and black pants watch him while he was drinking with a friend, and then disappear. And a female villager said she saw a woman wearing a white dress standing on a bridge alone at the dawn. She knew instantly that it was a [[hungry ghost]]. One woman says she had come across a ghost of two boys without a shirt. They forced her to give them dessert.<ref name=\"\u0e1c\u0e35\">{{IMDb title|3253618|I Wouldn't Go in There}}</ref>\n*'''The Hui Mansion (now [[Ho Chi Minh City Museum of Fine Arts]])''': One of the most mysterious places in [[Ho Chi Minh City]], located at 97 Ph\u00f3 \u0110\u1ee9c Ch\u00ednh Street, [[District 1, Ho Chi Minh City|District 1]]. People believe that the mansion is haunted by the ghost of Mr. Hui Bon Hoa's [[leprosy]] daughter.<ref name=\"Indochina\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://saigoneer.com/saigon-culture/1922-saigon-urban-legends-the-ghost-of-the-fine-arts-museum|title=Saigon Urban Legends: The Ghost of the Fine Arts Museum|author=Dang Bui|publisher=Saigoneer|date=8 May 2014|accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Category see also|Reportedly haunted locations}}\n{{Commons category|Ghosts}}\n<!-- Note to editors: Entries should be in alphabetical order. -->\n*[[Ghost hunting]]\n*[[Haunted house]]\n*[[List of ghosts]]\n*[[List of ghost films]]\n*[[List of Ghost Adventures episodes|List of ''Ghost Adventures'' episodes]] (includes lists of reportedly haunted locations mostly in the United States that have been investigated)\n*[[List of Ghost Hunters episodes|List of ''Ghost Hunters'' episodes]] (includes lists of reportedly haunted locations in the United States that have been investigated)\n*[[List of Most Haunted episodes|List of ''Most Haunted'' episodes]] (includes lists of reportedly haunted locations in the United Kingdom and Ireland that have been investigated)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Ghosts|state=expanded}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haunted locations in the world}}\n[[Category:Lists of places]]\n[[Category:Reportedly haunted locations by country| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of reportedly haunted locations| ]]\n", "name_user": "Junkynixes", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChina", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_reportedly_haunted_locations"}
{"title_page": "Helene Weinstein", "text_new": "{{short description|New York State Assemblymember from Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name = Helene Weinstein\n| office = Member of the [[New York Assembly]] from the 41st District\n| term_start = January 3, 1981\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = Murray Weinstein\n| successor = \n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|09|06}}\n| birth_place = [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| alma_mater = [[American University]] (B.A.)<br>[[New England School of Law]] (J.D.)\n| website = [https://nyassembly.gov/mem/Helene-E-Weinstein/ Official website]\n| religion = [[Jewish]]\n}}\n\n'''Helene E. Weinstein''' (born September 6, 1952)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4AM8AQAAIAAJ&q=%22Helene+Weinstein%22+AND+%22born%22&dq=%22Helene+Weinstein%22+AND+%22born%22&hl=en&ei=JpnVTfboKsma0QH4y424Bw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAA]</ref> represents District 41 in the [[New York State Assembly]], which comprises [[Sheepshead Bay]], [[Flatlands, Brooklyn|Flatlands]], East Flatbush, [[Midwood]] and [[Canarsie]].\n\n==Biography==\nFirst elected in 1980, Weinstein currently chairs the Assembly's Ways and Means Committee and is a member of the standing committees on Aging, Codes, Rules . She previously chaired the Assembly Committee on Governmental Employees, Election law and Judiciary. And the Assembly Task Force on Women's Issues for seven years.\n\nWeinstein chairs the Assembly Standing Committee on Judiciary. She is the first woman in New York State's history to be appointed to this position. The Judiciary Committee presides over virtually all legislation affecting the state's judicial system, Family and Domestic Relations Law, Trusts and Estates, as well as civil practice in the courts. Weinstein has sponsored major reforms in the state's jury system and is the leading proponent of ensuring civil legal services for low-income New Yorkers. Weinstein led the successful effort to increase 18B and Law Guardian rates. Weinstein is also a member of the Court Facilities Capital Review Board.\n\nShe has been involved in the drafting and passage of several key pieces of legislation, especially with respect to family law. She is the sponsor of the Family Protection and Domestic Violence Intervention Act, as well as the Child Support Standards Act.\n\nWeinstein has previously served as an appointee of former Governor [[Mario Cuomo]] to the New York State Child Support Commission and the Governor's Commission on Domestic Violence.\n\nOver her political career since 1998, the two groups contributing the greatest amounts to her campaigns have been trial lawyers/lobbyists and public sector unions.<ref>http://www.followthemoney.org/database/uniquecandidate.phtml?uc=3772&so9=a&p9=1#sorttable9</ref>\n\nOn 14 March 2020, Weinstein tested positive for [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/14/assembly-members-charles-barron-helene-weinstein-have-coronavirus/amp/|title=Assembly members Charles Barron, Helene Weinstein have coronavirus|date=14 March 2020|website=nypost.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nWeinstein holds a B.A. in Economics from [[American University]] as well as a degree from the [[New England School of Law]].\n\n===Occupation===\nWeinstein is of counsel to her family's personal-injury law firm, Weinstein, Chase, Messinger & Peters, P.C.  She has been licensed to practice law in New York since 1977.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.brooklynaccidents.com/The_Firm/index.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=8 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303235336/http://www.brooklynaccidents.com/The_Firm/index.html |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://assembly.state.ny.us/mem/?ad=041 New York Assembly Member Website]\n*[http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/23094/helene-weinstein#.VP0DlmTF_pk: Key Votes from Project Vote Smart]\n*[https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F70A13FB3E590C7B8EDDAB0894DD404482&n=Top%2fNews%2fScience%2fTopics%2fDNA%20Deoxyribonucleic%20Acid Switch by a Former Supporter Shows Evolution of Death Law]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ny-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Murray Weinstein]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[New York State Assembly]]<br>41st District|years=1981\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{New York State Assembly}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weinstein, Helene}}\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Jewish American politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the New York State Assembly]]\n[[Category:Women state legislators in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:American University alumni]]\n[[Category:New England Law Boston alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name = Helene Weinstein\n| office = Member of the [[New York Assembly]] from the 41st District\n| term_start = January 3, 1981\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = Murray Weinstein\n| successor = \n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|09|06}}\n| birth_place = [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| alma_mater = [[American University]] (B.A.)<br>[[New England School of Law]] (J.D.)\n| website = [https://nyassembly.gov/mem/Helene-E-Weinstein/ Official website]\n| religion = [[Jewish]]\n}}\n\n'''Helene E. Weinstein''' (born September 6, 1952)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4AM8AQAAIAAJ&q=%22Helene+Weinstein%22+AND+%22born%22&dq=%22Helene+Weinstein%22+AND+%22born%22&hl=en&ei=JpnVTfboKsma0QH4y424Bw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAA]</ref> represents District 41 in the [[New York State Assembly]], which comprises [[Sheepshead Bay]], [[Flatlands, Brooklyn|Flatlands]], East Flatbush, [[Midwood]] and [[Canarsie]].\n\n==Biography==\nFirst elected in 1980, Weinstein currently chairs the Assembly's Ways and Means Committee and is a member of the standing committees on Aging, Codes, Rules . She previously chaired the Assembly Committee on Governmental Employees, Election law and Judiciary. And the Assembly Task Force on Women's Issues for seven years.\n\nWeinstein chairs the Assembly Standing Committee on Judiciary. She is the first woman in New York State's history to be appointed to this position. The Judiciary Committee presides over virtually all legislation affecting the state's judicial system, Family and Domestic Relations Law, Trusts and Estates, as well as civil practice in the courts. Weinstein has sponsored major reforms in the state's jury system and is the leading proponent of ensuring civil legal services for low-income New Yorkers. Weinstein led the successful effort to increase 18B and Law Guardian rates. Weinstein is also a member of the Court Facilities Capital Review Board.\n\nShe has been involved in the drafting and passage of several key pieces of legislation, especially with respect to family law. She is the sponsor of the Family Protection and Domestic Violence Intervention Act, as well as the Child Support Standards Act.\n\nWeinstein has previously served as an appointee of former Governor [[Mario Cuomo]] to the New York State Child Support Commission and the Governor's Commission on Domestic Violence.\n\nOver her political career since 1998, the two groups contributing the greatest amounts to her campaigns have been trial lawyers/lobbyists and public sector unions.<ref>http://www.followthemoney.org/database/uniquecandidate.phtml?uc=3772&so9=a&p9=1#sorttable9</ref>\n\nOn 14 March 2020, Weinstein tested positive for [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/14/assembly-members-charles-barron-helene-weinstein-have-coronavirus/amp/|title=Assembly members Charles Barron, Helene Weinstein have coronavirus|date=14 March 2020|website=nypost.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nWeinstein holds a B.A. in Economics from [[American University]] as well as a degree from the [[New England School of Law]].\n\n===Occupation===\nWeinstein is of counsel to her family's personal-injury law firm, Weinstein, Chase, Messinger & Peters, P.C.  She has been licensed to practice law in New York since 1977.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.brooklynaccidents.com/The_Firm/index.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=8 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303235336/http://www.brooklynaccidents.com/The_Firm/index.html |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://assembly.state.ny.us/mem/?ad=041 New York Assembly Member Website]\n*[http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/23094/helene-weinstein#.VP0DlmTF_pk: Key Votes from Project Vote Smart]\n*[https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F70A13FB3E590C7B8EDDAB0894DD404482&n=Top%2fNews%2fScience%2fTopics%2fDNA%20Deoxyribonucleic%20Acid Switch by a Former Supporter Shows Evolution of Death Law]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ny-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Murray Weinstein]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[New York State Assembly]]<br>41st District|years=1981\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{New York State Assembly}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weinstein, Helene}}\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Jewish American politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the New York State Assembly]]\n[[Category:Women state legislators in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:American University alumni]]\n[[Category:New England Law Boston alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Daniel Case", "label": "safe", "comment": "+{{short description}}", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helene_Weinstein"}
{"title_page": "2006 Highschool Football League", "text_new": "The '''2006''' season of '''[[Highschool Football League]]''' began on February 16, 2006 and ended on May 25, 2006. [[National Pei Men Senior High School|National Pei Men Senior High School football team]] of [[Tainan County]] became the first champion of the league.\n\n== League table ==\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=Q\n|sortable_table=y\n\n|team1=PMN|name_PMN=[[National Pei Men Senior High School|Pei Men]]\n|team2=SCH|name_SCH=[[National San Chung Senior High School|San Chung]]\n|team3=YIL|name_YIL=[[National Yilan Senior High School|Yilan]]\n|team4=HUA|name_HUA=[[National Hualien Senior High School|Hualien]]\n|team5=CCH|name_CCH=[[Chung Cheng Industrial Vocational High School|Chung Cheng]]\n|team6=HSF|name_HSF=[[National Hsin Feng Senior High School|Hsin Feng]]\n|team7=CSH|name_CSH=[[Chung Shan Industrial and Commercial School|Chung Shan]]\n|team8=TAI|name_TAI=[[Taibei High School|Taibei]]\n|win_PMN=8|draw_PMN=1|loss_PMN=1|gf_PMN=26|ga_PMN=7\n|win_SCH=6|draw_SCH=3|loss_SCH=1|gf_SCH=24|ga_SCH=14\n|win_YIL=6|draw_YIL=2|loss_YIL=2|gf_YIL=22|ga_YIL=8\n|win_HUA=4|draw_HUA=1|loss_HUA=5|gf_HUA=23|ga_HUA=18\n|win_CCH=4|draw_CCH=0|loss_CCH=6|gf_CCH=25|ga_CCH=38\n|win_HSF=3|draw_HSF=2|loss_HSF=5|gf_HSF=14|ga_HSF=15\n|win_CSH=1|draw_CSH=3|loss_CSH=6|gf_CSH=9|ga_CSH=24\n|win_TAI=1|draw_TAI=2|loss_TAI=7|gf_TAI=14|ga_TAI=33\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\n\n== Qualification ==\nThe top 4 teams of [[Chinese Taipei National Youth Cup]] 2005 season ([[National Yilan Senior High School|Yilan]], [[National Pei Men Senior High School|Pei Men]], [[National San Chung Senior High School|San Chung]], and [[National Hualien Senior High School|Hualien]]) were automatically granted to become the league members. The remaining 4 places were contested by [[Taipei County Ching Shui Senior High School|Ching Shui]], [[Chung Cheng Industrial Vocational High School|Chung Cheng]], [[Chung Shan Industrial and Commercial School|Chung Shan]], [[National Hsin Feng Senior High School|Hsin Feng]], [[National Hualien Vocational High School of Agriculture|Hualien Agriculture]], [[National Pingtung Senior High School|Pingtung]], and [[Taibei High School|Taibei]] though a qualification competition held on December 19 and 20, 2005.\n\nIn the qualification competition, the teams are placed in either group A or group B and play every team in their group once. The winner of each group qualifies for the 2006 season of the Highschool Football League while the second-placed team in each group plays the third-placed team in the other group in a playoff to determine the final two teams that qualify for the league.\n\n=== Group A ===\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=Q\n|show_positions=n\n\n|team1=HSF|name_HSF=[[National Hsin Feng Senior High School|Hsin Feng]]\n|team2=CSH|name_CSH=[[Chung Shan Industrial and Commercial School|Chung Shan]]\n|team3=CCH|name_CCH=[[Chung Cheng Industrial Vocational High School|Chung Cheng]]\n|win_HSF=1|draw_HSF=1|loss_HSF=0|gf_HSF=4|ga_HSF=3\n|win_CSH=0|draw_CSH=?|loss_CSH=?|gf_CSH=?|ga_CSH=?\n|win_CCH=?|draw_CCH=?|loss_CCH=?|gf_CCH=?|ga_CCH=?\n\n|col_A=#ccffcc|text_A=\n|result1=A\n|col_B=#ccccff|text_B=\n|result2=B|result3=B\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\n\n{{football box\n|date= December 19, 2005\n|team1= [[National Hsin Feng Senior High School|Hsin Feng]]\n|score= 1 - 1\n|team2= [[Chung Shan Industrial and Commercial School|Chung Shan]]\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=\n|report=[http://www.ctfa.com.tw/news.asp?category=A&news_id=429 (Report)]\n}}\n----\n{{football box\n|date= December 19, 2005\n|team1= [[Chung Cheng Industrial Vocational High School|Chung Cheng]]\n|score= ? - ?\n|team2= [[Chung Shan Industrial and Commercial School|Chung Shan]]\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=\n|report=\n}}\n----\n{{football box\n|date= December 19, 2005\n|team1= ''[[National Hsin Feng Senior High School|Hsin Feng]]''\n|score= 3 - 2\n|team2= [[Chung Cheng In