{"title_page": "Kevin O'Leary", "text_new": "{{about|the Canadian businessman|other uses|Kevin O'Leary (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Kevin O'Leary\n|image       = Kevin O'Leary 2012.jpg\n|caption     = O'Leary in 2012\n|birth_name  = Terence Thomas Kevin O'Leary<ref name=\"CHTBML\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=17mOVkAZV2sC&pg=PT25|title=Cold Hard Truth: On Business, Money & Life|first=Kevin|last=O'Leary|publisher=Doubleday|year=2011|isbn=9780385671750|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref>\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1954|7|9}}\n|birth_place = [[Montreal]], Quebec, Canada\n|citizenship = {{hlist|Canada|Ireland}}\n|alias       = Mr. Wonderful\n|residence   = {{hlist|Rosedale, Toronto|Boston, Massachusetts}}\n|known_for   = [[Reality television|Reality TV]] star,<br />[[CNBC]] and [[Business News Network|BNN]] contributor,<br />[[Investor|Venture capital investor]]\n|education   = [[University of Waterloo]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BSc]])<br />[[Ivey Business School|University of Western Ontario]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n|party       = [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative]]\n|spouse      = {{marriage|Linda O'Leary|1990}}\n|children    = 2\n|website     = {{official website|http://kevinoleary.com/}}\n}}\n{{Kevin O'Leary series}}\n\n'''Terence Thomas Kevin O'Leary''' (born 9 July 1954) is a Canadian businessman, author, politician,  and television personality.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kitconews/2012/05/09/kevin-olearys-cold-hard-truth-on-gold-investing|title=Kevin O'Leary's 'Cold, Hard, Truth' on Gold Investing|work=[[Forbes]]|date=9 May  2012|accessdate=31 July 2015|author=Daniela Cambone}}</ref> He co-founded O'Leary Funds and [[SoftKey]]. From 2004 to 2014, he appeared on various Canadian television shows, including the business news programmes ''SqueezePlay'' and ''[[The Lang and O'Leary Exchange]]'', as well as the [[reality television]] shows ''[[Dragons' Den (Canadian TV series)|Dragons' Den]]'' and ''[[Redemption Inc.]]''<ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themontrealeronline.com/2012/02/kevin-oleary|title=Kevin O'Leary \u2013 from Dragon's Den to Redemption Inc.|work=The Montrealer}}</ref> In 2008, he appeared on [[Discovery Channel]]'s ''[[Project Earth]]''. Since 2009, he has appeared on ''[[Shark Tank]]'', the American equivalent of ''[[Dragons' Den]]''.\n\nO'Leary co-founded [[SoftKey|SoftKey Software Products]], a technology company that sold software geared toward family education and entertainment. During the late 1980s and 1990s, SoftKey acquired rival companies such as Compton's New Media, [[The Learning Company]] and [[Br\u00f8derbund]]. SoftKey later changed its name to The Learning Company, and was acquired by [[Mattel]] in 1999, with the sale making O'Leary a multimillionaire.<ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web|url=http://archive.newswire.ca/en/story/169663/leading-canadian-entrepreneur-kevin-o-leary-named-to-genstar-strategic-advisory-board|title=Leading Canadian Entrepreneur Kevin O'Leary Named to Genstar Strategic Advisory Board|publisher=CNW|date=1 August 2007|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"plays one\"/> O'Leary was soon fired by Mattel after the acquisition resulted in significant losses and multiple shareholder lawsuits.<ref name=\"plays one\"/>\n\nIn 2017, he campaigned to be the leader of the [[Conservative Party of Canada]], drawing comparisons in the press to [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/25/opinions/meet-canadas-trump-kennedy-opinion/| title =Can Canada's Trump repeat the Donald's success?|date=25 January 2017|publisher=[[CNN.com]]|first=Sean|last=Kennedy}}</ref><ref name=\"fast track\"/><ref name=\"makes late entry\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/oleary-conservative-leadership-race-1.3940596|title=Kevin O'Leary makes late entry into Conservative leadership race|date=2017-01-18}}</ref> He was a frontrunner in the polls during much of that time, but dropped out in April 2017, one month before [[2017 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election|the election]], citing a lack of support in [[Quebec]].<ref name=\"dropping out\">{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/kevin-oleary-dropping-out-of-conservative-leadership-race|title=Kevin O\u2019Leary drops out of Conservative leadership race and will support rival Maxime Bernier|work=[[National Post]]|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nO'Leary was born in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada, one of two sons of Georgette (n\u00e9e Bukalam; 1919-2008), a small-business owner and investor of [[Lebanese Canadians|Lebanese]] descent, and Terry O'Leary, a salesman of [[Irish Canadians|Irish]] descent. Kevin's brother is Shane O'Leary.<ref name=\"CHTBML\"/><ref name=\"jasonmcbride\">{{cite web|url=http://torontolife.com/city/business/kevin-oleary|title=Operation O'Leary|author=Jason McBride|work=Toronto Life}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=17mOVkAZV2sC&pg=PT19|title=Cold Hard Truth: On Business, Money & Life|publisher=Doubleday|author=O'Leary, Kevin|year=2011}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">Allemang, John. [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/small-business/kevin-oleary-the-shark-who-swims-alone/article2178538 \"Kevin O'Leary: The shark who swims alone\"], ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', 23 September 2011.</ref><ref>Schlesinger, Joel. [http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/opinion/columnists/the-dragons-pen-130900253.html \"The dragon's pen: Reality TV villain writes about life and money in new autobiography\"], ''Winnipeg FreePress'', 1 October 2011.</ref> Due to his paternal heritage, O'Leary also holds Irish citizenship and carries an Irish passport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/kevin-oleary-leadership-campaign-1.3967543|title=O'Leary spent almost all of the 1st week of his campaign in the U.S.|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary's parents divorced when he was a child, largely due to his father's alcoholism.<ref name=\"CHTBML\"/> His father died shortly thereafter. After his father's death, his mother ran the business as an executive.<ref name=\"The Montrealer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themontrealeronline.com/2012/02/kevin-oleary|title=Kevin O'Leary \u2013 from Dragon's Den to Redemption Inc.|work=The Montrealer|date=1 February 2012 |accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref> His mother later married an economist, George Kanawaty,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/ottawacitizen/obituary.aspx?n=georgette-kanawaty&pid=115674218|title=Georgette Kanawaty's Obituary on Ottawa Citizen|website=Ottawa Citizen}}</ref> who worked with the UN's [[International Labour Organization]].<ref name=\"auto4\"/><ref name=\"janemacdougall\">{{cite web|url=http://www.macleans.ca/culture/the-other-kevin-oleary|title=Dragons' Den star Kevin O'Leary has another passion\u2014photography|author=Jane MacDougall|work=Maclean's}}</ref> His stepfather's international assignments caused the family to move frequently, and O'Leary lived in many places while growing up, including [[Cambodia]], [[Tunisia]], and [[Cyprus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abc.go.com/shows/shark-tank/episode-guide/season-06/619-week-19-luminaid-taaluma-totes-keen-home-scholly|title=Shark Tank : Week 19: LuminAID, Taaluma Totes, Keen Home, Scholly - Season 6 Episode 19 Recap |publisher=ABC}}</ref> O'Leary attended [[Stanstead College]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/breakaway/2011/10/13/kevin-oleary-on-business-and-his-townships-past|title=Breakaway - Kevin O'Leary and his Townships past|date=3 September 2014|publisher=cbc.ca}}</ref> and [[St. George's School of Montreal|St. George's School]], both in Quebec.<ref name=\"auto7\"/>\n\nO'Leary's mother was a skilled investor, investing a third of her weekly paycheque in large-cap, dividend-paying stocks and interest-bearing bonds, ultimately achieving high returns in her investment portfolio.  She kept her investment portfolio secret, so O'Leary only discovered his mother's skill as an investor after her death, when her will was executed.<ref name=\"auto1\" /> Many of his investment lessons came from his mother, including the admonition to save one-third of his money.<ref name=\"auto7\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"uwo.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ivey.uwo.ca/advisoryboard/membership/t-kevin-oleary/|title=T. Kevin O'Leary|publisher=uwo.ca|access-date=9 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710030844/http://www.ivey.uwo.ca/advisoryboard/membership/t-kevin-oleary/|archive-date=10 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/funds-and-etfs/funds/the-kevin-oleary-machine/article4085244/|title=The Kevin O'Leary machine|work=The Globe and Mail |location=Toronto|date=6 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n\ntoby'Leary had aspired to become a photographer, but on the advice of his stepfather attended university,<ref name=\"janemacdougall\"/> where he continued to develop his interest in business and investing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/kevin-olearys-best-advice-from-his-20s-2015-7?r=UK&IR=T|title=Kevin O'Leary's best advice from his 20s |date=28 July 2015|work=Business Insider}}</ref> He received an honours bachelor's degree in [[environmental studies]] and psychology from the [[University of Waterloo]] in 1977<ref>O'Leary, Kevin. (2012) ''Cold Hard Truth on Men, Women & Money''. [[Doubleday Canada]], page 106</ref><ref name=\"auto9\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=8607880&privcapId=33072202 |title=Kevin T. O'Leary |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ivey.uwo.ca/advisoryboard/membership/t-kevin-oleary/ |title=T. Kevin O'Leary |publisher=Ivey Business School, University of Western Ontario |accessdate=8 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710030844/http://www.ivey.uwo.ca/advisoryboard/membership/t-kevin-oleary/ |archive-date=10 July 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and an MBA in entrepreneurship from the [[Ivey Business School]] at the [[University of Western Ontario]] in 1980.<ref name=\"auto9\"/><ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n\n==Business career==\nIn 1979, between the first and second years of his MBA program, O'Leary was selected for an internship at [[Nabisco]] in downtown Toronto, and then worked as an assistant brand manager for Nabisco's cat food brand.<ref name=\"uwo.ca\"/><ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/kevin-oleary/be-like-a-magpie_b_7097052.html|title=Be Like a Magpie|work=[[The Huffington Post]] | date=19 April 2015}}</ref> O'Leary credits his later success at The Learning Company to the skills he developed in marketing during his days at Nabisco.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://strategyonline.ca/1992/11/16/6696-19921116/ |title=The secret of Softkey's success |publisher=Strategy Online |date=16 November 1992 |accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter leaving Nabisco, O'Leary began a brief career as a television producer. With two of his former MBA classmates, Scott Mackenzie and Dave Toms (both of whom had assisted on O'Leary's MBA documentary), O'Leary co-founded Special Event Television (SET).<ref name=\"The Montrealer\" /><ref name=\"Toronto Life\">{{cite web|url=http://www.torontolife.com/informer/people/2014/09/26/kevin-oleary-dragons-den-q-and-a/|title=Kevin O'Leary on leaving the CBC, learning from Don Cherry, and befriending Dragons|work=Toronto Life|access-date=31 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150804182911/http://www.torontolife.com/informer/people/2014/09/26/kevin-oleary-dragons-den-q-and-a/|archive-date=4 August 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Ellen Ashton-Haiste\">{{cite web |url=http://foreveryoungnews.com/posts/2286-the-real-kevin-o-leary |title=The Real Kevin O'Leary |publisher=Forever Young Information |date=24 August 2013 |accessdate=31 July 2015 |author=Ellen Ashton-Haiste}}</ref> SET was an independent television production company that produced original sports programming such as ''The Original Six'', ''Don Cherry's Grapevine'' and ''Bobby Orr and the Hockey Legends''. The company achieved limited success with minor television shows, soccer films, sports documentaries, and short in-between-period commercials for local professional hockey games.<ref name=\"plays one\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/rob-magazine/kevin-oleary-hes-not-a-billionaire-he-just-plays-one-on-tv/article4564334/?page=all|title=Kevin O'Leary: He's not a billionaire, he just plays one on TV|work=The Globe and Mail |location=Toronto|date=28 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"uwo.ca\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctv.ca/SharkTank/Articles/News/Kevin_OLeary_Shark_Tank.aspx|title=Shark Tank - Latest News - From cameraman to Mr. Wonderful: Kevin O'Leary on where he started and what's coming up on 'Shark Tank'|publisher=CTV.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,1921635,00.html|title=Kevin O'Leary, TV's 'Shark Tank' Guru: In Real Life, No Business Whiz |date=10 September 2009|work=Time}}</ref><ref name=\"steveburgess\">{{cite web|url=http://nuvomagazine.com/magazine/autumn-2010/kevin-oleary|title=Kevin O'Leary|author=Steve Burgess|work=NUVO Magazine}}</ref> One of his partners later bought out his share of the venture for $25,000.<ref name=\"auto7\"/><ref name=\"Ellen Ashton-Haiste\"/>\n\n=== Softkey ===\nAfter selling his share of SET, O'Leary started Softkey in a Toronto basement in 1986, along with business partners John Freeman and Gary Babcock.<ref name=\"steveburgess\" /> The company was a publisher and distributor of CD-ROM-based personal computer software for Windows and Macintosh computers. A major financial backer who had committed $250,000 in development capital to the company backed out the day before signing the documents and delivering his cheque, which left O'Leary looking for funding to support the fledgling business. He used the proceeds from the sale of his share of SET and convinced his mother to lend him $10,000 in seed capital to establish SoftKey Software Products.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-best-money-kevin-oleary-ever-spent-2015-4|title='Shark Tank' investor Kevin O'Leary explains how a $10,000 loan from his mother helped him build a $4 billion company|publisher=businessinsider.com|date=17 April 2015|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe software and personal-computer industries were growing rapidly in the early 1980s, and O'Leary convinced printer manufacturers to bundle Softkey's program with their hardware. With distribution assured, the company developed a number of educational software products focused on mathematics and reading education. Softkey products typically consisted of software intended for home users, especially [[shovelware|compilation discs]] containing various [[freeware]] or [[shareware]] games packaged in \"jewel-case\" CD-ROMs.<ref name=\"plays one\"/><ref name=\"auto6\" />\n\nSoftkey weathered stiff competition from other software companies in the late 1980s and prospered throughout the 1990s. By 1993, Softkey had become a major consolidator in the educational software market, acquiring rivals such as [[WordStar]] and [[Spinnaker Software]].<ref name=\"willett19930524\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PTsEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA31&dq=softkey%20worstar&pg=PA31#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Merger is first step to a consumer orientation for WordStar | accessdate=6 March 2011 | author=Willett, Shawn | date=1993-05-24 | publisher=InfoWorld | page=31}}</ref><ref name=\"ieeetimeline\">{{cite web | url=http://www.computer.org/portal/web/computingnow/annals/extras/wordvol28n4 | title=Word Processing Timeline | accessdate=6 March 2011 | author=Bergin, Thomas J. | date=Oct\u2013Dec 2006 | publisher=IEEE Annals of the History of Computing}}</ref> In 1995, Softkey acquired [[The Learning Company]] (TLC) for $606 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/08/business/softkey-reaches-agreement-to-buy-learning-company.html|title=Softkey Reaches Agreement to Buy Learning Company|publisher=nytimes.com|date=8 December 1995|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref> adopting its name, and moved its headquarters to [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts]].\n\nTLC lost $105 million (US) in 1998 on revenues $800 million and suffered losses over the previous two years.<ref name=\"joecastaldo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.canadianbusiness.com/business-strategy/kevin-oleary-the-natural/|title=Kevin O'Leary: The natural |author=Joe Castaldo|work=Canadian Business}}</ref> TLC bought its former rival [[Br\u00f8derbund]] in June 1998 for $416 million.\n\nIn 1999, TLC was acquired by [[Mattel]] for US$4.2 billion.<ref name=\"steveburgess\" /> Sales and earnings for Mattel soon dropped, and O'Leary departed Mattel. The purchase by Mattel was later called one of the most disastrous acquisitions in recent history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/4467013/Mattel-sale-ends-3.6bn-fiasco.html|title=Mattel sale ends $3.6bn fiasco|last=Cave|first=Andrew|date=|work=|newspaper=[[Telegraph.co.uk]]|language=en|access-date=2017-01-20|via=}}</ref> Following the acquisition, Mattel experienced a US$105 million loss where management had projected a $50 million profit. Mattel's stock dropped, wiping out US$3 billion of shareholder value in a single day. Mattel's shareholders later filed a class-action lawsuit accusing Mattel executives, O'Leary, and former TLC CEO Michael Perik of misleading investors about the health of TLC and the benefits of its acquisition. The lawsuit alleged that TLC used accounting tricks to hide losses and inflate quarterly revenues. O'Leary and his defendants disputed all of the charges. Mattel paid $122 million to settle the lawsuit in 2003. O'Leary blamed the technology meltdown and a culture clash of management of the two companies for the failure of the acquisition.<ref name=\"joecastaldo\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,1921635,00.html|title=TV's Shark Tank Guru: In Real Life, No Business Whiz|last=Gandel|first=Stephen|date=2009-09-10|newspaper=Time|issn=0040-781X|access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary and backers from Citigroup made an unsuccessful attempt to acquire the video game company [[Atari]], and O'Leary made plans to start a video-gaming television channel that never came to fruition.<ref name=\"plays one\" />\n\n=== StorageNow Holdings ===\nIn 2003, O'Leary became a co-investor and director at StorageNow Holdings, a Canadian developer of climate-controlled storage facilities, a company controlled by Reza Satchu and Asif Satchu.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/reza-satchu-38/article18450222/|title=Reza Satchu, 38|first=Allison|last=Dunfield|publisher=The Globe and Mail|date=2008-05-05|accessdate=2019-11-25}}</ref> StorageNow became the operator of storage services in Canada, with facilities in 11 cities, and was acquired by in Storage REIT in March 2007 for $110 million.<ref name=\"plays one\"/> He sold his shares, originally worth $500,000, for more than $4.5 million.<ref name=\"plays one\"/>\n\nIn May 2005, Reza Satchu and O'Leary's operating partner, Wheeler, filed a $10-million wrongful-dismissal lawsuit, charging that they had altered an agreed-upon compensation deal and illegally reduced Wheeler's share of the profits.<ref name=\"plays one\"/> O'Leary and Satchu claimed Wheeler failed to reach performance targets.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.canadianbusiness.com/blogs-and-comment/kevin-oleary-conservative-leadership-bid-business-record|title=A history of Kevin O'Leary's spotty business record, in four deals|date=19 January 2017|work=|newspaper=Canadian Business|language=en-US|access-date=17 October 2017}}</ref> The case was settled out of court.<ref name=\"plays one\" />\n\n===Other projects===\nIn March 2007, O'Leary joined the advisory board of [[Genstar Capital]], a [[private equity]] firm that focuses on investing in healthcare services, industrial technology, business services and software. Genstar Capital appointed O'Leary to its Strategic Advisory Board to seek new investment opportunities for its $1.2 billion fund.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/leading-canadian-entrepreneur-kevin-oleary-named-to-genstar-strategic-advisory-board-57750162.html|title=Leading Canadian Entrepreneur Kevin O'Leary Named to Genstar Strategic Advisory Board|date=1 August 2007|publisher=PNR|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n====O'Leary Funds====\nIn 2008, O'Leary co-founded O'Leary Funds Inc., a mutual fund company focused on global yield investing. He is the company's chairman and lead investor, while his brother Shane O'Leary serves as the director. The fund's assets under management grew from $400 million in 2011 to $1.2-billion in 2012.<ref name=\"Oysey, Dan\">{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/executive/leadership/partnering-with-fame?__lsa=01f5-6de0|title=Kevin O'Leary and Connor O'Brien use celebrity branding to take on Canada's fund managers|publisher=Financial Post|date=1 May 2012|accessdate=19 January 2016|author=Oysey, Dan}}</ref> The fund's primary manager was Stanton Asset Management, a firm controlled by the husband-and-wife team of [[Connor O'Brien (alpine skier)|Connor O'Brien and Louise Ann Poirier]].<ref name=\"auto6\"/>\n\nAccording to research by [[Mark R. McQueen]], the fund increased distribution yield from his funds by returning invested capital to shareholders.  While this is not unusual, it was contrary to O'Leary's statements.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://business.financialpost.com/news/kevin-olearys-business-history-back-in-spotlight-after-entering-race-for-conservative-party-leader|title=Kevin O'Leary's business history back in spotlight after entering race for Conservative Party leader|newspaper=Financial Post|language=en|access-date=17 October 2017}}</ref> Another analysis also found that one quarter of the distributions from one of O'Leary's funds were return of capital.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nIn November 2014, O'Leary Funds Management agreed to pay penalties to the [[Autorit\u00e9 des march\u00e9s financiers (Qu\u00e9bec)|Autorit\u00e9 des march\u00e9s financiers]] for violating certain technical provisions of the Securities Act. At the time of the agreement, O'Leary Funds reported that it had taken steps to correct the violations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lautorite.qc.ca/en/news-2014-conso.html_2014_gestion-de-fonds-o-leary-to-pay-38-000-in-administrative-penalties04-11-2014-00-0.html|title=Gestion de fonds O'Leary to pay $38,000 in administrative penalties|website=lautorite.qc.ca|access-date=6 September 2016}}</ref> On 15 October 2015, O'Leary Funds was sold to Canoe Financial, a private investment-management company owned by Canadian businessman [[W. Brett Wilson]], who once was an investor with O'Leary on CBC's ''Dragons' Den.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bnn.ca/News/2015/10/15/Canoe-Financial-buys-OLeary-Funds-investment-assets.aspx|title=Dragons reunite as Canoe picks up Kevin O'Leary's fund shop|date=15 October 2015|publisher=Business News Network|accessdate=15 January 2016|author=Cain, Terry}}</ref>\n\n====O'Leary Ventures====\nO'Leary founded O'Leary Ventures, a private early-stage venture capital investment company,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://olearyventures.com/|title=About O'Leary Ventures|publisher=O'Leary Ventures|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> O'Leary Mortgages, O'Leary books, and O'Leary Fine Wines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vinelandwineshop.com/categories.php?category=O'Leary-Wines|title=O'Leary Wines|accessdate=25 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029213504/http://www.vinelandwineshop.com/categories.php?category=O%27Leary-Wines|archive-date=29 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwire.com/press-release/oleary-fine-wines-wins-best-value-at-intervin-international-wine-awards-1708921.htm|title=O'Leary Fine Wines Wins \"Best Value\" at InterVin International Wine Awards|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> In April 2014, O'Leary Mortgages closed.<ref>McLister, Rob. [http://www.canadianmortgagetrends.com/canadian_mortgage_trends/2014/04/oleary-mortgages-is-no-more.html \"O'Leary Mortgages Is No More\"]. CanadianMortgageTrends.com. 10 April 2014 {{unreliable?|date=October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== ETF and investing ====\nOn 14 July 2015, O'Leary launched an [[Exchange-traded fund|ETF]] through O'Shares Investments, a division of his investment fund, O'Leary Funds Management LP, where O'Leary serves as chairman. A [[value investor]], he has given advice on [[personal finance]].<ref name=\"Smith\">{{cite news|url=http://www.fool.ca/2016/04/28/steal-these-4-investing-tips-from-kevin-oleary/|title=Steal These 4 Investing Tips from Kevin O'Leary|date=28 April 2016|work=Motley Fool|author=Nelson Smith}}</ref> He advocates [[Diversification (finance)|portfolio diversification]] and suggests that investors have their age as the percentage of [[Bond (finance)|bonds]] in their portfolios (i.e., 30% in bonds and 70% in stocks for a 30-year old investor, with an increasing proportion of bonds and decreasing proportion of stocks as the investor ages).<ref name=\"Smith\"/> O'Leary has also \"stated on many occasions that he won\u2019t invest in a publicly traded stock unless it pays him a [[dividend]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fool.ca/2016/04/13/collect-1000-per-month-by-investing-like-kevin-oleary/|title=Collect $1,000 per month by investing like Kevin O'Leary|date=16 April 2016|author=Smith, Nelson}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary also ventured into [[gold as an investment|gold investing]], with five percent of his financial portfolio invested in physical gold. However, he does not invest in stocks of gold-mining companies because he says [[cash flow]] is an important investment factor to him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kitconews/2012/05/09/kevin-olearys-cold-hard-truth-on-gold-investing/1/|title=Kevin O'Leary's 'Cold, Hard, Truth' on Gold Investing|date=5 November 2012|work=Forbes|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontariofarmer.com/sitepages/?aid=3544&cn=TO%20SUBSCRIBE%20TO%20ONTARIO%20FARMER&an=Three%20investment%20tips%20from%20a%20dragon|title=Three investment tips from a dragon|publisher=Ontario Farmer|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://spikedfinance.com/kevin-oleary-on-dividend-investing|title=Kevin O'Leary on Dividend Investing|date=3 May 2014|publisher=Spiked Finance|accessdate=9 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110081342/http://spikedfinance.com/kevin-oleary-on-dividend-investing/|archive-date=10 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> O'Leary also advises diversification in multiple industry sectors so that no more than 20% of one's financial portfolio is held in one sector.<ref>{{cite book|title=Cold Hard Truth on Men, Women, and Money|publisher=[[Simon and Schuster]]|author=O'Leary, Kevin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bnn.ca/News/2015/12/18/OLeary-tells-a-young-investor-how-to-turn-10000-in-a-nest-egg.aspx|title=Kevin O'Leary tells a young investor how to turn $10,000 in a nest egg|date=18 December 2015|publisher=BNN|accessdate=15 January 2016|author=Padanyi, Matt}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nIn September 2011, O'Leary released his first book, ''Cold Hard Truth: On Business, Money & Life'', in which he shares his views on entrepreneurship, business, finance, money and life.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/small-business/sb-growth/success-stories/kevin-oleary-the-shark-who-swims-alone/article595744|title=Kevin O'Leary: The shark who swims alone|work=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=6 August 2012|location=Toronto}}</ref> A sequel, ''The Cold Hard Truth on Men, Women, and Money: 50 Common Money Mistakes and How to Fix Them'', was published in 2012. It focused on [[financial literacy]] and financial education as a foundation for achieving wealth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kevinoleary.com/books|title=Order your copy of Cold Hard Truth on Men, Women & Money|publisher=[[Doubleday Canada]]|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> O'Leary released a followup in 2013 in which he covers subjects relating to important life choices: education, careers, marriage and family, and retirement. He discusses the obstacles of raising a family while working to provide financial security for them and gives advice for developing financial literacy in family members, saving and investing money, and managing debt and credit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://penguinrandomhouse.ca/books/239501/cold-hard-truth-family-kids-and-money#9780385682411|title=Cold Hard Truth on Family, Kids and Money|publisher=Penguin Random House Canada|accessdate=1 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n===''Dragons' Den'' and ''Shark Tank''===\nIn 2006, O'Leary appeared as one of the five venture capitalists on the then-new show ''[[Dragons' Den (Canadian TV series)|Dragons' Den]]'' on CBC, the Canadian installment of the international ''[[Dragons' Den]]'' format. On the show, O'Leary developed a [[persona]] as a blunt, abrasive, bullying investor, who at one point told a contestant who started crying, \"Money doesn't care. Your tears don't add any value.\"<ref name=\"plays one\"/><ref name=\"not the next\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jmaureenhenderson/2017/01/20/why-shark-tanks-kevin-oleary-is-not-the-next-donald-trump/#6bc0d2eb4637|title=Why Shark Tank's Kevin O'Leary Is Not The Next Donald Trump|publisher=Forbes|first= J. Maureen |last=Henderson|date=20 January 2017}}</ref> This television persona was encouraged by executive producer Stuart Coxe, who during the first two seasons occasionally asked O'Leary to be \"more evil\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Meet the man who helped Kevin O'Leary shape his powerful personal brand|url=http://www.cbc.ca/radio/day6/episode-319-becoming-kevin-o-leary-saving-shaker-music-google-renewables-marrying-robots-and-more-1.3921088/meet-the-man-who-helped-kevin-o-leary-shape-his-powerful-personal-brand-1.3921093|first=Brent|last=Bambury|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CBC Radio}}</ref> ''Dragons' Den'' became one of the most-watched shows in CBC history, with around two million viewers per episode.<ref name=\"plays one\"/> Coxe attributed the show's success in large part to O'Leary's presence.<ref name=\"plays one\"/>\n\nIn 2009, the American version of ''Dragons' Den'', ''[[Shark Tank]]'', began, and ''Shark Tank'' executive producer [[Mark Burnett]] invited two of the CBC ''Dragons' Den'' investors, O'Leary and [[Robert Herjavec]], to appear on the show. Both have remained with ''Shark Tank'' since the beginning. For several years, they appeared on both shows, although Herjavec left ''Dragons' Den'' in 2012, and O'Leary left in 2014. ''Shark Tank'' became a ratings hit, averaging 9 million viewers per episode at its peak in the 2014-15 season.<ref name=\"entertainment2015\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/05/2014-15-full-tv-season-ratings-shows-rankings-1201431167/ |title=Full 2014\u201315 Series Rankings |work=Deadline Hollywood|date=22 May 2015|accessdate=22 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YifxgqG8?url=http://deadline.com/2015/05/2014-15-full-tv-season-ratings-shows-rankings-1201431167|archivedate=22 May 2015}}</ref> It has also been a critical favorite, winning the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Structured Reality Program]] three times.<ref name=\"emmys\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/shark-tank|title=Shark Tank \u2013 Awards & Nominations|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary's appearances on ''Dragons' Den'' and ''Shark Tank'' popularized the nickname \"Mr. Wonderful\" for him; he has said that he is often referred to by that name in public.<ref name=\"boston q&a\">{{cite magazine|title=Q&A: Shark Tank\u2019s Kevin O'Leary|url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/arts-entertainment/blog/2013/10/10/shark-tank-kevin-oleary-boston|first=Melissa|last=Malamut|magazine=Boston Magazine|date=10 October 2013}}</ref> O'Leary has said that the nickname serves both as a tongue-in-cheek reference to his reputation for being mean,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/what-its-like-working-with-kevin-oleary-on-shark-tank-2013-11|title=What It's Like Working With the Meanest Investor on \"Shark Tank\"|date=25 November 2013|publisher=Business Insider|author=Vivian Giang|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> as well as a reflection of his view that his blunt assessments are helpful to misguided entrepreneurs. In a 2013 interview, O'Leary implied that he could not remember how he got the nickname.<ref name=\"boston q&a\" /> He had already referred to himself as \"Mr. Wonderful\" in a 2006 casting video for ''Dragon's Den'', predating either show.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kevin O'leary Mr Wonderful from his Audition tape for CA Dragons Den |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GvthgyV5Pow |publisher=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nBesides his blunt persona, O'Leary also gained a reputation on both shows for preferring deals in which he loans the entrepreneurs money in exchange for [[royalty payment|a percentage of future revenue]], rather than taking a share of the company.<ref name=\"how debt\">{{cite web|title=Shark Tank's Kevin O'Leary: How Debt And Licensing Deals Can Benefit Entrepreneurs More|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/trangho/2016/04/10/shark-tanks-kevin-oleary-how-debt-and-licensing-deals-can-benefit-entrepreneurs-more/2/#28b172336f28|date=10 April 2016|first=Ky Trang|last=Ho|publisher=Forbes}}</ref>\n\nNotable deals in which O'Leary has been involved on ''Shark Tank'' include investments in [[Talbott Teas]] (later bought by [[Jamba Juice]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Jamba Juice buys Talbott Teas|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-02-21/business/chi-jamba-juice-acquires-talbott-teas-20120221_1_jamba-juice-green-tea-specialty-tea|first=Corilyn|last=Shropshire|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=21 February 2012}}</ref> and GrooveBook (later bought by [[Shutterfly]]), the latter with [[Mark Cuban]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Shark Tank-Backed GrooveBook Acquired By Shutterfly For $14.5 Million|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/11/17/shark-tank-backed-groovebook-acquired-by-shutterfly-for-14-5-million|first=Sarah|last=Perez|publisher=[[TechCrunch]]|date=17 November 2014}}</ref> O'Leary has a holding company, called \"Something Wonderful\", for managing his ''Dragons' Den'' and ''Shark Tank'' investments.<ref name=\"how debt\"/>\n\n===Discovery Channel's ''Discovery Project Earth''===\nIn 2008, O'Leary worked as a co-host for the [[Discovery Channel]]'s ''[[Discovery Project Earth]]'', a show that explores innovative ways to reverse [[climate change]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/project-earth/task-force/task-force.html|title=Discovery|publisher=Discovery|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120807111952/http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/project-earth/task-force/task-force.html|archivedate=7 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Kevin O'Leary: Success Story|url=http://www.investopedia.com/university/kevin-oleary-biography/kevin-oleary-success-story.asp|date=12 August 2014|work=Toronto Star|author= Colin Dodds}}</ref>\n\n=== The Lang and O'Leary Exchange ===\nIn 2009, O'Leary began appearing with journalist [[Amanda Lang]] on [[CBC News Network]]'s ''[[The Lang and O'Leary Exchange]]''. During a segment of ''The Lang & O'Leary Exchange'' on the [[Occupy Wall Street]] protests in 2011, O'Leary criticized Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist [[Chris Hedges]] for sounding \"like a left-wing nutbar.\" Hedges said afterwards that \"it will be the last time\" he would appear on the show and compared the CBC to [[Fox News]].<ref>James Crugnale (12 October 2011). [http://www.mediaite.com/tv/journalist-chris-hedges-argues-with-cbcs-kevin-oleary-this-sounds-like-fox-news-and-i-don%E2%80%99t-go-on-fox-news/ \"Journalist Chris Hedges Argues With CBC's Kevin O'Leary: 'This Sounds Like Fox News And I Don't Go On Fox News!'\"], [[Mediaite]]; retrieved 24 January 2014.</ref> CBC's ombudsman found O'Leary's behaviour to be a violation of the public broadcaster's journalistic standards.<ref>Szklarski, Cassandra. [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/olearys-nutbar-remark-breach-of-policy-cbc-ombudsman-says/article2201757/ \"O'Leary's 'nutbar' remark breach of policy, CBC ombudsman says.\"] ''Globe & Mail'', 14 October 2011; retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref>\n\nIn January 2014, on ''The Lang and O'Leary Exchange'', O'Leary remarked, {{cquote|It's fantastic, and this is a great thing because it inspires everybody, gets them motivation to look up to the one percent and say, 'I want to become one of those people, I'm going to fight hard to get up to the top.' This is fantastic news, and, of course, I applaud it. What can be wrong with this? I celebrate capitalism. Don't tell me that you want to redistribute wealth again, that's never gonna happen... Redistribution of wealth doesn\u2019t work, we tried it in the Soviet Union, North Korea, would you like to live there? <ref>{{cite web|title=Kevin O'Leary Goes Off On Thomas Piketty, And It's Embarrassing (VIDEO) |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2014/05/24/kevin-oleary-thomas-piketty_n_5383535.html|publisher=The Huffington Post|date=5 May 2014}}</ref><ref>Kludt, Tom (22 January 2014). [http://talkingpointsmemo.com/livewire/kevin-oleary-oxfam-poverty-fantastic Businessman, TV Host: It's 'Fantastic' That 85 People Have More Wealth Than Billions In Poverty (VIDEO)]. ''[[Talking Points Memo]]''; retrieved 22 January 2014.</ref><ref>[[Abby Martin#Presenters|Martin, Abby]] (23 January 2014). [http://rt.com/shows/breaking-set-summary/ukraine-protests-bp-employees-063/ \"Orwell's Kiev, warnings from BP employees, 4 years of corporate personhood\"], ''[[Breaking the Set]]''; retrieved 24 January 2014.</ref><ref>Hulsman, Noel (22 January 2014). [http://ca.finance.yahoo.com/blogs/insight/kevin-o-leary-thinks-global-wealth-gap-fantastic-172254753.html \"Kevin O'Leary thinks global wealth gap is 'fantastic news'\"], [[Yahoo News]]; retrieved 31 January 2014.</ref>}}\n\nO'Leary later clarified these statements, saying, {{cquote|No I don\u2019t think poverty is fantastic. I don\u2019t think income disparity is fantastic. What I think is how successful capitalism has been over the last hundred years reducing poverty and reducing income disparity. In the last 30 years the number of people living on this globe in extreme poverty has been reduced from 42% down to 17%. Amanda, I want you to thank capitalism for that, because that\u2019s how it happened.<ref>{{cite web|title=O'Leary's hyperbole|url=http://www.ombudsman.cbc.radio-canada.ca/en/complaint-reviews/2014/o-leary-s-hyperbole|author= Esther Enkin| publisher= CBC Radio Canada|date= 6 March 2014}}</ref>}}\n\n===Other projects===\nO'Leary has produced and hosted his own reality show, ''[[Redemption Inc.]]'', in which he tries to help ex-convicts start and develop their own businesses.<ref name=\"auto7\"/> Having also been a co-host of ''SqueezePlay'' on [[Bell Media]]'s [[Business News Network]] (BNN), he returned to the Discovery Channel on 1 September 2014 to join as a contributor for its radio and television stations such as [[CTV Television Network|CTV]].<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/kevin-o-leary-bruce-croxon-leaving-cbc-s-dragons-den-1.2572003|title=Kevin O'Leary, Bruce Croxon leaving CBC's Dragon's Den|date=13 March 2014|publisher=CBC.ca|accessdate=14 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2014/08/12/former_dragon_kevin_oleary_leaves_cbc_to_join_ctv.html|title=Former 'Dragon' Kevin O'Leary leaves CBC to join CTV|date=12 August 2014|work=Toronto Star|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 May 2015, O'Leary made an appearance on the game show ''[[Celebrity Jeopardy]]'' and received $10,000 for his charity despite finishing 3rd and in negative points after both Double Jeopardy and Final Jeopardy rounds.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/kevin-oleary-did-not-do-very-well-on-celebrity-jeopardy-770858|title=Kevin O'Leary did not do very well on Celebrity Jeopardy!|first=Ishmael N.|last=Daro|date=13 May 2015|newspaper=National Post|accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> \nIn September of that year, O'Leary appeared as a celebrity judge in the 95th [[Miss America]] pageant.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Field|first1=Sarah|title=How Miss America Judges Can Impress Judge Kevin O'Leary|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2416820/how-miss-america-contestants-can-impress-judge-kevin-oleary|website=Inquisitr.com|publisher=The Inquisitr|accessdate=13 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe is currently a member of ARHT Media's Board of Advisors, alongside [[Paul Anka]] and [[Carlos Slim]].<ref>{{cite web |author1=FRANCOIS MARCHAND |title=Put your head on my (virtual) shoulder: Paul Anka sings past classics while embracing the future in hologram technology |url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/your+head+virtual+shoulder+paul+anka+sings+past+classics+while+embracing+future/11319075/story.html |website=www.vancouversun.com |language=en-ca}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nIn January 2016, O'Leary offered to invest $1 million in the economy of [[Alberta]] in exchange for the resignation of [[Premier of Alberta|Premier]] [[Rachel Notley]]<ref name=\"cpc\">{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary circling as key Conservatives test Tory leadership waters|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/conservative-leadership-kevin-o-leary-1.3401967|accessdate=14 January 2016|work=[[CBC News]]|date=14 January 2016}}</ref> and appeared with four other prospective leadership candidates at a conference for federal Conservatives in late February 2016 where he gave a presentation titled \"If I Run, This is How.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/potential-tory-leadership-candidates-test-waters-at-weekend-conference-1.2795509|title=Potential Tory leadership candidates test waters at weekend conference|website=CTVNews|access-date=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/conservative-leadership-wherry-1.3467788|title=5 auditions to lead the post-Harper Conservatives|website=cbc.ca|access-date=17 October 2017}}</ref> During his speech he predicted that the Liberal government would fall within four years from economic collapse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hilltimes.com/news/politics/2016/02/26/oleary-shakes-up-manning-conference-predicts-economic-collapse-liberal/45447|title=Leary shakes up Manning conference, predicts economic collapse, Liberal turmoil|last=Naumetz|first=Tim|website=hilltimes.com|publisher=The Hill Times|access-date=17 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017 federal Conservative Party leadership race===\n[[File:Kevin O'Leary and Andrew Scheer - 2018 (46074808521) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|O'Leary with [[Andrew Scheer]] in 2018]]\nFollowing [[Stephen Harper]]'s resignation as leader of the [[Conservative Party of Canada]], O'Leary attended Conservative party gatherings in February and May 2016, leading to public speculation about whether he would run for [[2017 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election|2017 leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/the-conservative-partys-kevin-oleary-factor/|title=Will he or won't he? The Conservatives' Kevin O'Leary factor|date=26 May 2016|work=Macleans.ca|access-date=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, [[Maxime Bernier]], a Conservative Quebecois politician, criticized O'Leary, calling him a \"tourist\"<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/Politique/2016/02/27/004-maxime-bernier-attaque-kevin-oleary-course-succession-harper-touristes.shtml|title=\"Un touriste!: \"Maxime Bernier s'en prend \u00e0 l'ex-dragon Kevin O'Leary\"|last=ICI.Radio-Canada.ca|first=Zone Nouvelles|website=Radio-Canada.ca|language=fr-ca|access-date=28 February 2016}}</ref> for wanting to be prime minister without being able to speak French.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2016/02/27/maxime-bernier-slams-english-only-kevin-oleary|title=Maxime Bernier slams English-only Kevin O'Leary|website=Toronto Sun|access-date=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/oleary-brings-the-trump-formula-north/article28955226|title=Kevin O'Leary may speak jobs, but it's French that Quebecers want to hear from next Tory leader, says Bernier|website=Globe and Mail|access-date=1 March 2016}}</ref> Bernier later explained that he wanted all leadership candidates to learn French and praised his fellow leadership contender [[Lisa Raitt]], who was trying to improve her French. O'Leary stated that he was taking French lessons, and promised to learn French in time for the next federal election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/o-leary-shows-off-his-french-lessons-promises-proficiency-by-2019-1.3240840|title=O'Leary shows off his French lessons, promises proficiency by 2019|access-date=17 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 January 2017, O'Leary officially entered the Conservative leadership race.<ref name=\"makes late entry\"/> That same day, his former ''Dragons' Den'' co-star [[Arlene Dickinson]] stated that she found O'Leary to be too \"self-interested and opportunistic\" to be qualified for the office of prime minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/kevin-o-leary-is-self-interested-says-former-co-star-arlene-dickinson-1.3249077|title=Kevin O'Leary is 'self-interested' says former co-star Arlene Dickinson|first=Graham|last=Slaughter|publisher=CTV News|date=18 January 2017|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref> In response, another former ''Dragons' Den'' co-star, [[W. Brett Wilson]], endorsed O'Leary, highlighting differences between O'Leary as a businessman and his TV persona.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/brett-wilson-kevin-o-leary-1.3944082|title=Brett Wilson endorses Kevin O'Leary after Arlene Dickinson's scathing column|first=David|last=Bell|publisher=CBC|date=2017-01-23|accessdate=2017-01-23}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 2017, O'Leary posted a video of himself shooting in a [[Miami]] gun range. It was removed from [[Facebook]] out of respect for the funeral for three victims of the [[Quebec City mosque shooting]] on that day. It was also revealed that he was in New York promoting one of his business ventures when this occurred. O'Leary later apologized for the timing of this post.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/oleary-gun-range-shooting-thursday-1.3963724|title=Kevin O'Leary pulls gun range video 'out of respect' for shooting victims' funeral|first=Catherine|last=Cullen|publisher=CBC|date=2 February 2017|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2017/02/02/oleary-gun-video-posted-on-day-of-mosque-funeral-insensitive-public-safety-minister.html|title=O'Leary gun video posted on day of Mosque funeral 'insensitive:' public safety minister|author=Canadian Press|date=2 February 2017|accessdate=4 February 2017|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref>\n\nThroughout his run for the leadership of the Conservative Party of Canada, O'Leary was compared in the press to [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/25/opinions/meet-canadas-trump-kennedy-opinion/| title =Can Canada's Trump repeat the Donald's success?|date=25 January 2017|publisher=[[CNN.com]]|first=Sean|last=Kennedy}}</ref><ref name=\"fast track\"/> Commentators noted that both were wealthy businessmen who gained greater fame as a result of appearing on [[reality television]],<ref>{{cite web |title= Canada's Donald Trump? 'Shark Tank' star Kevin O'Leary runs for Tory leadership |url= http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/19/politics/canada-kevin-oleary-conservatives |first= Joshua |last= Berlinger |date= 19 January 2017 |publisher= CNN.com}}</ref> prior to running for office, on a platform that included lowering taxes and regulations.<ref>{{cite news |title= The Spectator's View: Kevin O'Leary isn't like Trump. Honest. |url= http://www.thespec.com/opinion-story/7073247-the-spectator-s-view-kevin-o-leary-isn-t-like-trump-honest- |date= 19 January 2017 |newspaper= The Hamilton Spectator |first= Howard |last=Elliott}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url= https://ipolitics.ca/2017/01/17/could-oleary-teach-millennials-to-love-the-conservatives |title= Could O'Leary teach millennials to love the Conservatives? |date= 17 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title= Kevin O'Leary on His Run for Prime Minister and How Trump Is Doing So Far |url= http://www.inc.com/anna-hensel/kevin-oleary-on-why-canadas-top-office-needs-an-entrepreneur.html |date= February 7, 2017 |first=Anna |last= Hensel |magazine=Inc.|quote=O'Leary says he's going to have to match Trump's corporate tax rates and his regulatory moves.}}</ref> Some commentators also found similarities in what they called both men's brash, outspoken style,<ref name=\"great white north\">{{cite web|title=Trump of the Great White North?|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/444150/kevin-oleary-canadian-trump-anti-establishment-businessman-tv-star|first=Michael|last=Taube|date=January 24, 2017 |publisher=National Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/kevin-oleary-leitch-cpc-1.3759631| title = Kevin O'Leary 'writing off' Kellie Leitch's Tory leadership bid| date = 2016-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Kevin O'Leary: Rebel without a (notwithstanding) clause |url= https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/kevin-oleary-rebel-without-a-notwithstanding-clause/article34446126 |first=Gary |last=Mason |newspaper= The Globe and Mail |date=March 28, 2017}}</ref> though various also stated that O'Leary's bluntness, unlike Trump's, was simply part of a \"carefully-cultivated persona\".<ref name=\"not the next\"/><ref name=\"too boring\"/>\n\nO'Leary has praised Trump personally, calling him \"smart as a fox\",<ref name=\"trumpism goes\">{{cite magazine |title= TRUMPISM Goes to CANADA: SHARK TANK STAR MULLING RUN for PARLIAMENT |url= http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2016/01/shark-tank-kevin-oleary-parliament|first=Tina|last=Nguyen|date=21 January 2016|magazine=Vanity Fair}}</ref> but tended to dismiss comparisons to him by noting that, in contrast to Trump's anti-immigration rhetoric and specifically his pledge to build a [[Mexico\u2013United States barrier|wall]] on the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]], \"I'm of Lebanese-Irish descent, I don't build walls, I am very proud of the society we're building in Canada, I think it is the envy of the planet. There's no walls in my world. I wouldn't exist if Canada had walls.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/canadian-politics/i-am-not-donald-trump-kevin-oleary-denies-parallels-with-bombastic-american|title='I am not Donald Trump': Kevin O'Leary denies parallels with bombastic American|access-date=17 October 2017}}</ref> Other commentators pointed out the differences between Trump and O'Leary on other issues, including [[free trade]], [[abortion]], [[same-sex marriage]], [[marijuana legalization]] and the future of [[NATO]].<ref name=\"too boring\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/opinion/o-leary-canadian-trump-1.3941549|work=CBC News|title=Kevin O'Leary is way too boring to be called Canada's Donald Trump: Robyn Urback|author= Robyn Urback|date=16 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"not the next\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wusa9.com/news/reality-tv-star-taking-trump-inspired-politics-north-of-the-border/388575398|title=Reality TV star taking Trump-inspired politics north of the border|publisher=CBS News|first= Michael|last=King|date=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary was a frontrunner in the polls throughout most of his run. Nevertheless, he dropped out of the leadership race on April 26, 2017, stating that, though he still thought he could win the leadership election, a lack of support for him in Quebec meant that it would be difficult for him to beat Trudeau in 2019, and that it would thus be \"selfish\" of him to continue. On dropping out, he endorsed Bernier, considered the other main frontrunner for the position.<ref name=\"dropping out\"/> ([[Andrew Scheer]] eventually won the leadership election, narrowly edging out Bernier.)\n\n===Political positions===\n====Economy and trade====\nO'Leary supports multi-lateral free trade agreements such as the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]]. He described hypothetical trade negotiations between [[Donald Trump]] and [[Justin Trudeau]] as \"Godzilla versus Bambi\".<ref>{{cite news|title='I'm going to be his worst nightmare': 'Shark Tank' judge Kevin O'Leary is running to lead the Conservative Party in Canada|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/kevin-oleary-is-running-to-lead-the-conservative-party-in-canada-2017-1|work=Business Insider}}</ref> O'Leary believes [[Taxation in Canada|corporate tax rates in Canada]] are too high, and has promised to eliminate the national carbon tax.<ref name=\"globalnews.ca\">{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary promises to scrap the carbon tax if elected prime minister|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/3196009/kevin-oleary-promises-to-scrap-the-carbon-tax-if-elected-prime-minister/}}</ref> O'Leary has threatened to punish [[Canadian provinces|provinces]] by withholding transfer payments if they do not eliminate their respective carbon taxes.<ref name=\"globalnews.ca\" /> O'Leary is a critic of deficit spending and supports eliminating the national debt.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary on why he's running for the Tory leadership|url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/qa-kevin-oleary-on-why-hes-running-for-the-tory-leadership/|work=Maclean's}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary opposes control of the [[CRTC]] over Canada's telecommunications system.<ref name=\"bnn.ca\">{{cite news|title=Bank mergers, housing and marijuana: Kevin O\u2019Leary on his leadership bid|url=http://www.bnn.ca/bank-mergers-housing-and-marijuana-kevin-o-leary-on-his-leadership-bid-1.652967}}</ref>\n\n====Energy====\nO'Leary supports building a pipeline from the [[Athabasca oil sands]] to [[Eastern Canada]] with the intentions of making Canada \"energy independent\". He has criticized Canada's reliance on Saudi Arabia for oil and gas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary: 'If I don\u2019t deliver a majority mandate in 2019, fire me'|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/3188715/kevin-oleary-majority-beat-justin-trudeau-or-fire-me/}}</ref> He has stated he would support a national referendum on the issue of pipelines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/kevin-oleary/its-time-to-end-canadas-p_b_12008776.html|title=It's Time to End Canada's Pipeline Circus|first=Kevin|last=O'Leary|work=The Huffington Post|date=2016-09-14|accessdate=2017-01-23}}</ref>\n\n====Social====\nO'Leary describes his social policies as \"very liberal\". He supports [[Same-sex marriage in Canada|same-sex marriage]] and [[transgender]] rights.<ref name=\"ctvnews.ca\">{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary enters Conservative leadership race: 'I'm in'|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/kevin-o-leary-enters-conservative-leadership-race-i-m-in-1.3245919}}</ref> O'Leary supports the legalization and regulation of [[marijuana]].<ref name=\"bnn.ca\" />\n\nO'Leary supports [[assisted suicide]] and cited Switzerland as a model for Canada to follow.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary is way too boring to be called Canada's Donald Trump|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/opinion/o-leary-canadian-trump-1.3941549}}</ref>\n\n====Foreign and military policy====\nO'Leary supported ending [[Operation Impact|Canadian airstrikes on ISIS]] and supports taking a peacekeeping role in the [[Syrian Civil War]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary supports ending airstrikes against ISIS|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/kevin-o-leary-supports-ending-airstrikes-against-isis-1.2772888}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary described Russia as \"neither an ally or a foe\" in an interview with the CBC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PnPCBC/status/818600755405864960|title=Kevin O'Leary on Russia|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary has criticized [[Justin Trudeau]]'s procurement plan. He supports purchasing [[Unmanned combat aerial vehicle|aerial combat drones]] to defend [[Canadian airspace]] and supports phasing out use of the [[Lockheed CP-140 Aurora]] citing cost reasons.<ref name=\"ctvnews.ca\"/> He has criticized the lack of funding of the [[Canadian Armed Forces]] and supports spending the [[NATO]] recommended 2% of GDP on military expenditures.<ref name=\"ctvnews.ca\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary explains his vision for Canada, says he's 'coming' for PM Trudeau|url=http://globalnews.ca/video/3189215/kevin-oleary-explains-his-vision-for-canada-says-hes-coming-for-pm-trudeau}}</ref>\n\n====Immigration====\nO'Leary has proposed creating a \"fast track\" for citizenship for immigrants who graduate from college or university and find employment, as well as for their spouses and children.<ref name=\"fast track\">{{cite web|title=Kevin O'Leary proposes 'fast-track' to citizenship for skilled immigrants|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/kevin-o-leary-proposes-fast-track-to-citizenship-for-skilled-immigrants-1.3271254|publisher=CTV News|first=Jeff|last=Lagerquist|date=4 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary has advocated for increased border security in order to tackle the issue of illegal immigration.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2017/03/06/kevin-oleary-says-refugees-exploiting-an-immigration-loophole|date=6 March 2017|title=Kevin O'Leary says refugees exploiting an immigration 'loophole'}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=kevinolearytv|author=Kevin O'Leary|number=839186062501003265|date=7 March 2017|title=#2. Increase border security to halt the flow of illegals into Canada & work w/ US border security to better understand our deficiencies.}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|number=839184454975434758|user=kevinolearytv|author=Kevin O'Leary|date=7 March 2017|title=Illegal immigration compromises Canada's security & is a slap in the face to families who are waiting to move to our country legitimately.}}</ref>\n\n====Senate====\nIn a 2017 interview with Evan Solomon, O'Leary suggested that [[Senate of Canada|Senators]] should pay money every year, instead of being paid, thus turning \"a cost centre to Canada\" into \"a profit centre.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/senate-seats-for-sale-o-leary-says-he-d-consider-it-1.3240864|title=Senate seats for sale? O'Leary says he'd consider it|first=Josh|last=Dehaas|publisher=CTV|date=15 January 2017|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Leadership debt and lawsuit ===\nIn November 2018, O'Leary hired lawyer [[Joseph Groia]] and sued [[Elections Canada]] and Canada's federal elections commissioner over campaign finance laws which limited candidates to spending only $25,000 of their own money for their leadership campaign. At the time of the lawsuit, O'Leary still owed $430,000 to creditors. O'Leary had proposed to Elections Canada that he pay off the debt now with his own money and fundraise the money later, but was rebuffed, since this would be illegal. O'Leary made public statements that the law promoted mediocrity since rich people would be discouraged from running and hurt the businesses who had pledged money for his failed leadership campaign.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/powerandpolitics/pnp-tasker-oleary-suing-elections-canada-1.4905684|title=Kevin O'Leary suing Elections Canada over fundraising limits|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|date=November 14, 2018|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=November 14, 2018|last2=Kapelos|first2=Vassy|language=en-CA|author-link2=Vassy Kapelos}}</ref>\n\nIn O'Leary's legal submissions, he argued that the laws preventing the use of personal money over $25,000 were a restriction of his [[Section 2 of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|Section 2]] [[Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|Charter]] right to free expression and the threat of jail time in those laws violated his [[Section 7 of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|Section 7]] right to security of the person.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nO'Leary and his wife, Linda, have been married since 1990.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/69295-who-is-kevin-olearys-wife-linda-is-mrs-wonderful-totally-lives-up-to-the-name|title=Who Is Kevin O'Leary's Wife? Linda Is Mrs. Wonderful & Totally Lives Up to the Name|publisher=Bustle|accessdate=12 April 2015|author=Laura Rosenfeld}}</ref> The couple separated in 2011, but resumed their marriage after two years.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/small-business/sb-growth/kevin-oleary-the-shark-who-swims-alone/article595744|title=Kevin O'Leary: The shark who swims alone|work=Globe and Mail|accessdate=23 September 2011|author=John Allemang}}</ref> Linda now serves as the VP of Marketing for O'Leary Wines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailyentertainmentnews.com/tv/linda-oleary-shark-tank-kevin-olearys-wife|title=Linda O'Leary: Shark Tank Kevin O'Leary's Wife|publisher=Daily Entertainment News|accessdate=12 April 2015}}</ref> They have two children.<ref name=\"inbetween\">{{cite web|url=http://inbetween.ca/kevin-oleary-shark-dragon-dad|title=Kevin O'Leary: Shark, Dragon, Dad|work=Inbetween Magazine|accessdate=12 April 2015}}</ref> Trevor is a music producer and DJ while Savannah is a multimedia producer at the Huffington Post.<ref name=\"inbetween\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://torontolife.com/city/business/kevin-oleary/|title=Kevin O'Leary is a blowhard, a relentless self-promoter and, maybe, Canada's future leader|first=Jason|last=McBride|publisher=Toronto Life|date=2016-08-24|accessdate=2019-11-25}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc. Magazine]]'' writer [[Brian D Evans]] O'Leary stated: \"In a successful growing business, it eats your time alive. Then later in life, you can provide for your family things that many others can't have. But because you sacrificed, you're then given the reward of freedom.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inc.com/brian-d-evans/inside-kevin-olearys-unconventional-wealth-building-habits.html|title=Inside Kevin O'Leary's unconventional wealth-building habits|first=Bryan|last=Evans|date=2016-09-22|accessdate=2019-01-17}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary's primary residence and tax residency is in [[Toronto]], Ontario. He also maintains a cottage in [[District Municipality of Muskoka|Muskoka]] as well as homes in [[Boston]] and [[Geneva]], Switzerland.<ref name=\"Kevin O'Leary is a blowhard, a relentless self-promoter\">{{cite news |url=http://torontolife.com/city/business/kevin-oleary/|work=Toronto Life|title= Kevin O'Leary is a blowhard, a relentless self-promoter|date=24 August 2016|author=Jason McBride}}</ref><ref name=\"Transcript: O'Leary on his bid for Conservative leadership\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2017/01/18/transcript-oleary-on-his-bid-for-conservative-leadership.html|title=Transcript: O'Leary on his bid for Conservative leadership|work=The Toronto Star|date=18 January 2017|author=Alex Boutilier}}</ref><ref name=\"Where is home? Kevin O\u2019Leary who\u2019s called Boston 'home' says his priority is Canada\">{{cite news|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2456900/where-is-home-kevin-oleary-whos-called-boston-home-says-his-priority-is-canada|title= Where is home? Kevin O\u2019Leary who\u2019s called Boston \u2018home\u2019 says his priority is Canada|publisher=Global News|date=15 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary is a fan of the [[American football|football]] team the [[New England Patriots]], and claims to watch all of their games, even when he is traveling around the world and the games occur during the middle of the night.<ref name=\"boston q&a\"/> He is a [[oenophilia|wine aficionado]], and belongs to the [[Confr\u00e9rie des Chevaliers du Tastevin]], an international association of [[burgundy wine]] enthusiasts.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Look At Mr. Wonderful's Secret Society for Wine Snobs|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/a-look-at-mr-wonderfuls-secret-society-for-wine-snobs|first=Eric|last=Grundhauser|date=February 9, 2016|publisher=Atlas Obscura}}</ref> He is also a lifelong photographer, and has exhibited and sold prints of his photographs, donating the proceeds to charity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tycoon Kevin O'Leary says when it comes to photography, he is \"a starving artist, hold the starving\"|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/tycoon-kevin-oleary-says-when-it-comes-to-photography-he-is-a-starving-artist-hold-the-starving|first=Peter|last=Kuitenbrouwer|publisher=National Post|date=2 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, 2019, O'Leary was involved in a fatal crash on [[Lake Joseph]] in [[Muskoka]], Ontario. A 64-year-old man and a 48-year-old woman died when a boat owned by O'Leary was involved in a collision with another boat. O'Leary said in a statement that he is cooperating with the police investigation, that he was a passenger in his boat, and that the other boat did not have its lights on and \"fled the scene\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/kevin-o-leary-boat-crash-1.5262492|title=Kevin O'Leary confirms he was passenger in boat involved in double-fatal crash}}</ref> The police stated that both boats left the scene to \"attend a location and both parties called 911.\"<ref name=\"called911\">{{cite web| url=https://www.cp24.com/news/man-killed-in-boat-crash-involving-kevin-o-leary-was-fun-loving-father-of-2-his-brother-says-1.4569878| title=Man killed in boat crash involving Kevin O'Leary was 'fun-loving' father of 2, his brother says| first=Codi| last=Wilson| website=CP24.com| date=August 29, 2019}}</ref> On September 24, Linda O'Leary, the operator of the O'Leary's boat, was charged with \"careless operation of a vessel\" under the small vessel regulations of the ''Canada Shipping Act'', a charge that carries a maximum 18 months imprisonment and a $1-million fine. The driver of the other boat, Richard Ruh of [[Orchard Park, New York]], was charged with \"failing to exhibit navigation light while underway.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/kevin-o-leary-s-wife-charged-in-fatal-ontario-boat-crash-1.4608037|title=Kevin O'Leary's wife charged in fatal Ontario boat crash|publisher=ctvnews.ca|date=September 24, 2019}}</ref> On October 11, the [[Public Prosecution Service of Canada]] ruled out any jail time for Linda.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/linda-o-leary-not-facing-jail-time-for-charge-in-fatal-boat-crash-1.4634435|title=Linda O'Leary not facing jail time for charge in fatal boat crash|publisher=toronto.ctvnews.ca|date=October 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Cold Hard Truth: On Business, Money & Life''. Doubleday Canada. 2011. {{ISBN|978-0385671743}}\n* ''Cold Hard Truth on Men, Women & Money''. Doubleday Canada. 2012. {{ISBN|978-0-385-67850-6}}\n* ''Cold Hard Truth on Family, Kids and Money''. Doubleday Canada. 2013. {{ISBN|978-0385682404}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://kevinoleary.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|2891968|Kevin O'Leary}}\n\n{{Shark Tank}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oleary, Kevin}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Anglophone Quebec people]]\n[[Category:Artists from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in information technology]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in metals]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:Canadian art collectors]]\n[[Category:Canadian Broadcasting Corporation people]]\n[[Category:Canadian business and financial journalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian business writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian chairmen of corporations]]\n[[Category:Canadian commodities traders]]\n[[Category:Canadian computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Canadian documentary filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian film producers]]\n[[Category:Canadian finance and investment writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian financial company founders]]\n[[Category:Canadian financiers]]\n[[Category:Canadian game show hosts]]\n[[Category:Canadian money managers]]\n[[Category:Canadian motivational writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Lebanese descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian photographers]]\n[[Category:Canadian real estate businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Canadian stock traders]]\n[[Category:Canadian technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:Canadian technology company founders]]\n[[Category:Canadian television company founders]]\n[[Category:Canadian television producers]]\n[[Category:Canadian television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Canadian venture capitalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian winemakers]]\n[[Category:CTV Television Network people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:Participants in Canadian reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Mount Royal, Quebec]]\n[[Category:University of Waterloo alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Western Ontario alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Montreal]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Canadian businessman|other uses|Kevin O'Leary (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Kevin O'Leary\n|image       = Kevin O'Leary 2012.jpg\n|caption     = O'Leary in 2012\n|birth_name  = Terence Thomas Kevin O'Leary<ref name=\"CHTBML\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=17mOVkAZV2sC&pg=PT25|title=Cold Hard Truth: On Business, Money & Life|first=Kevin|last=O'Leary|publisher=Doubleday|year=2011|isbn=9780385671750|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref>\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1954|7|9}}\n|birth_place = [[Montreal]], Quebec, Canada\n|citizenship = {{hlist|Canada|Ireland}}\n|alias       = Mr. Wonderful\n|residence   = {{hlist|Rosedale, Toronto|Boston, Massachusetts}}\n|known_for   = [[Reality television|Reality TV]] star,<br />[[CNBC]] and [[Business News Network|BNN]] contributor,<br />[[Investor|Venture capital investor]]\n|education   = [[University of Waterloo]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BSc]])<br />[[Ivey Business School|University of Western Ontario]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n|party       = [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative]]\n|spouse      = {{marriage|Linda O'Leary|1990}}\n|children    = 2\n|website     = {{official website|http://kevinoleary.com/}}\n}}\n{{Kevin O'Leary series}}\n\n'''Terence Thomas Kevin O'Leary''' (born 9 July 1954) is a Canadian businessman, author, politician,  and television personality.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kitconews/2012/05/09/kevin-olearys-cold-hard-truth-on-gold-investing|title=Kevin O'Leary's 'Cold, Hard, Truth' on Gold Investing|work=[[Forbes]]|date=9 May  2012|accessdate=31 July 2015|author=Daniela Cambone}}</ref> He co-founded O'Leary Funds and [[SoftKey]]. From 2004 to 2014, he appeared on various Canadian television shows, including the business news programmes ''SqueezePlay'' and ''[[The Lang and O'Leary Exchange]]'', as well as the [[reality television]] shows ''[[Dragons' Den (Canadian TV series)|Dragons' Den]]'' and ''[[Redemption Inc.]]''<ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themontrealeronline.com/2012/02/kevin-oleary|title=Kevin O'Leary \u2013 from Dragon's Den to Redemption Inc.|work=The Montrealer}}</ref> In 2008, he appeared on [[Discovery Channel]]'s ''[[Project Earth]]''. Since 2009, he has appeared on ''[[Shark Tank]]'', the American equivalent of ''[[Dragons' Den]]''.\n\nO'Leary co-founded [[SoftKey|SoftKey Software Products]], a technology company that sold software geared toward family education and entertainment. During the late 1980s and 1990s, SoftKey acquired rival companies such as Compton's New Media, [[The Learning Company]] and [[Br\u00f8derbund]]. SoftKey later changed its name to The Learning Company, and was acquired by [[Mattel]] in 1999, with the sale making O'Leary a multimillionaire.<ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web|url=http://archive.newswire.ca/en/story/169663/leading-canadian-entrepreneur-kevin-o-leary-named-to-genstar-strategic-advisory-board|title=Leading Canadian Entrepreneur Kevin O'Leary Named to Genstar Strategic Advisory Board|publisher=CNW|date=1 August 2007|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"plays one\"/> O'Leary was soon fired by Mattel after the acquisition resulted in significant losses and multiple shareholder lawsuits.<ref name=\"plays one\"/>\n\nIn 2017, he campaigned to be the leader of the [[Conservative Party of Canada]], drawing comparisons in the press to [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/25/opinions/meet-canadas-trump-kennedy-opinion/| title =Can Canada's Trump repeat the Donald's success?|date=25 January 2017|publisher=[[CNN.com]]|first=Sean|last=Kennedy}}</ref><ref name=\"fast track\"/><ref name=\"makes late entry\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/oleary-conservative-leadership-race-1.3940596|title=Kevin O'Leary makes late entry into Conservative leadership race|date=2017-01-18}}</ref> He was a frontrunner in the polls during much of that time, but dropped out in April 2017, one month before [[2017 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election|the election]], citing a lack of support in [[Quebec]].<ref name=\"dropping out\">{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/kevin-oleary-dropping-out-of-conservative-leadership-race|title=Kevin O\u2019Leary drops out of Conservative leadership race and will support rival Maxime Bernier|work=[[National Post]]|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nO'Leary was born in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada, one of two sons of Georgette (n\u00e9e Bukalam; 1919-2008), a small-business owner and investor of [[Lebanese Canadians|Lebanese]] descent, and Terry O'Leary, a salesman of [[Irish Canadians|Irish]] descent. Kevin's brother is Shane O'Leary.<ref name=\"CHTBML\"/><ref name=\"jasonmcbride\">{{cite web|url=http://torontolife.com/city/business/kevin-oleary|title=Operation O'Leary|author=Jason McBride|work=Toronto Life}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=17mOVkAZV2sC&pg=PT19|title=Cold Hard Truth: On Business, Money & Life|publisher=Doubleday|author=O'Leary, Kevin|year=2011}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">Allemang, John. [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/small-business/kevin-oleary-the-shark-who-swims-alone/article2178538 \"Kevin O'Leary: The shark who swims alone\"], ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', 23 September 2011.</ref><ref>Schlesinger, Joel. [http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/opinion/columnists/the-dragons-pen-130900253.html \"The dragon's pen: Reality TV villain writes about life and money in new autobiography\"], ''Winnipeg FreePress'', 1 October 2011.</ref> Due to his paternal heritage, O'Leary also holds Irish citizenship and carries an Irish passport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/kevin-oleary-leadership-campaign-1.3967543|title=O'Leary spent almost all of the 1st week of his campaign in the U.S.|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary's parents divorced when he was a child, largely due to his father's alcoholism.<ref name=\"CHTBML\"/> His father died shortly thereafter. After his father's death, his mother ran the business as an executive.<ref name=\"The Montrealer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themontrealeronline.com/2012/02/kevin-oleary|title=Kevin O'Leary \u2013 from Dragon's Den to Redemption Inc.|work=The Montrealer|date=1 February 2012 |accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref> His mother later married an economist, George Kanawaty,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/ottawacitizen/obituary.aspx?n=georgette-kanawaty&pid=115674218|title=Georgette Kanawaty's Obituary on Ottawa Citizen|website=Ottawa Citizen}}</ref> who worked with the UN's [[International Labour Organization]].<ref name=\"auto4\"/><ref name=\"janemacdougall\">{{cite web|url=http://www.macleans.ca/culture/the-other-kevin-oleary|title=Dragons' Den star Kevin O'Leary has another passion\u2014photography|author=Jane MacDougall|work=Maclean's}}</ref> His stepfather's international assignments caused the family to move frequently, and O'Leary lived in many places while growing up, including [[Cambodia]], [[Tunisia]], and [[Cyprus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abc.go.com/shows/shark-tank/episode-guide/season-06/619-week-19-luminaid-taaluma-totes-keen-home-scholly|title=Shark Tank : Week 19: LuminAID, Taaluma Totes, Keen Home, Scholly - Season 6 Episode 19 Recap |publisher=ABC}}</ref> O'Leary attended [[Stanstead College]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/breakaway/2011/10/13/kevin-oleary-on-business-and-his-townships-past|title=Breakaway - Kevin O'Leary and his Townships past|date=3 September 2014|publisher=cbc.ca}}</ref> and [[St. George's School of Montreal|St. George's School]], both in Quebec.<ref name=\"auto7\"/>\n\nO'Leary's mother was a skilled investor, investing a third of her weekly paycheque in large-cap, dividend-paying stocks and interest-bearing bonds, ultimately achieving high returns in her investment portfolio.  She kept her investment portfolio secret, so O'Leary only discovered his mother's skill as an investor after her death, when her will was executed.<ref name=\"auto1\" /> Many of his investment lessons came from his mother, including the admonition to save one-third of his money.<ref name=\"auto7\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"uwo.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ivey.uwo.ca/advisoryboard/membership/t-kevin-oleary/|title=T. Kevin O'Leary|publisher=uwo.ca|access-date=9 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710030844/http://www.ivey.uwo.ca/advisoryboard/membership/t-kevin-oleary/|archive-date=10 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/funds-and-etfs/funds/the-kevin-oleary-machine/article4085244/|title=The Kevin O'Leary machine|work=The Globe and Mail |location=Toronto|date=6 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary had aspired to become a photographer, but on the advice of his stepfather attended university,<ref name=\"janemacdougall\"/> where he continued to develop his interest in business and investing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/kevin-olearys-best-advice-from-his-20s-2015-7?r=UK&IR=T|title=Kevin O'Leary's best advice from his 20s |date=28 July 2015|work=Business Insider}}</ref> He received an honours bachelor's degree in [[environmental studies]] and psychology from the [[University of Waterloo]] in 1977<ref>O'Leary, Kevin. (2012) ''Cold Hard Truth on Men, Women & Money''. [[Doubleday Canada]], page 106</ref><ref name=\"auto9\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=8607880&privcapId=33072202 |title=Kevin T. O'Leary |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ivey.uwo.ca/advisoryboard/membership/t-kevin-oleary/ |title=T. Kevin O'Leary |publisher=Ivey Business School, University of Western Ontario |accessdate=8 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710030844/http://www.ivey.uwo.ca/advisoryboard/membership/t-kevin-oleary/ |archive-date=10 July 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and an MBA in entrepreneurship from the [[Ivey Business School]] at the [[University of Western Ontario]] in 1980.<ref name=\"auto9\"/><ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n\n==Business career==\nIn 1979, between the first and second years of his MBA program, O'Leary was selected for an internship at [[Nabisco]] in downtown Toronto, and then worked as an assistant brand manager for Nabisco's cat food brand.<ref name=\"uwo.ca\"/><ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/kevin-oleary/be-like-a-magpie_b_7097052.html|title=Be Like a Magpie|work=[[The Huffington Post]] | date=19 April 2015}}</ref> O'Leary credits his later success at The Learning Company to the skills he developed in marketing during his days at Nabisco.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://strategyonline.ca/1992/11/16/6696-19921116/ |title=The secret of Softkey's success |publisher=Strategy Online |date=16 November 1992 |accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter leaving Nabisco, O'Leary began a brief career as a television producer. With two of his former MBA classmates, Scott Mackenzie and Dave Toms (both of whom had assisted on O'Leary's MBA documentary), O'Leary co-founded Special Event Television (SET).<ref name=\"The Montrealer\" /><ref name=\"Toronto Life\">{{cite web|url=http://www.torontolife.com/informer/people/2014/09/26/kevin-oleary-dragons-den-q-and-a/|title=Kevin O'Leary on leaving the CBC, learning from Don Cherry, and befriending Dragons|work=Toronto Life|access-date=31 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150804182911/http://www.torontolife.com/informer/people/2014/09/26/kevin-oleary-dragons-den-q-and-a/|archive-date=4 August 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Ellen Ashton-Haiste\">{{cite web |url=http://foreveryoungnews.com/posts/2286-the-real-kevin-o-leary |title=The Real Kevin O'Leary |publisher=Forever Young Information |date=24 August 2013 |accessdate=31 July 2015 |author=Ellen Ashton-Haiste}}</ref> SET was an independent television production company that produced original sports programming such as ''The Original Six'', ''Don Cherry's Grapevine'' and ''Bobby Orr and the Hockey Legends''. The company achieved limited success with minor television shows, soccer films, sports documentaries, and short in-between-period commercials for local professional hockey games.<ref name=\"plays one\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/rob-magazine/kevin-oleary-hes-not-a-billionaire-he-just-plays-one-on-tv/article4564334/?page=all|title=Kevin O'Leary: He's not a billionaire, he just plays one on TV|work=The Globe and Mail |location=Toronto|date=28 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"uwo.ca\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctv.ca/SharkTank/Articles/News/Kevin_OLeary_Shark_Tank.aspx|title=Shark Tank - Latest News - From cameraman to Mr. Wonderful: Kevin O'Leary on where he started and what's coming up on 'Shark Tank'|publisher=CTV.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,1921635,00.html|title=Kevin O'Leary, TV's 'Shark Tank' Guru: In Real Life, No Business Whiz |date=10 September 2009|work=Time}}</ref><ref name=\"steveburgess\">{{cite web|url=http://nuvomagazine.com/magazine/autumn-2010/kevin-oleary|title=Kevin O'Leary|author=Steve Burgess|work=NUVO Magazine}}</ref> One of his partners later bought out his share of the venture for $25,000.<ref name=\"auto7\"/><ref name=\"Ellen Ashton-Haiste\"/>\n\n=== Softkey ===\nAfter selling his share of SET, O'Leary started Softkey in a Toronto basement in 1986, along with business partners John Freeman and Gary Babcock.<ref name=\"steveburgess\" /> The company was a publisher and distributor of CD-ROM-based personal computer software for Windows and Macintosh computers. A major financial backer who had committed $250,000 in development capital to the company backed out the day before signing the documents and delivering his cheque, which left O'Leary looking for funding to support the fledgling business. He used the proceeds from the sale of his share of SET and convinced his mother to lend him $10,000 in seed capital to establish SoftKey Software Products.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-best-money-kevin-oleary-ever-spent-2015-4|title='Shark Tank' investor Kevin O'Leary explains how a $10,000 loan from his mother helped him build a $4 billion company|publisher=businessinsider.com|date=17 April 2015|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe software and personal-computer industries were growing rapidly in the early 1980s, and O'Leary convinced printer manufacturers to bundle Softkey's program with their hardware. With distribution assured, the company developed a number of educational software products focused on mathematics and reading education. Softkey products typically consisted of software intended for home users, especially [[shovelware|compilation discs]] containing various [[freeware]] or [[shareware]] games packaged in \"jewel-case\" CD-ROMs.<ref name=\"plays one\"/><ref name=\"auto6\" />\n\nSoftkey weathered stiff competition from other software companies in the late 1980s and prospered throughout the 1990s. By 1993, Softkey had become a major consolidator in the educational software market, acquiring rivals such as [[WordStar]] and [[Spinnaker Software]].<ref name=\"willett19930524\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PTsEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA31&dq=softkey%20worstar&pg=PA31#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Merger is first step to a consumer orientation for WordStar | accessdate=6 March 2011 | author=Willett, Shawn | date=1993-05-24 | publisher=InfoWorld | page=31}}</ref><ref name=\"ieeetimeline\">{{cite web | url=http://www.computer.org/portal/web/computingnow/annals/extras/wordvol28n4 | title=Word Processing Timeline | accessdate=6 March 2011 | author=Bergin, Thomas J. | date=Oct\u2013Dec 2006 | publisher=IEEE Annals of the History of Computing}}</ref> In 1995, Softkey acquired [[The Learning Company]] (TLC) for $606 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/08/business/softkey-reaches-agreement-to-buy-learning-company.html|title=Softkey Reaches Agreement to Buy Learning Company|publisher=nytimes.com|date=8 December 1995|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref> adopting its name, and moved its headquarters to [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts]].\n\nTLC lost $105 million (US) in 1998 on revenues $800 million and suffered losses over the previous two years.<ref name=\"joecastaldo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.canadianbusiness.com/business-strategy/kevin-oleary-the-natural/|title=Kevin O'Leary: The natural |author=Joe Castaldo|work=Canadian Business}}</ref> TLC bought its former rival [[Br\u00f8derbund]] in June 1998 for $416 million.\n\nIn 1999, TLC was acquired by [[Mattel]] for US$4.2 billion.<ref name=\"steveburgess\" /> Sales and earnings for Mattel soon dropped, and O'Leary departed Mattel. The purchase by Mattel was later called one of the most disastrous acquisitions in recent history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/4467013/Mattel-sale-ends-3.6bn-fiasco.html|title=Mattel sale ends $3.6bn fiasco|last=Cave|first=Andrew|date=|work=|newspaper=[[Telegraph.co.uk]]|language=en|access-date=2017-01-20|via=}}</ref> Following the acquisition, Mattel experienced a US$105 million loss where management had projected a $50 million profit. Mattel's stock dropped, wiping out US$3 billion of shareholder value in a single day. Mattel's shareholders later filed a class-action lawsuit accusing Mattel executives, O'Leary, and former TLC CEO Michael Perik of misleading investors about the health of TLC and the benefits of its acquisition. The lawsuit alleged that TLC used accounting tricks to hide losses and inflate quarterly revenues. O'Leary and his defendants disputed all of the charges. Mattel paid $122 million to settle the lawsuit in 2003. O'Leary blamed the technology meltdown and a culture clash of management of the two companies for the failure of the acquisition.<ref name=\"joecastaldo\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,1921635,00.html|title=TV's Shark Tank Guru: In Real Life, No Business Whiz|last=Gandel|first=Stephen|date=2009-09-10|newspaper=Time|issn=0040-781X|access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary and backers from Citigroup made an unsuccessful attempt to acquire the video game company [[Atari]], and O'Leary made plans to start a video-gaming television channel that never came to fruition.<ref name=\"plays one\" />\n\n=== StorageNow Holdings ===\nIn 2003, O'Leary became a co-investor and director at StorageNow Holdings, a Canadian developer of climate-controlled storage facilities, a company controlled by Reza Satchu and Asif Satchu.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/reza-satchu-38/article18450222/|title=Reza Satchu, 38|first=Allison|last=Dunfield|publisher=The Globe and Mail|date=2008-05-05|accessdate=2019-11-25}}</ref> StorageNow became the operator of storage services in Canada, with facilities in 11 cities, and was acquired by in Storage REIT in March 2007 for $110 million.<ref name=\"plays one\"/> He sold his shares, originally worth $500,000, for more than $4.5 million.<ref name=\"plays one\"/>\n\nIn May 2005, Reza Satchu and O'Leary's operating partner, Wheeler, filed a $10-million wrongful-dismissal lawsuit, charging that they had altered an agreed-upon compensation deal and illegally reduced Wheeler's share of the profits.<ref name=\"plays one\"/> O'Leary and Satchu claimed Wheeler failed to reach performance targets.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.canadianbusiness.com/blogs-and-comment/kevin-oleary-conservative-leadership-bid-business-record|title=A history of Kevin O'Leary's spotty business record, in four deals|date=19 January 2017|work=|newspaper=Canadian Business|language=en-US|access-date=17 October 2017}}</ref> The case was settled out of court.<ref name=\"plays one\" />\n\n===Other projects===\nIn March 2007, O'Leary joined the advisory board of [[Genstar Capital]], a [[private equity]] firm that focuses on investing in healthcare services, industrial technology, business services and software. Genstar Capital appointed O'Leary to its Strategic Advisory Board to seek new investment opportunities for its $1.2 billion fund.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/leading-canadian-entrepreneur-kevin-oleary-named-to-genstar-strategic-advisory-board-57750162.html|title=Leading Canadian Entrepreneur Kevin O'Leary Named to Genstar Strategic Advisory Board|date=1 August 2007|publisher=PNR|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n====O'Leary Funds====\nIn 2008, O'Leary co-founded O'Leary Funds Inc., a mutual fund company focused on global yield investing. He is the company's chairman and lead investor, while his brother Shane O'Leary serves as the director. The fund's assets under management grew from $400 million in 2011 to $1.2-billion in 2012.<ref name=\"Oysey, Dan\">{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/executive/leadership/partnering-with-fame?__lsa=01f5-6de0|title=Kevin O'Leary and Connor O'Brien use celebrity branding to take on Canada's fund managers|publisher=Financial Post|date=1 May 2012|accessdate=19 January 2016|author=Oysey, Dan}}</ref> The fund's primary manager was Stanton Asset Management, a firm controlled by the husband-and-wife team of [[Connor O'Brien (alpine skier)|Connor O'Brien and Louise Ann Poirier]].<ref name=\"auto6\"/>\n\nAccording to research by [[Mark R. McQueen]], the fund increased distribution yield from his funds by returning invested capital to shareholders.  While this is not unusual, it was contrary to O'Leary's statements.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://business.financialpost.com/news/kevin-olearys-business-history-back-in-spotlight-after-entering-race-for-conservative-party-leader|title=Kevin O'Leary's business history back in spotlight after entering race for Conservative Party leader|newspaper=Financial Post|language=en|access-date=17 October 2017}}</ref> Another analysis also found that one quarter of the distributions from one of O'Leary's funds were return of capital.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nIn November 2014, O'Leary Funds Management agreed to pay penalties to the [[Autorit\u00e9 des march\u00e9s financiers (Qu\u00e9bec)|Autorit\u00e9 des march\u00e9s financiers]] for violating certain technical provisions of the Securities Act. At the time of the agreement, O'Leary Funds reported that it had taken steps to correct the violations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lautorite.qc.ca/en/news-2014-conso.html_2014_gestion-de-fonds-o-leary-to-pay-38-000-in-administrative-penalties04-11-2014-00-0.html|title=Gestion de fonds O'Leary to pay $38,000 in administrative penalties|website=lautorite.qc.ca|access-date=6 September 2016}}</ref> On 15 October 2015, O'Leary Funds was sold to Canoe Financial, a private investment-management company owned by Canadian businessman [[W. Brett Wilson]], who once was an investor with O'Leary on CBC's ''Dragons' Den.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bnn.ca/News/2015/10/15/Canoe-Financial-buys-OLeary-Funds-investment-assets.aspx|title=Dragons reunite as Canoe picks up Kevin O'Leary's fund shop|date=15 October 2015|publisher=Business News Network|accessdate=15 January 2016|author=Cain, Terry}}</ref>\n\n====O'Leary Ventures====\nO'Leary founded O'Leary Ventures, a private early-stage venture capital investment company,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://olearyventures.com/|title=About O'Leary Ventures|publisher=O'Leary Ventures|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> O'Leary Mortgages, O'Leary books, and O'Leary Fine Wines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vinelandwineshop.com/categories.php?category=O'Leary-Wines|title=O'Leary Wines|accessdate=25 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029213504/http://www.vinelandwineshop.com/categories.php?category=O%27Leary-Wines|archive-date=29 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwire.com/press-release/oleary-fine-wines-wins-best-value-at-intervin-international-wine-awards-1708921.htm|title=O'Leary Fine Wines Wins \"Best Value\" at InterVin International Wine Awards|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> In April 2014, O'Leary Mortgages closed.<ref>McLister, Rob. [http://www.canadianmortgagetrends.com/canadian_mortgage_trends/2014/04/oleary-mortgages-is-no-more.html \"O'Leary Mortgages Is No More\"]. CanadianMortgageTrends.com. 10 April 2014 {{unreliable?|date=October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== ETF and investing ====\nOn 14 July 2015, O'Leary launched an [[Exchange-traded fund|ETF]] through O'Shares Investments, a division of his investment fund, O'Leary Funds Management LP, where O'Leary serves as chairman. A [[value investor]], he has given advice on [[personal finance]].<ref name=\"Smith\">{{cite news|url=http://www.fool.ca/2016/04/28/steal-these-4-investing-tips-from-kevin-oleary/|title=Steal These 4 Investing Tips from Kevin O'Leary|date=28 April 2016|work=Motley Fool|author=Nelson Smith}}</ref> He advocates [[Diversification (finance)|portfolio diversification]] and suggests that investors have their age as the percentage of [[Bond (finance)|bonds]] in their portfolios (i.e., 30% in bonds and 70% in stocks for a 30-year old investor, with an increasing proportion of bonds and decreasing proportion of stocks as the investor ages).<ref name=\"Smith\"/> O'Leary has also \"stated on many occasions that he won\u2019t invest in a publicly traded stock unless it pays him a [[dividend]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fool.ca/2016/04/13/collect-1000-per-month-by-investing-like-kevin-oleary/|title=Collect $1,000 per month by investing like Kevin O'Leary|date=16 April 2016|author=Smith, Nelson}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary also ventured into [[gold as an investment|gold investing]], with five percent of his financial portfolio invested in physical gold. However, he does not invest in stocks of gold-mining companies because he says [[cash flow]] is an important investment factor to him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kitconews/2012/05/09/kevin-olearys-cold-hard-truth-on-gold-investing/1/|title=Kevin O'Leary's 'Cold, Hard, Truth' on Gold Investing|date=5 November 2012|work=Forbes|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontariofarmer.com/sitepages/?aid=3544&cn=TO%20SUBSCRIBE%20TO%20ONTARIO%20FARMER&an=Three%20investment%20tips%20from%20a%20dragon|title=Three investment tips from a dragon|publisher=Ontario Farmer|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://spikedfinance.com/kevin-oleary-on-dividend-investing|title=Kevin O'Leary on Dividend Investing|date=3 May 2014|publisher=Spiked Finance|accessdate=9 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110081342/http://spikedfinance.com/kevin-oleary-on-dividend-investing/|archive-date=10 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> O'Leary also advises diversification in multiple industry sectors so that no more than 20% of one's financial portfolio is held in one sector.<ref>{{cite book|title=Cold Hard Truth on Men, Women, and Money|publisher=[[Simon and Schuster]]|author=O'Leary, Kevin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bnn.ca/News/2015/12/18/OLeary-tells-a-young-investor-how-to-turn-10000-in-a-nest-egg.aspx|title=Kevin O'Leary tells a young investor how to turn $10,000 in a nest egg|date=18 December 2015|publisher=BNN|accessdate=15 January 2016|author=Padanyi, Matt}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nIn September 2011, O'Leary released his first book, ''Cold Hard Truth: On Business, Money & Life'', in which he shares his views on entrepreneurship, business, finance, money and life.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/small-business/sb-growth/success-stories/kevin-oleary-the-shark-who-swims-alone/article595744|title=Kevin O'Leary: The shark who swims alone|work=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=6 August 2012|location=Toronto}}</ref> A sequel, ''The Cold Hard Truth on Men, Women, and Money: 50 Common Money Mistakes and How to Fix Them'', was published in 2012. It focused on [[financial literacy]] and financial education as a foundation for achieving wealth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kevinoleary.com/books|title=Order your copy of Cold Hard Truth on Men, Women & Money|publisher=[[Doubleday Canada]]|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> O'Leary released a followup in 2013 in which he covers subjects relating to important life choices: education, careers, marriage and family, and retirement. He discusses the obstacles of raising a family while working to provide financial security for them and gives advice for developing financial literacy in family members, saving and investing money, and managing debt and credit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://penguinrandomhouse.ca/books/239501/cold-hard-truth-family-kids-and-money#9780385682411|title=Cold Hard Truth on Family, Kids and Money|publisher=Penguin Random House Canada|accessdate=1 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n===''Dragons' Den'' and ''Shark Tank''===\nIn 2006, O'Leary appeared as one of the five venture capitalists on the then-new show ''[[Dragons' Den (Canadian TV series)|Dragons' Den]]'' on CBC, the Canadian installment of the international ''[[Dragons' Den]]'' format. On the show, O'Leary developed a [[persona]] as a blunt, abrasive, bullying investor, who at one point told a contestant who started crying, \"Money doesn't care. Your tears don't add any value.\"<ref name=\"plays one\"/><ref name=\"not the next\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jmaureenhenderson/2017/01/20/why-shark-tanks-kevin-oleary-is-not-the-next-donald-trump/#6bc0d2eb4637|title=Why Shark Tank's Kevin O'Leary Is Not The Next Donald Trump|publisher=Forbes|first= J. Maureen |last=Henderson|date=20 January 2017}}</ref> This television persona was encouraged by executive producer Stuart Coxe, who during the first two seasons occasionally asked O'Leary to be \"more evil\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Meet the man who helped Kevin O'Leary shape his powerful personal brand|url=http://www.cbc.ca/radio/day6/episode-319-becoming-kevin-o-leary-saving-shaker-music-google-renewables-marrying-robots-and-more-1.3921088/meet-the-man-who-helped-kevin-o-leary-shape-his-powerful-personal-brand-1.3921093|first=Brent|last=Bambury|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CBC Radio}}</ref> ''Dragons' Den'' became one of the most-watched shows in CBC history, with around two million viewers per episode.<ref name=\"plays one\"/> Coxe attributed the show's success in large part to O'Leary's presence.<ref name=\"plays one\"/>\n\nIn 2009, the American version of ''Dragons' Den'', ''[[Shark Tank]]'', began, and ''Shark Tank'' executive producer [[Mark Burnett]] invited two of the CBC ''Dragons' Den'' investors, O'Leary and [[Robert Herjavec]], to appear on the show. Both have remained with ''Shark Tank'' since the beginning. For several years, they appeared on both shows, although Herjavec left ''Dragons' Den'' in 2012, and O'Leary left in 2014. ''Shark Tank'' became a ratings hit, averaging 9 million viewers per episode at its peak in the 2014-15 season.<ref name=\"entertainment2015\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/05/2014-15-full-tv-season-ratings-shows-rankings-1201431167/ |title=Full 2014\u201315 Series Rankings |work=Deadline Hollywood|date=22 May 2015|accessdate=22 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YifxgqG8?url=http://deadline.com/2015/05/2014-15-full-tv-season-ratings-shows-rankings-1201431167|archivedate=22 May 2015}}</ref> It has also been a critical favorite, winning the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Structured Reality Program]] three times.<ref name=\"emmys\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/shark-tank|title=Shark Tank \u2013 Awards & Nominations|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary's appearances on ''Dragons' Den'' and ''Shark Tank'' popularized the nickname \"Mr. Wonderful\" for him; he has said that he is often referred to by that name in public.<ref name=\"boston q&a\">{{cite magazine|title=Q&A: Shark Tank\u2019s Kevin O'Leary|url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/arts-entertainment/blog/2013/10/10/shark-tank-kevin-oleary-boston|first=Melissa|last=Malamut|magazine=Boston Magazine|date=10 October 2013}}</ref> O'Leary has said that the nickname serves both as a tongue-in-cheek reference to his reputation for being mean,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/what-its-like-working-with-kevin-oleary-on-shark-tank-2013-11|title=What It's Like Working With the Meanest Investor on \"Shark Tank\"|date=25 November 2013|publisher=Business Insider|author=Vivian Giang|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> as well as a reflection of his view that his blunt assessments are helpful to misguided entrepreneurs. In a 2013 interview, O'Leary implied that he could not remember how he got the nickname.<ref name=\"boston q&a\" /> He had already referred to himself as \"Mr. Wonderful\" in a 2006 casting video for ''Dragon's Den'', predating either show.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kevin O'leary Mr Wonderful from his Audition tape for CA Dragons Den |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GvthgyV5Pow |publisher=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nBesides his blunt persona, O'Leary also gained a reputation on both shows for preferring deals in which he loans the entrepreneurs money in exchange for [[royalty payment|a percentage of future revenue]], rather than taking a share of the company.<ref name=\"how debt\">{{cite web|title=Shark Tank's Kevin O'Leary: How Debt And Licensing Deals Can Benefit Entrepreneurs More|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/trangho/2016/04/10/shark-tanks-kevin-oleary-how-debt-and-licensing-deals-can-benefit-entrepreneurs-more/2/#28b172336f28|date=10 April 2016|first=Ky Trang|last=Ho|publisher=Forbes}}</ref>\n\nNotable deals in which O'Leary has been involved on ''Shark Tank'' include investments in [[Talbott Teas]] (later bought by [[Jamba Juice]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Jamba Juice buys Talbott Teas|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-02-21/business/chi-jamba-juice-acquires-talbott-teas-20120221_1_jamba-juice-green-tea-specialty-tea|first=Corilyn|last=Shropshire|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=21 February 2012}}</ref> and GrooveBook (later bought by [[Shutterfly]]), the latter with [[Mark Cuban]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Shark Tank-Backed GrooveBook Acquired By Shutterfly For $14.5 Million|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/11/17/shark-tank-backed-groovebook-acquired-by-shutterfly-for-14-5-million|first=Sarah|last=Perez|publisher=[[TechCrunch]]|date=17 November 2014}}</ref> O'Leary has a holding company, called \"Something Wonderful\", for managing his ''Dragons' Den'' and ''Shark Tank'' investments.<ref name=\"how debt\"/>\n\n===Discovery Channel's ''Discovery Project Earth''===\nIn 2008, O'Leary worked as a co-host for the [[Discovery Channel]]'s ''[[Discovery Project Earth]]'', a show that explores innovative ways to reverse [[climate change]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/project-earth/task-force/task-force.html|title=Discovery|publisher=Discovery|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120807111952/http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/project-earth/task-force/task-force.html|archivedate=7 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Kevin O'Leary: Success Story|url=http://www.investopedia.com/university/kevin-oleary-biography/kevin-oleary-success-story.asp|date=12 August 2014|work=Toronto Star|author= Colin Dodds}}</ref>\n\n=== The Lang and O'Leary Exchange ===\nIn 2009, O'Leary began appearing with journalist [[Amanda Lang]] on [[CBC News Network]]'s ''[[The Lang and O'Leary Exchange]]''. During a segment of ''The Lang & O'Leary Exchange'' on the [[Occupy Wall Street]] protests in 2011, O'Leary criticized Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist [[Chris Hedges]] for sounding \"like a left-wing nutbar.\" Hedges said afterwards that \"it will be the last time\" he would appear on the show and compared the CBC to [[Fox News]].<ref>James Crugnale (12 October 2011). [http://www.mediaite.com/tv/journalist-chris-hedges-argues-with-cbcs-kevin-oleary-this-sounds-like-fox-news-and-i-don%E2%80%99t-go-on-fox-news/ \"Journalist Chris Hedges Argues With CBC's Kevin O'Leary: 'This Sounds Like Fox News And I Don't Go On Fox News!'\"], [[Mediaite]]; retrieved 24 January 2014.</ref> CBC's ombudsman found O'Leary's behaviour to be a violation of the public broadcaster's journalistic standards.<ref>Szklarski, Cassandra. [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/olearys-nutbar-remark-breach-of-policy-cbc-ombudsman-says/article2201757/ \"O'Leary's 'nutbar' remark breach of policy, CBC ombudsman says.\"] ''Globe & Mail'', 14 October 2011; retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref>\n\nIn January 2014, on ''The Lang and O'Leary Exchange'', O'Leary remarked, {{cquote|It's fantastic, and this is a great thing because it inspires everybody, gets them motivation to look up to the one percent and say, 'I want to become one of those people, I'm going to fight hard to get up to the top.' This is fantastic news, and, of course, I applaud it. What can be wrong with this? I celebrate capitalism. Don't tell me that you want to redistribute wealth again, that's never gonna happen... Redistribution of wealth doesn\u2019t work, we tried it in the Soviet Union, North Korea, would you like to live there? <ref>{{cite web|title=Kevin O'Leary Goes Off On Thomas Piketty, And It's Embarrassing (VIDEO) |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2014/05/24/kevin-oleary-thomas-piketty_n_5383535.html|publisher=The Huffington Post|date=5 May 2014}}</ref><ref>Kludt, Tom (22 January 2014). [http://talkingpointsmemo.com/livewire/kevin-oleary-oxfam-poverty-fantastic Businessman, TV Host: It's 'Fantastic' That 85 People Have More Wealth Than Billions In Poverty (VIDEO)]. ''[[Talking Points Memo]]''; retrieved 22 January 2014.</ref><ref>[[Abby Martin#Presenters|Martin, Abby]] (23 January 2014). [http://rt.com/shows/breaking-set-summary/ukraine-protests-bp-employees-063/ \"Orwell's Kiev, warnings from BP employees, 4 years of corporate personhood\"], ''[[Breaking the Set]]''; retrieved 24 January 2014.</ref><ref>Hulsman, Noel (22 January 2014). [http://ca.finance.yahoo.com/blogs/insight/kevin-o-leary-thinks-global-wealth-gap-fantastic-172254753.html \"Kevin O'Leary thinks global wealth gap is 'fantastic news'\"], [[Yahoo News]]; retrieved 31 January 2014.</ref>}}\n\nO'Leary later clarified these statements, saying, {{cquote|No I don\u2019t think poverty is fantastic. I don\u2019t think income disparity is fantastic. What I think is how successful capitalism has been over the last hundred years reducing poverty and reducing income disparity. In the last 30 years the number of people living on this globe in extreme poverty has been reduced from 42% down to 17%. Amanda, I want you to thank capitalism for that, because that\u2019s how it happened.<ref>{{cite web|title=O'Leary's hyperbole|url=http://www.ombudsman.cbc.radio-canada.ca/en/complaint-reviews/2014/o-leary-s-hyperbole|author= Esther Enkin| publisher= CBC Radio Canada|date= 6 March 2014}}</ref>}}\n\n===Other projects===\nO'Leary has produced and hosted his own reality show, ''[[Redemption Inc.]]'', in which he tries to help ex-convicts start and develop their own businesses.<ref name=\"auto7\"/> Having also been a co-host of ''SqueezePlay'' on [[Bell Media]]'s [[Business News Network]] (BNN), he returned to the Discovery Channel on 1 September 2014 to join as a contributor for its radio and television stations such as [[CTV Television Network|CTV]].<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/kevin-o-leary-bruce-croxon-leaving-cbc-s-dragons-den-1.2572003|title=Kevin O'Leary, Bruce Croxon leaving CBC's Dragon's Den|date=13 March 2014|publisher=CBC.ca|accessdate=14 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2014/08/12/former_dragon_kevin_oleary_leaves_cbc_to_join_ctv.html|title=Former 'Dragon' Kevin O'Leary leaves CBC to join CTV|date=12 August 2014|work=Toronto Star|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 May 2015, O'Leary made an appearance on the game show ''[[Celebrity Jeopardy]]'' and received $10,000 for his charity despite finishing 3rd and in negative points after both Double Jeopardy and Final Jeopardy rounds.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/kevin-oleary-did-not-do-very-well-on-celebrity-jeopardy-770858|title=Kevin O'Leary did not do very well on Celebrity Jeopardy!|first=Ishmael N.|last=Daro|date=13 May 2015|newspaper=National Post|accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> \nIn September of that year, O'Leary appeared as a celebrity judge in the 95th [[Miss America]] pageant.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Field|first1=Sarah|title=How Miss America Judges Can Impress Judge Kevin O'Leary|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2416820/how-miss-america-contestants-can-impress-judge-kevin-oleary|website=Inquisitr.com|publisher=The Inquisitr|accessdate=13 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe is currently a member of ARHT Media's Board of Advisors, alongside [[Paul Anka]] and [[Carlos Slim]].<ref>{{cite web |author1=FRANCOIS MARCHAND |title=Put your head on my (virtual) shoulder: Paul Anka sings past classics while embracing the future in hologram technology |url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/your+head+virtual+shoulder+paul+anka+sings+past+classics+while+embracing+future/11319075/story.html |website=www.vancouversun.com |language=en-ca}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nIn January 2016, O'Leary offered to invest $1 million in the economy of [[Alberta]] in exchange for the resignation of [[Premier of Alberta|Premier]] [[Rachel Notley]]<ref name=\"cpc\">{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary circling as key Conservatives test Tory leadership waters|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/conservative-leadership-kevin-o-leary-1.3401967|accessdate=14 January 2016|work=[[CBC News]]|date=14 January 2016}}</ref> and appeared with four other prospective leadership candidates at a conference for federal Conservatives in late February 2016 where he gave a presentation titled \"If I Run, This is How.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/potential-tory-leadership-candidates-test-waters-at-weekend-conference-1.2795509|title=Potential Tory leadership candidates test waters at weekend conference|website=CTVNews|access-date=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/conservative-leadership-wherry-1.3467788|title=5 auditions to lead the post-Harper Conservatives|website=cbc.ca|access-date=17 October 2017}}</ref> During his speech he predicted that the Liberal government would fall within four years from economic collapse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hilltimes.com/news/politics/2016/02/26/oleary-shakes-up-manning-conference-predicts-economic-collapse-liberal/45447|title=Leary shakes up Manning conference, predicts economic collapse, Liberal turmoil|last=Naumetz|first=Tim|website=hilltimes.com|publisher=The Hill Times|access-date=17 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017 federal Conservative Party leadership race===\n[[File:Kevin O'Leary and Andrew Scheer - 2018 (46074808521) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|O'Leary with [[Andrew Scheer]] in 2018]]\nFollowing [[Stephen Harper]]'s resignation as leader of the [[Conservative Party of Canada]], O'Leary attended Conservative party gatherings in February and May 2016, leading to public speculation about whether he would run for [[2017 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election|2017 leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/the-conservative-partys-kevin-oleary-factor/|title=Will he or won't he? The Conservatives' Kevin O'Leary factor|date=26 May 2016|work=Macleans.ca|access-date=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, [[Maxime Bernier]], a Conservative Quebecois politician, criticized O'Leary, calling him a \"tourist\"<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/Politique/2016/02/27/004-maxime-bernier-attaque-kevin-oleary-course-succession-harper-touristes.shtml|title=\"Un touriste!: \"Maxime Bernier s'en prend \u00e0 l'ex-dragon Kevin O'Leary\"|last=ICI.Radio-Canada.ca|first=Zone Nouvelles|website=Radio-Canada.ca|language=fr-ca|access-date=28 February 2016}}</ref> for wanting to be prime minister without being able to speak French.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2016/02/27/maxime-bernier-slams-english-only-kevin-oleary|title=Maxime Bernier slams English-only Kevin O'Leary|website=Toronto Sun|access-date=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/oleary-brings-the-trump-formula-north/article28955226|title=Kevin O'Leary may speak jobs, but it's French that Quebecers want to hear from next Tory leader, says Bernier|website=Globe and Mail|access-date=1 March 2016}}</ref> Bernier later explained that he wanted all leadership candidates to learn French and praised his fellow leadership contender [[Lisa Raitt]], who was trying to improve her French. O'Leary stated that he was taking French lessons, and promised to learn French in time for the next federal election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/o-leary-shows-off-his-french-lessons-promises-proficiency-by-2019-1.3240840|title=O'Leary shows off his French lessons, promises proficiency by 2019|access-date=17 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 January 2017, O'Leary officially entered the Conservative leadership race.<ref name=\"makes late entry\"/> That same day, his former ''Dragons' Den'' co-star [[Arlene Dickinson]] stated that she found O'Leary to be too \"self-interested and opportunistic\" to be qualified for the office of prime minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/kevin-o-leary-is-self-interested-says-former-co-star-arlene-dickinson-1.3249077|title=Kevin O'Leary is 'self-interested' says former co-star Arlene Dickinson|first=Graham|last=Slaughter|publisher=CTV News|date=18 January 2017|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref> In response, another former ''Dragons' Den'' co-star, [[W. Brett Wilson]], endorsed O'Leary, highlighting differences between O'Leary as a businessman and his TV persona.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/brett-wilson-kevin-o-leary-1.3944082|title=Brett Wilson endorses Kevin O'Leary after Arlene Dickinson's scathing column|first=David|last=Bell|publisher=CBC|date=2017-01-23|accessdate=2017-01-23}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 2017, O'Leary posted a video of himself shooting in a [[Miami]] gun range. It was removed from [[Facebook]] out of respect for the funeral for three victims of the [[Quebec City mosque shooting]] on that day. It was also revealed that he was in New York promoting one of his business ventures when this occurred. O'Leary later apologized for the timing of this post.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/oleary-gun-range-shooting-thursday-1.3963724|title=Kevin O'Leary pulls gun range video 'out of respect' for shooting victims' funeral|first=Catherine|last=Cullen|publisher=CBC|date=2 February 2017|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2017/02/02/oleary-gun-video-posted-on-day-of-mosque-funeral-insensitive-public-safety-minister.html|title=O'Leary gun video posted on day of Mosque funeral 'insensitive:' public safety minister|author=Canadian Press|date=2 February 2017|accessdate=4 February 2017|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref>\n\nThroughout his run for the leadership of the Conservative Party of Canada, O'Leary was compared in the press to [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/25/opinions/meet-canadas-trump-kennedy-opinion/| title =Can Canada's Trump repeat the Donald's success?|date=25 January 2017|publisher=[[CNN.com]]|first=Sean|last=Kennedy}}</ref><ref name=\"fast track\"/> Commentators noted that both were wealthy businessmen who gained greater fame as a result of appearing on [[reality television]],<ref>{{cite web |title= Canada's Donald Trump? 'Shark Tank' star Kevin O'Leary runs for Tory leadership |url= http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/19/politics/canada-kevin-oleary-conservatives |first= Joshua |last= Berlinger |date= 19 January 2017 |publisher= CNN.com}}</ref> prior to running for office, on a platform that included lowering taxes and regulations.<ref>{{cite news |title= The Spectator's View: Kevin O'Leary isn't like Trump. Honest. |url= http://www.thespec.com/opinion-story/7073247-the-spectator-s-view-kevin-o-leary-isn-t-like-trump-honest- |date= 19 January 2017 |newspaper= The Hamilton Spectator |first= Howard |last=Elliott}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url= https://ipolitics.ca/2017/01/17/could-oleary-teach-millennials-to-love-the-conservatives |title= Could O'Leary teach millennials to love the Conservatives? |date= 17 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title= Kevin O'Leary on His Run for Prime Minister and How Trump Is Doing So Far |url= http://www.inc.com/anna-hensel/kevin-oleary-on-why-canadas-top-office-needs-an-entrepreneur.html |date= February 7, 2017 |first=Anna |last= Hensel |magazine=Inc.|quote=O'Leary says he's going to have to match Trump's corporate tax rates and his regulatory moves.}}</ref> Some commentators also found similarities in what they called both men's brash, outspoken style,<ref name=\"great white north\">{{cite web|title=Trump of the Great White North?|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/444150/kevin-oleary-canadian-trump-anti-establishment-businessman-tv-star|first=Michael|last=Taube|date=January 24, 2017 |publisher=National Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/kevin-oleary-leitch-cpc-1.3759631| title = Kevin O'Leary 'writing off' Kellie Leitch's Tory leadership bid| date = 2016-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Kevin O'Leary: Rebel without a (notwithstanding) clause |url= https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/kevin-oleary-rebel-without-a-notwithstanding-clause/article34446126 |first=Gary |last=Mason |newspaper= The Globe and Mail |date=March 28, 2017}}</ref> though various also stated that O'Leary's bluntness, unlike Trump's, was simply part of a \"carefully-cultivated persona\".<ref name=\"not the next\"/><ref name=\"too boring\"/>\n\nO'Leary has praised Trump personally, calling him \"smart as a fox\",<ref name=\"trumpism goes\">{{cite magazine |title= TRUMPISM Goes to CANADA: SHARK TANK STAR MULLING RUN for PARLIAMENT |url= http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2016/01/shark-tank-kevin-oleary-parliament|first=Tina|last=Nguyen|date=21 January 2016|magazine=Vanity Fair}}</ref> but tended to dismiss comparisons to him by noting that, in contrast to Trump's anti-immigration rhetoric and specifically his pledge to build a [[Mexico\u2013United States barrier|wall]] on the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]], \"I'm of Lebanese-Irish descent, I don't build walls, I am very proud of the society we're building in Canada, I think it is the envy of the planet. There's no walls in my world. I wouldn't exist if Canada had walls.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/canadian-politics/i-am-not-donald-trump-kevin-oleary-denies-parallels-with-bombastic-american|title='I am not Donald Trump': Kevin O'Leary denies parallels with bombastic American|access-date=17 October 2017}}</ref> Other commentators pointed out the differences between Trump and O'Leary on other issues, including [[free trade]], [[abortion]], [[same-sex marriage]], [[marijuana legalization]] and the future of [[NATO]].<ref name=\"too boring\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/opinion/o-leary-canadian-trump-1.3941549|work=CBC News|title=Kevin O'Leary is way too boring to be called Canada's Donald Trump: Robyn Urback|author= Robyn Urback|date=16 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"not the next\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wusa9.com/news/reality-tv-star-taking-trump-inspired-politics-north-of-the-border/388575398|title=Reality TV star taking Trump-inspired politics north of the border|publisher=CBS News|first= Michael|last=King|date=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary was a frontrunner in the polls throughout most of his run. Nevertheless, he dropped out of the leadership race on April 26, 2017, stating that, though he still thought he could win the leadership election, a lack of support for him in Quebec meant that it would be difficult for him to beat Trudeau in 2019, and that it would thus be \"selfish\" of him to continue. On dropping out, he endorsed Bernier, considered the other main frontrunner for the position.<ref name=\"dropping out\"/> ([[Andrew Scheer]] eventually won the leadership election, narrowly edging out Bernier.)\n\n===Political positions===\n====Economy and trade====\nO'Leary supports multi-lateral free trade agreements such as the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]]. He described hypothetical trade negotiations between [[Donald Trump]] and [[Justin Trudeau]] as \"Godzilla versus Bambi\".<ref>{{cite news|title='I'm going to be his worst nightmare': 'Shark Tank' judge Kevin O'Leary is running to lead the Conservative Party in Canada|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/kevin-oleary-is-running-to-lead-the-conservative-party-in-canada-2017-1|work=Business Insider}}</ref> O'Leary believes [[Taxation in Canada|corporate tax rates in Canada]] are too high, and has promised to eliminate the national carbon tax.<ref name=\"globalnews.ca\">{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary promises to scrap the carbon tax if elected prime minister|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/3196009/kevin-oleary-promises-to-scrap-the-carbon-tax-if-elected-prime-minister/}}</ref> O'Leary has threatened to punish [[Canadian provinces|provinces]] by withholding transfer payments if they do not eliminate their respective carbon taxes.<ref name=\"globalnews.ca\" /> O'Leary is a critic of deficit spending and supports eliminating the national debt.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary on why he's running for the Tory leadership|url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/qa-kevin-oleary-on-why-hes-running-for-the-tory-leadership/|work=Maclean's}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary opposes control of the [[CRTC]] over Canada's telecommunications system.<ref name=\"bnn.ca\">{{cite news|title=Bank mergers, housing and marijuana: Kevin O\u2019Leary on his leadership bid|url=http://www.bnn.ca/bank-mergers-housing-and-marijuana-kevin-o-leary-on-his-leadership-bid-1.652967}}</ref>\n\n====Energy====\nO'Leary supports building a pipeline from the [[Athabasca oil sands]] to [[Eastern Canada]] with the intentions of making Canada \"energy independent\". He has criticized Canada's reliance on Saudi Arabia for oil and gas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary: 'If I don\u2019t deliver a majority mandate in 2019, fire me'|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/3188715/kevin-oleary-majority-beat-justin-trudeau-or-fire-me/}}</ref> He has stated he would support a national referendum on the issue of pipelines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/kevin-oleary/its-time-to-end-canadas-p_b_12008776.html|title=It's Time to End Canada's Pipeline Circus|first=Kevin|last=O'Leary|work=The Huffington Post|date=2016-09-14|accessdate=2017-01-23}}</ref>\n\n====Social====\nO'Leary describes his social policies as \"very liberal\". He supports [[Same-sex marriage in Canada|same-sex marriage]] and [[transgender]] rights.<ref name=\"ctvnews.ca\">{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary enters Conservative leadership race: 'I'm in'|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/kevin-o-leary-enters-conservative-leadership-race-i-m-in-1.3245919}}</ref> O'Leary supports the legalization and regulation of [[marijuana]].<ref name=\"bnn.ca\" />\n\nO'Leary supports [[assisted suicide]] and cited Switzerland as a model for Canada to follow.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary is way too boring to be called Canada's Donald Trump|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/opinion/o-leary-canadian-trump-1.3941549}}</ref>\n\n====Foreign and military policy====\nO'Leary supported ending [[Operation Impact|Canadian airstrikes on ISIS]] and supports taking a peacekeeping role in the [[Syrian Civil War]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary supports ending airstrikes against ISIS|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/kevin-o-leary-supports-ending-airstrikes-against-isis-1.2772888}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary described Russia as \"neither an ally or a foe\" in an interview with the CBC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PnPCBC/status/818600755405864960|title=Kevin O'Leary on Russia|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary has criticized [[Justin Trudeau]]'s procurement plan. He supports purchasing [[Unmanned combat aerial vehicle|aerial combat drones]] to defend [[Canadian airspace]] and supports phasing out use of the [[Lockheed CP-140 Aurora]] citing cost reasons.<ref name=\"ctvnews.ca\"/> He has criticized the lack of funding of the [[Canadian Armed Forces]] and supports spending the [[NATO]] recommended 2% of GDP on military expenditures.<ref name=\"ctvnews.ca\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Kevin O'Leary explains his vision for Canada, says he's 'coming' for PM Trudeau|url=http://globalnews.ca/video/3189215/kevin-oleary-explains-his-vision-for-canada-says-hes-coming-for-pm-trudeau}}</ref>\n\n====Immigration====\nO'Leary has proposed creating a \"fast track\" for citizenship for immigrants who graduate from college or university and find employment, as well as for their spouses and children.<ref name=\"fast track\">{{cite web|title=Kevin O'Leary proposes 'fast-track' to citizenship for skilled immigrants|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/kevin-o-leary-proposes-fast-track-to-citizenship-for-skilled-immigrants-1.3271254|publisher=CTV News|first=Jeff|last=Lagerquist|date=4 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary has advocated for increased border security in order to tackle the issue of illegal immigration.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2017/03/06/kevin-oleary-says-refugees-exploiting-an-immigration-loophole|date=6 March 2017|title=Kevin O'Leary says refugees exploiting an immigration 'loophole'}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=kevinolearytv|author=Kevin O'Leary|number=839186062501003265|date=7 March 2017|title=#2. Increase border security to halt the flow of illegals into Canada & work w/ US border security to better understand our deficiencies.}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|number=839184454975434758|user=kevinolearytv|author=Kevin O'Leary|date=7 March 2017|title=Illegal immigration compromises Canada's security & is a slap in the face to families who are waiting to move to our country legitimately.}}</ref>\n\n====Senate====\nIn a 2017 interview with Evan Solomon, O'Leary suggested that [[Senate of Canada|Senators]] should pay money every year, instead of being paid, thus turning \"a cost centre to Canada\" into \"a profit centre.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/senate-seats-for-sale-o-leary-says-he-d-consider-it-1.3240864|title=Senate seats for sale? O'Leary says he'd consider it|first=Josh|last=Dehaas|publisher=CTV|date=15 January 2017|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Leadership debt and lawsuit ===\nIn November 2018, O'Leary hired lawyer [[Joseph Groia]] and sued [[Elections Canada]] and Canada's federal elections commissioner over campaign finance laws which limited candidates to spending only $25,000 of their own money for their leadership campaign. At the time of the lawsuit, O'Leary still owed $430,000 to creditors. O'Leary had proposed to Elections Canada that he pay off the debt now with his own money and fundraise the money later, but was rebuffed, since this would be illegal. O'Leary made public statements that the law promoted mediocrity since rich people would be discouraged from running and hurt the businesses who had pledged money for his failed leadership campaign.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/powerandpolitics/pnp-tasker-oleary-suing-elections-canada-1.4905684|title=Kevin O'Leary suing Elections Canada over fundraising limits|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|date=November 14, 2018|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=November 14, 2018|last2=Kapelos|first2=Vassy|language=en-CA|author-link2=Vassy Kapelos}}</ref>\n\nIn O'Leary's legal submissions, he argued that the laws preventing the use of personal money over $25,000 were a restriction of his [[Section 2 of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|Section 2]] [[Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|Charter]] right to free expression and the threat of jail time in those laws violated his [[Section 7 of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|Section 7]] right to security of the person.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nO'Leary and his wife, Linda, have been married since 1990.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/69295-who-is-kevin-olearys-wife-linda-is-mrs-wonderful-totally-lives-up-to-the-name|title=Who Is Kevin O'Leary's Wife? Linda Is Mrs. Wonderful & Totally Lives Up to the Name|publisher=Bustle|accessdate=12 April 2015|author=Laura Rosenfeld}}</ref> The couple separated in 2011, but resumed their marriage after two years.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/small-business/sb-growth/kevin-oleary-the-shark-who-swims-alone/article595744|title=Kevin O'Leary: The shark who swims alone|work=Globe and Mail|accessdate=23 September 2011|author=John Allemang}}</ref> Linda now serves as the VP of Marketing for O'Leary Wines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailyentertainmentnews.com/tv/linda-oleary-shark-tank-kevin-olearys-wife|title=Linda O'Leary: Shark Tank Kevin O'Leary's Wife|publisher=Daily Entertainment News|accessdate=12 April 2015}}</ref> They have two children.<ref name=\"inbetween\">{{cite web|url=http://inbetween.ca/kevin-oleary-shark-dragon-dad|title=Kevin O'Leary: Shark, Dragon, Dad|work=Inbetween Magazine|accessdate=12 April 2015}}</ref> Trevor is a music producer and DJ while Savannah is a multimedia producer at the Huffington Post.<ref name=\"inbetween\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://torontolife.com/city/business/kevin-oleary/|title=Kevin O'Leary is a blowhard, a relentless self-promoter and, maybe, Canada's future leader|first=Jason|last=McBride|publisher=Toronto Life|date=2016-08-24|accessdate=2019-11-25}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc. Magazine]]'' writer [[Brian D Evans]] O'Leary stated: \"In a successful growing business, it eats your time alive. Then later in life, you can provide for your family things that many others can't have. But because you sacrificed, you're then given the reward of freedom.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inc.com/brian-d-evans/inside-kevin-olearys-unconventional-wealth-building-habits.html|title=Inside Kevin O'Leary's unconventional wealth-building habits|first=Bryan|last=Evans|date=2016-09-22|accessdate=2019-01-17}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary's primary residence and tax residency is in [[Toronto]], Ontario. He also maintains a cottage in [[District Municipality of Muskoka|Muskoka]] as well as homes in [[Boston]] and [[Geneva]], Switzerland.<ref name=\"Kevin O'Leary is a blowhard, a relentless self-promoter\">{{cite news |url=http://torontolife.com/city/business/kevin-oleary/|work=Toronto Life|title= Kevin O'Leary is a blowhard, a relentless self-promoter|date=24 August 2016|author=Jason McBride}}</ref><ref name=\"Transcript: O'Leary on his bid for Conservative leadership\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2017/01/18/transcript-oleary-on-his-bid-for-conservative-leadership.html|title=Transcript: O'Leary on his bid for Conservative leadership|work=The Toronto Star|date=18 January 2017|author=Alex Boutilier}}</ref><ref name=\"Where is home? Kevin O\u2019Leary who\u2019s called Boston 'home' says his priority is Canada\">{{cite news|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2456900/where-is-home-kevin-oleary-whos-called-boston-home-says-his-priority-is-canada|title= Where is home? Kevin O\u2019Leary who\u2019s called Boston \u2018home\u2019 says his priority is Canada|publisher=Global News|date=15 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nO'Leary is a fan of the [[American football|football]] team the [[New England Patriots]], and claims to watch all of their games, even when he is traveling around the world and the games occur during the middle of the night.<ref name=\"boston q&a\"/> He is a [[oenophilia|wine aficionado]], and belongs to the [[Confr\u00e9rie des Chevaliers du Tastevin]], an international association of [[burgundy wine]] enthusiasts.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Look At Mr. Wonderful's Secret Society for Wine Snobs|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/a-look-at-mr-wonderfuls-secret-society-for-wine-snobs|first=Eric|last=Grundhauser|date=February 9, 2016|publisher=Atlas Obscura}}</ref> He is also a lifelong photographer, and has exhibited and sold prints of his photographs, donating the proceeds to charity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tycoon Kevin O'Leary says when it comes to photography, he is \"a starving artist, hold the starving\"|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/tycoon-kevin-oleary-says-when-it-comes-to-photography-he-is-a-starving-artist-hold-the-starving|first=Peter|last=Kuitenbrouwer|publisher=National Post|date=2 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, 2019, O'Leary was involved in a fatal crash on [[Lake Joseph]] in [[Muskoka]], Ontario. A 64-year-old man and a 48-year-old woman died when a boat owned by O'Leary was involved in a collision with another boat. O'Leary said in a statement that he is cooperating with the police investigation, that he was a passenger in his boat, and that the other boat did not have its lights on and \"fled the scene\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/kevin-o-leary-boat-crash-1.5262492|title=Kevin O'Leary confirms he was passenger in boat involved in double-fatal crash}}</ref> The police stated that both boats left the scene to \"attend a location and both parties called 911.\"<ref name=\"called911\">{{cite web| url=https://www.cp24.com/news/man-killed-in-boat-crash-involving-kevin-o-leary-was-fun-loving-father-of-2-his-brother-says-1.4569878| title=Man killed in boat crash involving Kevin O'Leary was 'fun-loving' father of 2, his brother says| first=Codi| last=Wilson| website=CP24.com| date=August 29, 2019}}</ref> On September 24, Linda O'Leary, the operator of the O'Leary's boat, was charged with \"careless operation of a vessel\" under the small vessel regulations of the ''Canada Shipping Act'', a charge that carries a maximum 18 months imprisonment and a $1-million fine. The driver of the other boat, Richard Ruh of [[Orchard Park, New York]], was charged with \"failing to exhibit navigation light while underway.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/kevin-o-leary-s-wife-charged-in-fatal-ontario-boat-crash-1.4608037|title=Kevin O'Leary's wife charged in fatal Ontario boat crash|publisher=ctvnews.ca|date=September 24, 2019}}</ref> On October 11, the [[Public Prosecution Service of Canada]] ruled out any jail time for Linda.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/linda-o-leary-not-facing-jail-time-for-charge-in-fatal-boat-crash-1.4634435|title=Linda O'Leary not facing jail time for charge in fatal boat crash|publisher=toronto.ctvnews.ca|date=October 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Cold Hard Truth: On Business, Money & Life''. Doubleday Canada. 2011. {{ISBN|978-0385671743}}\n* ''Cold Hard Truth on Men, Women & Money''. Doubleday Canada. 2012. {{ISBN|978-0-385-67850-6}}\n* ''Cold Hard Truth on Family, Kids and Money''. Doubleday Canada. 2013. {{ISBN|978-0385682404}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://kevinoleary.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|2891968|Kevin O'Leary}}\n\n{{Shark Tank}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oleary, Kevin}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Anglophone Quebec people]]\n[[Category:Artists from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in information technology]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in metals]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:Canadian art collectors]]\n[[Category:Canadian Broadcasting Corporation people]]\n[[Category:Canadian business and financial journalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian business writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian chairmen of corporations]]\n[[Category:Canadian commodities traders]]\n[[Category:Canadian computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Canadian documentary filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian film producers]]\n[[Category:Canadian finance and investment writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian financial company founders]]\n[[Category:Canadian financiers]]\n[[Category:Canadian game show hosts]]\n[[Category:Canadian money managers]]\n[[Category:Canadian motivational writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Lebanese descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian photographers]]\n[[Category:Canadian real estate businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Canadian stock traders]]\n[[Category:Canadian technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:Canadian technology company founders]]\n[[Category:Canadian television company founders]]\n[[Category:Canadian television producers]]\n[[Category:Canadian television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Canadian venture capitalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian winemakers]]\n[[Category:CTV Television Network people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:Participants in Canadian reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Mount Royal, Quebec]]\n[[Category:University of Waterloo alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Western Ontario alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Montreal]]\n", "name_user": "71.204.185.144", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kevin_O%27Leary"}
{"title_page": "Ellerton, East Riding of Yorkshire", "text_new": "{{Short description|Village in the East Riding of Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                  England\n|coordinates =              {{coord|53.850158|-0.930275|display=inline,title}}\n|static_image =             Ellerton, St Mary's Church.jpg\n|static_image_caption =     St Mary's Church, Ellerton, 2004\n|official_name =            Ellerton\n|population =               \n|civil_parish =             [[Ellerton and Aughton]]\n|unitary_england =          [[East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n|region =                   Yorkshire and the Humber\n|lieutenancy_england =      [[East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[Haltemprice and Howden (UK Parliament constituency)|Haltemprice and Howden]]\n|post_town =                YORK\n|postcode_district =        YO42\n|postcode_area =            YO\n|dial_code =                01757\n|os_grid_reference =        SE704398\n|london_distance_mi =       165<!-- straight line per MOS \u2013 constant and comparable with other place distances -->\n|london_direction =         S\t\n}}\n'''Ellerton''' is a village in the [[East Riding of Yorkshire]], England.  It is situated approximately {{Convert|8|mi|km|0}} north-west of the [[market town]] of [[Howden]] and 8 miles south-west of the [[market town]] of [[Pocklington]].\nIt lies west of the [[B1228 road]] and east of the [[River Derwent, Yorkshire|River Derwent]].\n\nTogether with [[Aughton, East Riding of Yorkshire|Aughton]] it forms the [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] of [[Ellerton and Aughton]].\n\n==History==\nA [[priory]] of [[Canon (priest)|canons]] of the [[Gilbertine Order]] existed at Ellerton, which was known as [[Ellerton on Spalding Moor Priory]]. The priory was founded before 1212, and relinquished on 11 December 1536 under the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries|Suppression of the Monasteries]]. The site of the priory is now a [[scheduled ancient monument]].<ref>{{NHLE|num=1005225|desc=Site of Ellerton Priory|accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1823 Ellerton, was in the [[Hundred (county division)#Wapentake|Wapentake]] of [[Harthill Wapentake|Harthill]], and contained a [[Methodism|Methodist]] chapel and a chapel dedicated to St Mary. The village had a population of 318, with occupations including ten farmers, a corn miller, a tailor, and a shopkeeper. A shoemaker was also a [[Landlord#Licensed victualler|licensed victualler]] of The Board [[public house]]. Also directory-listed was a school master, a gentleman and a vicar. Once a week a carrier operated between the village and [[York]].<ref name=Baines>[[Edward Baines (1774\u20131848)|Baines, Edward]] (1823): ''History, Directory and Gazetteer of the County of York'', p.&nbsp;201</ref>\n\nThe parish church of St Mary, by architect [[John Loughborough Pearson]], was designated a Grade II [[listed building]] in December 1966 and is now recorded in the [[National Heritage List for England]], maintained by [[Historic England]].<ref name=hg>{{NHLE |num= 1083208|desc= Church of St Mary|accessdate= 21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|title=Gazetteer &mdash; A&ndash;Z of Towns Villages and Hamlets|year=2006|publisher=East Riding of Yorkshire Council|page=5<!--|accessdate=4 February 2011-->}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.ellerton.info |title=The Ellerton One-Place Study|quote=Provides the history of the parish|accessdate=29 April 2013}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Ellerton, East Riding of Yorkshire|Ellerton}}\n*{{OpenDomesday|OS=SE7039|name=ellerton|display=Ellerton}}\n\n{{Portalbar|Yorkshire|England|United Kingdom}}\n{{East Yorkshire|state=collapsed}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in the East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n\n\n{{EastRiding-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Village in the East Riding of Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                  England\n|coordinates =              {{coord|53.850158|-0.930275|display=inline,title}}\n|static_image =             Ellerton, St Mary's Church.jpg\n|static_image_caption =     St Mary's Church, Ellerton, 2004\n|official_name =            Ellerton\n|population =               \n|civil_parish =             [[Ellerton and Aughton]]\n|unitary_england =          [[East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n|region =                   Yorkshire and the Humber\n|lieutenancy_england =      [[East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[Haltemprice and Howden (UK Parliament constituency)|Haltemprice and Howden]]\n|post_town =                YORK\n|postcode_district =        YO42\n|postcode_area =            YO\n|dial_code =                01757\n|os_grid_reference =        SE704398\n|london_distance_mi =       165<!-- straight line per MOS \u2013 constant and comparable with other place distances -->\n|london_direction =         S\t\n}}\n'''Ellerton''' is a village in the [[East Riding of Yorkshire]], England.  It is situated approximately {{Convert|8|mi|km|0}} north-west of the [[market town]] of [[Howden]] and 8 miles south-west of the [[market town]] of [[Pocklington]].\nIt lies west of the [[B1228 road]] and east of the [[River Derwent, Yorkshire|River Derwent]].\n\nTogether with [[Aughton, East Riding of Yorkshire|Aughton]] it forms the [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] of [[Ellerton and Aughton]].\n\nA [[priory]] of [[Canon (priest)|canons]] of the [[Gilbertine Order]] existed at Ellerton, which was known as [[Ellerton on Spalding Moor Priory]]. The priory was founded before 1212, and relinquished on 11 December 1536 under the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries|Suppression of the Monasteries]]. The site of the priory is now a [[scheduled ancient monument]].<ref>{{NHLE|num=1005225|desc=Site of Ellerton Priory|accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1823 Ellerton, was in the [[Hundred (county division)#Wapentake|Wapentake]] of [[Harthill Wapentake|Harthill]], and contained a [[Methodism|Methodist]] chapel and a chapel dedicated to St Mary. The village had a population of 318, with occupations including ten farmers, a corn miller, a tailor, and a shopkeeper. A shoemaker was also a [[Landlord#Licensed victualler|licensed victualler]] of The Board [[public house]]. Also directory-listed was a school master, a gentleman and a vicar. Once a week a carrier operated between the village and [[York]].<ref name=Baines>[[Edward Baines (1774\u20131848)|Baines, Edward]] (1823): ''History, Directory and Gazetteer of the County of York'', p.&nbsp;201</ref>\n\nThe parish church of St Mary, by architect [[John Loughborough Pearson]], was designated a Grade II [[listed building]] in December 1966 and is now recorded in the [[National Heritage List for England]], maintained by [[Historic England]].<ref name=hg>{{NHLE |num= 1083208|desc= Church of St Mary|accessdate= 21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|title=Gazetteer &mdash; A&ndash;Z of Towns Villages and Hamlets|year=2006|publisher=East Riding of Yorkshire Council|page=5<!--|accessdate=4 February 2011-->}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.ellerton.info |title=The Ellerton One-Place Study|quote=Provides the history of the parish|accessdate=29 April 2013}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Ellerton, East Riding of Yorkshire|Ellerton}}\n*{{OpenDomesday|OS=SE7039|name=ellerton|display=Ellerton}}\n\n{{Portalbar|Yorkshire|England|United Kingdom}}\n{{East Yorkshire|state=collapsed}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in the East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n\n\n{{EastRiding-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Indoreli", "label": "safe", "comment": "Clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellerton,_East_Riding_of_Yorkshire"}
{"title_page": "Philip Cecil Crampton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n'''Philip Cecil Crampton''' [[Privy Council of Ireland|PC]] (May 1783 in [[Dublin]] \u2013 29 December 1862)<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rqeSXWqKAD8C&lpg=RA1-PA347&dq=%22Philip%20Cecil%20Crampton%22&pg=RA1-PA347#v=onepage&q=%22Philip%20Cecil%20Crampton%22&f=false |title=The Judges in Ireland, 1221-1921 |publisher=The Lawbook Exchange, Ltd.|year=2005|author=F. Elrington Ball|accessdate=2010-12-31}}</ref><ref name=\"ray1\">{{Rayment-hc|M|2|date=March 2012}}</ref> was a judge, politician and [[Solicitor-General for Ireland]]. He was also a noted supporter of the cause of [[total abstinence]] from [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]].\n\nHe was  born in [[Dublin]], the fourth son of the Reverend Cecil Crampton, vicar of  Headfort, [[County Galway]], and Nicola Mary Marsh, daughter of the Rev. Jeremy Marsh, rector of Athenry, aunt of [[Sir Henry Marsh]] and great-granddaughter of Archbishop [[Francis Marsh]]. His namesake, the celebrated doctor [[Sir Philip Crampton]], 1st Baronet, was a cousin, a fact which benefitted his career. He was educated at the [[University of Dublin]], where he was an outstanding student, and gold medallist; later becoming a Fellow of the University (1807\u201316) and  Regius Professor of Law in 1816. He entered [[Lincoln's Inn]] in 1808. He was called to the [[Irish Bar]] in 1810.\n\nHe was appointed Solicitor-General in 1830. He was elected [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Saltash (UK Parliament constituency)|Saltash]] in February 1831,<ref name=\"ray2\">{{Rayment-hc|S|2|date=March 2012}}</ref> and MP for [[Milborne Port (UK Parliament constituency)|Milborne Port]] in July 1831.<ref name=\"ray1\"/> He was judge of the [[Court of Queen's Bench (Ireland)]] 1834-1859.\n\nIn politics he was a [[Whig (British political party)|Whig]] and a strong  supporter of progressive Whig causes such as Parliamentary reform and [[abolitionism in the United Kingdom|abolition of the slave trade]]. Though a fine academic lawyer and a \"pleasant and tactful\" advocate, he was not considered much of a politician. His various proposals to reform the Irish legal system met with little support, and he clashed repeatedly with [[Daniel O'Connell]] (he was to be one of the judges at O'Connell's trial in 1844).\n\nO'Connell opposed Crampton's appointment to the Bench, calling him \"utterly incompetent\", lacking in integrity, and chosen  only  due to  his friendships with senior judges. O'Connell  however disliked and despised nearly all the Irish judges of his time, and his low  opinion of Crampton was not generally shared: when he retired, it was said that no judge's reputation stood higher. Most contemporaries praised him as \"a true gentleman, a true Christian, and a noted philanthropist\".\n\nHe married firstly in 1817 Sidney Mary Browne, who died in 1839, and secondly Margaret Duffy. By his second marriage he had one son, Cecil, who died young.\n\nHe lived in considerable state at his home St. Valery, near [[Bray, County Wicklow]], but was not noted for hospitality. A strict advocate of [[temperance movement|temperance]], he refused to serve alcohol to his guests,  and according to a much repeated story, poured the entire contents of the St. Valery wine cellar into the nearby  River [[Dargle]].\n\nHe retired from the Bench in 1859 and died at St. Valery in 1862. Cecil, his only son,  died four years later while still in his teens. The estate passed to another branch of the Crampton family.\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-philip-crampton | Philip Cecil Crampton }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n\n{{s-bef| before = [[Henry Vane, 2nd Duke of Cleveland|Earl of Darlington]]<br />[[John Gregson (MP)|John Gregson]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Saltash (UK Parliament constituency)|Saltash]]\n       | with   = [[Henry Vane, 2nd Duke of Cleveland|Earl of Darlington]]\n       | years  = February 1831 \u2013 May 1831}}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Frederick Villiers Meynell|Frederick Villiers]]<br />[[Bethell Walrond]] }}\n\n{{s-bef| before = [[Richard Lalor Sheil]]<br />[[George Byng, 2nd Earl of Strafford|George Byng]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Milborne Port (UK Parliament constituency)|Milborne Port]]\n       | with   = [[George Byng, 2nd Earl of Strafford|George Byng]]\n       | years  = July 1831\u20131832}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n\n{{s-legal}}\n{{succession box  | title  = [[Solicitor-General for Ireland]]  | years  = 1830\u20131834  | before = [[John Doherty (Irish politician)|John Doherty]]  | after  = [[Sir Michael O'Loghlen, 1st Baronet|Michael O'Loghlen]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crampton, Philip Cecil}}\n[[Category:1783 births]]\n[[Category:1862 deaths]]\n[[Category:Solicitors-General for Ireland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Members of Lincoln's Inn]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Saltash]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Milborne Port]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1830\u20131831]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1831\u20131832]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Irish King's Bench]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n'''Philip Cecil Crampton''' [[Privy Council of Ireland|PC]] (May 1783 in [[Dublin]] \u2013 29 December 1862)<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rqeSXWqKAD8C&lpg=RA1-PA347&dq=%22Philip%20Cecil%20Crampton%22&pg=RA1-PA347#v=onepage&q=%22Philip%20Cecil%20Crampton%22&f=false |title=The Judges in Ireland, 1221-1921 |publisher=The Lawbook Exchange, Ltd.|year=2005|author=F. Elrington Ball|accessdate=2010-12-31}}</ref><ref name=\"ray1\">{{Rayment-hc|M|2|date=March 2012}}</ref> was a judge, politician and [[Solicitor-General for Ireland]]. He was also a noted supporter of the cause of [[total abstinence]] from [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]].\n\nHe was  born in [[Dublin]], the fourth son of the Reverend Cecil Crampton, vicar of  Headfort, [[County Galway]], and Nicola Mary Marsh, daughter of the Rev. Jeremy Marsh, rector of Athenry, aunt of [[Sir Henry Marsh]] and great-granddaughter of Archbishop [[Francis Marsh]]. His namesake, the celebrated doctor [[Sir Philip Crampton]], 1st Baronet, was a cousin, a fact which benefitted his career. He was educated at the [[University of Dublin]], where he was an outstanding student, and gold medallist; later becoming a Fellow of the University (1807\u201316) and  Regius Professor of Law in 1816. He entered [[Lincoln's Inn]] in 1808. He was called to the [[Irish Bar]] in 1810.\n\nHe was appointed Solicitor-General in 1830. He was elected [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Saltash (UK Parliament constituency)|Saltash]] in February 1831,<ref name=\"ray2\">{{Rayment-hc|S|2|date=March 2012}}</ref> and MP for [[Milborne Port (UK Parliament constituency)|Milborne Port]] in July 1831.<ref name=\"ray1\"/> He was judge of the [[Court of Queen's Bench (Ireland)]] 1834-1859.\n\nIn politics he was a [[Whig (British political party)|Whig]] and a strong  supporter of progressive Whig causes such as Parliamentary reform and [[abolitionism in the United Kingdom|abolition of the slave trade]]. Though a fine academic lawyer and a \"pleasant and tactful\" advocate, he was not considered much of a politician. His various proposals to reform the Irish legal system met with little support, and he clashed repeatedly with [[Daniel O'Connell]] (he was to be one of the judges at O'Connell's trial in 1844).\n\nO'Connell opposed Crampton's appointment to the Bench, calling him \"utterly incompetent\", lacking in integrity, and chosen  only  due to  his friendships with senior judges. O'Connell  however disliked and despised nearly all the Irish judges of his time, and his low  opinion of Crampton was not generally shared: when he retired, it was said that no judge's reputation stood higher. Most contemporaries praised him as \"a true gentleman, a true Christian, and a noted philanthropist\".\n\nHe married firstly in 1817 Sidney Mary Browne, who died in 1839, and secondly Margaret Duffy. By his second marriage he had one son, Cecil, who died young.\n\nHe lived in considerable state at his home St. Valery, near [[Bray, County Wicklow]], but was not noted for hospitality. A strict advocate of [[temperance movement|temperance]], he refused to serve alcohol to his guests,  and according to a much repeated story, poured the entire contents of the St. Valery wine cellar into the nearby  River [[Dargle]].\n\nHe retired from the Bench in 1859 and died at St. Valery in 1862. Cecil, his only son,  died four years later while still in his teens. The estate passed to another branch of the Crampton family.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-philip-crampton | Philip Cecil Crampton }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n\n{{s-bef| before = [[Henry Vane, 2nd Duke of Cleveland|Earl of Darlington]]<br />[[John Gregson (MP)|John Gregson]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Saltash (UK Parliament constituency)|Saltash]]\n       | with   = [[Henry Vane, 2nd Duke of Cleveland|Earl of Darlington]]\n       | years  = February 1831 \u2013 May 1831}}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Frederick Villiers Meynell|Frederick Villiers]]<br />[[Bethell Walrond]] }}\n\n{{s-bef| before = [[Richard Lalor Sheil]]<br />[[George Byng, 2nd Earl of Strafford|George Byng]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Milborne Port (UK Parliament constituency)|Milborne Port]]\n       | with   = [[George Byng, 2nd Earl of Strafford|George Byng]]\n       | years  = July 1831\u20131832}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n\n{{s-legal}}\n{{succession box  | ti